[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {Hello everyone, and welcome.  I’m English Grandmaster Gawain Jones, and this is my third Chessable course. The first two were a Lifetime Repertoire built around the King’s Indian. Armed with those ideas we can be confident against not just1.d4, but all White’s first move tries apart from1.e4.  Quite a few people have asked me to recommend a good companion opening to the King’s Indian when facing1.e4and this course is the result.  We start by reacting solidly with1...e5, but we’re intending on soon creating our beloved King’s Indian formation. I hope this will appeal to King’s Indian players and all those who want to fight for the initiative.  For a while, I was struggling to choose a king’s pawn defense. I wrote a two-volume series on the Dragon for Quality Chess. My results against the top players were pretty good: a victory against Yu Yangyi (2744) in the final round of Gibraltar 2016, and my infamous battle with Magnus Carlsen in Wijk aan Zee. I was a clear piece up out of the opening, but converting was an altogether trickier matter.  The issue was against lower-rated players. The lines are very forcing, and a well-booked-up opponent could either force a draw or go into complications where Black needs to find a sequence of only moves to survive. Neither case gave any room to outplay the opponent.  I experimented a bit with the Dragondorf, but I wasn’t at all convinced it passed the sound test. I moved on to1.e4e5in 2007 for the UK - China match. Our coach Tony Kosten, an English GM living in France, suggested the Gajewski Variation (a Chigorin Variation where Black plays10...d5rather than10...c5).  The surprise worked very well, Wang Hao even initially wrote 10...c5 on his scoresheet before looking back at the board puzzled. The game ended as a draw after I’d been pressing. Playing1...e5gives us great flexibility.  I’ve jumped around testing different variations against the Spanish. I first played a version of the lines examined here in 2015, winning a classical game in 14 moves. It became one of my main lines in 2018, when I used it to score an important victory in the 2018 European Individual Championships (eventually coming 2nd equal).  The last few years have seen me playing around with the move orders. Now I’m ready to share my findings! I’ve read too many books in the past which have an interesting idea or two, but there’s a problem that kills off the entire opening. I end up feeling a bit tricked, having devoted effort fruitlessly. Therefore my first objective is always that my recommendations are sound. For similar reasons, I want to first examine the main lines. After all, these are the lines you’re most likely to encounter.  It’s not much good memorizing various refutations of subpar alternatives if you dislike the positions you’re much more likely to reach. However, playing sound chess doesn’t mean it has to be dull. I’m sharing my own repertoire against1.e4, and I always want to play for the win. In fact, I think I spent the most time on lines where we had an option of dull equality.  I wanted to offer something more interesting. I hope I’ve succeeded, even against notoriously drawish openings. Our opponents are not going to find it easy to kill off the game. As tends to be the case, the course has ended up being longer than intended. But one of the chief reasons for that is that I’ve offered quite a few alternatives. This allows you more choices to build your repertoire.  The most in-depth coverage of an alternative comes against the Italian, where I’ve covered both setups with the bishop on c5 and a fianchettoed bishop on g7.  I hope you all enjoy the course. As with the King’s Indian courses, if you have any queries don’t hesitate to ask. I’ll reply as soon as I can. After all, this is my repertoire too, so it’s definitely in my interest to make sure there are no holes. Best of luck!  Gawain} 1. --
