9. Ne7 {Let's compare this to a Classical King's Indian. Black's only odd move there would be ...a7-a6, although we've played ...Bd7 a little earlier than we normally would. In the meantime, White has wasted a tempo on c2-c3, as that pawn will definitely want to advance to c4, and a couple of tempi with his bishop.   Now is probably the right time to discuss the light-squared bishop exchange. In thematic King's Indians, Black's bishop has a dual purpose on c8. It holds the queenside together by defending the b7-pawn, useful when White opens the b-file in variations such as the Bayonet Attack. It also sits patiently waiting to be sacrificed to open up the kingside.   The typical scenario is when the kingside is completely blocked after we've pushed our pawns to f4 and g3, and White has reacted with f2-f3 and h2-h3. Here ...Bxh3 is a key idea to uncork White's king. With bishops exchanged, therefore, play will be a little slower.   We shouldn't rush into closing the kingside unless White has already given us a hook (an early h2-h3 say). But we have other ways to get at White's king. We generally want to keep the pawn on f5 to put maximum pressure on the e4-pawn. We'll often combine that with ...c7-c6, the model game Bjerre-Carlsen is a good example.   White's play is much slower on the queenside. In fact, we can often choose to play on that wing too. Overall, this is a pretty good King's Indian, and therefore the strongest White players tend to steer clear.} 
10. c4 {The most thematic. White sets up his Mar del Plata structure and gets ready to develop the knight to c3. Starting with10.Bc2looks rather odd.10...b5!?is actually likely to transpose as White doesn't have better than11.c4, while there's nothing wrong with the usual10...O-Oeither, followed by ...Ne8 and ...f7-f5.} 
10. b5 {Playing for the maximum. We exploit White's delay in exchanging bishops. We're claiming we now have the better bishop. Meanwhile, White's knight won't feel so comfortable on c3.  White should now hold off exchanging on b5, as11.cxb5axb5is just extremely pleasant for us.We'll castle, followed by the usual useful move ...h7-h6. We can then either start on the kingside or fight for control of the center with ...c7-c6. White will struggle to find any queenside counterplay. They have no c4-c5 leverage, and we have no weaknesses.} 
11. Bb3 {White faces a tough choice where to put their bishop. b3 is a more passive square, but at least it defends the c4-pawn.} 
11. O-O {We're ready to fight for control of the center.} 
12. c5 {Probably White's best try.} 
12. Bg4 {By pinning the knight, we indirectly defend our e-pawn. We now threaten to capture on c5. Having said that,12...dxc5is certainly not ridiculous. The position after13.Nxe5Ne8!?is very complicated.} 
13. c6 {White grabs as much space as they can.13.cxd6cxd6doesn't put any pressure on our position.Next up will be ...Nd7 and ...f7-f5.} 
13. Nh5 {Zapata-Onischuk, Toluca 2009. We're ready to generate counterplay with ...Nf4 and ...f7-f5. White's b3-bishop is completely offside.} 
