1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez or Spanish Variation, White's primary try in the king's pawn openings.} 
3. a6 {So far so normal. I'll discuss the pros and cons of alternative move orders later.} 
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. O-O {Hundreds of thousands of games have reached this point. Black has a wide choice. The most common move is5...Be7.  At the top level, they're generally aiming for a Marshall, but Black could also intend many other variations: Breyer, Zaitsev, Chigorin, etc. Black could also put their bishop on c5, either immediately or after playing5...b5. Finally, the Open Variation with5...Nxe4is also very topical.  Hopefully, you get a flavor of the amount of theory White needs to know. But all that knowledge won't be very helpful after our next.} 
5. d6 {This rather rare move is my recommendation. We defend our e5-pawn and prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop. From g7 our bishop exerts a lot of pressure on White's center. We've also given the e-pawn additional support, and so ...b7-b5 and ...Na5 collecting White's light-squared bishop is an idea.   If White advances with d2-d4-d5, then we quickly reach a King's Indian style structure, but one in which White is rather slower on the queenside than usual. After all, the c-pawn had to stop at c3.   If White keeps the tension, they will have some issues developing the b1-knight. Playing Nb1-d2-f1-g3 is very usual in Spanish structures, but it's a lot less effective against our setup. That's because our g6-pawn controls the f5-square, and so the knight is dominated on g3.   As the knight starts that journey, we should also be ready with a well-timed ...exd4. Not only is the d4-pawn rather vulnerable, but we also have ideas of ...Nc6-b4 and into d3 to collect White's dark-squared bishop.} 
6. Re1
6. Bd7 {We need to be accurate with our move order here. First, we break the pin and prepare to recapture on c6 with the bishop.6...g6?!7.Bxc6+bxc68.d4is rather annoying.} 
7. c3 {White needs to prepare to push the d-pawn. The immediate7.d4would fall to the same trick as on the previous move.} 
7. g6 {Time to fianchetto.} 
8. d4
8. Bg7
9. d5 {White closes the center. Time for a King's Indian!} 
9. Ne7 {Let's compare this to a Classical King's Indian. Black's only odd move there would be ...a7-a6, although we've played ...Bd7 a little earlier than we normally would. In the meantime, White has wasted a tempo on c2-c3, as that pawn will definitely want to advance to c4, and a couple of tempi with his bishop.   Now is probably the right time to discuss the light-squared bishop exchange. In thematic King's Indians, Black's bishop has a dual purpose on c8. It holds the queenside together by defending the b7-pawn, useful when White opens the b-file in variations such as the Bayonet Attack. It also sits patiently waiting to be sacrificed to open up the kingside.   The typical scenario is when the kingside is completely blocked after we've pushed our pawns to f4 and g3, and White has reacted with f2-f3 and h2-h3. Here ...Bxh3 is a key idea to uncork White's king. With bishops exchanged, therefore, play will be a little slower.   We shouldn't rush into closing the kingside unless White has already given us a hook (an early h2-h3 say). But we have other ways to get at White's king. We generally want to keep the pawn on f5 to put maximum pressure on the e4-pawn. We'll often combine that with ...c7-c6, the model game Bjerre-Carlsen is a good example.   White's play is much slower on the queenside. In fact, we can often choose to play on that wing too. Overall, this is a pretty good King's Indian, and therefore the strongest White players tend to steer clear.} 
10. Bxd7+
10. Nxd7 {Recapturing this way makes a lot of sense to me. We free the f-file in preparation for our thematic break.} 
11. c4 {One of White's main two tries. They accept the loss of a tempo, but the knight can now develop more actively on c3.} 
11. h6 {The typical prelude to ...f7-f5.} 
12. Nc3
12. f5 {For12...O-O, check out the model game Bjerre-Carlsen, Copenhagen 2019.} 
13. b4
13. a5 {A useful idea to remember. We make it as difficult as possible for White to get in c4-c5.} 
14. bxa5 {Unfortunately for White, it's not possible to maintain a pawn on b4, as their rook would hang after14.a3?axb415.axb4?Rxa1.} 
14. Rxa5 {We have another very decent-looking King's Indian. As long as we make it as difficult as possible for White to push c4-c5, we can be very optimistic.} 
