10. Bxd7+
10. Nxd7 {Recapturing this way makes a lot of sense to me. We free the f-file in preparation for our thematic break.} 
11. Be3 {White's most commonly played move, and tried a couple of times by Sergey Karjakin. The idea is to develop the bishop before Nfd2 and f2-f3 to support the center.} 
11. h6 {Let's be consistent.11...f5!?might be possible, but the position after12.Ng5Nf813.f4!?is very murky. I wouldn't recommend that path.However, Pavlovic's suggestion of11...Ng8!?is intriguing. The idea is to exchange bishopswith ...Bh6, and was once played by Magnus Carlsen.Finally, the straightforward11...O-Ois also possible. There Black should follow up with a planof ...Kh8 and ...Ng8 to once again exchange the dark-squared bishops.} 
12. Nfd2 {Played exclusively.} 
12. f5 {Threatening to trap the bishop.12...Bf6!?is another interesting idea, once played by the legendary GM and trainer, Artur Jussupow (or Yusupov if you prefer). We'll use a similar idea next move.} 
13. f3 {We're at another crossroads.} 
13. Bf6 {Our idea is very similar to Artur's. We want to exchange the bishops before we close the kingside. With a locked center White would have the more valuable bishop.} 
14. Bf2 {Otherwise, we'd take the opportunity to put our bishop on h4. White really doesn't want to play g2-g3 as their kingside would then be much looser.} 
14. O-O {We could also start with14...Bg5.} 
15. c4
15. Bg5 {Continuing to activate the bishop.} 
16. Nc3 {Time for another choice.} 
16. b6 {Black maintains the tension and adds further support to the c5-square.} 
17. b4 {This was seen in the highly important game Karjakin-Sasikiran, Tromso 2013 from the World Cup. Here Black got on with it on the kingside with17...Nf6, but I'd prefer to slow White's play first.} 
17. a5 {We make sure it won't be easy for White to break with c4-c5. Once again it's impossible to maintain a pawn on b4, as the knight would be hanging after18.a3?axb419.axb4?Rxa120.Qxa1Bxd2.  See the main chapter for a deeper examination of this position.} 
