[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez or Spanish Variation, White's primary try in the king's pawn openings.} 
3. a6 {So far so normal. I'll discuss the pros and cons of alternative move orders later.} 
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. O-O {Hundreds of thousands of games have reached this point. Black has a wide choice. The most common move is5...Be7.  At the top level, they're generally aiming for a Marshall, but Black could also intend many other variations: Breyer, Zaitsev, Chigorin, etc. Black could also put their bishop on c5, either immediately or after playing5...b5. Finally, the Open Variation with5...Nxe4is also very topical.  Hopefully, you get a flavor of the amount of theory White needs to know. But all that knowledge won't be very helpful after our next.} 
5. d6 {This rather rare move is my recommendation. We defend our e5-pawn and prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop. From g7 our bishop exerts a lot of pressure on White's center. We've also given the e-pawn additional support, and so ...b7-b5 and ...Na5 collecting White's light-squared bishop is an idea.   If White advances with d2-d4-d5, then we quickly reach a King's Indian style structure, but one in which White is rather slower on the queenside than usual. After all, the c-pawn had to stop at c3.   If White keeps the tension, they will have some issues developing the b1-knight. Playing Nb1-d2-f1-g3 is very usual in Spanish structures, but it's a lot less effective against our setup. That's because our g6-pawn controls the f5-square, and so the knight is dominated on g3.   As the knight starts that journey, we should also be ready with a well-timed ...exd4. Not only is the d4-pawn rather vulnerable, but we also have ideas of ...Nc6-b4 and into d3 to collect White's dark-squared bishop.} 
6. Re1
6. Bd7 {We need to be accurate with our move order here. First, we break the pin and prepare to recapture on c6 with the bishop.6...g6?!7.Bxc6+bxc68.d4is rather annoying.} 
7. c3 {White needs to prepare to push the d-pawn. The immediate7.d4would fall to the same trick as on the previous move.} 
7. g6 {Time to fianchetto.} 
8. d4
8. Bg7
9. Nbd2 {Developing the knight has to be the most logical move, and it's no surprise that it's historically the main line. But we have a good antidote, and recently the top players have switched to Grandelius' recommendation of9.h3!?We'll examine that later.  Finally, White could try9.Bb3, but after we castle White won't be able to avoid transposing into another line.} 
9. O-O {Our plan is to exchange on d4. If the knight moves from d2 we'll increase the pressure with ...Bg4, perhaps preceded by ...b7-b5 to prevent White from exchanging on c6.   If White keeps the knight on d2, we have ideas of ...Nh5 to open the long diagonal for our bishop. Finally, we also have ideas of annoying White with a ...Nb4 jump, exploiting the weak d3-square.} 
10. Nf1 {Logical, the knight continues its thematic Spanish journey to g3. Just two problems: firstly, the knight doesn't actually do a lot on g3 with our pawn on g6. Secondly, this isn't helping defend the d-pawn at all.We'll investigate the old main line with10.h3later on.} 
10. exd4 {The plan is to expel the bishop with ...b7-b5 and then ...Bg4. We've already seen the concept, for example against9.Bg5.} 
11. cxd4 {This is the automatic recapture.} 
11. b5 {Fabiano Caruana preferred the immediate11...Bg4, but I don't want to allow White the additional defense of12.Bxc6. Wherever the bishop drops back we'll put our bishop on g4, but then modify our plan slightly.} 
12. Bc2
12. Bg4 {The point of our previous couple of moves. The d-pawn is not at all easy to defend.} 
13. Be3
13. Nh5 {This appears to be a novelty but was recommended by Irina Bulmaga in her course on the Smyslov Ruy Lopez with 3...g6. In the past, players have always dropped the knight back to d7, but it's handy to control the f4 and g3-squares.Irina's course overlaps with this one after 8 moves, but reaches the position in quite a different manner:3...g64.O-OBg75.c3a66.Ba4d67.d4Bd78.Re1Nf6. I'll go into more detail about possible move orders elsewhere.} 
14. Ng3
14. Qf6 {We increase the pressure. We have threats of both capturing on f3 and then d4, or after ...Bxf3 and gxf3, simply jumping our knight into the new outpost on f4.} 
