8. Nxd4 {Vladimir Kramnik considered this the more serious move and the top players generally agree with him.} 
8. c5 {Our pawn is attacked: we should move it.} 
9. Nc6 {This is a weird-looking move, but it's been established as the only testing try. The knight will be quite good on a5.9.Nb3was the final choice for that knight,but ...a6-a5 followed by ...a5-a4 is a good antidote.} 
9. Qd7 {The only move.} 
10. Na5 {If White tries this line at the top level, then it's this position they're aiming for. The white knight has found an outpost, albeit on the edge of the board, and for now, our queen is misplaced.} 
10. Qa4 {Continuing to harass the knight and getting out of the way of our bishop. We're making it as difficult as possible for White to both maintain the knight and complete their development.} 
11. Bd2
11. Be7 {Esipenko played the immediate11...Bg4, but that's inaccurate. First, we should get a step closer to castling. By blocking the e-file, the e4-pawn is now also vulnerable.} 
12. Re1 {White simply defends the e-pawn.12.f3Be6will be very similar. Attention! Care is now required, as White has their cunning Nc3 trick aimed against castling.} 
12. Bg4 {Unmentioned by Werle in his Smart Ruy Lopez course. It's important to force f2-f3 once White has committed rook to e1. This was clearly Esipenko's intention, but he got confused and played it a move too early. If we started with12...Be6, then White could expel our queen with13.b3.Don't rush to castle here.12...O-O?!13.Nc3!With the bishop on d2, this is a lot more than a simplifying tactic.13...Qxa514.Nd5is very unpleasant. White regains the piece immediatelywith Nxe7+. Then Bc3 will start a vicious attack on the dark squares. Please avoid this.} 
13. f3 {Were the queen to sidestep, we could grab the e-pawn.} 
13. Be6 {Objective achieved. White would prefer that f-pawn back on f2.14.b3is now impossible, as14...Qd4+collects the rook.} 
14. c4 {White decides to remove the queens from the board.} 
14. Qxd1
15. Rxd1
15. Nd7 {The typical maneuver. Next, we'll put our bishop on f6. We have promising long-term chances with our central outpost on d4. This is quite a theoretical line, as we've transposed to something that more often comes from the Berlin, but Black is not under any pressure.12...Bg4!is important to remember, and we should always be ready for White's temporarypiece sacrificewith Nc3-d5 once we castle.} 
