[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez or Spanish Variation, White's primary try in the king's pawn openings.} 
3. a6 {So far so normal. I'll discuss the pros and cons of alternative move orders later.} 
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. d3 {A popular shortcut. White wishes to play the Ruy Lopez without having to memorize tonnes of theory, especially in the Open Variation(5.O-ONxe4).  This has been recommended in many places, notably by Christof Sielecki in his new Keep it Simple1.e42.0, and as an alternative by Nils Grandelius in his Grand Ruy Lopez.} 
5. d6 {Luckily for us, we can play exactly the same setup that we were intended against 5.O-O.   Play is generally slower in this variation, as the two armies have not yet made contact. White can develop without worrying about their d4-pawn, but at some point will need to come up with a plan.   One immediate point is that we threaten to get rid of White's light-squared bishop with ...b7-b5 and ...Na5. This is almost always a good trade for us. The light-squared bishop is far more useful than our slightly misplaced c6-knight.} 
6. O-O {White continues on autopilot, ignoring our threat.} 
6. b5 {Let's grab that bishop. It's also possible to play6...g6, when we'll likely transpose to either6.c3or6.c4lines, but we should punish White.} 
7. Bb3
7. Na5 {That bishop isn't going anywhere. We don't need to rush to take it, but we should just make sure we don't allow it to run.    Now that we've spent a bit of time going after White's bishop, e7 will be a better placement for our own bishop. We don't want White opening the center with d3-d4 before we're ready. Don't worry, long-term we still want to attack.   A reliable setup is to play a combination of castling, capturing on b3, ...c7-c5, ...Bb7, move the knight, and play ...f7-f5. As White's light-squared bishop will be off the board, ours on b7 will be a monster.} 
8. Re1 {Starting with8.Nbd2will come to the same thing.} 
8. Be7 {We're not altering our plan.} 
9. Nbd2
9. O-O {The precise move order generally matters little here. White is slowly bringing the knight round to g3, while we're going to construct our ideal formation.Starting with9...c5is also perfectly fine. I would just hold off putting the bishop on b7 for now. Once White puts their knight on g3, they're threatening to hop into f5. Our bishop on c8 does a good job of guarding that square.} 
10. Nf1
10. c5
11. Ng3 {White could play c2-c3 at any time, when we'll always react by capturing on b3. The move order is unimportant.} 
11. Re8
12. c3
12. Nxb3
13. axb3
13. Bf8 {A very typical position in these careless d3-Spanish lines. White has achieved the thematic idea of bringing the knight round to g3 but now struggles with a plan. If White further prevaricates, then we can improve our position with ...h7-h6, maybe even ...g7-g6, and play for the ...d6-d5 break.} 
14. d4 {White has run out of improving moves.} 
14. exd4
15. cxd4
15. h6 {Maintaining the tension. If White sits, then we'll capture on d4 followed by going after the e4-pawn with ...Bb7.It was also perfectly fine to capture on d4 immediately. After15...cxd416.Nxd4Bb7, White has to find17.Ndf5!when the game will likely peter out to a draw. We're not really running any risk there, but let's play for more.} 
16. d5
16. Bg4 {We're about to switch back to more familiar types of positions. Our plan: ...g7-g6, ...Bg7, ...a6-a5 and ...Nd7. Our bishop will rule the roost.} 
