3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez or Spanish Variation, White's primary try in the king's pawn openings.} 
3. a6 {So far so normal. I'll discuss the pros and cons of alternative move orders later.} 
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. d3 {A popular shortcut. White wishes to play the Ruy Lopez without having to memorize tonnes of theory, especially in the Open Variation(5.O-ONxe4).  This has been recommended in many places, notably by Christof Sielecki in his new Keep it Simple1.e42.0, and as an alternative by Nils Grandelius in his Grand Ruy Lopez.} 
5. d6 {Luckily for us, we can play exactly the same setup that we were intended against 5.O-O.   Play is generally slower in this variation, as the two armies have not yet made contact. White can develop without worrying about their d4-pawn, but at some point will need to come up with a plan.   One immediate point is that we threaten to get rid of White's light-squared bishop with ...b7-b5 and ...Na5. This is almost always a good trade for us. The light-squared bishop is far more useful than our slightly misplaced c6-knight.} 
6. c4 {We've seen the problems that White encounters should we win their light-squared bishop. Now we'll look at the two main moves. This one is a bit anti-positional. White has to be very careful as there's a chronic weakness on d4. On the other hand, White can at least develop their knight actively to c3 and hopes to make something of the d5-square control.We'll look at the main line6.c3next. Finally, it should be mentioned that White can keep the bishop with6.a3!?, but it doesn't threaten anything. We can just get on with our usual plan with6...g6and 7...Bg7.} 
6. g6 {We're not winning the bishop here, so back to the usual setup. Our plan is to exploit our new outpost on d4. We'll do that by playing ...Bg7, castling, and ...Nd7, when the other knight will be ready to hop into d4.} 
7. Nc3 {Starting with7.O-Oor7.h3will come to the same thing after7...Bg7.} 
7. Bg7
8. h3 {This tends to be the route the top players are trying right now. It's useful for White to control the g4-square to prevent either ...Ng4 plans, hitting the e3-bishop (if it stops there immediately or gets shunted back from g5), or an annoying pin with ...Bg4.} 
8. O-O
9. Be3 {This is actually White's most common move, but I think it's an inaccuracy.} 
9. Nd7 {This concept is very strong. By retreating the knight we're ready to hop the other knight into d4. White's best try is discombobulating with Bg5, but that doesn't make a lot of sense when the bishop just stopped at e3.} 
10. Bxc6 {White tends to prevent the knight jump for good.} 
10. bxc6 {This position has been encountered quite frequently, with even strong GMs playing White, but I think we're already better. Our f-pawn is about to start marching. The bishop on e3 will give us an extra tempo. White could claim our structure is damaged, but the c-pawn is doing a useful job controlling the d5-square, while we have play down the b-file.} 
11. d4
11. Rb8 {Yuriy Krykun's recommendation. We develop with tempo, and will follow it up with ...f7-f5. White's position is miserable.} 
