2. Nc6
3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez or Spanish Variation, White's primary try in the king's pawn openings.} 
3. a6 {So far so normal. I'll discuss the pros and cons of alternative move orders later.} 
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. d3 {A popular shortcut. White wishes to play the Ruy Lopez without having to memorize tonnes of theory, especially in the Open Variation(5.O-ONxe4).  This has been recommended in many places, notably by Christof Sielecki in his new Keep it Simple1.e42.0, and as an alternative by Nils Grandelius in his Grand Ruy Lopez.} 
5. d6 {Luckily for us, we can play exactly the same setup that we were intended against 5.O-O.   Play is generally slower in this variation, as the two armies have not yet made contact. White can develop without worrying about their d4-pawn, but at some point will need to come up with a plan.   One immediate point is that we threaten to get rid of White's light-squared bishop with ...b7-b5 and ...Na5. This is almost always a good trade for us. The light-squared bishop is far more useful than our slightly misplaced c6-knight.} 
6. c3 {Overwhelmingly the top choice. White gives the bishop an escape route.} 
6. g6 {Back to the normal plan. We're going to fianchetto and castle, and then see how White has placed their pieces. As Grandelius observes, White shouldn't play Be3 too early, as then our plan of ...f7-f5 will be extremely strong. That's because ...f5-f4 will come with tempo.    White is usually content to play a combination of castling, Re1, and knight round from b1 to g3. If White isn't going to take the center then we will. We'll generally either play ...h6-h6, ...Re8 and ...d6-d5 or achieve the ...f7-f5 break.   From a practical perspective, it's better to play without ...b7-b5, so that White cannot generate play on the queenside with a2-a4.} 
7. O-O {White's most natural move.} 
7. Bg7 {Once again White has to decide on a setup. White usually decides on the plan of bringing the knight to g3. They can also decide on developing the bishop, but there are downsides to both e3 and g5-squares.We'll investigate White's main move,8.Re1, soon. First, we'll have a look at White's other options.} 
8. d4 {Once again, playing this in two moves is only scary for White.} 
8. O-O {Not only has White lost a tempo with d2-d3-d4, but we haven't had to take a time-out with ...Bd7 either. As everything is simply a better version, I haven't gone into a lot of depth, but below are a few sample lines.} 
9. Re1 {White defends the pawn. We could also reach this with White starting with8.Re1and then 9.d4.} 
9. b5 {First, we ask the bishop a question. It's always a tough one to answer. On the one hand, the bishop sometimes goes from b3 to c2, so White could argue they're gaining a tempo by going there directly. But, as we've seen in the main line of Spanish, that bishop might actually be better placed on b3.} 
10. Bb3
10. Bg4 {We could also start by capturing on d4, but we have a sneaky idea in mind. When White's bishop is on b3, we have to watch out for Bd5 ideas, and so the ...Nh5 setups aren't as strong.    By the way, this position is very popular with the bishop on e7 rather than g7. Clearly, our bishop is much better placed on the long diagonal, as the d4-pawn is vulnerable.} 
11. d5
11. Na5 {We gain time on White's bishop. Now our opponents wish they'd gone all the way back directly.} 
12. Bc2
12. c6 {Undermining White's center before they can get any support. Don't worry about our knight being hit here, we actually want to recapture on c6 with the queen anyway.   Our knight is already on a good circuit. c4 is a good square, and being kicked back to b6 is also fine. We're going to aim to break with ...d6-d5.} 
