9. Re1 {White defends the pawn. We could also reach this with White starting with8.Re1and then 9.d4.} 
9. b5 {First, we ask the bishop a question. It's always a tough one to answer. On the one hand, the bishop sometimes goes from b3 to c2, so White could argue they're gaining a tempo by going there directly. But, as we've seen in the main line of Spanish, that bishop might actually be better placed on b3.} 
