[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez or Spanish Variation, White's primary try in the king's pawn openings.} 
3. a6 {So far so normal. I'll discuss the pros and cons of alternative move orders later.} 
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. d3 {A popular shortcut. White wishes to play the Ruy Lopez without having to memorize tonnes of theory, especially in the Open Variation(5.O-ONxe4).  This has been recommended in many places, notably by Christof Sielecki in his new Keep it Simple1.e42.0, and as an alternative by Nils Grandelius in his Grand Ruy Lopez.} 
5. d6 {Luckily for us, we can play exactly the same setup that we were intended against 5.O-O.   Play is generally slower in this variation, as the two armies have not yet made contact. White can develop without worrying about their d4-pawn, but at some point will need to come up with a plan.   One immediate point is that we threaten to get rid of White's light-squared bishop with ...b7-b5 and ...Na5. This is almost always a good trade for us. The light-squared bishop is far more useful than our slightly misplaced c6-knight.} 
6. c3
6. g6
7. O-O
7. Bg7
8. Re1 {Clearing the way for the knight. This is White's most common and most flexible move.8.Nbd2is likely to come to the same thing. White will follow it up with Re1 to give the knight a square.8.h3O-Owill also be a transposition, either to Grandelius' recommendation of 9.h3 or to 8.Be3.} 
8. O-O {After investigating White's earlier tries, we've now reached the main branching point of the d3-Spanish.  In his Keep it Simple 2.0, Sielecki recommends the most straightforward plan of9.Nbd2intending to reroute the knight to g3. This is White's most common idea, but I don't think it puts any pressure on our position.Grandelius offers the subtle9.h3!?, keeping the option of developing the bishop. I think this is objectively White's best try, but White needs to understand all the nuances of the position to play it accurately.We have a few plans available. We can play in the center with ...h7-h6, ...Re8, and ...d6-d5. Another plan is to grab space on the queenside with ...b7-b5 followed by ...a6-a5-a4.   I've also tried to offer alternative plans where we succeed in our thematic King's Indian ...f7-f5 break. This works particularly well if White does something provocative like putting the bishop on e3. Then the plan of ...f7-f5 works so much better as we'll always gain time on the bishop. Talking of provocation,we cover9.d4via the 8.d4 move order.SHORTCUT ALERT:8...Bd7would actually transpose to6.Re1Bd77.d3!?. There's no need to touch the bishop here, but that's another good way to reach complicated positions.} 
9. h3 {Grandelius. White keeps their options open. They might transpose back to the main lines with9.Nbd2or they might develop the bishop to e3. This is perhaps White's best try in the whole d3-Spanish complex.} 
9. Kh8 {An interesting alternative plan. I think this works well against White's last. The idea is to punish White for neglecting their development. We're going for the attack!   Our king wants to be in the corner when we play ...f7-f5, but we're flexible about where to put the knight. As far as I can see this has never been played, but I'll offer a couple of possible lines.} 
10. Nbd2 {The usual, but now we're pretty fast.} 
10. Nd7 {This seems the most precise square. Sometimes we might pop out again on c5, while we're also keeping the e5-pawn supported.} 
11. Nf1
11. f5 {Here we go. If White doesn't now capture, we'll run over them with ...f5-f4 and ...g6-g5. Then we get ready to crash through with ...g5-g4, perhaps by putting the queen on g6. White's knight on f1 would do nothing in these circumstances.} 
12. exf5
12. gxf5
13. d4 {Otherwise, we just control the center.} 
13. e4
14. Ng5
14. Nf6 {Next, we'll bring the other knight round to g6. We already have a very promising attack.} 
