8. O-O {After investigating White's earlier tries, we've now reached the main branching point of the d3-Spanish.  In his Keep it Simple 2.0, Sielecki recommends the most straightforward plan of9.Nbd2intending to reroute the knight to g3. This is White's most common idea, but I don't think it puts any pressure on our position.Grandelius offers the subtle9.h3!?, keeping the option of developing the bishop. I think this is objectively White's best try, but White needs to understand all the nuances of the position to play it accurately.We have a few plans available. We can play in the center with ...h7-h6, ...Re8, and ...d6-d5. Another plan is to grab space on the queenside with ...b7-b5 followed by ...a6-a5-a4.   I've also tried to offer alternative plans where we succeed in our thematic King's Indian ...f7-f5 break. This works particularly well if White does something provocative like putting the bishop on e3. Then the plan of ...f7-f5 works so much better as we'll always gain time on the bishop. Talking of provocation,we cover9.d4via the 8.d4 move order.SHORTCUT ALERT:8...Bd7would actually transpose to6.Re1Bd77.d3!?. There's no need to touch the bishop here, but that's another good way to reach complicated positions.} 
9. Nbd2 {The main line.} 
9. h6 {I don't think Sielecki covers either this or the very similar9...Re8. I'm going to offer alternatives here. My primaryrecommendations will be the established equalizers with ...Re8 followed by ...d6-d5, or by advancing on the queenside. But I'll also offer alternatives where we attack on the kingside.   For both plans, ...h7-h6 is useful. We'd like to prevent White from any annoying Bg5 once the knight has dropped back to f1.Starting with9...Re8is also completely okay.But starting with ...h7-h6 means we haven't completely given up on playing ...f7-f5. Against the rook move, Arkadij Naiditsch tried10.a3!?Against such a waiting move we could now switch back to our direct route with10...Nh7and ...f7-f5.9...Kh8could also be played here,but Nbd2 is clearly more useful than h2-h3 if we're playing the ...f7-f5 plan.} 
10. Nf1 {White continues the autopilot rerouting.} 
10. Nh7 {If you wish to keep the King's Indian dream alive, then I recommend this approach. Otherwise, you can go for10...Re8as recommended in the relevant chapter.} 
11. Ng3 {Pushing the h-pawn would transpose to 10.h3.} 
11. Bd7 {But here we should rest a moment. The immediate11...f5?!is a bit too rash. White would get an advantage by capturing and the Nh5 jump.As White hasn't played h2-h3, they're a tempo ahead comparedto10.h3, and so we shouldn't rush things.Don't worry, ...f7-f5 is still the plan.} 
12. h3 {The typical improving move.} 
12. f5 {The addition of h2-h3 and ...Bd7 is firmly in our favor.} 
13. exf5
13. gxf5 {We'll now meet Nh5 with ...Be8, and so the knight won't be able to sit there indefinitely. After an exchange on g7, our bishop will take up the post on h5.} 
