5. d6 {Let's keep to our intended setup. This is rare but has the approval of Levon Aronian. With the e-pawn defended, White now needs to address the problem of their light-squared bishop.6.d3is played a lot here, but we cover that via5.d3d66.Nc3, while6.O-Ois covered via5.O-Oin White's remaining bits and bobs. Neither address the problem with White's bishop at all, and so we'll play6...b5and 7...Na5.} 
6. Bxc6+ {White has to part with the bishop before advancing in the center.} 
