4. dxc6 {The Exchange Spanish. White gives up the bishop pair for a slight lead in development and the nominally better structure. It used to be considered that Black had to be careful. White's plan is to exchange everything and win the king and pawn endgame. But the rise of the Berlin demonstrated that Black actually has little to fear in most endgames.} 
5. Nc3
5. f6 {The classic strengthening of the center. The main line of the entire Exchange Ruy Lopez would be this position with5.O-Orather than5.Nc3. This is a worse version,as White isn't in time to recapture on d1 with the rook.  Oddly, the opposite would be true if we started with ...Qf6, as the queenside rook is one tempo nearer developing.5...Qf6, our usual setup isn't advisable here.6.d4exd47.Bg5Qd68.Nxd4is the difference. White has an improved version over the main line, as they're able to recaptureon d1 with the rook.} 
6. d4
6. exd4
7. Nxd4
7. c5 {Please don't repeat my blunder of7...Bc5??8.Qh5+. In my defense, it was a late-night blitz game in the Titled Tuesday series of tournaments on chess.com.} 
8. Nde2
8. Qxd1+ {The big difference between the main line and 5.Nc3. White cannot recapture with the rook.} 
9. Nxd1
9. Be6 {We're intending the typical ...O-O-O and ...Ne7. See the main chapter for a deeper examination of this position.} 
