8. Be7 {We still want to castle queenside. Question time for White. Exchanging has been shown to be very comfortable, so the recent trend is to drop back.} 
9. Bxe7
9. Nxe7 {Here, the key thing to remember is that our king still wants to go long. In the early kick-off for the final round of the Olympiad, I was a bit befuddled and suffered after castling kingside.} 
10. Nc3
10. Bd7 {This development plan should look familiar by now. White finds it tough to do anything when they have to defend their d4-knight, so they always drop it back somewhere.  See the main chapter for a deeper examination of this position.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − Scotch"]
[Black "3.d4 − 6.e5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. d4 {Time to move on to the Scotch. This is one of White's most direct tries. They open lines for their pieces like in the Open Sicilian. We having played1...e5rather than1...c5changes a couple of things. First of all, we can develop much more easily. With White's knight about to move for a second time, we are about to take the lead in development.  White has to be very careful or their king can easily run into trouble. The structure, however, is much better for White compared to a Sicilian. We don't have an extra central pawn, and if White is allowed to develop unimpeded, we're often suffering with less space. Therefore, it's vital we play dynamically.} 
3. exd4
4. Nxd4 {White logically recaptures the pawn.4.Bc4is examined via the move order3.Bc4Nf64.d4exd4, while4.c3will be looked at together with White's other early gambits.} 
4. Nf6 {This has to be the most logical move. We develop and attack the pawn. The Scotch used to be my primary opening. Black has alternatives, but if it weren't for this move, I'd still be very happy to play it every game.} 
5. Nxc6 {If White plays this move order, then this is generally their approach.5.Nc3would be the Scotch Four Knights.} 
5. bxc6
6. e5 {The principled try. The game instantly becomes very sharp. As White isn't getting anywhere at all here, there's been a recent trend for the slower6.Bd3and6.Nd2. We'll analyze these at the end of this Quickstarter, but Black is very comfortable.} 
6. Qe7 {An important move. Simply moving the knight gives White time to develop freely. But now White will need to be very creative to develop their pieces.} 
7. Qe2
7. Nd5 {The battle lines are drawn. In White's favor, they have more space, especially after the main move8.c4, and the better structure. We also need to be careful about our light-squared bishop, which is often blocked out of the game.In our favor, we're already one piece ahead in development, and White will find it difficult to defend the e5-pawn.  The Scotch has to be the sharpest of White's main options against 1...e5, and therefore the opening with the most forcing lines. White is calling for a scrap, and we're happy to oblige!} 
8. c4 {The main move, and we continue to follow the most forcing route. But White has hit a bit of a brick wall here in the last few years, and so attention switched to Sethuraman's recommendation of8.h4!?. We'll analyze that deeply too, of course.  Note that White has quite a few different move orders. Kasimdzhanov prefers8.g3, transposing after8...g69.c4Ba610.b3. This was also my own try in a recent game against Ivan Cheparinov.} 
8. Ba6 {Dropping back with8...Nb6is another heavily debated line, but I prefer the pin. White won't find it so easy to both develop their pieces and hold onto the e-pawn.} 
9. b3 {The most efficient way to give White's pawns more support. The c-pawn is now safely defended, and the bishop can support the e-pawn via b2. White also has ideas of Ba3 attacking our queen.} 
9. g6 {Our bishop belongs on the long diagonal. Not only will we threaten the e-pawn, but White's rook could also be in trouble.I remember there being a trend for9...g5after its use in the 1995 World Championship match between Kasparov and Anand. Its popularity abated,as it was discovered White has some dangerous ideas involving h2-h4.White now has a big choice.10.f4and10.Bb2are two main lines, while10.Ba3!?became quite topical in the past couple of years. We'll examine those next. Finally,10.Nd2will be covered via the earlier9.Nd2.} 
10. Bb2 {The most visually logical move. White fianchettoes the bishop.} 
10. Bg7 {But now White should transpose with11.g3O-O, which is the main line of10.g3, while11.Nd2Nb4will be covered via9.Nd2.} 
11. Qe4 {White frequently puts the queen on e4 in these Scotch setups, but there's a thematic refutation.} 
11. f5 {The queen is undefended so en-passant is impossible.} 
12. Qd4 {Going back doesn't help much.12.Qe2d6wins the e-pawn.} 
12. Nb4 {Threatening the family fork.} 
13. Na3
13. d6 {The e-pawn falls anyway, and that's not the end of the suffering. White's king is exposed, and the knight on a3 is terrible.} 
*
