16. Rd1
16. Qf6 {Next will come ...Bb4. Once again, White isn't in time to get their king to safety. I'll leave a few more moves as a clickable here, to demonstrate how a practical game continued.17.Na4is the critical test.17...Bb4+18.Kf2Qh6, our queen didn't have many squares, but this one suits us just fine.19.Bxh8Rxd120.g3Rd2+, it's not surprising that White is busted with so many of our pieces in the attack, but care still has to be taken.21.Ke3− Perez-Perez Ponsa,Villa Martelli 2016. In the game, the Argentinian GM grabbed on a2, but actually lost.21...Bb7!,bringing our final piece into the attack; ...c6-c5 will be killing.22.c5, White prevents the threat but gives away a very important outpost.22...Nd5+23.Kf3g4+!Taking with the queen is immediate mate with 24...Qe3.24.Kxg4Ne3+25.Kf3Nxf126.Rxf1Ba6and, as usual, once White loses the light-squared bishop they have no chance.} 
