11. fxg5 {White should probably capture the pawn.} 
11. O-O-O {More testing than11...Bg7.What's our compensation for the pawn? Well, we've castled and are one move away from connecting our rooks. It will still take White three tempi to castle (and we're not going to make it easy). The g5 and e5-pawns are both very vulnerable. In fact, White has problems with all the dark squares. White really needs bishops on both b2 and d2 to plug the holes.} 
12. h4 {White cannot afford the tempo to hold on to the pawn.} 
12. h6 {Opening up more lines.} 
13. gxh6 {The unnatural13.Qb2!was the most tenacious.But after we simply drop the knight back to b6, our initiative continues.} 
13. Rxh6 {So far we'd been following the elite clash Navara-Jakovenko, Saint-Quentin 2014. The Russian recaptured with the bishop, but this exchange sacrifice would have left David in all kinds of trouble. If White declines the offer, we'll grab on h4.} 
14. Bxh6
14. Bxh6 {We're an exchange and a pawn down, but our domination on the dark squares signals the end for White. ...Ne3 is our big threat, but the main problem is simply that White cannot coordinate in the slightest.} 
