5. Nxc6 {If White plays this move order, then this is generally their approach.5.Nc3would be the Scotch Four Knights.} 
5. bxc6
6. e5 {The principled try. The game instantly becomes very sharp. As White isn't getting anywhere at all here, there's been a recent trend for the slower6.Bd3and6.Nd2. We'll analyze these at the end of this Quickstarter, but Black is very comfortable.} 
6. Qe7 {An important move. Simply moving the knight gives White time to develop freely. But now White will need to be very creative to develop their pieces.} 
7. Qe2
7. Nd5 {The battle lines are drawn. In White's favor, they have more space, especially after the main move8.c4, and the better structure. We also need to be careful about our light-squared bishop, which is often blocked out of the game.In our favor, we're already one piece ahead in development, and White will find it difficult to defend the e5-pawn.  The Scotch has to be the sharpest of White's main options against 1...e5, and therefore the opening with the most forcing lines. White is calling for a scrap, and we're happy to oblige!} 
8. c4 {The main move, and we continue to follow the most forcing route. But White has hit a bit of a brick wall here in the last few years, and so attention switched to Sethuraman's recommendation of8.h4!?. We'll analyze that deeply too, of course.  Note that White has quite a few different move orders. Kasimdzhanov prefers8.g3, transposing after8...g69.c4Ba610.b3. This was also my own try in a recent game against Ivan Cheparinov.} 
8. Ba6 {Dropping back with8...Nb6is another heavily debated line, but I prefer the pin. White won't find it so easy to both develop their pieces and hold onto the e-pawn.} 
9. Nd2
9. g6 {9.Nd2 used to be my main approach in the Scotch. Then I ran into Vladimir Kramnik in the final round of the Isle of Man 2017. After the pain of that game, I decided that I'd only touch it from the Black side. White's subtle idea is to defend the e-pawn with their queenside knight. This is very interesting, but it does take some time. White will have to accept their king will stay and will never be very happy.} 
10. Nf3 {The consistent approach.} 
10. Qb4+ {The problem. Despite White having three pieces that can go to d2, none of them can successfully fulfill the role. White's king is forced to start walking.} 
11. Kd1 {White gives up their castling rights.} 
11. Ne7 {Black has a huge range of possibilities here. Back in 2017, this one came as an unpleasant surprise. The main choice was between Leko's11...Rb8!?and11...Nb6. Both are still healthy, but Kramnik's move is very logical. The knight is simply on a better route here.We generally want to play ...c7-c5 and ...Bb7, when White has problems holding onto the e-pawn and dealing with a knight jump into d4.  White can play many different moves, but our plan remains the same. Objectively I think White is probably okay here, but the positions are easier for us to play. If you're a correspondence player and want to get an interesting position in the Scotch, then this wouldn't be the worst option, but I think the upsides are very limited in an 'OTB' game.} 
12. Qc2 {My own choice. This is considered best after11...Rb8, but here it might be a bit too slow.} 
12. c5 {At a stroke the bishop and knight are both activated. I was already pretty unhappy.} 
13. Qb3
13. Qb6 {An important strategic idea. White will only get the queen exchange in return for mending our structure.} 
14. Qxb6
14. axb6 {The e-pawn remains a liability. There's no longer anything positive about White's position.} 
