8. c4 {The main move, and we continue to follow the most forcing route. But White has hit a bit of a brick wall here in the last few years, and so attention switched to Sethuraman's recommendation of8.h4!?. We'll analyze that deeply too, of course.  Note that White has quite a few different move orders. Kasimdzhanov prefers8.g3, transposing after8...g69.c4Ba610.b3. This was also my own try in a recent game against Ivan Cheparinov.} 
8. Ba6 {We'll now wrap up White's remaining tries after 8.c4. These are sidelines for a good reason. If White doesn't transpose to lines already covered, they're likely to end up in trouble.} 
9. Qe4 {A draw offer.} 
9. Nb4 {Correctly playing for more. Our big threat is ...d7-d5.9...Nf6leaves White with nothing better than retreatingto e2.} 
10. Nc3 {The only way for White to remain on the board.10.Bd2?!is White's second-best try. The idea isto later capture on b4 with the bishop, but White remains in trouble after10...Qe6!, intending to expel the queen witheither ...d7-d5 or ...f7-f5.} 
10. Rd8 {We're preparing ...d7-d5. We're doing extremely well here, but a few of our tactical motifs are unusual. Therefore, I've decided to go quite deep. See the main chapter for a deeper examination of this position.} 
