[Black "3.d4 − 6.e5 #15"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. d4 {Time to move on to the Scotch. This is one of White's most direct tries. They open lines for their pieces like in the Open Sicilian. We having played1...e5rather than1...c5changes a couple of things. First of all, we can develop much more easily. With White's knight about to move for a second time, we are about to take the lead in development.  White has to be very careful or their king can easily run into trouble. The structure, however, is much better for White compared to a Sicilian. We don't have an extra central pawn, and if White is allowed to develop unimpeded, we're often suffering with less space. Therefore, it's vital we play dynamically.} 
3. exd4
4. Nxd4 {White logically recaptures the pawn.4.Bc4is examined via the move order3.Bc4Nf64.d4exd4, while4.c3will be looked at together with White's other early gambits.} 
4. Nf6 {This has to be the most logical move. We develop and attack the pawn. The Scotch used to be my primary opening. Black has alternatives, but if it weren't for this move, I'd still be very happy to play it every game.} 
5. Nxc6 {If White plays this move order, then this is generally their approach.5.Nc3would be the Scotch Four Knights.} 
5. bxc6
6. e5 {The principled try. The game instantly becomes very sharp. As White isn't getting anywhere at all here, there's been a recent trend for the slower6.Bd3and6.Nd2. We'll analyze these at the end of this Quickstarter, but Black is very comfortable.} 
6. Qe7 {An important move. Simply moving the knight gives White time to develop freely. But now White will need to be very creative to develop their pieces.} 
7. Qe2
7. Nd5 {The battle lines are drawn. In White's favor, they have more space, especially after the main move8.c4, and the better structure. We also need to be careful about our light-squared bishop, which is often blocked out of the game.In our favor, we're already one piece ahead in development, and White will find it difficult to defend the e5-pawn.  The Scotch has to be the sharpest of White's main options against 1...e5, and therefore the opening with the most forcing lines. White is calling for a scrap, and we're happy to oblige!} 
8. h4 {Probably White's most interesting try at the time of writing. I used it myself to beat Esipenko in the French Team Championships in 2022. White can't claim an advantage, but the positions are highly complex.  This is Sethuraman's recommendation in his Lifetime Repertoire on the Scotch. It's something of a useful waiting move. One idea is to take control of the g5-square, perhaps to develop the bishop there. Another crucial idea is to swing the rook via h3-e3. I've added a couple of informational lines to try and demonstrate what White is hoping for.} 
8. Qe6 {We react with something of a waiting move too. We get out of the way of the bishop. If White does nothing, we'll play either ...d7-d6 or ...Bc5. Just be careful. We'll now meet c2-c4 by moving our knight. We can no longer pin, as cxd5 will attack our queen. We have a lot of options here.Ivan Cheparinov was one of the early proponents of this variation. When we played I chose the other main line,8...f6, and that was also Esipenko's choice against me. That is also fine, but a bit more forcing. I think our choice is a bit tougher for White to play logically against.} 
9. g3 {The choice of the rising star Nodirbek Abdusattorov in a couple of blitz games.} 
9. d6 {It turns out that we're much happier with this exchange now. With our queen out of the way, we're going to recapture on d6 with the bishop. The pawn on g3 actually damages White's structure, as we have a hook for an f-pawn advance. The other logical move,9...Bc5is also fine.} 
10. c4 {White should first force our knight to be sidelined.} 
10. Nb6
11. exd6 {The most common, and most natural, but we're doing well with our lead in development.} 
11. Bxd6 {Once again we want to recapture this way. We're developing as quickly as possible.} 
12. Be3 {An aggressive try played in Nepomniachtchi-Kramnik, Leuven 2017. White wants to keep the queens on the board.} 
12. O-O
13. Nd2 {White needs to keep an eye on the c-pawn.13.Nc3Ba6is awkward.14.b3Bb4followed by ...Qf6 leaves White in a lot of trouble on the dark squares.} 
13. Re8 {Kramnik chose13...Ba6, but that didn't really achieve very much.Now we're threatening to capture on g3, as the e3-bishop would drop.} 
14. O-O-O
14. Na4 {Even stronger than grabbing the pawn. Our attack is very powerful.} 
