[White "Quickstarter Guide − Italian"]
[Black "3.Bc4 Nf6 4.d3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4 {Time to move onto the Italian, or the Giuoco Piano. Incidentally, when will we stop using the confusing medieval spelling and change it to the modern Italian 'gioco'?  We're in very old territory here, with games going back hundreds of years. When I was growing up this was looked down upon. Sure, you have natural development, but if you want to be a proper player then you should play the Spanish.  It was often played as a sort of mirrored London System. White would play Bc4, d2-d3, c2-c3, Bb3, Nbd2-f1-g3, h2-h3 and then stop and think. In the past decade or so there's been a radical overhaul, and almost all the top players now have the Italian in their repertoire.} 
3. Nf6 {The first decision. I'm proposing developing the knight first for two reasons. First, I believe the sidelines we're allowing here,4.Ng5and4.d4, are more interesting than allowing3...Bc54.c3followed by a quick d2-d4. Secondly, this gives us an additional setup, as we're not yet committed to developing ourbishop to c5.} 
4. d3 {The main line. White defends their pawn. We'll check out the alternatives later. Now we have a choice. I'm offering4...Bc5followed by ...d7-d6 and ...a7-a5 as our primary defense. This has an extremely good pedigree, having been used by Magnus Carlsen to wrap up his defense of the World Champion title against Ian Nepomniachtchi.I've also offered an interesting approach with4...h6,followed by ...d7-d6 and either ...g7-g5 or ...g7-g6. This is obviously riskier but puts White on the immediate backfoot.  Despite the Italian's recent reincarnation as a principled try, a lot of players still use it as a rote opening like the London System. They have a series of moves they wish to play, regardless of the setup Black employs. They'll have a rude awakening here.} 
4. Bc5 {I've played quite a few Italians, or Giuoco Pianos, with both colors, but the move orders still confuse me. Still, I hope this repertoire will make sense. Against most setups, our next two moves will be ...d7-d6 and ...a7-a5.} 
5. c3 {Both sides have thousands of possible move orders and nearly identical subtleties. It's impossible to cover absolutely everything, but I'll make sure we have all of White's critical tries covered, and hopefully provide a good grounding as to why they're critical.  White already has plenty of tries, but this is the main line. As we've seen in the Spanish, White needs a pawn on c3 to expand in the center with d3-d4. Here White may also want to push the b-pawn, while the c4-bishop will also need an escape route.} 
5. d6 {I believe this is the simplest. We don't yet commit our king, as then the lines with Bg5 become very sharp.} 
6. O-O
6. a5 {A few years ago, I was studying these positions in quite a lot of depth, as the Italian became my main opening. Black has many different setups, but this one seems quite straightforward. We give our bishop a retreat square and fight for possession of the queenside.  One key point is that we're almost always happy to offer an exchange of bishops with ...Be6. The structure after ...fxe6 can be a bit depressing if White can seize all the space on the queenside, but that's no longer possible.} 
7. Re1 {Once again, White has plenty of possible moves, but the rook is always useful on e1. It defends the e-pawn and helps prepare d3-d4, and gets out of the way of the b1-knight rerouting to the kingside via f1.} 
7. Ba7 {This was brought to prominence when Magnus Carlsen used it to wrap up the World Champion title in 2021. We have to drop the bishop back at some point, as White will prepare to push in the center with d3-d4. By playing it early, we don't need to know as much in the early Bg5 lines.7...h6is also possible, but we're hoping to do without that until absolutely necessary.} 
8. Nbd2 {The typical Italian setup.} 
8. O-O {With the c1-bishop blocked, we don't need to spend a tempo on the h-pawn; ...Ba7 is more useful than ...h7-h6. Our next move will be ...Be6, challenging White's bishop. If White declines the trade, we'll hop our knight round to g6. White will need both h2-h3 and Nf1 to successfully carry out d3-d4. It doesn't matter much to us which they start with.} 
9. Nf1 {White continues the knight's journey. Logical, but not very challenging.} 
9. Be6
10. Bxe6
10. fxe6 {As Wesley So put it: 'With the pawn on a5 controlling space, the doubled-pawns are not much of a problem for Black. White does not have the usual plan of advancing on the queenside with b4-a4'. This is a key reason behind the recent popularity of ...a7-a5. Without that plan, White struggles to do very much. In the meantime, we have play down the semi-open f-file.} 
11. Be3 {The safest. White continues exchanging.} 
11. Bxe3
12. Nxe3
12. Qe8 {12...Qd7was chosen by Magnus Carlsen in a couple of blitz games, but I think this is a more precise square. We're ready to slideto g6, perhaps after ...a5-a4. We'll slowly build up an attack.} 
