7. Ba7 {This was brought to prominence when Magnus Carlsen used it to wrap up the World Champion title in 2021. We have to drop the bishop back at some point, as White will prepare to push in the center with d3-d4. By playing it early, we don't need to know as much in the early Bg5 lines.7...h6is also possible, but we're hoping to do without that until absolutely necessary.} 
8. Nbd2 {The typical Italian setup.} 
8. O-O {With the c1-bishop blocked, we don't need to spend a tempo on the h-pawn; ...Ba7 is more useful than ...h7-h6. Our next move will be ...Be6, challenging White's bishop. If White declines the trade, we'll hop our knight round to g6. White will need both h2-h3 and Nf1 to successfully carry out d3-d4. It doesn't matter much to us which they start with.} 
9. Nf1 {White continues the knight's journey. Logical, but not very challenging.} 
9. Be6
10. Bb5
10. Ne7 {The typical rerouting.} 
11. d4 {White pushes immediately. But now they will have to be very careful to hold onto their center. Starting with11.Ng3has no independent significance. After11...Ng6, White will transpose elsewhere with either12.h3or12.d4.} 
11. Ng6 {Our knight has found its rightful posting.} 
12. Ng3 {12.h3is covered via the 9.h3 move order.} 
12. c6 {First, we force White to decide where to put the bishop.} 
13. Bd3 {White almost has their ideal structure.} 
13. Bg4 {But this is a problem. We hit the d4-pawn.} 
14. Be3
14. d5 {Just in time we contest for the center. White has to be careful to maintain equality. MVL-Rodshtein, Mayrhofen 2022.} 
