8. O-O {With the c1-bishop blocked, we don't need to spend a tempo on the h-pawn; ...Ba7 is more useful than ...h7-h6. Our next move will be ...Be6, challenging White's bishop. If White declines the trade, we'll hop our knight round to g6. White will need both h2-h3 and Nf1 to successfully carry out d3-d4. It doesn't matter much to us which they start with.} 
9. h3 {This subtlety appears to be White's best try. For now, the knight is needed on d2 to cover the e4-square.} 
9. Be6 {As we saw in the Spanish, White will probably need h2-h3 to prepare d3-d4. Otherwise, the pin with ...Bg4 will be very annoying. Here we don't need to worry about White's intricacies. We just continue with our plan.} 
10. Bb5 {It looks odd to move the bishop again, but with the light-squared bishops exchanged White struggles to do very much. The game starts to resemble a very slow Spanish.} 
10. Ne7 {Our knight carries out the same journey as White's; g6 is a reliable square. It can't easily be shifted, it controls the e5-pawn making it easier to play ...d6-d5, and it's ready to hop menacingly into f4.} 
11. Nf1 {The autopilot route is not challenging.} 
11. Ng6 {Or starting with11...c6. White should now transpose with12.d4. Otherwise, we'll be first in the center.} 
12. Ng3
12. c6 {Expelling the bishop. We could also start with ...d6-d5 directly.} 
13. Ba4
13. d5 {It's important to strike. Against Wesley So I hesitated with13...h6, but then14.d4gave White the slightly more pleasant position.} 
14. exd5
14. Nxd5 {A position played by Carlsen and Giri amongst others. The e-pawn is indirectly defended. We've comfortably equalized.} 
15. Nxe5
15. Nxe5
16. Rxe5
16. Bxf2+ {This is the shot to remember.} 
17. Kxf2
17. Qf6+ {We've won the exchange.} 
