6. a5 {A few years ago, I was studying these positions in quite a lot of depth, as the Italian became my main opening. Black has many different setups, but this one seems quite straightforward. We give our bishop a retreat square and fight for possession of the queenside.  One key point is that we're almost always happy to offer an exchange of bishops with ...Be6. The structure after ...fxe6 can be a bit depressing if White can seize all the space on the queenside, but that's no longer possible.} 
7. Re1 {Once again, White has plenty of possible moves, but the rook is always useful on e1. It defends the e-pawn and helps prepare d3-d4, and gets out of the way of the b1-knight rerouting to the kingside via f1.} 
7. Ba7 {This was brought to prominence when Magnus Carlsen used it to wrap up the World Champion title in 2021. We have to drop the bishop back at some point, as White will prepare to push in the center with d3-d4. By playing it early, we don't need to know as much in the early Bg5 lines.7...h6is also possible, but we're hoping to do without that until absolutely necessary.} 
8. Na3 {The main theoretical test of the early bishop retreat. White aims to gain time with Nb5.} 
8. h6 {It's possible to start by castling, but I'd prefer to steer clear of the pin. Na3 turns out to be quite a useful move there.} 
9. Nc2 {Seen in the World Championship match, but not scary.} 
9. O-O {We can calmly continue our development.} 
10. Be3
10. Bxe3 {Nothing extravagant is needed here.} 
11. Nxe3
11. Re8 {Preparing to exchange on e6.} 
12. a4
12. Be6 {Nepomniachtchi-Carlsen, Dubai 2021. The Russian needed to win, but it never looked likely. He quickly imploded and the Norwegian held onto the title.} 
