5. Nc3 {A serious alternative setup. It used to be considered that the c3-square was for the exclusive use of the c-pawn. With a knight in the way, it's very difficult to achieve the d4-break. Still, this is pretty fashionable these days. White either wants to grab our bishop with Na4, or take control of the d5-square.} 
5. a6 {Our bishop is now safe. Pushing the pawn two squares makes less sense here. White controls the light squares well, so we should compete for them.} 
6. Bg5 {White's main line, and the most forcing.} 
6. h6 {We ask the question. Dropping back to h4 wouldn't have much logic. We'll be able to block it out of the game either with ...g7-g5 immediately or after 7...d6.} 
7. Bxf6
7. Qxf6
8. Nd5
8. Qd8 {White must press on or we'll have time to consolidate.} 
9. c3
9. d6 {Starting by dropping the bishop back will come to the same thing.} 
10. d4
10. Ba7
11. dxe5 {White is anxious to make something of the initiative. Care should be taken here.11...dxe5?!12.Qe2is actually a bit awkward.White is putting their rook on d1, when our queen is uncomfortable.} 
11. Nxe5
12. Nxe5
12. dxe5
13. Qh5 {This is the point of White's previous few moves. As well as the threats to e5 and f7, White is clearing space for the rook to go to the d-file.} 
13. O-O {We should hurry to get our king to safety. The pawn sacrifice is only temporary.} 
14. Qxe5 {14.Rd1c6isn't getting White anywhere.} 
14. Re8 {Now it's White who has to deal with our initiative.} 
15. Qf4 {The only square to hold on to the e-pawn.} 
15. Qd6 {We force White's queen away.} 
16. Qf3 {White holds onto their ill-gotten gains, but there's a price to pay.} 
16. Be6
17. O-O-O
17. Qe5 {White's pieces are very awkwardly placed. 18...c6 is already a big threat.} 
