1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4 {Time to move onto the Italian, or the Giuoco Piano. Incidentally, when will we stop using the confusing medieval spelling and change it to the modern Italian 'gioco'?  We're in very old territory here, with games going back hundreds of years. When I was growing up this was looked down upon. Sure, you have natural development, but if you want to be a proper player then you should play the Spanish.  It was often played as a sort of mirrored London System. White would play Bc4, d2-d3, c2-c3, Bb3, Nbd2-f1-g3, h2-h3 and then stop and think. In the past decade or so there's been a radical overhaul, and almost all the top players now have the Italian in their repertoire.} 
3. Nf6 {The first decision. I'm proposing developing the knight first for two reasons. First, I believe the sidelines we're allowing here,4.Ng5and4.d4, are more interesting than allowing3...Bc54.c3followed by a quick d2-d4. Secondly, this gives us an additional setup, as we're not yet committed to developing ourbishop to c5.} 
4. Ng5
4. d5
5. exd5
5. Na5
6. Bb5+ {Overwhelmingly played. We just investigated White's dodgy alternatives.} 
6. c6 {The principal reaction. We make it a proper pawn sacrifice and damage our queenside into the bargain. But in return, White struggles to find a safe haven for their bishop.} 
7. dxc6
7. bxc6 {White has a wide choice. These days the odd looking8.Bd3is by far the most popular and was endorsed by both So and Krykun. We'll examine that soon. The classical8.Be2is still seen from time to time, while the weird8.Qf3sees an occasional outing or two.} 
8. Be2 {The Classical main line. This is the most comfortable spot for the bishop but does leave the knight to fend for itself.} 
8. h6 {Now the knight is the problem. It lacks a good square.} 
9. Nf3 {The normal square, but White has gone off this in recent years.} 
9. e4 {The knight is forced to hop again.} 
10. Ne5
10. Bc5 {We play the same way. The threat of ...Qd4 is extremely awkward.10...Bd6is also promising.} 
11. O-O {This isn't very inspiring but seems to be the only way to keep the game balanced.} 
11. Qd6 {The simplest. Both11...Qd4!?and11...O-Oalso provide good play. But now White has to be extremely careful.} 
12. Ng4 {A slightly better retreat than12.Nc4?but White is still in a lot of trouble.} 
12. Bxg4
13. Bxg4
13. h5 {Our knight wants the g4-square. The following includes some very pretty mating patterns. See the main chapter for a deeper examination of this position.} 
