1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4 {Time to move onto the Italian, or the Giuoco Piano. Incidentally, when will we stop using the confusing medieval spelling and change it to the modern Italian 'gioco'?  We're in very old territory here, with games going back hundreds of years. When I was growing up this was looked down upon. Sure, you have natural development, but if you want to be a proper player then you should play the Spanish.  It was often played as a sort of mirrored London System. White would play Bc4, d2-d3, c2-c3, Bb3, Nbd2-f1-g3, h2-h3 and then stop and think. In the past decade or so there's been a radical overhaul, and almost all the top players now have the Italian in their repertoire.} 
3. Nf6 {The first decision. I'm proposing developing the knight first for two reasons. First, I believe the sidelines we're allowing here,4.Ng5and4.d4, are more interesting than allowing3...Bc54.c3followed by a quick d2-d4. Secondly, this gives us an additional setup, as we're not yet committed to developing ourbishop to c5.} 
4. Ng5
4. d5
5. exd5
5. Na5
6. Bb5+ {Overwhelmingly played. We just investigated White's dodgy alternatives.} 
6. c6 {The principal reaction. We make it a proper pawn sacrifice and damage our queenside into the bargain. But in return, White struggles to find a safe haven for their bishop.} 
7. dxc6
7. bxc6 {White has a wide choice. These days the odd looking8.Bd3is by far the most popular and was endorsed by both So and Krykun. The classical8.Be2is still seen from time to time, while the weird8.Qf3sees an occasional outing or two.} 
8. Bd3 {We've seen the problems White has encountered in the other lines, so this retreat square is chosen by the process of elimination. Blocking the d-pawn looks very strange, but White is fighting for control of the e4-square.} 
8. Nd5 {As White's knight now has access to the e4-square, it's less logical to hit it with the pawn. By moving the knight we open up an attack on the knight and prepare either to hop in with ...Nf4 or get our f-pawn involved.} 
9. h4 {Quite a fashionable alternative. White maintains the knight on g5, but it's obviously very risky. These positions can get extremely messy. We'll analyze the main move,9.Nf3, in the next segment.} 
9. h6 {We have a range of options, but I think this one is the simplest.9...Qc7and9...Bc5are also fine.9...Be7is probably also okay, but I think this is what White is hoping for. We have a mess after10.Qf3. White manages to sacrifice their bishop for three pawns, while our king has to start walking.} 
10. Qh5 {The point. White threatens mate. We should take a bit of care here.} 
10. Qf6 {The correct defense. We need to know how to handle White's various knight jumps.} 
11. Ne4
11. Qe6 {White's pieces don't coordinate well here at all. We'll exploit White's queen with either ...g7-g6 and ...f7-f5 or ...Nf4.Objectively, White's best here is to repeat with12.Ng5. Gustafsson says we can't avoid the draw, but I think we can get away with dropping our queenback to e7. We'll take a look.} 
12. b3 {Probably White's best attempt at continuing the game, but I think the position is much easier for us to play.} 
12. g6 {Time to grab some space.} 
13. Qe2
13. f5
14. Nec3 {The only move to maintain equality.} 
14. Bg7 {To be honest, White's position looks ridiculous. What exactly is the knight doing on b1? And that pawn on h4? White will also have to exchange our problem piece, that knight on a5, in order to develop. Still, I suppose White is a pawn up. But with our activity and control of the center, I'd certainly choose Black.  See the main chapter for a deeper examination of this position.} 
