3. Nf6 {The first decision. I'm proposing developing the knight first for two reasons. First, I believe the sidelines we're allowing here,4.Ng5and4.d4, are more interesting than allowing3...Bc54.c3followed by a quick d2-d4. Secondly, this gives us an additional setup, as we're not yet committed to developing ourbishop to c5.} 
4. O-O {This isn't great, but at least it's sort of playable.} 
4. Nxe4 {We could also play4...Bc5, but we might as well exploit White's move order.} 
5. d4 {Clearly, White prefers having castled rather than playing c2-c3, but it's still not enough to equalize. We’ll play the same way against 4.c3?!} 
5. d5
6. Bb5 {Against6.Re1we can either take on c4 or6...Nxf2!?.} 
6. exd4 {Next, we'll block the pin.7.Qxd4Qd7!is also a successful concept against4.c3?!.} 
7. Nxd4
7. Bd7 {Should White pin along us along the e-file with Re1 we can either block with ...Be7 or defend tactically with ...Bd6 exploiting White's weakened h2 and f2-pawns. White doesn't have compensation for the pawn in either case.} 
8. c4 {I think this is the only move we should check.} 
8. Bc5 {Developing with tempo.} 
9. Nb3
9. Bxf2+ {Transforming the advantage.9...Ne7was also possible.} 
10. Rxf2
10. Nxf2
11. Kxf2
11. Ne7 {With such an open position, our rook and two pawns are worth more than White's two pieces.} 
