3. Bc4 {Time to move onto the Italian, or the Giuoco Piano. Incidentally, when will we stop using the confusing medieval spelling and change it to the modern Italian 'gioco'?  We're in very old territory here, with games going back hundreds of years. When I was growing up this was looked down upon. Sure, you have natural development, but if you want to be a proper player then you should play the Spanish.  It was often played as a sort of mirrored London System. White would play Bc4, d2-d3, c2-c3, Bb3, Nbd2-f1-g3, h2-h3 and then stop and think. In the past decade or so there's been a radical overhaul, and almost all the top players now have the Italian in their repertoire.} 
3. Nf6 {The first decision. I'm proposing developing the knight first for two reasons. First, I believe the sidelines we're allowing here,4.Ng5and4.d4, are more interesting than allowing3...Bc54.c3followed by a quick d2-d4. Secondly, this gives us an additional setup, as we're not yet committed to developing ourbishop to c5.} 
4. d4 {The most direct approach. White opens the center.} 
4. exd4 {We could also get this position from a Scotch move order:3.d4exd44.Bc4Nf6. White's most challenging try is5.e5, which we'll examine next. First, we'll check out White's other options.} 
5. O-O {White develops as swiftly as possible, but this does give up a second central pawn. I used this as a surprise weapon to defeat Wesley So in a rapid game, but, so long as we're careful, it's White who has to be more accurate to equalize.} 
5. Nxe4 {Grabbing the pawn. Were it not for this then White's opening would be quite promising.6.Nxd4d57.Bb5Bd7is examined in White's offbeat 4th moves.} 
6. Re1 {This pin is White's whole point.} 
6. d5 {White has tried an array of moves here, but only one keeps the game balanced.} 
7. Bxd5 {This mini tactic is White's whole point. White will regain the sacrificed pawns, but no more than that. Neither7.Bb5Bb4or7.Bd3Be7gets close to providing White with enough compensation.} 
7. Qxd5
8. Nc3 {A very pretty move and White's point. Thanks to the pins, we can't capture the knight. But all White is doing is retrieving their sacrificed piece.} 
8. Qd7 {Black has plenty of squares to choose from. The typical choice has been between a5 and h5, but I think this one is actually best. It's handy to keep White pinned along the d-file. It looks odd to block in our bishop, but we want to be able to recapture on c6 with our queen.  This line is actually quite strategically risky for White. If they're not able to make something of their light initiative, they'll really suffer against our bishop pair.} 
9. Rxe4+
9. Be7
10. Nxd4 {As Sethuraman points out, after10.Nb5O-O, we're in time to meet11.Bf4with11...Bd8.} 
10. f5 {We force the rook to go passive. With our queen back on d8, White would have the powerful 11.Bh6, but here it doesn't work. After capturing the rook, our queen can slide out to g4.} 
11. Rf4
11. O-O {I lost this position as White in a blitz game against German GM Dmitrij Kollars. White is struggling with the misplaced rook and against the bishop pair.} 
