3. Nf6 {The first decision. I'm proposing developing the knight first for two reasons. First, I believe the sidelines we're allowing here,4.Ng5and4.d4, are more interesting than allowing3...Bc54.c3followed by a quick d2-d4. Secondly, this gives us an additional setup, as we're not yet committed to developing ourbishop to c5.} 
4. d4 {The most direct approach. White opens the center.} 
4. exd4 {We could also get this position from a Scotch move order:3.d4exd44.Bc4Nf6. White's most challenging try is5.e5.} 
5. e5 {The pure Scotch Gambit. White solves the problem of the hanging pawn by pushing it. This was my recommendation in my Coffeehouse 1.e4 Repertoire.} 
5. d5 {The most principled response. We force White to move their bishop again. These days5...Ne4is quite topical, but the positions there can be very dry.} 
6. Bb5 {White should add this pin or they'll struggle to recoup their pawn. White has two aims. One is to capture on c6 and then get a bind over the c5-square. If White achieves it, then Black is left with a weakened queenside and no counterplay. The second is to use the e5-pawn to start kingside operations. In an ideal world, the f2-pawn joins its compatriot on the fifth rank.} 
6. Nd7 {An unusual retreat. This will catch your opponents off-guard. The main line is6...Ne4.The d7-square looks more passive, but the knight often gets hit on e4, and simply accelerates White's plan of pushing the f-pawn. White now needs to be careful to keep the e-pawn defended.  The main idea is to contest for control of the c6-square. Blocking the a4-e8 diagonal is also useful. White will be forced to capture on c6 before they can take our d4-pawn. Our strategy is then to take control of the center with ...c6-c5. I see elite players are starting to agree with me. Levon Aronian played this way in August 2022, while a few days before writing, Yu Yangyi opted for our main line against Martyn Kravtsiv.} 
7. O-O {White shouldn't rush to reclaim the pawn.7.Nxd4?Ncxe5and ...c7-c6 next. We're just up a pawn.} 
7. Be7 {Modest development, but there's not much point in putting our bishop on c5 here. We want to keep that square free for our newly minted c-pawn.} 
8. Bxc6 {The main line. White cashes in and reclaims the pawn.} 
8. bxc6
9. Nxd4 {White has to continue playing dynamically. Taking with the queen wouldn't make much sense. We can just castle, play ...Re8, drop our knight back to f8, and play for ...c6-c5.} 
9. Nb8 {Once again we see our key concept. It may look very odd to undevelop this knight, but control of the c6-square is vital. We're ready with our plan of fighting back in the center with ...c6-c5.Capturing9...Nxe5would have been an error. White can develop swiftly with10.Bf4, and will quickly regain their pawn.} 
10. Qf3 {White wants to hop the knight to f5.} 
10. c5 {We continue with our plan.} 
11. Nf5 {Thematic, but this doesn't really work.} 
11. Bxf5
12. Qxf5
12. Qd7 {We're always very happy with queen exchanges here. We'll recapture with our king. The c- and d-pawns do a great job of preventing White's bishop from finding a purpose.} 
13. Qh5
13. Nc6 {Duda-Aronian, Miami 2022. Levon already had the upper hand. As well as the typical knight hops into d4, we're also ready to castle kingside and play ...f7-f6. We have the initiative.} 
