[White "Quickstarter Guide − Others"]
[Black "Scotch Four Knights 4.d4 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6 {We now move on to the Four Knights complex. With a symmetrical position, White can play almost anything, but the main division is between the Spanish Four Knights with4.Bb5and the Scotch Four Knights with4.d4.} 
4. d4 {The more topical route.4.Bb5is the Spanish Four Knights, which will be examined shortly.4...Bc5!?This has been my preference for a more double-edged game.4...Nd4is the best if you want to force a draw, but White has a few ways to kill any enjoyment, including the immediate exchange, and 6.e5.  Keeping the symmetry with4...Bb4is also fine of course. If White now plays slowly we'll be doing well by exchanging a pair of knightswith ...Nd4.   We know from our Italian and Spanish that the c6-knight tends to be our worst-placed piece. White's critical attempts involve playing Nxe5 followed by forking our bishop and knight with d2-d4.} 
4. exd4
5. Nxd4 {We could also get this position via a Scotch move order.} 
5. Bb4 {Black has tried other moves, but this is the only satisfactory one. We immediately attack the e-pawn, which is a perennial problem in the Scotch setups.Sethuraman's recommendation of5...Nxe4!?is interesting, but from a practical point of view, I don't like that White can decide whether to embrace the chaos or immediately make the game exceedingly dull.} 
6. Nxc6 {White has to first exchange knights to be able to defend the pawn with the bishop.} 
6. bxc6 {White still has to address the defense of their e-pawn.} 
7. Bd3 {Most of White's other options simply transpose elsewhere.7.Bg5h68.Bh4O-Ois a transposition. Likewise7.f3O-Oand7.Qd3O-Oare both covered.If White tries7.Bd2, then we can either transpose to 9.Bd2 after7...O-O8.Bd3Re89.O-O, or punish White with7...Qe7going after the e-pawn.} 
7. O-O {7...d5is the main line these days, but we're going for a slightly different approach. Rather than exchanging central pawns immediately, we want to continue putting pressure on the e-pawn. We'll only offer the trade once White's bishop is sidetracked.} 
8. O-O {Neither8.Bg5h6nor8.Bd2Re8will alter play.} 
8. Re8 {The secondary line in terms of popularity. We attack the e-pawn. Keeping the central pawns on the board keeps more life in the game.  I believe our opponents won't feel as comfortable here as in the main lines. White now has to choose how to defend the e-pawn.} 
9. Re1
9. d6 {It might look a bit odd, but moving our pawn just one square is quite a bit more aggressive. Our idea is to reroute our knight round to e5.} 
10. h3
10. Nd7 {White ruled out the g4-route, but we can go this way too. We're not committed to the e5-square either, we might want to hop into c5 to put more pressure on the e4-pawn. We've also made way for our queen to join the action on f6.} 
11. Be3 {Clearly not forced, but quite an illustrative move. White could try to prevent the doubling of their pawns with11.Bd2, but we can then exploit the weakening of the b2-pawn with11...Rb8. It's then not clear how White is going to continue.} 
11. Bxc3 {We don't need to rush with the exchange, but we're now getting a nice double-edged structure.} 
12. bxc3
12. c5 {This is the type of position we're aiming for. It's not that we're better, but we've maintained equality while keeping good winning chances. We'll put pressure on both e4 and c3-pawns with ...Bb7 and ...Qf6.} 
