8. Re8 {The secondary line in terms of popularity. We attack the e-pawn. Keeping the central pawns on the board keeps more life in the game.  I believe our opponents won't feel as comfortable here as in the main lines. White now has to choose how to defend the e-pawn.} 
9. Bg5 {White typically uses this pin to defend indirectly.} 
9. h6 {Let's sideline the bishop.} 
10. Bh4 {Giving us the bishop pair for free would be a mistake. White now threatens f2-f4 so we need to play actively.} 
10. d5 {Now that White's bishop is out of play we can revert to the ...d5 setups. White can no longer swap everything. This setup is fairly rare and wasn't covered in Christof Sielecki's highly regarded Keep It Simple: 1.e4.The main line is to snatch the e-pawn with10...g5and takeon c3 and e4, but I don't like it. In return for the pawn, White gets an initiative.  If you want to keep playing with the pawn on d6, then10...Be7is the most precise. We can follow upwith ...d7-d6 and ...Nd7, when play will be quite similar.} 
11. exd5
11. g5 {We're not giving White another opportunity to capture on f6. The position now becomes quite sharp. The pawn on g5 has obviously weakened our kingside a bit, but we have sufficient control of the center. White's bishop won't be great on g3 either.} 
12. Bg3
12. cxd5 {We've reached the typical Scotch Four Knights structure with the important difference that White no longer has the option of exchanging on f6. The natural f3-square is also ruled out as a roost for White's queen, as ...Bg4 would trap it.} 
13. Nb5 {White almost always targets our c-pawn.} 
13. Ba5 {The bishop does a good job defending the c7-pawn. We're going to force the knight back. If we have time we'll start with ...Bd7 so that we have the c6-square under control.} 
14. Nd4 {White tends to force matters this way. Should White wait with14.c3we'll improve with14...Bd7. We're ready toexpel the knight and then play ...c7-c5.} 
14. Bd7 {We take control of the c6-square and prepare to either push our c-pawn or play ...Bb6.} 
15. Nf5 {This looks scary, but White's only attacking with one piece.} 
15. Bxf5
16. Bxf5
16. Ne4 {Our centralized knight makes our position very safe. We threaten to win material with ...Nd2. Presuming that's dealt with, we'll play ...c7-c6 and ...Qf6. All our pieces are active, and White will have to be careful to maintain equality.} 
