3. Nf6 {We now move on to the Four Knights complex. With a symmetrical position, White can play almost anything, but the main division is between the Spanish Four Knights with4.Bb5and the Scotch Four Knights with4.d4.} 
4. Bb5 {Let's move onto the Spanish Four Knights.} 
4. Bc5 {Black has plenty of choices here. If we want to force a draw, then4...Nd4is probably best, but there are a few forced draw lines and some that are very tedious.  Keeping the symmetry with4...Bb4is also a good option, but I believe this is the most ambitious. White is really forced to act. If we're given time to complete our development and exchange a pair of knights on d4, we're doing well. The critical lines arethose where White captures on e5, and then plays d2-d4 forking our bishop and knight.} 
5. O-O
5. O-O
6. Nxe5 {The critical test. We've seen this theme already, but it's generally considered more accurate for White to include castling.} 
6. Nxe5
7. d4
7. Bd6 {The main approach. We don't want to give White our bishop for free.} 
8. f4 {Critical. White shouldn't rush to regain the piece. Instead, they start taking space.} 
8. Neg4 {There are a few choices where to go with the knight, but this one seems to be the most reliable. If we can recapture on f6 with the knight, then we're very close to controlling the key e4-square.   As we've already castled, dropping back to c6 is no longer so reliable. We're not in time to take control of the f5 and e4-squares. Now White has to decide which knight to go after.} 
9. Be2
9. Bb4 {This is generally the idea. We want the e4-pawn. White again has to decide which knight they want.} 
10. e5
10. d6 {We want to force White into a decision} 
11. exf6
11. Nxf6
12. f5 {As we've already seen, there's a big fight for the f5-square in this variation. Therefore, this must be critical.} 
12. d5 {The pin isn't so scary while we still have our dark-squared bishop on the board, but starting with12...h6is also fine.} 
13. Bg5
13. Be7 {Jurcik-Banusz, Batumi 2019. We block the pin. We'll continue with ...Re8. White is likely to improve their bishop with Bd3 when we can respond with ...Bd7. White cannot win a pawn with Bxf6 and Nxd5, as the d4-pawn also hangs.  As White gets ready on the kingside, we'll break with ...c7-c5, activating our pieces. We have very good long-term chances with our outpost on e4.} 
