3. Bc5 {Of course, there are many options, but when I was looking at playing this with White, this one really bothered me. White can't even successfully transpose into an Italian, as the knight is not yet committed to c6.   If you recall, that knight is often our worst-placed piece in the Italian setups, and we happily spend a couple of tempi to move it. If White does a nothing move then we'll construct a setup with ...d7-d6, ...c7-c6, ...O-O, and ...a7-a5.} 
4. f4 {Playing in true Vienna spirit, but very risky.} 
4. d5 {Our turn to sacrifice a pawn. White is going to have issues with their king. Perhaps White's best is the uninspiring5.Nxd5. Then we'd play5...Nxe4followedby ...Qh4+. White is under a lot of pressure.} 
5. exd5
5. e4 {Our e-pawn is a thorn in White's side. We both prevent the knight from developing to f3 and make it difficult for White to block the g1-a7 diagonal.} 
6. d4
6. exd3
7. Qxd3 {7.cxd3Bg4!followed by ...O-O keeps White from coordinating.} 
7. O-O {...Re8 is coming next.} 
8. Nge2
8. Re8 {We have a lot of pressure for our sacrificed pawn.} 
9. h3 {White fights for control of the g4-square.9.Bd2Ng4was highly unpleasant.} 
9. a6 {We want to open up the queenside. White is not going to find a safe home for the king.} 
