7. Bb5 {This is what Nepo played himself.} 
7. a6 {Forcing White to resolve the tension.} 
8. Bxc6+
8. bxc6 {White still has to do something about the kingside. Taking on f4 still fails to ...g5-g4.} 
9. Qd3 {Nepomniachtchi-Alekseenko, chess.com 2022.} 
9. g4 {Shaw's recommendation appears to refute Ian's try.9...a5with the ideaof ...Ba6 also looks promising. Alekseenko instead went for9...Bg4,but Nepomniachtchi could then safely capture on f4. The bishop got in the way of the usual ...g5-g4 idea.} 
10. Nh4
