4. g5 {We defend our pawn. We have a few transpositions here.5.Bc4h6is covered via the 4.Bc4 move order.5.Nc3Bg7is extremely likely to transpose elsewhere too, for example,6.Bc4h6is back in 4.Bc4, while6.g3will be covered via 5.g3.} 
5. h4 {We've finally made it to the main line. But there's a reason neither John nor Ian wanted to play this way.} 
5. g4 {We have an extra d2-d4 and ...d7-d6 over the 3...g5 main line. That doesn't look so bad for White, but it's actually a big improvement for us. The main line of Ne5 is obviously now impossible.} 
6. Ng1 {The knight is forced to retreat.} 
6. Qf6 {We're in time to hold on to our extra pawn. We'll add more support with ...Bh6 and complete our kingside development with ...Ne7. If we succeed, then not only do we have an extra pawn but White will also struggle to either develop their queenside or defend the d4-pawn.} 
7. Nc3 {7.Ne2Bh6will likely come to the same thing.} 
7. Ne7 {Make sure not to allow the knight to jump into d5.} 
8. Nge2 {White is going to build up maximum pressure on our pawn.8.Qd2Bh69.Nge2is just a transposition.} 
8. Bh6 {We're staking everything on our extra pawn.} 
9. Qd2 {White points everything at our f4-pawn.} 
9. Nbc6 {The pressure on the d4-pawn ensures White can still not regain the pawn.} 
10. g3 {White has succeeded in generating maximum pressure against our pawn.} 
10. Bg7 {But now we switch. The d-pawn is too hard to defend.} 
11. Nb5 {We'd meet11.d5in the same way.} 
11. fxg3 {We needn't defend the c7-pawn yet.} 
12. Nxc7+
12. Kd8
13. Nxa8
13. Qf2+ {With ...g3-g2 next, we'll immediately get one piece for the rook. The knight on a8 will never escape either.} 
