[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. f4 {The King's Gambit. Despite playing 1...e5 for many years, I'm yet to face it in a classical FIDE-rated game.} 
2. exf4 {With the King's Gambit, White sacrifices a pawn to reach a murky complicated position. Let's be a pawn up in the complications!} 
3. Bc4 {The Bishop's Gambit. The choice of players who think merely playing the King's Gambit isn't exciting enough. Perhaps White dreams of playing another Immortal Game.} 
3. Nc6 {This is generally considered the drawback. John Shaw went as far as claiming it as the refutation of 3.Bc4. It's more accurate to start with3...Nc6rather than3...d6, as our bishop might want to develop more actively. We're now very likely to transpose to the 4.Bc4 lines examined in the previous segment.3...Qh4+is perfectly playable and computer-approved, but that type of mess is what White craves.} 
4. Nc3 {Provocative. White is really asking for the check.} 
4. Qh4+ {Here I think we should oblige. Our control of the d4-square turns out to be important.} 
5. Kf1 {Sometimes White is able to play g2-g3 sacrificing another pawn, but here5.g3?fxg36.Nf3fails to6...g2+. We lose our queen for a move, but another one appears on h1.} 
5. Bc5 {The reason behind our move order. We are able to develop and threaten mate. With our knight back on b8 White would be able to react with d2-d4, but now White's obliged to exchange queens.} 
6. Qe2 {Clearly White wants to keep the queens on the board, but now they run into tactical problems.} 
6. Nd4
7. Nf3 {White attempts a tactical defense. Now we could exchange queens, but we have even stronger.} 
7. Nxf3
8. Qxf3
8. Nf6 {We can choose whether to next defend our extra pawn with ...g7-g5 or to transform the material advantage into a violent attack with ...d7-d5. Or both. Either way, we're already more or less winning.} 
