1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. c3 {The Ponziani. Another opening I dabbled with from the White side. White is attempting to play a sort of Alapin or c3-Sicilian. The downside, as against the Sicilian, is White's loss of control of the d5-square.} 
3. d5 {3...Nf6is also fine, but seeing as the intended 4.Bb5? has now been refuted, this feels correct.} 
4. Qa4 {If White wants to play a true Ponziani, then this is what they sadly have to try.} 
4. Bd7 {The Cozio Variation. This one scared me a lot from the White side. Recently4...f6has become the main line, and is recommended in quite a few Chessable courses already.4...Bd7is pretty forcing. Our idea is to exchange a pairof knights with ...Nd4xf3. White will be able to collect a pawn, but their development is very slow. We're going to combine attacking on the kingside with keeping White as passively placed as possible. I see this was even Anatoly Karpov's choice in a game from July 2022.} 
5. exd5 {The whole point was to take the pawn.} 
5. Nd4
6. Qd1 {White has to retreat.} 
6. Nxf3+
7. Qxf3
7. Nf6 {Pushing the f-pawn is tempting, but White can then fight back in the center with d2-d4. For now, we're just going to develop and make it as hard as possible for White to coordinate. One threat is ...Bg4 followed by ...Qxd5.} 
8. Bc4 {White has to try and hold on to the d-pawn, or there wasn't much point.} 
8. b5 {A rare move order, but it's handy to force White's bishop back. Later we'll gain space on the queenside.} 
9. Bb3 {White wants to keep the d5-pawn protected.} 
9. e4 {A further space gain before White has time for d2-d3.} 
10. Qe2
10. Bd6 {Matters are already getting serious. White may have an extra pawn, but all it's doing, for now, is preventing White's light-squared bishop from having a life. The queenside is still dormant.} 
11. d4 {11.d3O-Oisn't helping. White cannot win the pawn as12.dxe4Nxe413.Qxe4?Re8would collect the queen. Castling is scary too, as we'll see. We're going to be quickwith ...Ng4 and ...f7-f5.} 
11. O-O
12. O-O {Logical, but castling is now really scary.} 
12. Ng4 {White has no minor pieces to defend on the kingside.} 
13. g3
13. f5 {We defend the e-pawn. We threaten to crash through with ...f5-f4, but we can also play it slowly. Bringing the queen round to h5 or defending the e-pawn with ...Re8 or ...Nf6 to prepare ...f5-f4. In the meantime, White has zero counterplay.} 
