[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5 {Now, we'll examine a bunch of White gambit lines.} 
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. d4
3. exd4 {Here, the Scotch with4.Nxd4and the Scotch Gambit with4.Bc4are by far White's main options.} 
4. c3 {The Göring Gambit. Delaying the sacrifice for a move is more challenging than the Danish Gambit we will see next.} 
4. d5 {Of course, it's possible to take the pawn too, but I think this is easiest. After all, we don't want to give White what they want. As in the Ponziani, we'll take advantage of the fact that the b1-knight is temporarily deprived of the c3-square.  Another good option is4...Nf6. That's a direct transposition to a Ponziani, but a different variation to the one I recommend.} 
5. exd5
5. Qxd5
6. cxd4 {Taking the pawn is White's only sensible approach.6.Be2might not be so bad, but6...d3is a simple way to defuse it. If White takes with the queen, we'll exchangeand play ...Bg4. Otherwise, we'll put our bishop on e6.} 
6. Bg4 {We should remember bishops before knights here. Wait, that doesn't sound right. Still, we should always react to specific circumstances.Here our mission is to attack the d-pawn and prevent White from easily castling. Starting with6...Bb4+is likely to come to the same thing.} 
7. Be2 {7.Nc3Bb4will simply transpose, while taking on f3 is also playable there.} 
7. Bb4+ {The key move to remember. White should now walk into the pin.} 
8. Nc3
8. Bxf3
9. Bxf3
9. Qc4 {This is our whole point. We're not making it easy for White to castle. Our king is destined for the queenside.} 
10. Bxc6+
10. bxc6 {We want to keep White's king stranded in the center.} 
11. Qe2+ {White's king is in danger; therefore, they tend to exchange queens.} 
11. Qxe2+
12. Kxe2
12. O-O-O {An interesting position, but we're completely fine at the very least. White's d-pawn is more vulnerable than our doubled c-pawns. We'll increase the pressure with ...Ne7-f5 and ...Rhe8.} 
