[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Ruy Lopez Main Line: White breaks the tension"]
[Black "6.Re1 Bd7 − 9.Bxc6 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. O-O
5. d6
6. Re1
6. Bd7 {We need to be accurate with our move order here. First, we break the pin and prepare to recapture on c6 with the bishop.6...g6?!7.Bxc6+bxc68.d4is rather annoying.} 
7. c3 {White needs to prepare to push the d-pawn. The immediate7.d4would fall to the same trick as on the previous move.} 
7. g6 {Time to fianchetto.} 
8. d4
8. Bg7
9. Bxc6 {We should probably check this one first. White sees a tactic that nets a pawn, but we needn't panic. This was actually an old recommendation by the Russian GM, and former FIDE World Champion, Alexander Khalifman. But times move on, and computer engines get much stronger!} 
9. Bxc6 {Recapturing with the bishop was the main reason for the earlier ...Bd7. Not only do we maintain our structure, but we also attack the e4-pawn.} 
10. Qc2 {Defending the e-pawn is too slow.} 
10. O-O {We're now defending the e-pawn tactically.} 
11. dxe5
11. dxe5
12. Nxe5 {That pawn no longer tastes any good.} 
12. Bxe4 {We immediately regain the pawn and have a nice advantage thanks to our bishop pair on the open board.} 
13. Rxe4 {White isn't getting two pieces for the rook.} 
13. Nxe4
14. Qxe4
14. Qd1+ {Oops.} 
