12. Qxc7 {Let's pause for a moment and examine the position. White has an extra pawn. So where does our compensation lie?   Well, we've developed all our pieces, while White still has to figure out what to do with their queenside. Our bishop pair on the open board promises us compensation typical of the Marshall Attack. Finally, the c3-pawn is quite a nuisance for White, especially as they lack a light-squared bishop. Not only does the pawn get in the way of the development of the b1-knight, but also it has chronically weakened the d3-square.} 
13. Qc2 {It's too late for this move to have any effect.} 
13. Rfe8 {We defend the knight. The following game shows how difficult White's position is to play.} 
14. Be3
14. Nd6 {A strong retreat. We're now threatening to capture on f3, and then go after White's remaining bishop with ...Nf5.} 
15. Nd4 {Defending against both threats, but there's a very pretty refutation.} 
15. Bxg2 {Ouch!} 
16. Kxg2
16. Bxd4 {The bishop cannot be taken with either bishop or pawn, as the queen and e1-rook are undefended.} 
