10. h6
11. Bh4 {This pin is the point of White's setup. Capturing on f6 would just give us the bishop pair for free.} 
11. exd4 {We again have a choice between this and11...Qe8, but let's follow Laurent Fressinet. With a knight on d2, White has to be careful to hold onto the d-pawn.} 
12. Nxd4 {Or12.cxd4g5!Releasing the pin, and thereby activating the g7-bishop. Check out the model game, Harikrishna-Fressinet. It's impressive how quickly White's position collapsed, even with such a strong player handling the pieces.} 
12. Nxd4 {We would still like to play against White's center.} 
13. cxd4 {Visually, it looks like White should have a small but stable advantage here, but actually, it's pretty hard to maintain the center. Their minor pieces aren't particularly helpful.} 
13. Bxa4 {Preparing a slightly unusual way to break the pin.} 
14. Qxa4
14. Qd7 {We're happy to offer the queen exchange, as that will simply make it more difficult to defend the center. Once our knight moves, we'll unleash the monster on g7.} 
15. Qxd7 {Probably not the best, but we'll still get strong pressure on White's center after15.Qb3Nh516.Nf3Rfe8. The most pertinent aspect of the position is the relative activity of the bishops.} 
15. Nxd7 {It's not at all easy to hold on to the d-pawn. Should White put their knight on f3, then ...g6-g5-g4 will come, while Nb3 can be met by pushing the a-pawn. White would really like to play Be3, hence why we included ...h7-h6 earlier.} 
