6. Bd7 {We need to be accurate with our move order here. First, we break the pin and prepare to recapture on c6 with the bishop.6...g6?!7.Bxc6+bxc68.d4is rather annoying.} 
7. c3 {White needs to prepare to push the d-pawn. The immediate7.d4would fall to the same trick as on the previous move.} 
7. g6 {Time to fianchetto.} 
8. d4
8. Bg7
9. Bc2 {A decent move, but probably just an alternative move order to the current trend with9.h3O-O10.Bc2.} 
9. O-O {We can try to exploit White's move order with9...exd4followed by 10...Bg4, but let's keep it simple.} 
10. Nbd2 {For10.h3see the relevant chapter, and10.Bg5was covered via9.Bg5O-O10.Bc2.} 
10. exd4 {This capture is strong.} 
11. cxd4
11. Nh5 {Not11...Bg4this time. With White's knight on d2, they can simply respondwith h2-h3. This, on the other hand, is very annoying. We attack the d-pawn and it's not simple to defend.} 
12. d5 {Never a move that White particularly wants. The position is opened for our g7-bishop, while White's one developed on c2 isn't happy. It's blocked in by its own pawns.} 
12. Nb4 {White's center isn't even particularly secure. We can dismantle it with ...c7-c6.} 
13. Bb1
13. a5 {Just make sure we don't lose our knight! Now the knight can drop back to a6. We'll combine putting pressure on the e-pawn with ...Re8 and ...Na6-c5 with a well-timed ...c7-c6. It's still difficult for White to figure out how to complete their development.} 
