[White "4) Ruy Lopez Main Line: White's other sidelines"]
[Black "9.Nbd2 O-O 10.Bxc6 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. O-O
5. d6
6. Re1
6. Bd7 {We need to be accurate with our move order here. First, we break the pin and prepare to recapture on c6 with the bishop.6...g6?!7.Bxc6+bxc68.d4is rather annoying.} 
7. c3 {White needs to prepare to push the d-pawn. The immediate7.d4would fall to the same trick as on the previous move.} 
7. g6 {Time to fianchetto.} 
8. d4
8. Bg7
9. Nbd2 {Developing the knight has to be the most logical move, and it's no surprise that it's historically the main line. But we have a good antidote, and recently the top players have switched to Grandelius' recommendation of9.h3!?We'll examine that later.  Finally, White could try9.Bb3, but after we castle White won't be able to avoid transposing into another line.} 
9. O-O {Our plan is to exchange on d4. If the knight moves from d2 we'll increase the pressure with ...Bg4, perhaps preceded by ...b7-b5 to prevent White from exchanging on c6.   If White keeps the knight on d2, we have ideas of ...Nh5 to open the long diagonal for our bishop. Finally, we also have ideas of annoying White with a ...Nb4 jump, exploiting the weak d3-square.} 
10. Bxc6 {White's driest attempt. It's important to realize this still doesn't win a pawn. However, if you want to bypass this, then9...exd4was a decent move order.} 
10. Bxc6
11. dxe5
11. dxe5 {If you want to keep some life in the game, then11...Nh5is possible, but I don't believe we have full compensation for the pawn.} 
12. Nxe5
12. Bxe4 {This is the key tactic. We immediately regain the pawn due to White's overworked rook.} 
13. Nxe4
13. Qxd1 {White cannot hold onto both their knights. We could also play13...Nxe4. In that case, White wouldn't be able to capture the knight due to the vulnerable back rank.} 
14. Rxd1
14. Nxe4
15. Nd7
15. Rfd8 {The knight is a bit of a nuisance on d7, but we can force it backward with ...Nd6.} 
16. Bf4
16. Rac8 {We simply defend the pawn. We have ideas of forcing the bishop back with ...g6-g5 and ...f7-f5, or simply ...Nd6 to expel White's knight. The position is equal.} 
