7. g6 {Time to fianchetto.} 
8. d4
8. Bg7
9. Nbd2 {Developing the knight has to be the most logical move, and it's no surprise that it's historically the main line. But we have a good antidote, and recently the top players have switched to Grandelius' recommendation of9.h3!?We'll examine that later.  Finally, White could try9.Bb3, but after we castle White won't be able to avoid transposing into another line.} 
9. O-O {Our plan is to exchange on d4. If the knight moves from d2 we'll increase the pressure with ...Bg4, perhaps preceded by ...b7-b5 to prevent White from exchanging on c6.   If White keeps the knight on d2, we have ideas of ...Nh5 to open the long diagonal for our bishop. Finally, we also have ideas of annoying White with a ...Nb4 jump, exploiting the weak d3-square.} 
10. h3 {After navigating White's various alternatives, we've arrived at the old main line. We saw the issues White has if we're allowed to pin the knight, and so White takes a time out to control the g4-square. They're now ready to play Nf1 unimpeded.} 
10. exd4 {This new twist is the reason top White players have switched to playing h2-h3 on the previous move. We're going to claim the knight is misplaced on d2.10...Re8has typically been the main try, when11.Bc2reaches an old main line. I believe this is playable for Black, but a bit worse. We're solid but it's difficult to find an active plan. In that structure, I prefer the rook on f8, as it's easier to support the ...f7-f5 advance.} 
11. cxd4
11. Nb4 {This is the idea. We're getting ready to hop into d3.} 
12. e5 {White's most forcing continuation.} 
12. Bxa4 {We should try to remember the tactics behind the next few moves.} 
13. Qxa4
