14. Ne4
14. dxe5 {The right time for this pawn exchange. We both weaken the e-pawn and prepare to push our c-pawn.} 
15. dxe5
15. c5 {I really like this dynamic plan. We're advancing on the queenside in an effort to claim the d3-square as an outpost.It is possible to win the e5-pawn with15...Nd3, but I think it's too risky. After16.Rd1, we're in a pretty horrible pin.} 
16. Bg5 {Developing with tempo strikes me as the most natural try.} 
16. Qc7 {Our plan is unchanged.} 
17. Nf6+ {Let's just make sure we're ready against White's most aggressive move.} 
17. Bxf6 {We'd prefer to keep this bishop, but not if it's caged in on h8.} 
18. exf6
18. b5
19. Qd1 {White has to keep an eye on the c2-square, and giving us a bonus ...c5-c4 doesn't make any sense.} 
19. Rad8 {Eyeing the queen, and preparing to capture on f6.} 
20. a3 {White prepares to sacrifice their queen.20.Nh2!?is tricky. White is attempting to activate the knight via g4. I think20...h5, taking that g4-square under control, is simplest, but20...Qc621.Ng4h5also looks fine.} 
20. Nxf6 {We bravely get rid of the pawn.} 
21. Qxd8 {The most accurate way to do it. White needs one of our pieces on d8 so that we're pinned.} 
21. Qxd8
22. axb4 {For now, we have a big material advantage with queen and pawn for rook and bishop, but our knight is rather precarious.} 
22. h6 {So this is important. We're happy to give back one pawn to escape the pin.} 
23. Rad1
23. hxg5 {We return our extra material to reach a level endgame.} 
24. Rxd8
24. Rxd8
25. bxc5
25. Rc8 {That passed pawn is firmly under control.} 
