6. Bd7 {We need to be accurate with our move order here. First, we break the pin and prepare to recapture on c6 with the bishop.6...g6?!7.Bxc6+bxc68.d4is rather annoying.} 
7. c3 {White needs to prepare to push the d-pawn. The immediate7.d4would fall to the same trick as on the previous move.} 
7. g6 {Time to fianchetto.} 
8. d4
8. Bg7
9. Nbd2 {Developing the knight has to be the most logical move, and it's no surprise that it's historically the main line. But we have a good antidote, and recently the top players have switched to Grandelius' recommendation of9.h3!?We'll examine that later.  Finally, White could try9.Bb3, but after we castle White won't be able to avoid transposing into another line.} 
9. O-O {Our plan is to exchange on d4. If the knight moves from d2 we'll increase the pressure with ...Bg4, perhaps preceded by ...b7-b5 to prevent White from exchanging on c6.   If White keeps the knight on d2, we have ideas of ...Nh5 to open the long diagonal for our bishop. Finally, we also have ideas of annoying White with a ...Nb4 jump, exploiting the weak d3-square.} 
10. h3 {After navigating White's various alternatives, we've arrived at the old main line. We saw the issues White has if we're allowed to pin the knight, and so White takes a time out to control the g4-square. They're now ready to play Nf1 unimpeded.} 
10. exd4 {This new twist is the reason top White players have switched to playing h2-h3 on the previous move. We're going to claim the knight is misplaced on d2.10...Re8has typically been the main try, when11.Bc2reaches an old main line. I believe this is playable for Black, but a bit worse. We're solid but it's difficult to find an active plan. In that structure, I prefer the rook on f8, as it's easier to support the ...f7-f5 advance.} 
11. cxd4
11. Nb4 {This is the idea. We're getting ready to hop into d3.} 
12. Bxd7 {Almost exclusively played.} 
12. Qxd7 {I've previously recaptured with the knight,12...Nxd7, but that allows White to consolidate their position with13.Nb3. Here13.Nb3wouldn't make any sense, as we have too much pressure on the e-pawn. We can simply react with13...Rfe8, while even13...Qa4is interesting.  We've reached a very interesting position. Were White's knight on c3, they would have a pleasant advantage. As it is, White finds it difficult to complete their development. If it was our turn we'd play...Nd3. White has tried a few different ways to prevent it.} 
13. Qb3 {By far the most common move, and the most logical. White prevents ...Nd3, and gains time.} 
13. a5 {We support the knight. It's useful to have ...a5-a4 later. If White waits we have a few ideas, ...Qc6 is probably our primary threat. We threaten ...Nc2 to fork the rooks. We're very happy if White pushes their d-pawn. The e4-pawn becomes a long-term weakness, and we have a fantastic bishop.} 
14. a3 {White always expels our knight.} 
14. Nc6 {We're ready to win control of the light squares with ...a5-a4. The b7-pawn is currently poisoned, as the queen wouldn't escape.} 
15. d5
15. Nb8 {A pawn sacrifice, but our knight will be wonderful on c5.15...Na7is more complex, but I think White has chances to be better there.} 
16. Qxb7 {Grabbing the pawn has to be critical, and has been chosen by everyone so far.} 
16. Na6 {White has to be careful with their queen, while the e-pawn remains a liability.} 
17. e5 {We should check this forcing try too.} 
17. dxe5 {There's nothing wrong with17...Nc5either, which will simply transpose to 17.Qc6 after18.Qc6.} 
18. Nxe5
18. Qxd5
19. Nc6 {A rather odd-looking setup.} 
19. Kh8 {Getting out of the way of any Ne7+ business. We're threatening to trap the queen with ...Rfb8. White will have to play extremely accurately to maintain equality.} 
