11. a4 {Extremely rare, but this is Nils Grandelius' recommendation. I think it's the major test of our entire strategy. The good news − we're not refuted, and your opponents will only play this way if they've studied that course. I just want to warn you that the following lines are incredibly complicated.   Even though this move is rare, I've chosen to analyze it deeply.  Nils explains White's reasoning well. White wants to develop the knight to c4 without being hit by ...b7-b5. It's also something of a high-class waiting move. As we're getting ready to play ...f7-f5, putting the bishop on e3 would just put it in the line of fire.As Grandelius observes, the immediate11.Na3can be met by11...b5, when the knight doesn't have anything better to do than retreat.} 
