[Black "10.Bc2 Nh5 11.a4 #7"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. O-O
5. d6
6. Re1
6. Bd7 {We need to be accurate with our move order here. First, we break the pin and prepare to recapture on c6 with the bishop.6...g6?!7.Bxc6+bxc68.d4is rather annoying.} 
7. c3 {White needs to prepare to push the d-pawn. The immediate7.d4would fall to the same trick as on the previous move.} 
7. g6 {Time to fianchetto.} 
8. d4
8. Bg7
9. h3 {A very sophisticated move. This is Nils Grandelius' recommendation in his Grand Ruy Lopez course.   We've seen the issues White has faced. If the knight isn't on d2, then ...Bg4 was a real nuisance, while with the knight on d2, White has issues defending the d4-pawn and parrying our knight jump into d3.  Therefore, White takes a prophylactic time-out now to try and quell our activity. Needless to say, your opponents will only choose this move if they're well booked up.} 
9. O-O
10. Bc2 {Another highly sophisticated move. White is trying to reach the old main line while avoiding the plan we analyzed previously.10.Nbd2would be a direct transposition there.} 
10. Nh5 {I agree with Nils that this is Black's strongest. Firstly, we increase the pressure on the d-pawn. This prevents White from playing an immediate Nbd2. Secondly, we're getting ready for the thematic King's Indian break with ...f7-f5.   White's last couple of moves prevented our ...exd4 plan, but they were slow and neglected development. The pawn on h3 might also turn out to be a hook for our attack. Therefore, I think our aggression is justified.10...Re8is the main line. I think White should be a little better, but it's playable of course. You have to be very patient, and wait to see how White develops. However, we are very solid and all the pieces remain on the board, so it's a decent try to slowly outplay your opponent.If you're looking for a less forcing route, then I think10...a5!?is a good alternative. It was recently played by the strong GM Kiril Alekseenko. We're extremely flexible. The main idea is to grab space on the queenside, but we're ready to hop back to our kingside play too.} 
11. a4 {Extremely rare, but this is Nils Grandelius' recommendation. I think it's the major test of our entire strategy. The good news − we're not refuted, and your opponents will only play this way if they've studied that course. I just want to warn you that the following lines are incredibly complicated.   Even though this move is rare, I've chosen to analyze it deeply.  Nils explains White's reasoning well. White wants to develop the knight to c4 without being hit by ...b7-b5. It's also something of a high-class waiting move. As we're getting ready to play ...f7-f5, putting the bishop on e3 would just put it in the line of fire.As Grandelius observes, the immediate11.Na3can be met by11...b5, when the knight doesn't have anything better to do than retreat.} 
11. Qe8 {Getting our pieces in order. We need to keep an eye on our h5-knight before playing ...f7-f5. This is because we want to recapture on f5 with the g-pawn. Before ...Qe8, we would then have had a hanging knight.} 
12. Na3 {We'll keep Nils' recommendation as our primary line here.} 
12. f5 {Here comes the counterplay.} 
13. Nc4
13. fxe4 {13...f4and going for the pawn storm is good fun, but Grandelius demonstrates a narrow path for White to be better.  I still think it's a decent shot, especially at quicker time controls, but now we're focusing on proving the viability of this line as a true lifetime repertoire! And don't worry. The lines we're examining here remain fascinating and double-edged. First of all, we're opening up the f-file towards White's king.} 
14. Bxe4 {The more natural recapture. This was essayed in a correspondence game from 2021.} 
14. Qf7 {Our queen is a bit precarious on the e-file so let's move it. Apart from the immediate hit on the c4-knight, we also have ideas of capturing twice on d4 to open the f-file.} 
15. dxe5 {White defends the knight tactically.} 
15. Be6 {We prevent an embarrassing Bd5, and renew the threat to White's king. Nils gave up to here as an explanation as to why he preferred the other capture on e4.} 
16. Bxc6 {Hardly the first move that comes to mind, but another critical try. In general, White's moves are much harder to find than ours here. White doesn't want to allow ...Nxe5.} 
16. bxc6
17. Na5 {Another move that doesn't strike me as the most natural. Playing White here I'd be rather concerned about my king's safety. Nevertheless, this is White's only challenging try.  Instead, retreating with17.Ncd2isn't worrying. One option would be to recapture immediately with17...dxe5. We would have an ugly structure,but with ...Rad8 coming next, we'll have very active pieces. My choice would probablybe17...Rae8!?sacrificing the pawn but keeping our structure; ...Bxe5 would be a threat, while ...Nf4 is also going to be tough to deal with.} 
17. Bd5 {We defend the c6-pawn, and prepare to capture on e5.} 
18. exd6 {White has gone too far. They can't go back to playing natural moves now.18.e6is a better alternative, but we still have good pressure after18...Bxe619.Nxc6Rae8. All our pieces are pointing towards White's king, while White remains with a problem of lack of coordination.} 
18. cxd6 {White is a pawn up, but that's where the good news stops. We can capture on f3 whenever we'd like. Also, keep an eye out to exploit the undefended a5-knight. Capturing on f3 followed by ...Qc7 would attack both queen and knight.} 
