17. Ncxe5 {This is where Nils leaves it. White does indeed have sufficient compensation for their modest investment (exchange for a pawn), thanks to that powerful knight on e5, but I believe our position to be fully playable too.} 
17. Nf6 {The knight has fulfilled its purpose. We now want to stick our knight on e4. We'll do that by defending the d5-pawn either with ...c7-c6 or ...Be6.} 
18. Bf4 {This feels like the most natural move to me. The bishop controls some central squares. It also makes use of the hidey-hole on h2.} 
18. c6 {Now White isn't bringing the bishop to the a3-f8 diagonal, we can support the d5-pawn this way.} 
19. Qd2
19. Qe7 {Making space for our rook to develop. We'll probably play ...Ne4 next. Apologies for going so deeply into such a rare line, but Nils Grandelius is a well-respected theoretician, having been in Magnus Carlsen's camp during World Championship matches, as well as a strong GM in his own right. Therefore, we have to take his recommendations extremely seriously.} 
