17. Kh8 {We cannot take the bishop yet, due to Ng5+, but White shouldn't forget about the other hanging minor piece.} 
18. Ncd2
18. Bh6 {We force the bishop to retreat and prepare our own breakthrough.} 
19. Bd3
19. Bxh3 {If we gave White enough time to shore up their king's safety, then we would be a little worse due to our looser king. Instead, it's our turn! The main point of our capture is that it will be difficult for White to maintain their knight on f3.} 
20. gxh3
20. Rg8+ {Unfortunately, we cannot yet take on d2, as White would recapture with the queen and threaten a nasty check on h6.} 
21. Kh1
21. Raf8 {Bringing all our pieces to the party. It's rather difficult for White's queenside pieces to join the fray. If White sits, then our knight will hop round to f4.} 
22. Be2 {White's best try. Overprotecting the f3-knight allows the other to move.} 
22. Qf5 {We're aiming for the e4-square. Other routes were also available.} 
23. Qf1
23. Bxd2 {Let's get rid of that knight before it moves.} 
24. Bxd2
24. Qe4 {A powerful square for our queen. We're ready to regain most of our material with ...Rxf3. White is able to defend it with25.Qd1, but then they're back to being stuck. We should activate our final piece with25...Na5, intending a jump into b3 or c4.  We'll still be a pawn down, but White continues having problems with their king. I continued pretty deeply here. We have sufficient resources even against a perfect defense.} 
