10. Nh5 {I agree with Nils that this is Black's strongest. Firstly, we increase the pressure on the d-pawn. This prevents White from playing an immediate Nbd2. Secondly, we're getting ready for the thematic King's Indian break with ...f7-f5.   White's last couple of moves prevented our ...exd4 plan, but they were slow and neglected development. The pawn on h3 might also turn out to be a hook for our attack. Therefore, I think our aggression is justified.10...Re8is the main line. I think White should be a little better, but it's playable of course. You have to be very patient, and wait to see how White develops. However, we are very solid and all the pieces remain on the board, so it's a decent try to slowly outplay your opponent.If you're looking for a less forcing route, then I think10...a5!?is a good alternative. It was recently played by the strong GM Kiril Alekseenko. We're extremely flexible. The main idea is to grab space on the queenside, but we're ready to hop back to our kingside play too.} 
11. Be3 {Overwhelmingly the main move played in practice, but now our ...f7-f5 breaks will come with added power.} 
11. Qe8 {With the bishop on e3, we'll likely need both ...Qe8 and ...Kh8 as preparatory moves before playing the ...f7-f5 break. Otherwise, our f8-rook might get embarrassed. Therefore,11...Kh8is also fine, and will generally transpose.} 
12. Nbd2
12. Kh8 {Now we're ready to start our counterplay. Quite a few games have reached this far, but a consensus hasn't been reached as to how White should continue. However, we're playing ...f7-f5 against almost everything.Note that12...f5?!is premature, but it's useful to know why.13.exf5gxf514.dxe5dxe515.Bc5!The move we always have to be ready for.15...Rf616.Nxe5!This is the problem. White's pieces are too active and,with Bd4 coming, we're caught in a couple of horrible pins. We can't simply block with a later ...Re6, as Bb3 brings another pin. With our king on h8, Bb3 won't be a problem.} 
13. Nc4 {The same square for the knight as chosen by Grandelius, albeit via a different route. Rare, but objectively I think this is White's best try after 11.Be3. However, White does have to be willing to undevelop with Bc1! in many positions.  White has two ideas. One is to reroute the knight to d5 via e3. The other is to exploit Nxe5 tactics after the center opens with ...f7-f5.} 
13. f5 {The most consistent. As White does not yet have any direct threat, we have lots of options. My favorite of the others is the mysterious13...Rc8!?The point is to have the c7-pawn defended once the white knight lands on d5.} 
14. exf5 {We have to be careful here, as there are a lot of tactics lying just under the surface.} 
14. gxf5 {Generally, we like these pawns, but here White has a strong tactic.} 
15. dxe5
15. dxe5
16. Nfxe5 {Our center collapses.} 
16. Nxe5
17. Nxe5
17. Bxe5 {The queen is needed to defend h5 and d7, but now we're in a horrible pin.} 
18. Bd4 {Please don't let this happen to you.} 
