12. Kh8 {Now we're ready to start our counterplay. Quite a few games have reached this far, but a consensus hasn't been reached as to how White should continue. However, we're playing ...f7-f5 against almost everything.Note that12...f5?!is premature, but it's useful to know why.13.exf5gxf514.dxe5dxe515.Bc5!The move we always have to be ready for.15...Rf616.Nxe5!This is the problem. White's pieces are too active and,with Bd4 coming, we're caught in a couple of horrible pins. We can't simply block with a later ...Re6, as Bb3 brings another pin. With our king on h8, Bb3 won't be a problem.} 
13. Nc4 {The same square for the knight as chosen by Grandelius, albeit via a different route. Rare, but objectively I think this is White's best try after 11.Be3. However, White does have to be willing to undevelop with Bc1! in many positions.  White has two ideas. One is to reroute the knight to d5 via e3. The other is to exploit Nxe5 tactics after the center opens with ...f7-f5.} 
13. a5 {White has no threat, so we can get away with fighting for some queenside squares. However, the real idea is that it turns out to control of the a5-square is really important in the tactical melee after ...f7-f5. Clearly, this is a lot less forcing than the immediate13...f5.} 
14. a4 {The automatic response. White prevents the pawn from advancing further. This is also Leela's recommendation.} 
14. f5 {Here we go.} 
15. exf5 {Let's see the real difference now that both a-pawns have moved.} 
15. e4 {This is bad with the pawn back on a6, but best here. We'll see why in a moment.} 
16. d5 {Allowing us to play ...gxf5 would be pretty disastrous.} 
16. exf3
17. dxc6
17. Bxc6
18. Bg5
18. Qf7 {Here we're doing well. We're attacking the knight. Once that moves, we'll play ...gxf5 and then attack down the g-file. However, had we tried this with the pawn back on a6, then Na5! would have been really annoying, attacking our powerful bishop. Of course, I think it's impossible to envisage this nuance back on move 13.} 
