13. a5 {White has no threat, so we can get away with fighting for some queenside squares. However, the real idea is that it turns out to control of the a5-square is really important in the tactical melee after ...f7-f5. Clearly, this is a lot less forcing than the immediate13...f5.} 
14. Bc1 {Another move where you'd just have to doff your cap to your opponent. I really can't imagine anyone willingly playing this as White, even if they'd prepared this really deeply. Against14.dxe5, we should react with14...Nxe5, as after capturing with the pawn15.Ba4is a bit unpleasant.White can't switch the order around though, as14.Ba4allows14...Nxd4!We attack the bishop on a4 and threaten to capture on f3 with check.} 
14. b6 {A modest move, just solidifying the queenside a bit. Once again we have plenty of options,14...a4is also reasonable for instance.However, we have to hold off with ...f7-f5, as White would be able to exchange all the central pawns followed by Nfxe5!, exploiting the pin along the e-file. Therefore, it's not so easy for either side to improve. If White waits, then ...Rd8 or ...Rc8 is a slight improvement.} 
15. Ne3
15. f5 {With pressure taken off the e5-square, we can now get back to business.} 
16. Nd5
16. Rc8 {A complicated double-edged position. One plan is ...Nf6 to both challenge White's central knight and to threaten ...Nxe4. The other is to close off the kingside with ...f5-f4, followed by ...g6-g5 and attack!} 
