6. Re1
6. Bd7 {We need to be accurate with our move order here. First, we break the pin and prepare to recapture on c6 with the bishop.6...g6?!7.Bxc6+bxc68.d4is rather annoying.} 
7. c3 {White needs to prepare to push the d-pawn. The immediate7.d4would fall to the same trick as on the previous move.} 
7. g6 {Time to fianchetto.} 
8. d4
8. Bg7
9. h3 {A very sophisticated move. This is Nils Grandelius' recommendation in his Grand Ruy Lopez course.   We've seen the issues White has faced. If the knight isn't on d2, then ...Bg4 was a real nuisance, while with the knight on d2, White has issues defending the d4-pawn and parrying our knight jump into d3.  Therefore, White takes a prophylactic time-out now to try and quell our activity. Needless to say, your opponents will only choose this move if they're well booked up.} 
9. O-O
10. Bc2 {Another highly sophisticated move. White is trying to reach the old main line while avoiding the plan we analyzed previously.10.Nbd2would be a direct transposition there.} 
10. Nh5 {I agree with Nils that this is Black's strongest. Firstly, we increase the pressure on the d-pawn. This prevents White from playing an immediate Nbd2. Secondly, we're getting ready for the thematic King's Indian break with ...f7-f5.   White's last couple of moves prevented our ...exd4 plan, but they were slow and neglected development. The pawn on h3 might also turn out to be a hook for our attack. Therefore, I think our aggression is justified.10...Re8is the main line. I think White should be a little better, but it's playable of course. You have to be very patient, and wait to see how White develops. However, we are very solid and all the pieces remain on the board, so it's a decent try to slowly outplay your opponent.If you're looking for a less forcing route, then I think10...a5!?is a good alternative. It was recently played by the strong GM Kiril Alekseenko. We're extremely flexible. The main idea is to grab space on the queenside, but we're ready to hop back to our kingside play too.} 
11. Be3 {Overwhelmingly the main move played in practice, but now our ...f7-f5 breaks will come with added power.} 
11. Qe8 {With the bishop on e3, we'll likely need both ...Qe8 and ...Kh8 as preparatory moves before playing the ...f7-f5 break. Otherwise, our f8-rook might get embarrassed. Therefore,11...Kh8is also fine, and will generally transpose.} 
12. Nbd2
12. Kh8 {Now we're ready to start our counterplay. Quite a few games have reached this far, but a consensus hasn't been reached as to how White should continue. However, we're playing ...f7-f5 against almost everything.Note that12...f5?!is premature, but it's useful to know why.13.exf5gxf514.dxe5dxe515.Bc5!The move we always have to be ready for.15...Rf616.Nxe5!This is the problem. White's pieces are too active and,with Bd4 coming, we're caught in a couple of horrible pins. We can't simply block with a later ...Re6, as Bb3 brings another pin. With our king on h8, Bb3 won't be a problem.} 
13. Bb3 {A very odd-looking move considering the bishop just went to c2, but we actually transpose to a few games. They started as d3-Lopezes, with White playing d3-d4 last move.} 
13. f5 {Continuing normally.13...Rd8!?has also been tried, and looks absolutely fine. White has to exchange now, or the e3-bishop will be in a lot of trouble.} 
14. exf5
14. gxf5 {We always like to recapture with the pawn, unless there's a tactical justification not to, for example a Nxe5 hit.} 
15. dxe5
15. dxe5
16. Bc5
16. Rf6 {Forced, as White has their bishop covering the g8-square. This position has been reached three times, with grandmasters playing White in everyone. Twice they've attempted to refute our opening outright (extremely unsuccessfully).} 
17. Nxe5 {Despite Leela's initial blessing, this simply doesn't work.} 
17. Nxe5 {Ok you've got a nice pin, but we are a piece up. Show us what you've got.} 
18. Bd4 {White's best try.18.Nc4?!Re6!was seen in David-Vlachos, Port-Marly 2022. White's compensation for the piece was a solitary pawn.} 
18. Rg6 {As the e6-square is still controlled, we should go this way. This time White will actually regain their piece, but the price will be too high. Note that our h5-knight is not really hanging, as we can meet19.Qxh5with19...Rxg2+followed by capturing their queen.} 
19. Bxe5
19. Bxe5
20. Nf3 {Durarbayli-Sanal, chess.com 2018. Quite an important position. White has found a way to trap us along the e-file. There's no escape for the bishop, so will we just be a pawn down?} 
20. Rxg2+ {Nope! It's our turn, and our attack is decisive.} 
21. Kxg2
21. Nf4+ {White has four squares to choose from, but the king won't survive on any of them.} 
22. Kh2 {22.Kg1is the simplest to refute. Simply22...Qg6+and mate on g2. But unsurprisingly, walking into the bishop's firing line won't save White either.} 
22. Qh5
23. Ng1 {The only way to defend the h3-pawn.} 
23. Qh4 {Now we threaten mate with ...Qxf2+ and ...Qg2.} 
24. Qf3
24. Bd6 {A calm move keeping our bishop. Our threat is 25...Nxh3+ with a discovered check. The white king can't run, as25.Kh1Bc6collects the queen.} 
