6. Bd7 {We've spent a lot of time on the main move of7.c3, but White has a few other options.} 
7. c4 {This is one of White's more serious tries. They want to play d2-d4 without allowing our Noah's Ark trap of ...b7-b5, exchange on d4, and ...c7-c5-c4, trapping the bishop.} 
7. Bg4 {Moving the bishop a second time looks strange, but White's last was a big concession. The fight is all about the d4-square now that White cannot play c4-c3.I played7...Be7myself,but I don't want to allow the option of capturing on c6, Nc3, and d2-d4. It's not the end of the world, but we're a bit passive. With the pawn on c4 White has an improved version of the lines we'll see after7.Bxc6.} 
8. Qb3 {An unusual move I witnessed in the Spanish League in 2022. White escapes the pin and attacks the b7-pawn.} 
8. Rb8 {Simply defending the pawn.} 
9. d4 {Otherwise, there was little logic to White's previous. In Ayats Llobera-Alekseenko, Linares 2022, Black erred with9...Nd7?when he was under a lot of pressure after10.d5. That c6-knight didn't have a good square.} 
9. Bxf3 {The correct reaction. Now we're ready to capture on d4.} 
10. Qxf3 {10.d5fails immediately to10...Bxe4!10.Bxc6is a better try, but we'll be able to take the pawn on d4 after the exchanges.} 
10. b5 {Escaping the pin. We'll take that big d-pawn for free.} 
