[White "7) Ruy Lopez 6.Re1: White's sidelines"]
[Black "6.Re1 Bd7 7.Bxc6 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. O-O
5. d6
6. Re1
6. Bd7 {We've spent a lot of time on the main move of7.c3, but White has a few other options.} 
7. Bxc6 {This is the most direct route to achieve d2-d4.} 
7. Bxc6 {Compared to6.Bxc6+, we can now recapture with the bishop.} 
8. d4 {Starting with8.Nc3Be7will come to the same thing.White's whole point is to play d2-d4, otherwise, they've given up the bishop for free.} 
8. Be7 {We have to develop quickly here; unfortunately, there's no time for the fianchetto.} 
9. Nc3 {Defending the e-pawn, and preparing to capture on e5.} 
9. exd4
10. Nxd4 {The much more active recapture. Taking with the queen would put no pressure on us at all. Just castle and then ...Re8, ...Nd7, and ...Bf6.} 
10. Bd7 {Controlling the f5-square and preventing the Nxc6 exchange. The game pans out a bit differently in this line than in most of the opening. The structure reminds me of an old-fashioned Philidor with ...exd4. There White's usually a little better, but Black remains solid.   This is a much better version for us as we've already nabbed that light-squared bishop. Still, play will proceed a bit more slowly. We should make sure White can't get anywhere on the kingside, and then I like advancing on the queenside with ...b7-b5 and ...c7-c5.    If you're worried that the drawing margin is too high be sure to check out the model game Kulaots-Van Foreest.} 
11. Qf3 {White tends to need this move to make any sense of their position. The knight is now supported should it jump into f5. White starting with a different move order won't alter our plan.} 
11. O-O {White has tried a wide range of moves here, generally, a sign that they're not particularly happy anywhere. One plan is to gain space with ...b7-b5 and ...c7-c5, and the other is to erect a solid position with ...Re8 and ...c7-c6.} 
12. Nf5 {The most direct route.} 
12. Bxf5 {That knight is a bit scary. Let's just remove it from the board.} 
13. exf5 {Aggressive, but a bit ugly White wants to throw their g-pawn towards our king. Such an approach is obviously risky but13.Qxf5Re8gets White nowhere.We'll continue with ...c7-c6 and ...Qc7. We'll see similar positions later in the chapter.} 
13. c6 {We defend the pawn and prepare ...d6-d5.} 
14. g4 {The only consistent continuation. Heberla-Gumularz, Warsaw 2021 now saw14...Nd7, but I think we should embrace the chaos.} 
14. d5 {Following the old adage of dealing with a flank attack by playing in the center. Playing14...Re8also looks fine.} 
15. g5
15. Ne8 {Our knight is temporarily pushed back, but it will resurface on d6.} 
16. h4
16. Nd6 {We'll challenge on the e-file with ...Re8 and ...Bf8. Our plan is simply to exchange the pieces as any endgame will be fantastic. The dream would be the king and pawn endgame. We're able to generate a passed pawn on the queenside, while White's 4 vs. 3 on the kingside will be useless.} 
17. f6 {We should check White's most forcing path, but this liquidates to a level position.} 
17. gxf6 {Now White needs to continue forcefully, or we'll simply have an extra pawn.} 
18. Rxe7
18. Qxe7
19. gxf6 {This looks scary but it's all under control.} 
19. Qe1+
20. Kg2
20. Kh8 {Preventing mate on g7.} 
21. Bh6 {White has to go all in.} 
21. Qxa1 {21...Qe5should also end in some sort of repetition. This looks very scary, but the queen and bishop won't be enough to mate us.} 
22. Qg4
22. Ne8 {We cover the vital g7-square. White's knight is unable to join the attack, so the position is just a draw.} 
23. Bg7+
23. Kg8
24. Bh6+
24. Kh8 {And a draw can be agreed.} 
