6. Bd7 {We've spent a lot of time on the main move of7.c3, but White has a few other options.} 
7. d3 {The most serious of White's alternatives. This is a tricky transposition to the d3-Spanish. It's not a direct transposition, as we've already committed our bishop to d7. Still, it certainly isn't the end of the world. Most of the time White will sooner or later play d3-d4, when we transpose to our typical positions, often a tempo up.} 
7. g6 {We can't yet go after the bishop, as after7...b58.Bb3Na5, White is able to open up the center before we're ready with9.d4.} 
8. d4 {This looks like it just loses a tempo, but White is hoping that ...g7-g6 turns out to be a weakness.} 
8. Bg7 {The 'trap' with ...b7-b5 and ...Nxd4 no longer works so well as we would need to block the e-file with our bishop. Then g6 would turn out to be a weakness. But instead, we can play our usual stuff.} 
9. d5 {The alternative would be to defend the pawn with c2-c3, but then White would definitely be a tempo down.} 
9. Ne7
10. Bxd7+
10. Nxd7
11. c4
11. h6 {A funny transposition to 9.d5 which we investigated back in the 'White immediately breaks the tension' chapter. White lost a tempo here with the d-pawn but gained it back by moving the c-pawn to c4 in one go.} 
