5. d6
6. Re1
6. Bd7 {We've spent a lot of time on the main move of7.c3, but White has a few other options.} 
7. d3 {The most serious of White's alternatives. This is a tricky transposition to the d3-Spanish. It's not a direct transposition, as we've already committed our bishop to d7. Still, it certainly isn't the end of the world. Most of the time White will sooner or later play d3-d4, when we transpose to our typical positions, often a tempo up.} 
7. g6 {We can't yet go after the bishop, as after7...b58.Bb3Na5, White is able to open up the center before we're ready with9.d4.} 
8. c3 {If White wants to play a d3-setup then this will be necessary eventually. Otherwise, once we make sure our king is safe, we'll play ...b7-b5 and ...Na5 and grab that bishop.} 
8. Bg7 {Here9.d4?!O-Owould just reach the main lines a tempo down. Against most of White's other setups, I recommend castling and playing ...Qe8. Not only is this an efficient route to playing our ...f7-f5 break, but it also contains a hidden trick.} 
9. h3 {Grandelius' recommended move order via his alternative move order with5.d3.} 
9. O-O {We have a few possible setups, but to make it easier I'll be recommending following with ...Qe8 against practically any setup. The move orders are quite confusing here, so it pays to have a consistent strategy.} 
10. Nbd2
10. Qe8 {Our plan is to play ...Kh8, ...Nh5, and ...f7-f5.} 
11. Nf1
11. Kh8 {We're ready to meet12.Ng3with12...Ng8and12.Ne3with12...Nh5. We'll see later that White's knight is really misplaced on g3. We don't want to make it too easy to exchange it.} 
