[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Ruy Lopez − 6.c3"]
[Black "6.c3 Bd7 7.Qe2 #1 | Informational 8...Bg7"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. O-O
5. d6 {So far we've been focussing on 6. Re1. From this chapter onwards we'll investigate White's early alternatives.} 
6. c3 {We'll start with White's other major line. As Kramnik observes in his excellent Understanding Chess Openings series, this used to be considered best, but nowadays Black is fine.   I'm going to suggest playing in a typical fashion, but I'll try to explain the additional options allowed for both sides.} 
6. Bd7 {Once again it's important to start with this before playing ...g7-g6 otherwise, Bxc6+ and d2-d4 is a bit unpleasant. White overwhelmingly plays7.Re1here, which is simply a transposition to the lines we've just examined.7.d3is possible, but we'll carry out the same plan we used against6.Re1Bd77.d3.We'll play our usual moves with ...g7-g6, ...Bg7, ...O-O, ...Qe8, and if necessary ...Kh8.   White will run out of constructive moves without playing Re1. Once they do we'll almost certainly have a direct transposition. If White instead plays d3-d4, they'll be a tempo down on the usual Steinitz Deferred positions.} 
7. Qe2 {The Worrall Attack approach. Generally, the rook is better placed on the e-file than the queen. If the center opens, the queen is going to do a terrible job of guarding the e-pawn. However, this is playable with a concrete idea.} 
7. g6 {Keeping loyal to our structure. There's nothing wrong with7...Be7.} 
8. d4
8. Bg7 {The automatic move. This is playable, but I think we're a bit worse in a passive position.} 
9. Bxc6
9. Bxc6
10. dxe5
10. Nxe4 {We've already examined this position with the queen back on d1 and rook on e1. That one is completely fine for us, but here White has an extra option.} 
11. Nd4 {With the queen back on d1, we had11...dxe5!here,followed by exchanging queens on d1 to drive the rook off the e-file. That's not an option here.Not11.exd6O-O!when we have fantastic compensation for the pawn.} 
11. d5 {I don't think this position is the end of the world, but White's a bit better in a Scotch Gambit-type position, and I struggle to see where our counterplay is coming from. Let's avoid it.} 
