4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. O-O
5. d6 {So far we've been focussing on 6. Re1. From this chapter onwards we'll investigate White's early alternatives.} 
6. c3 {We'll start with White's other major line. As Kramnik observes in his excellent Understanding Chess Openings series, this used to be considered best, but nowadays Black is fine.   I'm going to suggest playing in a typical fashion, but I'll try to explain the additional options allowed for both sides.} 
