2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. O-O
5. d6 {So far we've been focussing on 6. Re1. From this chapter onwards we'll investigate White's early alternatives.} 
6. c3 {We'll start with White's other major line. As Kramnik observes in his excellent Understanding Chess Openings series, this used to be considered best, but nowadays Black is fine.   I'm going to suggest playing in a typical fashion, but I'll try to explain the additional options allowed for both sides.} 
6. Bd7 {Once again it's important to start with this before playing ...g7-g6 otherwise, Bxc6+ and d2-d4 is a bit unpleasant. White overwhelmingly plays7.Re1here, which is simply a transposition to the lines we've just examined.7.d3is possible, but we'll carry out the same plan we used against6.Re1Bd77.d3.We'll play our usual moves with ...g7-g6, ...Bg7, ...O-O, ...Qe8, and if necessary ...Kh8.   White will run out of constructive moves without playing Re1. Once they do we'll almost certainly have a direct transposition. If White instead plays d3-d4, they'll be a tempo down on the usual Steinitz Deferred positions.} 
7. Bc2 {A more serious try. White defends the e-pawn and prepares to advance d2-d4. This is highly likely to transpose to the trendy 9.h3 main line.} 
7. g6
8. d4
8. Bg7 {Now9.Re1was covered in the Ruy Lopez main line − White's other sidelines, although it's likely to soon transpose to the current main line of9.h3.} 
9. d5
9. Ne7 {As White hasn't played Re1 yet, they definitely have an improved version of the lines we saw after 9.d5 back at the start of the course. Re1 is vaguely useful, but we can say they're probably half a tempo ahead. Still, we shouldn't be unhappy with our King's Indian structure.} 
10. c4
10. Nh5 {There's nothing wrong with castling, but the engines offer an interesting way of slowing White's queenside expansion.} 
11. Nc3
11. b5 {We're taught not to move pawns on the side we're weaker, but there are always exceptions. White's two main pawn thrusts are c4-c5 and a2-a4-a5. Both of these are now much more difficult to achieve.} 
12. b3
12. O-O {We're ready to carry out plan A, while it's not straightforward for White to find counterplay on the queenside.} 
