9. Nxe4 {The most natural10.Re1Bg7would transpose to 9.Bxc6 in the very first line we examined back in the White immediately breaks the tension chapter.} 
10. Nbd2
10. Nc5 {We're preparing to drop back to e6 to block the e-file.} 
11. Re1
11. Ne6 {We're ready to play ...Bg7 and ...O-O. If we get our king to safety, we'll have a nice advantage, so White has to act quickly.} 
12. Nd4
12. Bg7 {We can continue to ignore White.} 
13. Nxe6
13. fxe6
14. Qg4 {White logically goes after the e-pawn. Were they to start with14.exd6, then after14...Qxd6we would be able to castle long.} 
14. O-O {It turns out that we don't need to defend our pawn. We have a large lead in development.} 
15. Qxe6+ {Dangerous, but otherwise what was the point of White's last move?} 
15. Kh8 {It turns out that White should meekly retreat the queen.} 
16. exd6
16. Re8 {Oops. White is simply lost.} 
