1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. O-O
5. d6 {So far we've been focussing on 6. Re1. From this chapter onwards we'll investigate White's early alternatives.} 
6. c3 {We'll start with White's other major line. As Kramnik observes in his excellent Understanding Chess Openings series, this used to be considered best, but nowadays Black is fine.   I'm going to suggest playing in a typical fashion, but I'll try to explain the additional options allowed for both sides.} 
6. Bd7 {Once again it's important to start with this before playing ...g7-g6 otherwise, Bxc6+ and d2-d4 is a bit unpleasant. White overwhelmingly plays7.Re1here, which is simply a transposition to the lines we've just examined.7.d3is possible, but we'll carry out the same plan we used against6.Re1Bd77.d3.We'll play our usual moves with ...g7-g6, ...Bg7, ...O-O, ...Qe8, and if necessary ...Kh8.   White will run out of constructive moves without playing Re1. Once they do we'll almost certainly have a direct transposition. If White instead plays d3-d4, they'll be a tempo down on the usual Steinitz Deferred positions.} 
7. d4
7. g6 {White's most common move is once again8.Re1, with the aforementioned transposition, while8.Bc2and8.Qe2were covered earlier in the chapter.By the way, as I was preparing this course, I noticed that7...exd4followed by ...Nxe4 has had some traction in correspondence and seems to be a viable route. But let's keep the game in our structure.} 
8. d5 {Once again this is a slight improvement for White over the lines where they combine Re1 with d4-d5, but we should be happy with our structure.} 
8. Ne7
9. Bxd7+
9. Qxd7 {With the rook already on e1, I wanted to capture with the knight. That's also fine here, but this time it makes sense to keep the e-pawn attacked.} 
10. Re1
10. Bg7 {So we have the same position as in one of the previous chapters, except that we had to commit to capturing on d7 with the queen. Still, our position is perfectly healthy.} 
11. c4
11. O-O {The counterintuitive11...b5!?is liked by the engines here too, but let's play more logically.} 
12. Nc3
12. b6 {12...b5was played successfully in correspondence even here, but it became very sharp after13.c5c6.  Instead, I'll recommend this one, as I understand it a bit better.We've slowed the c4-c5 break, and are ready to play ...a6-a5 to make it as hard as possible for a White pawn to remain on b4. Then it's back to carrying out ...f7-f5.} 
