9. Nc3 {If White is choosing a slow setup then they probably need this. The exception would be if White wishes to play c2-c4 first.Starting with9.Bg5or9.h3will come to the same thing after we castle. White doesn't have a good way of playing that doesn't include Nc3.} 
9. O-O
10. Re1 {White prepares e4-e5. White could play it immediately, but with our king already safe, we have plenty of options.   The simplest is probably to move our knight, either to d7 or g4, followed by exchanging knight and pawn on e5. We'll reach a position with a slightly damaged queenside, but our two very powerful bishops on an open board provide more than enough counterplay.} 
10. Bg4 {The most active defense. We threaten to damage White's structure. Despite all, I said about our bishop pair we'll still be quite happy to exchange on f3. White will then struggle to play e4-e5, and so will lack a plan.} 
11. Qd3 {The most natural square. After11.Qe3Re8would make the queen uncomfortable.} 
11. Nd7 {We could also capture on f3 immediately, but as White's most common move is to attack our bishop we may as well gain half a tempo. By retreating the knight we take control of the e5-square, and prepare to activate our e7-bishop.} 
12. h3 {White doesn't have to attack our bishop immediately but after12.Bf4, we can reroute our knight with tempo with12...Nc5followedby ...Ne6.} 
12. Nc5 {We may as well get this move for free.} 
13. Qe3
13. Bxf3
14. Qxf3
14. Bf6 {We weren't able to put our bishop on g7, but the result is now the same. Our plan is to target the e4-pawn, while the b2-pawn is also going to be a nuisance. A further idea is to take control of the central dark squares with ...Be5 and ...Ne6.} 
15. Bf4
15. Bd4 {Keeping our bishop active. Next, we'll drop back with ...Ne6.} 
