10. c5 {We could also punish White's move order with10...d5, but this is simpler.} 
11. Qd3
11. Re8 {Our usual setup. If White does not now play Nc3, we can activate our knight with ...Nh5-f4. Just be careful not to allow Nd5. Otherwise, the usual ...a6-a5 will work well.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Ruy Lopez 6.Bxc6+"]
[Black "6.Bxc6+ bxc6 7.d4 #9"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. O-O
5. d6
6. Bxc6+ {The last of White's serious options. It looks a bit odd to capture on c6 when the bishop only dropped back to a4 two moves ago, but this is the last chance to double our pawns before we play ...Bd7.   We're actually about to transpose to a line of the Berlin Defense! But don't worry, it's definitely one of the more combative approaches for both sides.} 
6. bxc6 {We have a slightly damaged pawn structure, but the c6-pawn controls the important d5-square. Meanwhile, we'll be able to generate counterplay down the b-file. It was quite a concession to give up the light-squared bishop too.    White's critical try is to open up the center before we've completed our development. However, such an approach is also pretty risky. White has just given up the bishop pair after all. Chess wisdom dictates you should open the board when you have the bishops, not against them.   If White doesn't play an immediate d2-d4, then we'll slow the breakdown with ...Bg4. Comparing this position with the Berlin, when White's pawn would already be on d3, moving the d-pawn is the only logical move. Otherwise, White is in danger of simply being down a tempo.} 
7. d4 {The transposition to the Berlin.} 
7. exd4 {We examine a very similar position in the main line of the 5.Nc3 Spanish. The difference is White has castled here and left the knight on b1. This subtle difference changes how we react.  There I recommend supporting our pawn with7...Nd7, but that doesn't work so well here. Apart from8.c4, as played against me by Aryan Tari, White can also put the knight on c4, via either a3 or d2. That puts unpleasant pressure on both our e5-pawn and the pawn on c6 after Na5.  On the other hand, Nc3 is more useful after the capture on d4. White is quicker to advance in the center. Now the big question facing White is whether to recapture with knight or queen.} 
8. Qxd4 {White defends the e-pawn, but this gives us time to complete our development too.} 
8. Be7 {Time is of the essence. Unfortunately, we can't afford to fianchetto our bishop this time. White has broadly two approaches here. They can simply develop, and attempt to erect a bind, or they can break in the center immediately.} 
9. e5 {This is clearly the most forcing continuation, but we needn't be concerned.} 
9. c5 {This time we cannot simply move our knight, as exd6 would leave our g-pawn hanging. Instead, we force White's queen to commit.} 
10. Qf4
10. Nh5 {We gain a tempo with our knight. We no longer need to worry about our g-pawn. Going to d5 is also possible, but I don't want to give White the option of attacking with Qg3.} 
11. Qa4+ {The queen wouldn't be able to sit on e4, as we have11.Qe4d5.} 
11. Qd7 {We would be very happy with the queen exchange. Then we could show what our bishops are capable of.} 
12. Qb3
12. O-O {The only downside to our position is the misplaced knight. So long as we're careful not to allow any tricks, we can happily complete our development. We can be very optimistic about our long-term play on the light squares.} 
13. exd6 {It's just important to note that this tactic doesn't work for White.} 
13. cxd6 {Falling into White's trap.} 
14. Qd5 {Our rook and knight are forked, but this is costing White too much time.} 
14. Nf6
15. Qxa8
15. Bb7 {White is temporarily a rook up, but that queen won't escape.} 
16. Qa7
16. Qc6 {...Ra8 collects the queen. White would then have two rooks for the queen, but we're much better. We have a huge initiative on the light squares, and White's king is in a lot of trouble.} 
