1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. O-O
5. d6
6. Bxc6+ {The last of White's serious options. It looks a bit odd to capture on c6 when the bishop only dropped back to a4 two moves ago, but this is the last chance to double our pawns before we play ...Bd7.   We're actually about to transpose to a line of the Berlin Defense! But don't worry, it's definitely one of the more combative approaches for both sides.} 
6. bxc6 {We have a slightly damaged pawn structure, but the c6-pawn controls the important d5-square. Meanwhile, we'll be able to generate counterplay down the b-file. It was quite a concession to give up the light-squared bishop too.    White's critical try is to open up the center before we've completed our development. However, such an approach is also pretty risky. White has just given up the bishop pair after all. Chess wisdom dictates you should open the board when you have the bishops, not against them.   If White doesn't play an immediate d2-d4, then we'll slow the breakdown with ...Bg4. Comparing this position with the Berlin, when White's pawn would already be on d3, moving the d-pawn is the only logical move. Otherwise, White is in danger of simply being down a tempo.} 
7. d4 {The transposition to the Berlin.} 
7. exd4 {We examine a very similar position in the main line of the 5.Nc3 Spanish. The difference is White has castled here and left the knight on b1. This subtle difference changes how we react.  There I recommend supporting our pawn with7...Nd7, but that doesn't work so well here. Apart from8.c4, as played against me by Aryan Tari, White can also put the knight on c4, via either a3 or d2. That puts unpleasant pressure on both our e5-pawn and the pawn on c6 after Na5.  On the other hand, Nc3 is more useful after the capture on d4. White is quicker to advance in the center. Now the big question facing White is whether to recapture with knight or queen.} 
8. Nxd4 {Vladimir Kramnik considered this the more serious move and the top players generally agree with him.} 
8. c5 {Our pawn is attacked: we should move it.} 
9. Nc6 {This is a weird-looking move, but it's been established as the only testing try. The knight will be quite good on a5.9.Nb3was the final choice for that knight,but ...a6-a5 followed by ...a5-a4 is a good antidote.} 
9. Qd7 {The only move.} 
10. Na5 {If White tries this line at the top level, then it's this position they're aiming for. The white knight has found an outpost, albeit on the edge of the board, and for now, our queen is misplaced.} 
10. Qa4 {Continuing to harass the knight and getting out of the way of our bishop. We're making it as difficult as possible for White to both maintain the knight and complete their development.} 
11. Qe1 {White's reasoning for defending the knight this way is that they want to continue with c2-c4 without allowing a queen trade.} 
11. Be7 {We shouldn't get distracted by any ill-judged pawn grabs. We're preparing to get our king to safety. There's just one idea we have to be aware of.} 
12. c4
12. O-O {This time we can fall for the upcoming trick. We need to get our king safely castled before White can muster an attack with f2-f4.} 
13. Nc3 {White's trick, but this version is untroubling. White's alternatives weren't challenging either.13.b3Qd7would allow usour setup with ...c7-c6 and ...Qc7,while13.f3Be6transposes to the line we just saw with 12.f3.} 
13. Qxa5 {We could also drop back to d7 here, but there's nothing wrong with this capture.} 
14. Nd5 {The point. Our queen is undefended, and White is able to capture on e7 with check. But that simply restores material equality.} 
14. Qxe1
15. Nxe7+
15. Kh8
16. Rxe1
16. Re8 {All White has really achieved is an exchange of the a5-knight for the e7-bishop.} 
17. Nxc8 {Or17.Nd5Nxd518.cxd5f5.} 
17. Raxc8
18. f3
18. Nd7 {We've reached an equal endgame, but we still have winning potential. Our knight can hop around to c6 from where it eyes the outpost on d4.} 
