11. Be7 {Esipenko played the immediate11...Bg4, but that's inaccurate. First, we should get a step closer to castling. By blocking the e-file, the e4-pawn is now also vulnerable.} 
12. Re1 {White simply defends the e-pawn.12.f3Be6will be very similar. Attention! Care is now required, as White has their cunning Nc3 trick aimed against castling.} 
12. Bg4 {Unmentioned by Werle in his Smart Ruy Lopez course. It's important to force f2-f3 once White has committed rook to e1. This was clearly Esipenko's intention, but he got confused and played it a move too early. If we started with12...Be6, then White could expel our queen with13.b3.Don't rush to castle here.12...O-O?!13.Nc3!With the bishop on d2, this is a lot more than a simplifying tactic.13...Qxa514.Nd5is very unpleasant. White regains the piece immediatelywith Nxe7+. Then Bc3 will start a vicious attack on the dark squares. Please avoid this.} 
13. f3 {Were the queen to sidestep, we could grab the e-pawn.} 
13. Be6 {Objective achieved. White would prefer that f-pawn back on f2.14.b3is now impossible, as14...Qd4+collects the rook.} 
14. Qc1 {An ambitious try.} 
14. O-O {We can actually fall for White's trick this time; ...Be6 is a very useful extra tempo. An additional intriguing option is14...h5!?intending to simply marchwith ...h5-h4-h3.} 
15. c4 {Tried in a recent correspondence game, but unimpressive.} 
15. Rae8 {I already prefer Black. We'll move our pieces out of the way and blast out at White's center with ...f7-f5. Note the difficulties White has with their knights.} 
