 {I would like to take a quick interlude to discuss the various possible move orders and the reason why I chose the one I did.} 1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, and the first branching point. Here Black can try three (while a fourth might transpose) different move orders to reach our setup.} 
3. a6 {➟3...g6is Irina Bulmaga's recommended move order in her excellent course and a move order I've tried myself.Pros: We get to play our system immediately, without allowing White's early alternatives such as the Exchange Lopez. Cons: White has a wide range of lines here, and a few of them feel like improved Exchange Variations.4.c3is the main move.4.O-OBg7would be another route to our tabiya.5.c3a66.Ba4d67.d4Bd7,we can reach this position by various different move orders. I'll discuss what difference it makes that our knight is still on g8 and White's rook on f1 shortly.4.d4!?This one is a big headache. Without ...a7-a6 and Ba4 there are no Noah's Ark traps here.4...exd45.Bg5is the main line. Black should really exchange bishops here, when White will follow up with an exchange on c6. We reach some sort of improved Exchange Variation for White. While it's playable, it's certainly not worth allowing to avoid the pure Exchange Variation.5.c3!?A very dangerous pawn sacrifice that I used successfully against Sandipan. Again, Black's position is playable, but we're not the ones with the initiative, and we have to know what we're doing.4...a6,it's useful to be able to force the bishop back with ...b7-b5, while it's generally considered that the bishop is better placed on b5 than a4. From b5 it can sometimes drop back to d3 after d2-d4.5.Ba4,capturing on c6 is another serious try here.5...d65...Bg7is Irina's move order. Black now has to be willing to transpose to a main line Cozio Variation (traditionally reached via 3...Nge7, but that move order has encountered some problems).6.d4exd46...d6?!We're too late for our ideal setup.7.Bxc6+bxc68.dxe5,this is quite a miserable position.7.cxd4b5,the theory continues here. If you're interested, check out Irina's course and 1.e4 e5 Club Player's Dynamite by Simon Williams.6.d4Bd77.O-O7.Bg5!? is an additional option available to White via this move order.7...Bg7and we're back in the tabiya. We could try to force our way back into our main line with 7...Nf6!? too.➟3...d6?!The Steinitz Variation. Unfortunately, this doesn't work very well.4.d4!This is the problem. Once again we have no Noah's Ark trap.4...exd44...Bd75.Bxc6!Bxc66.Nc3is another position where Black is rather passive.5.Nxd4Bd76.Nc3andthis position might be playable, but once again we're rather more passive than I'd like. White definitely has an improved version of the 6.Bxc6+ lines.➟3...Nf6,yes, the Berlin!4.d3,of course this isn't White's only option.4...d65.O-Oand here White could also play 5.c3 amongst other tries, although Naroditsky successfully transposed back into our repertoire in his model game against Sevian.5...a66.Bxc6+bxc67.d4and we're back in the course; see 6.Bxc6+.7.Re1is a serious try recommended by Nils Grandelius. Compared to our course, White has an improved version with an extra d2-d3.} 
4. Ba4
4. d6 {This is the most common move order to reach the Steinitz Deferred, but I believe it gives White a lot more flexibility. As a reminder, I'm recommending we start with the usual4...Nf6.4...g6is a move order I considered playing a few years ago, but I couldn't quite get it to work. It is tried by Nakamura in speed chess but White can force us to play quite different positions than those intended.5.d4,once again, this is the problem. 5.c3 would transpose back to 3...g6.5...exd45...b5is Nakamura's usual attempt.6.Bb3exd4and with the pawn on g6 rather than d6 there's no Noah's Ark either.7.a4!?b48.Nxd4is playable, but outside the scope of our repertoire.6.Nxd4,if we develop with 6...Bg7, then 7.Nxc6 is rather annoying.6...Nge77.Bg5!But this is even worse. White is ready with both Bf6 and Nxc6.} 
5. O-O {This and5.c3are comfortably the most likely moves you'll face. We'd be happy to see5.c4Bg4, a position very similar to one in the course. Now5...Nf6would transpose to the course, but there are a couple of other tries.➟5.c3Bd7(Or5...g66.d4Bd7, reaching the same thing;5...f5!?is the Siesta Variation. Theoretically, it's standing pretty well, although Black needs to know a lot.)6.d4g6and we're back in a position we've already discussed, en-route to the tabiya.➟5.Bxc6+!?bxc66.d4Nf6!I think this is the most accurate move order.6...exd4is similar to the 6.Bxc6 lines, but White can claim a slightly improved version, as they've not yet castled.7.Qxd4Nf68.Nc3,developing the knight is slightly more useful than castling. One option for White is to castle long.8...Be79.e5,while this position is probably playable, I think we're in a worse version of the 6.Bxc6+ lines.7.Nc3(7.O-Owould be a direct transposition to 6.Bxc6+ (and the Berlin), while7.dxe5Nxe4will likely reach a type of Scotch Gambit style position.)7...Nd7!We've transposed to the 5.Nc3 Spanish.➟5.d4,unfortunately, falling into the trap is not so clear here either.5...b5!6.Bb3Nxd47.Nxd4exd48.c3!?This and 8.Bd5 are the main moves.8.Qxd4??Just a reminder:8...c59.Qd5Be610.Qc6+Bd711.Qd5c4and that's a piece. The World Championship challenger,  (perhaps even World Champion by the time you read this) no less, fell for this in a blitz game. Nepomniachtchi-Demchenko, chess.com 2020.8...dxc3,it's possible to prevent the immediate draw with 8...d3, but White has a nibble.9.Qd5is the annoying move. White has compensation with 9.Nxc3 too.9...Be610.Qc6+Bd711.Qd5and there's no way to escape the draw;11...Be6.} 
5. Bd7 {➟5...Bg4!?This pin has a bad reputation, but it was tried by Richard Rapport in the Belgrade Grand Prix in 2022.6.h3h5!This is Black's point. For now, opening the h-file is too scary, so Black maintains the pin. Black has to be ready to sacrifice soon though.7.d4After7.Bxc6+bxc68.d4,I always felt this line was rather uncomfortable.7...b58.Bb3Nxd49.hxg4,White is now obliged to capture the piece.9...hxg4The young English IM, Jonah Willow, recently played9...Nxb3!?. After the game, he told me it was all fine for Black according to his analysis.10.Ng5Nh6was MVL-Rapport, Belgrade 2022. A very complicated position. White is a piece for two pawns up, and not getting mated any time soon, but the knight on g5 is trapped.➟5...g6?!A mistaken move order I've attempted a couple of times in blitz.6.d4!The typical problem. Here there's no Noah's Ark trap as Qxd4 will hit our rook.6...Bg77.Bxc6+bxc68.dxe5and we're straddled with a horrible structure.} 
6. c3 {The main move.➟6.d4was Alexei Shirov's choice against me. It's pretty tough to get counterplay here.6...Nf66...exd47.Nxd4b5is Kuljasevic's recommendation on Modern Chess, but he accepts White is solid with some pressure.6...Nxd4is the most solid. Black is almost equal, but without counterplay.7.c4!?Alexei's approach. White is extremely solid, and it's hard to create play. After an exchange on d4, White has their Maroczy Bind structure.7.Bxc6Bxc68.Re1transposes back to the course, and was the route of the model game Kulaots-Van Foreest.7...b5!?I considered that this might be playable, and if you want to add in this move order I advise you to analyze this position.➟6.c4!?Perhaps the most painful move to face from a practical perspective.6...Nf66...Bg4is maybe the most interesting, but we would be a pure tempo down on the course. We had this with our knight already on f6 in the 6.c4 Bg4 line.6...g67.d4exd48.Bxc6!Keeping the option of taking on d4 with the queen should Black recapture with the pawn. After8...Bxc69.Nxd4,the structure reminds me of an ...exd4 King's Indian. Black is solid but struggles to find counterplay.7.Nc3and the following is a sample line sent to me by Tanmay Srinath, a correspondence player who gave a lot of useful feedback on my King's Indian courses.7...g68.Bxc6Bxc69.Re1Bg710.d4exd411.Nxd4O-O12.f3− Tanmay Srinath. Black's position is almost certainly within the drawing margin; it's just difficult to generate play. This kind of position has no place in the course!} 
6. g6
7. d4
7. Bg7 {We've reached this tabiya yet again, and it's finally time to discuss it. In the course, we have deeply studied the position after8.Re1Nf6. Here we could consider developing the knightto e7, although generally, that's just a more passive square.  There's also the option of playing ...f7-f5 immediately, but that's only on the cards if White now closes the centerwith8.d5(see my other game with Nigel Short in the notes to my game with Nigel Short in the Model Games chapter).I think it's more beneficial for White that they haven't yet played Re1, but I should mention that's overwhelmingly the top move chosen.} 
8. Re1 {8.Bg5!?The choice of both Richard Palliser and Sethuraman against me. This is White's main alternative.8...f6. Instead,8...Nf6is a slightly better version for White as they haven't yet had to play Re1.9.Bxc6,White can start a long forcing line.9...Bxc610.dxe5dxe511.Nxe5Qxd112.Rxd1Nxe413.Bf4g5!I think Black is okay, but we need to be accurate.} 
8. Nf6 {We've transposed to our main lines.8...Nge7could also be tried, as Magnus Carlsen did successfully in a rapid game from 2019 (see the model game Bjerre-Carlsen).But in general, I think our knight is just more actively played on f6. From e7 it doesn't put any pressure on White's center. If White doesn't oblige by closing the position with d4-d5, then it's very difficult to know what to do; ...f7-f5 is generally too risky with a flexible center.} 
