 {I’m never sure of the correct nomenclature. Is it the Delayed Smyslov or Steinitz Deferred? Apologies if I’ve not been consistent. What matters are the positions. I think it’s a greatly underrated opening, especially via the proposed move order.  We first checked our dream.6.d4?!is a natural move, but White immediately encounters problems. If they’re not very careful the bishop will simply be lost.We then moved on to a close investigation of the c2-c3 and d2-d4 structures. In practice, I think your opponents are very likely to feel uncomfortable with the fluid center.  The first moves we checked were White’s attempts at immediately resolving the tension. White can win a pawn with9.Bxc6, but we have fantastic compensation with our bishop pair and lead in development.9.dxe5is dull but presents no challenge to our setup.9.d5is much more interesting. Once the center is closed the game strongly resembles a King’s Indian. We’re going to attack on the kingside, while White tries their luck on the queenside. However, they are much slower than they would be in a traditional Classical King’s Indian, and we have good chances. Be sure to check out the model gameBjerre-Carlsen. The World Number One made it look extremely straightforward to defeat a strong well-prepared grandmaster.We then moved onto White’s other sidelines, most notably9.Nbd2O-O10.Nf1. White follows the pure Spanish guidelines and brings their queenside knight to the kingside as quickly as possible.However, this isn’t nearly as strong when we already have a pawn on g6. We control the f5-square, and so White’s knight is dominated. In fact, we can exploit White’s play even earlier with the exchange on d4 followed by ...b7-b5 and ...Bg4. It’s very difficult for White to maintain their center.    This theme of exchanging on d4 followed by the pin is a very important source of counterplay. Therefore White tried preventing it by playing9.Nbd2O-O10.h3. We can no longer pin, but we have another way into White’s position. This time, after the exchange on d4, we hop the knight into b4 and prepare to jump into d3. This way we exploit White’s misplaced knight on d2. The positions are sharp, but Black has won the theoretical debate.It was time for another switch from White. The current trend amongst the booked-up players is to leave the knight on b1, and play the immediate9.h3reacting to9...O-Owith10.Bc2!We can no longer use tricks involving ...exd4. Instead, it’s time to revert to King’s Indian-inspired play. With the plan of ...Nh5, ...Qe8 and ...f7-f5, we put maximum pressure on White’s position.   White will have to know their stuff, calculate well and have good nerves not to succumb. I think Nils Grandelius’ suggestion is the critical test, but hopefully, I’ve proven that our position is healthy, even against perfect defense from our opponents.I wrapped up the chapter with a look at White’s earlier alternatives. White starting with6.c3provides both sides with more options, but the vast majority of the time it will simply be a transposition to the lines above.6.Bxc6+is interesting. The game will quickly transpose to a line of the Berlin Defense. The structures are quite different, and there are a few important nuances to know, and so this should be studied carefully.Finally, we looked at White’s remaining bits and bobs. The most useful advice to take from there is to meet an early6.c4with6...Bg4. We should wrestle White for control of the d4-square.} 1. --
