6. Bxc6+ {The other solution to the threat. White exchanges on their own terms. We still get the bishop pair, but White claims our queenside is slightly compromised.} 
6. bxc6 {We already examined this structure in the main line Ruy Lopez with6.Bxc6+. But there the critical path was to try and target our king with aquick d2-d4. This combination is not at all worrying.} 
7. h3 {A move order tried by Russian GM and blitz specialist, Vladimir Fedoseev.} 
7. g6
8. Nc3 {Fedoseev's plan is to refrain from castling kingside. It shouldn't really work, but we should remember that White is going to hack.} 
8. Bg7
9. Be3 {Fedoseev-Matlakov, chess.com 2022. After9...O-O, White played10.Qd2and Bh6 with a nice attack.  Objectively we're fine, but let's show a bit of nuance so we don't have to defend.} 
9. Rb8 {Let's exploit White's last to make a slight weakening.} 
10. b3
10. c5 {And now we'll take the d4-square. We're delaying castling kingside until White confirms their intentions.} 
11. Qd2 {Trying to prevent our next with11.g4?!fails to11...h5.} 
11. Nh5 {Borrowing a typical King's Indian idea. We want to meet g2-g4 with ...Nf4. Capturing gives us an incredibly powerful dark-squared bishop.} 
12. Bh6
12. O-O {With our knight hopping into f4, we needn't fear castling.} 
13. g4
13. Nf4 {A nice outpost for our knight. If White takes, then our g7-bishop is far too powerful, especially with almost all of White's pawns on light squares.} 
14. Bxg7
14. Kxg7 {Our plan is ...Rh8 and ...h7-h5, when we're certainly not the one being attacked. Long-term, White might have some issues with their king too. Presuming White goes long, we can later open up lines with ...a6-a5-a4.} 
