1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. d3
5. d6
6. c4 {We've seen the problems that White encounters should we win their light-squared bishop. Now we'll look at the two main moves. This one is a bit anti-positional. White has to be very careful as there's a chronic weakness on d4. On the other hand, White can at least develop their knight actively to c3 and hopes to make something of the d5-square control.We'll look at the main line6.c3, in the next chapter. Finally, it should be mentioned that White can keep the bishop with6.a3!?, but it doesn't threaten anything. We can just get on with our usual plan with6...g6and 7...Bg7.} 
6. g6 {We're not winning the bishop here, so back to the usual setup. Our plan is to exploit our new outpost on d4. We'll do that by playing ...Bg7, castling, and ...Nd7, when the other knight will be ready to hop into d4.} 
7. d4 {I mention this idea in the move order discussion. It's a very decent plan, but here White has lost a tempo with the pawn stopping off at d3. I had this position against Alexei Shirov with ...Bd7 rather than ...g7-g6, but he had already castled.} 
7. exd4 {It is possible to play7...Bd7too, but that would justify White's play. After8.d5Ne7, White has no longer lost a tempo. The d-pawn was very slow, but the c-pawn got to c4 in one go. Compared to our main line,we're missing ...Bg7, while White has yet to castle and play Re1.} 
8. Nxd4
8. Bd7
9. Nc3
9. Nxd4 {An interesting try to punish White's move order.9...Bg7would likely come to the same thing after10.Nxc6Bxc6.} 
10. Bxd7+ {Otherwise, we'll misplace White's knight by capturing on a4.} 
10. Nxd7
11. Qxd4
11. Ne5 {If given time for ...Bg7, we'll be doing well. We have the better-placed minor pieces, and the c-pawn is not trivial to hold onto.} 
12. f4 {So we should check White's most forcing approach.} 
12. Qh4+ {An annoying check. White cannot block with the queen due to ...Nd3+, or the pawn because of a fork with ...Nf3+.} 
13. Kf1
13. c5 {We force that queen back.} 
14. Qd1
14. Ng4 {And threaten mate.} 
15. Qe2
15. Bg7 {And finally get back to completing our development. The position is around level, but White has to be careful with the misplaced king.} 
