2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. d3
5. d6
6. c4 {We've seen the problems that White encounters should we win their light-squared bishop. Now we'll look at the two main moves. This one is a bit anti-positional. White has to be very careful as there's a chronic weakness on d4. On the other hand, White can at least develop their knight actively to c3 and hopes to make something of the d5-square control.We'll look at the main line6.c3, in the next chapter. Finally, it should be mentioned that White can keep the bishop with6.a3!?, but it doesn't threaten anything. We can just get on with our usual plan with6...g6and 7...Bg7.} 
6. g6 {We're not winning the bishop here, so back to the usual setup. Our plan is to exploit our new outpost on d4. We'll do that by playing ...Bg7, castling, and ...Nd7, when the other knight will be ready to hop into d4.} 
7. Nc3 {Starting with7.O-Oor7.h3will come to the same thing after7...Bg7.} 
7. Bg7
8. h3 {This tends to be the route the top players are trying right now. It's useful for White to control the g4-square to prevent either ...Ng4 plans, hitting the e3-bishop (if it stops there immediately or gets shunted back from g5), or an annoying pin with ...Bg4.} 
8. O-O
9. Be3 {This is actually White's most common move, but I think it's an inaccuracy.} 
9. Nd7 {This concept is very strong. By retreating the knight we're ready to hop the other knight into d4. White's best try is discombobulating with Bg5, but that doesn't make a lot of sense when the bishop just stopped at e3.} 
10. O-O {Played once by the World Champion (Magnus Carlsen at time of writing), albeit only in a blitz game. He was quickly in a whole load of trouble.} 
10. Nd4 {Our knight is very powerful, and the bishop on a4 is simply misplaced. We're ready to advance on both sides of the board; ...c7-c6 is a good move to start with.} 
11. Bxd4 {Let's continue following Carlsen's game.} 
11. exd4
12. Bxd7 {12.Ne2c5is unpleasant, but this loses material.} 
12. dxc3 {Sequences where both sides ignore each other, are always fun.} 
13. Bxc8
13. cxb2 {White can't allow us to make another queen.} 
14. Rb1
14. Rxc8 {It's quite impressive that the e-pawn has made it to b2.} 
15. d4 {White's only try is to collect the b-pawn.} 
15. c5 {But White's center now collapses. The young Indian converted the full point. Carlsen-Nihal, chess24.com 2021.} 
