11. b5 {White's main problem is that they lack a plan. There isn't really a way to get any further on the kingside, as h3-h4 will always be met by ...Nf6. We can grab space on the queenside, when White won't have a safe haven for their king.} 
12. Bb3 {A slightly more active posting, but this provokes us to continue pushing. We have lots of choices against12.Bc2, but I like12...Nd8!?with the idea of taking control of the f4-square.} 
12. a5 {12...Nc5was played in Calzetta Ruiz-Daulyte Cornette, Arvier 2007, which is also fine, but I think grabbing space is simpler.} 
13. a4
13. b4 {If White now sits, then we could put a lot of pressure on the d3-pawn with ...Ba6 and a knight into c5. If we have time, I quite like returning to the plan of ...Nd8-e6 first.} 
14. h4 {I imagine White has to try this at some point, but it's easily dealt with.} 
14. Nf6 {Attacking the g-pawn. White isn't in time for h4-h5.} 
15. g5
15. Nh5 {White's kingside push has just left behind weakened squares and nowhere safe for their king.} 
