9. bxc6 {The same structure as the 6.Bxc6+ lines, but White is much more passive. The justification there was to play d2-d4 quickly to open up the board.} 
10. Nbd2 {White gets ready to capture on e5. Had they taken immediately, we'd have grabbed on e4.} 
10. exd4 {Good timing. The knight would much prefer to be on c3.} 
11. cxd4
11. Re8 {The usual plan. The e4-pawn is vulnerable after exchanging the light-squared bishop.} 
12. Re1
12. c5
13. dxc5
13. Bb7 {A strong temporary pawn sacrifice. White really struggles to develop the c1-bishop and hold onto the e4-pawn.} 
