[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) d3 Spanish − 6.c3 Main Line"]
[Black "7.O-O Bg7 8.Re1 O-O 9.h3 h6 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. d3
5. d6
6. c3
6. g6
7. O-O
7. Bg7
8. Re1 {Clearing the way for the knight. This is White's most common and most flexible move.8.Nbd2is likely to come to the same thing. White will follow it up with Re1 to give the knight a square.8.h3O-Owill also be a transposition, either to Grandelius' recommendation of 9.h3 or to 8.Be3.} 
8. O-O {After investigating White's earlier tries, we've now reached the main branching point of the d3-Spanish.  In his Keep it Simple 2.0, Sielecki recommends the most straightforward plan of9.Nbd2intending to reroute the knight to g3. This is White's most common idea, but I don't think it puts any pressure on our position.Grandelius offers the subtle9.h3!?, keeping the option of developing the bishop. I think this is objectively White's best try, but White needs to understand all the nuances of the position to play it accurately.We have a few plans available. We can play in the center with ...h7-h6, ...Re8, and ...d6-d5. Another plan is to grab space on the queenside with ...b7-b5 followed by ...a6-a5-a4.   I've also tried to offer alternative plans where we succeed in our thematic King's Indian ...f7-f5 break. This works particularly well if White does something provocative like putting the bishop on e3. Then the plan of ...f7-f5 works so much better as we'll always gain time on the bishop. Talking of provocation,we covered9.d4via the 8.d4 move order.SHORTCUT ALERT:8...Bd7would actually transpose to6.Re1Bd77.d3!?. There's no need to touch the bishop here, but that's another good way to reach complicated positions.} 
9. h3 {Grandelius. White keeps their options open. They might transpose back to the main lines with9.Nbd2or they might develop the bishop to e3. This is perhaps White's best try in the whole d3-Spanish complex.} 
9. h6 {Generally a very useful move for both ...d6-d5 and ...f7-f5 plans. First, we want to prevent Bg5, and second, any annoying Ng5 jumps.White's most common move now is to play10.Nbd2, but that will be covered via the9.Nbd2h610.h3move order.} 
10. Be3 {This is played a lot by strong players, but Grandelius correctly advises his followers to stay away.} 
10. Kh8 {The plan with ...f7-f5 will now be very strong as we'll gain a tempo on the bishop. Starting by moving the king wasn't mandatory, we could have started with a knight move. If in doubt, I like to keep maximum pressure on the e4-pawn, dissuading d3-d4.} 
11. Nbd2
11. Nd7
12. Bc2
12. f5 {This position was more or less the reason Nils didn't want to put his bishop on e3 before Black had committed to ...Re8. We already have a dangerous attack.} 
