8. O-O {After investigating White's earlier tries, we've now reached the main branching point of the d3-Spanish.  In his Keep it Simple 2.0, Sielecki recommends the most straightforward plan of9.Nbd2intending to reroute the knight to g3. This is White's most common idea, but I don't think it puts any pressure on our position.Grandelius offers the subtle9.h3!?, keeping the option of developing the bishop. I think this is objectively White's best try, but White needs to understand all the nuances of the position to play it accurately.We have a few plans available. We can play in the center with ...h7-h6, ...Re8, and ...d6-d5. Another plan is to grab space on the queenside with ...b7-b5 followed by ...a6-a5-a4.   I've also tried to offer alternative plans where we succeed in our thematic King's Indian ...f7-f5 break. This works particularly well if White does something provocative like putting the bishop on e3. Then the plan of ...f7-f5 works so much better as we'll always gain time on the bishop. Talking of provocation,we covered9.d4via the 8.d4 move order.SHORTCUT ALERT:8...Bd7would actually transpose to6.Re1Bd77.d3!?. There's no need to touch the bishop here, but that's another good way to reach complicated positions.} 
9. h3 {Grandelius. White keeps their options open. They might transpose back to the main lines with9.Nbd2or they might develop the bishop to e3. This is perhaps White's best try in the whole d3-Spanish complex.} 
9. h6 {Generally a very useful move for both ...d6-d5 and ...f7-f5 plans. First, we want to prevent Bg5, and second, any annoying Ng5 jumps.White's most common move now is to play10.Nbd2, but that will be covered via the9.Nbd2h610.h3move order.} 
10. a3 {Grandelius' sophisticated recommendation. Thus far it has only been played twice by the well-prepared Danish GM Jonas Bjerre, and once by Italy's number one, Daniele Vocaturo. White takes further control of the b4-square, either to prepare b2-b4 or d3-d4 without allowing our annoying ...Nb4 jumps.} 
10. b5 {We'll follow Grandelius' main line. It was still possible to revert back to attacking on the kingside with10...Nd7. Grandelius has a deep analysis demonstrating a White edge. I think he's probably correct, although White's play requires much more precision than ours, so it's still a very decent practical attempt.} 
11. Bc2
11. a5 {We grab space on the queenside. White normally wants to challenge us by putting a pawn on a4, but that would cost a tempo here.} 
12. Be3
12. d5 {Taking more space. I think we've equalized, although with all the material still on the board there's a lot of play left in the position. The following I'll leave as a clickable if you'd like to see how I would go about neutralizing Grandelius' suggestion.} 
13. Nbd2
13. Re8
14. Qc1 {Nils' tricky recommendation. White is preparing to fight back in the center.} 
14. Kh7 {Let's just defend that pawn.} 
15. d4
15. dxe4 {The right way to resolve the central tension.} 
16. Nxe4
16. Bf5 {We activate our bishop and prepare to exchange it for White's dangerous prelate on c2.} 
17. Nc5 {Tried in the only practical encounter that reached this far: Vocaturo-Cordts, Tegernsee 2022.17.Ng3Bxc218.Qxc2is where Grandelius leaves it. The position is complicated but equal. As he explains, White's plans are to complete developmentwith Rad1, and to loosen up our kingside with h4-h5.18...Qd7!We also wish to complete our development. As the center is opening, the e- and d-files are clearly the right places for the rooks.White can play h3-h4 at virtually any point. We should react by dropping our king back to g8.After19.Rad1exd420.cxd4, White's only challenging route. Otherwise, we'll start exchanging.20...Rad8, completing our development and making sure that Ne5 isn't a problem.Now we can exchange and play ...Nd5.The position remains double-edged. White will try to get somewhere on the kingside, but if they don't succeed we'll simply be better with our superior structure; d5 is a very comfy outpost. Just remember to react to21.h4with21...Kg8, getting out of the pin.} 
17. Nd5 {We don't have to move the bishop yet. We're allowing our structure to be compromised, but in return, we'll take the initiative.} 
18. Bxf5 {I don't really see what White does other than damage our structure.} 
18. gxf5
19. Nxe5
19. Nxe5
20. dxe5
20. Rxe5 {We threaten to capture on e3 and pick up the knight.} 
21. Nd3
21. Re4 {Despite our doubled f-pawns, I think we're doing pretty well. Our pieces are just so much more active than White's. With ...Qd6 and ...Rae8, we'll dominate the board.} 
