8. O-O {After investigating White's earlier tries, we've now reached the main branching point of the d3-Spanish.  In his Keep it Simple 2.0, Sielecki recommends the most straightforward plan of9.Nbd2intending to reroute the knight to g3. This is White's most common idea, but I don't think it puts any pressure on our position.Grandelius offers the subtle9.h3!?, keeping the option of developing the bishop. I think this is objectively White's best try, but White needs to understand all the nuances of the position to play it accurately.We have a few plans available. We can play in the center with ...h7-h6, ...Re8, and ...d6-d5. Another plan is to grab space on the queenside with ...b7-b5 followed by ...a6-a5-a4.   I've also tried to offer alternative plans where we succeed in our thematic King's Indian ...f7-f5 break. This works particularly well if White does something provocative like putting the bishop on e3. Then the plan of ...f7-f5 works so much better as we'll always gain time on the bishop. Talking of provocation,we covered9.d4via the 8.d4 move order.SHORTCUT ALERT:8...Bd7would actually transpose to6.Re1Bd77.d3!?. There's no need to touch the bishop here, but that's another good way to reach complicated positions.} 
9. Nbd2 {The main line.} 
9. h6 {I don't think Sielecki covers either this or the very similar9...Re8. I'm going to offer alternatives here. My primaryrecommendations will be the established equalizers with ...Re8 followed by ...d6-d5, or by advancing on the queenside. But I'll also offer alternatives where we attack on the kingside.   For both plans, ...h7-h6 is useful. We'd like to prevent White from any annoying Bg5 once the knight has dropped back to f1.Starting with9...Re8is also completely okay.But starting with ...h7-h6 means we haven't completely given up on playing ...f7-f5. Against the rook move, Arkadij Naiditsch tried10.a3!?Against such a waiting move we could now switch back to our direct route with10...Nh7and ...f7-f5.9...Kh8could also be played here,but Nbd2 is clearly more useful than h2-h3 if we're playing the ...f7-f5 plan.} 
10. Nf1 {White continues the autopilot rerouting.} 
10. Re8 {The plan of ...f7-f5 is shelved for now, but White needs to be ready for central play.11.h3was covered via the 10.h3 move order.} 
11. Ng3
11. d5 {An additional possibility when White is yet to play h2-h3. We could also start with11...b5, when play is very likely to transpose to 10.h3.} 
12. h3
12. b5 {White is ready for d3-d4, so time to shunt that bishop back. Hikaru Nakamura has had this position as White twice, albeit at speed chess. He went back to c2 the first time but lost to Magnus.} 
13. Bb3 {Hikaru's choice the second time.} 
13. Na5 {The usual response. We sideline our knight but in return free the way for our c-pawn.} 
14. Bc2
14. c5 {Or14...dxe4and ...Qxd1, according to taste. We've grabbed a lot of space and can be very satisfied with the outcome of the opening.} 
