13. a5 {The plan of pushing the pawn to a4 appeals to me. Nakamura-Carlsen, chess24.com 2020, instead saw13...Be6, which is also fine, while exchanging queens with13...dxe4also equalizes.} 
14. a4 {Otherwise, we were pushing ...a5-a4.} 
14. b4 {We can be very happy with this construction too. If White exchanges on d5, then the c3-pawn will be vulnerable, while the c2-bishop is not very happy. Next, we'll play ...Rb8 and ...Be6.    The d3-Spanish is very popular, as it cuts out a lot of theory, and allows White to follow the same development pattern, more or less regardless of Black's setup. However, it doesn't offer White any advantage, and I think the positions we've studied in this chapter are much easier for us to play, especially after having a grounding in our main line Spanish.    I understand playing in the center might not be for everyone, and so I've tried to offer a full alternative repertoire where we push the f-pawn at the earliest opportunity.} 
