[White "17) d3 Spanish: Conclusion"]
[Black "d3 Spanish − Conclusion"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {The d3 systems are very popular. It’s considered more challenging to delay touching the d-pawn until after castling, as then Black committed their bishop to e7. Of course, that wouldn’t apply to us. This way White is able to develop without needing to memorize vast quantities of theory. The downside, from their viewpoint, is that we are very flexible with our dark-squared bishop.   The Steinitz Deferred setup with ...d7-d6 followed by the kingside fianchetto is one of the two main lines. And for good reason. As we’ve already seen, from g7 the bishop does a good job of controlling the key d4-square, while the g6-pawn controls the f5-square, and therefore dominates the g3-knight.    We started by investigating White’s early sidelines. If White doesn’t move the c-pawn then our plan is simply to collect the bishop with ...b7-b5 and ...Na5.Therefore,6.c4!?is the best of the bunch.White keeps the c3-square available for their knight, but ceding control of the d4-square is very risky. We take advantage of that with our plan of fianchettoing the bishop, moving the f6-knight, and playing ...Nd4. Even Magnus Carlsen got into a lot of trouble against this plan.White overwhelmingly opts for6.c3.We’ll develop our kingside normally. We started by checking White’s early deviations. If White pushes d3-d4, then we tend to be a pure tempo up on our Deferred Steinitz positions. Putting the bishop on g5 is quite a common plan, but the bishop is often simply misplaced here. A quick ...g6-g5 and ...h6-h5 gives us a very dangerous initiative.    White’s main line is to castle, play the rook to e1 and then meander the b1-knight over to the kingside. I’ve offered two complete repertoires here. The established way to equalize is to combine gaining space on the queenside with the ...d6-d5 break in the center. There are no theoretical problems here, but the positions are a bit different to the rest of our repertoire. I’ve therefore also offered alternatives involving our typical kingside play with ...f7-f5.    Finally, it should be mentioned that we have a third path available. If we play an early ...Bd7 we’ll likely transpose to positions covered via6.Re1Bd77.d3g6in the main line Spanish.} 1. --
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) Introduction Spanish: White's early alternatives"]
[Black "Spanish: White's early alternatives − Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6 {We'll next take a look at White's early deviations. In this introduction I'll briefly outline White's tries.} 
4. Bxc6 {The Exchange Spanish. This has a reputation for being dull, but we can keep the game exciting.4.Ba4Nf65.d4is the most serious line examined here. Our coverage of this variation will end up being one of the longest in the entire course. The lines are very forcing, but if we know it we can be confident.5.Nc3,defending the e-pawn with the knight has started to become quite popular at the GM level. Most of the time White is following up with d2-d3, and trying to trick us out of our intended setup.5...d6!?We keep to our ideal formation. This is rare but was played recently by Levon Aronian, one of the all-time experts in 1.e4 e5 positions. A big practical benefit is that White's main two tries here are both errors.5.Qe2,defending the e-pawn with the queen is reasonably common, but I don't think much of it. It's now much harder for White to successfully control the center. I'll now offer a choice.5...d6is our thematic approach. We defend the e5-pawn and prepare to fianchetto our bishop. I'll also offer5...b5as an alternative.6.Bb3Bc5is a main line, and rather different from our usual formations. But the main point remains the same: tocontrol the d4-square. We make it as hard as possible for White to successfully expand in the center. I think we have an easier position to play.5.Bxc6is an oddly-timed exchange. I'm skeptical about White's claim that our move ...Nf6 was worse than passing. The Delayed Exchange exists with 5.O-O Be7 included, but that's because the bishop is then misplaced, and might have to move again to defend the e5-pawn.5...dxc6,now we'll be able to develop our bishop much more actively to the d6-square. An active plan is to prepare to castle queenside.5.c3?!The least of White's alternatives.5...Nxe4,White forgot about their e-pawn. With White having played c2-c3 rather than castling kingside, we have a great version of an Open Spanish.5...exd4,we should grab the pawn.6.O-O,White shouldn't start any central play until they've got their king to safety.6...Be7!Straightforward chess. We develop a piece, prepare to castle, and threaten to take on e4.7.e5!The traditional main line here is 7.Re1, but it's now known that White needs to force matters to hold equality.7...Ne4,the most accurate circuit. We'll be able to get rid of White's light-squared bishop.} 
4. dxc6
5. O-O {We'll also examine White's other tries, but castling is White's main idea.} 
5. Qf6 {A few years ago this was a minor sideline, but it's really exploded in popularity in recent years at the top level. It might still catch lower-rated players off-guard.   We defend the e-pawn and prepare to castle queenside. If White plays too hesitantly, we can quickly build up a vicious kingside attack.} 
