[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) Spanish 5.Nc3"]
[Black "5.Nc3 d6 6.Bxc6+ #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. Nc3 {This has started to become quite trendy at the top level. Black usually plays with ...Bc5, either immediately or after hitting the bishop back with ...b7-b5. White is then generally intending to transpose to a d3-setup.} 
5. d6 {Let's keep to our intended setup. This is rare but has the approval of Levon Aronian. With the e-pawn defended, White now needs to address the problem of their light-squared bishop.6.d3is played a lot here, but we covered that via5.d3d66.Nc3, while6.O-Ois covered via5.O-Oin White's remaining bits and bobs. Neither address the problem with White's bishop at all, and so we'll play6...b5and 7...Na5.} 
6. Bxc6+ {White has to part with the bishop before advancing in the center.} 
6. bxc6
7. d4 {The only consistent follow-up. Otherwise, we'd play ...c6-c5, when White won't have the chance. Such a position is examined after7.O-Oc5after 6.Bxc6+ in the main line Spanish.} 
7. Nd7 {An important idea. We want to maintain the pawn on e5. This works well here, as the knight is so misplaced on c3. It's dominated by our c6-pawn and a long way from having any effect on the position.7...exd4?!would make sense of White's already developed knight.8.Nxd4(8.Qxd4followed by an immediate e4-e5 isalso a bit unpleasant.)8...c59.Nc6Qd710.Na5. We've encountered a key difference to the 6.Bxc6+variation. With the knight already on c3, we cannot continue to hassle the other knight with ...Qa4.} 
8. dxe5
8. dxe5 {The first question to ask is whether we should be worried by this structure. Our queenside is damaged after all. But it's not at all easy for White to target our pawns. It would be a different matter entirely if White's c-pawn weren't in the way. The c6-pawn also does a great job of controlling the d5-square. We have the bishop pair, and both a semi-open b-file and a good spot for our bishop on a6 after we play ...a6-a5.} 
9. O-O
9. Bd6 {The right square for the bishop. It comfortably defends the e5-pawn. We control a lot of the center, and White finds it difficult to come up with a good plan.} 
