6. bxc6
7. d4 {The only consistent follow-up. Otherwise, we'd play ...c6-c5, when White won't have the chance. Such a position is examined after7.O-Oc5after 6.Bxc6+ in the main line Spanish.} 
7. Nd7 {An important idea. We want to maintain the pawn on e5. This works well here, as the knight is so misplaced on c3. It's dominated by our c6-pawn and a long way from having any effect on the position.7...exd4?!would make sense of White's already developed knight.8.Nxd4(8.Qxd4followed by an immediate e4-e5 isalso a bit unpleasant.)8...c59.Nc6Qd710.Na5. We've encountered a key difference to the 6.Bxc6+variation. With the knight already on c3, we cannot continue to hassle the other knight with ...Qa4.} 
8. Bg5
8. f6 {This move is in our plans anyway. The pawn might get in the way temporarily, but it does a great job of supporting the e5-pawn. If White could put a bishop on the a2-g8 diagonal, we'd be a bit worried, but that would only be the case in a game of bughouse here.} 
9. Be3
9. Be7
10. Qe2
10. a5 {The typical development idea.} 
11. Nh4
11. g6 {We'd prefer not to allow the knight to hop into f5.} 
12. f4 {So far we've been following Kovalev-Malaniuk, Hamburg 1995. Malaniuk captured on f4, but I think we can maintain the tension.} 
12. Ba6
13. Qf3
13. Nb6 {This plan again. Our knight is hopping into c4. White's kingside play looks dangerous, but they cannot make anything of it without better control of the light squares.} 
