[White "20) Spanish 5.Qe2 − The Wormald Attack"]
[Black "5.Qe2 d6 6.c3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. Qe2 {I believe this is officially known as the Wormald Attack, although in my brain I branch all these Qe2 setups as the Worrall. White's intention is to support the d2-d4 break by playing O-O, Rd1, and c2-c3. However, I believe the queen is generally misplaced on the e-file.Achieving the d2-d4 advance is tough, and even if they do, the e-pawn is likely to be very vulnerable. I'll be consistent and offer the unusual5...d6as our main approach, but I'll also briefly demonstrate a setup with the bishopon c5 as a straightforward alternative.} 
5. d6 {We continue with our thematic approach. I should also mention that Nigel Short has been successful with the wacky5...Qe7!?intending to reach our aimed structure too.} 
6. c3 {White gives the bishop an escape route and prepares to advance in the center. We can react to6.c4in the usual fashion with6...Bg4.Note that6.O-OBd77.c3g6is covered via 6.c3 in the Steinitz Deferred.} 
6. g6 {Continuing as usual. Starting with6...b5is also feasible, but after7.Bb3, we have to give up on oursetup as Ng5 is an annoying threat.} 
7. Bxc6+ {This has only been played once, but is perhaps White's most promising independent try.} 
7. bxc6
8. d4
8. a5 {A provocative try. Starting with8...Nd7is also fine, but we'd like to encourage White to capture the e-pawn. There's also nothing wrong with simplycapturing on d4.} 
9. dxe5 {White should ignore the pawn and castle. After9.O-ONd7, we get an interesting structure we analyzed a bit in the 5.Nc3 Spanish.White would be better with the pawn back on c2, but here there are a few holes on the light squares.} 
9. dxe5
10. Nxe5 {Hard to resist, but White is now going to have some problems completing development.} 
10. Ba6 {This isn't easy to deal with.} 
11. c4
11. Qd4 {Now we will at least regain the pawn with a pleasant position.} 
12. Nxc6 {That one is definitely poisoned.} 
12. Qc5 {There's no way back.} 
