[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21) Ruy Lopez 5.d4"]
[Black "5.d4 exd4 6.e5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. d4 {The primary advantage of this line is that White can almost guarantee it against 1...e5 (excepting the Berlin of course). Black is completely fine, but we do need to know a little bit. I used it as a surprise to beat David Anton in the 2022 Chessable Masters, but if we're prepared, we have our full share of the chances.} 
5. exd4
6. e5 {Premature.} 
6. Ne4 {We have an improved version of the main line, as we've not yet committed our bishop.} 
7. Nxd4 {A bad mistake.} 
7. Nxf2 {Boom. White's suddenly in a lot of trouble.} 
8. Kxf2 {8.Nxc6bxc69.Kxf2Qh4+and we regain our piece with interest.} 
8. Qh4+ {This reminds me of the Fried Liver Attack. We sacrifice a piece to winkle out White's king.} 
9. Ke3 {White's only practical try.9.g3Qxd4regains the piece.} 
9. b5 {We don't want to allow White to exchange with Bxc6.} 
10. Nxc6
10. dxc6 {White doesn't have time to save the bishop.} 
11. Bb3
11. Bc5+ {It's immediate mate.} 
12. Kd3
12. Qd4+
13. Ke2
13. Bg4+ {White can safely resign or allows us to deliver the mate on the next move.} 
