[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. d4 {The primary advantage of this line is that White can almost guarantee it against 1...e5 (excepting the Berlin of course). Black is completely fine, but we do need to know a little bit. I used it as a surprise to beat David Anton in the 2022 Chessable Masters, but if we're prepared, we have our full share of the chances.} 
5. exd4
6. O-O {White has to be careful with their move order. It's correct to wait for the bishop to develop to e7.} 
6. Be7 {We block the e-file, and so prepare to take on e4. If you want to go into unchartered territory, then6...h6is probably not so bad, but White will get an improved version of various gambits.} 
7. Re1 {Historically the most common move, but White can no longer equalize. The idea is to play e4-e5 without allowing ...Ne4.} 
7. b5 {But we get to move first.} 
8. Bb3
8. d6 {We take the e5-square under control. We're ready to develop with ...Bg4.} 
9. Bd5 {The forcing approach. White wants to regain that pawn.} 
9. Nxd5
10. exd5
10. Ne5 {A strong central square. White has to bypass our knight, as11.Nxe5?!dxe512.Rxe5O-Ois fantastic for us. We'replaying ...Bf6 next, and so the d4-pawn is safe, but the one on d5 will drop immediately. We'll be a clear pawn up. Coupling that with our bishop pair, we're more or less winning already.} 
11. Nxd4
11. O-O {Our king makes it to safety. There's been quite a lot of action here, but Black's results have been very good, and the theoretical consensus is that we're just better. We have the useful advantage of the bishop pair. White's unable to make anything of the c6-outpost, and so the pawn on d5 turns out to simply be a weakness.  By the way, if you're suddenly really worried about the Nc6 jump then ...c7-c5 is usually a good antidote, forcing the knight to retreat or to capture en-passant. Either way, they lose access to the c6-square.} 
12. f4 {Forcing our knight away is of course very logical, but it doesn't work.} 
12. Bg4 {Developing with tempo.} 
13. Qd2
13. Nc4 {And again with tempo.} 
14. Qd3
14. Bf6 {We move away from the fork just in time. Next, we'll play ...Re8. White's king is very vulnerable, and they've forgotten to develop their queenside.} 
