8. e5 {The more forcing continuation.} 
8. Nxe5 {The right knight to exchange. White can now choose how to recapture.} 
9. Rxe5 {Taking with the rook is more active. White wants to use the knight to capture on d4.} 
9. d6 {We could also start by taking the bishop, but I'd prefer to first expel the rook. White needs to be extremely careful here, or can quickly be much worse.} 
10. Rg5 {Going after the g-pawn is tempting, but the rook is running low on squares.} 
10. bxa4
11. Rxg7
11. Nh5 {Immediately collecting the rook.} 
12. Rg5 {The only attempt at compensation. Our bishop is clearly a better piece than our knight.} 
12. Bxg5
13. Bxg5
13. Qd7 {Now we want to meet14.Nxd4with14...Qg4.} 
14. Qxd4
14. O-O {A move that sometimes confuses people as to whether it's legal. You're not allowed to castle into, out of, or through a check, but when it's just the rook attacked it's completely fine. Our king looks a bit loose, but White is not able to take advantage. We have complete control on the light squares.} 
15. h3 {The only move played. White wants to prevent ...Qg4.} 
15. Bb7 {We followed Rogers-Howell, London 1988. Next, we can plug the holes with ...f7-f6.} 
