[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6
5. d4 {The primary advantage of this line is that White can almost guarantee it against 1...e5 (excepting the Berlin of course). Black is completely fine, but we do need to know a little bit. I used it as a surprise to beat David Anton in the 2022 Chessable Masters, but if we're prepared, we have our full share of the chances.} 
5. exd4
6. O-O {White has to be careful with their move order. It's correct to wait for the bishop to develop to e7.} 
6. Be7 {We block the e-file, and so prepare to take on e4. If you want to go into unchartered territory, then6...h6is probably not so bad, but White will get an improved version of various gambits.} 
7. e5 {White should continue forcing matters.} 
7. Ne4 {The most accurate circuit. The bishop won't be able to run from our knight on c5.} 
8. Re1 {A logical move. White continues prodding our knight.} 
8. Nc5 {But now we're collecting the bishop.} 
9. Bxc6
9. dxc6 {Once the d-pawn disappears, we have the Berlin Endgame structure. This is a clearly improved version. We haven't had to lose time by capturing on d8 with our king, and our knight is on a much better circuit on c5 rather than f5.   It's quite instructive to realize how big a concession it was playing e4-e5. With the pawn back on e4, White would have a safer pawn and control of the f5-square, which makes it harder for us to develop our light-squared bishop. Here we're already a little better.} 
10. Nxd4 {White has to make it as difficult as possible for us to develop our bishop.10.Qxd4Bf5and we're already clearly better.} 
10. Ne6 {Challenging White's knight. They're not going to be able to prevent our bishop from developing forever. Our plan is to exchange followed by ...Be6. We'll then play ...Qd7 and castle queenside.Starting with10...h5!?is also interesting. The positions will be extremely similar after alater ...Ne6. The pawn advance is pretty useful.} 
11. Nf5
11. Qxd1
12. Rxd1
12. Bf8 {A funny-looking move, but we want to keep our bishop pair. Our Berlin position is rock solid. We can afford to spend some time to keep all our advantages.} 
13. Nc3
13. h5 {A thematic Berlin advance. One of White's key ideas is to advance the kingside pawns. We preempt that and prepare to develop our rook via h5. If I glanced at this position, I'd swear it came from the Berlin Endgame, but another big improvement is that we're still allowed to castle; ...Bd7 and ...O-O-O is another sensible plan.} 
