5. Bxc6 {A curious decision. It was logical to capture on c6 on the previous move, when the bishop was attacked. There's also some sense to do it on the next move (after 5...Be7 or 5...Bc5). That's because our bishop wants to develop to d6, so it would at least cost Black another tempo. White's argument is that the knight is misplaced on f6, but that's a minor price to pay.} 
5. dxc6
6. O-O
6. Nxe4 {We should be very happy to open the position for our bishops. White would much prefer to keep their e-pawn over the one on the d-file. In the endgame, White can hope to make something of their 4 vs. 3 on the kingside. It's then easier to create a passed pawn. Now there's no longer a reason why White should have the better structure.} 
7. Re1 {7.d4Be7will come to the same thing. When our knight is attacked,we'll still drop it back to d6. Sethuraman points out that7.Qe2is inaccurate, as it gives us an additional route with7...Ng5followedby ...Ne6.} 
7. Nd6 {A better circuit for the knight. Now we'll find it easier to fight for control of the d4-square.} 
8. Nxe5
8. Be7
9. d4
9. O-O {White's position looks reasonable, but we're extremely solid and have our typical long-term trump of the bishop pair. We'll put our rook on the e-file, drop the bishop back and then expel the knight with ...f7-f6.} 
