[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Bxc6 {White's only realistic alternative to dropping back to a4. I suppose4.Bc4is possible,but ...a7-a6 will always be useful in the Italian.} 
4. dxc6 {The Exchange Spanish. White gives up the bishop pair for a slight lead in development and the nominally better structure. It used to be considered that Black had to be careful. White's plan is to exchange everything and win the king and pawn endgame. But the rise of the Berlin demonstrated that Black actually has little to fear in most endgames.} 
5. d4 {White wants to get the queens off the board immediately. The downside is that we haven't had to spend any time defending the e-pawn.} 
5. exd4
6. Qxd4 {6.Nxd4allowing6...c5followedby the queen exchange on d1 is not an improvement.} 
6. Qxd4
7. Nxd4
7. Bd7 {We'll analyze this structure a fair bit, but this is a pretty good version. White could have had O-O and Bg5 for free. Next, we'll castle, we should just investigate White's alternatives to castling kingside.} 
8. Be3 {Starting with8.Nc3is unlikely to be very different. We'll castle anyway.} 
8. O-O-O {White finds it very tough to do anything at all with their position, while we have plenty of useful improving moves. We'll combine putting our knight on g6 with putting pressure against the e4-pawn and advancing our h-pawn.} 
9. Nc3 {In case of9.Nd2, we'll play a similar plan as against 9.Nc3:9...Ne7. We'll put a rookon e8 and the knight on h4. White's kingside majority isn't that safe.} 
9. Re8 {We immediately eye the e-pawn; ...Bb4 is a big threat.} 
10. f3
10. Bb4
11. Nde2
11. f5 {White's position is starting to crumble.} 
