1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Bxc6 {White's only realistic alternative to dropping back to a4. I suppose4.Bc4is possible,but ...a7-a6 will always be useful in the Italian.} 
4. dxc6 {The Exchange Spanish. White gives up the bishop pair for a slight lead in development and the nominally better structure. It used to be considered that Black had to be careful. White's plan is to exchange everything and win the king and pawn endgame. But the rise of the Berlin demonstrated that Black actually has little to fear in most endgames.} 
5. O-O
5. Qf6 {A sideline that's really in vogue. We defend the pawn and prepare to develop our knight via e7 to g6. The plan is to castle queenside. If White plays slowly, we're able to generate very quick kingside attacks.5...f6is the main line.6.d4exd47.Nxd4and here it's quite difficult to castle queenside. Black tends to play7...c5and exchange queens. As Kramnik observes, Black should be okay, but White has some small pressure.7...Qd6!?is the recent choice in Solak-Shankland, Chennai 2022. Sam switches back to the plan of castling queenside against the Exchange Spanish.} 
6. d3
6. Ne7 {We're bringing our knight round to g6. It supports the e5-square and also starts to threaten ...Bg4 and ...Nh4.} 
7. Nbd2 {We'll play the same way against7.Be3too.} 
7. Ng6 {Continuing our thematic play7...c5and7...Bg4!?are legitimate alternatives.} 
8. Nc4 {White's automatic move, but a step in the wrong direction.} 
8. Bg4 {White has to watch out to hold onto their kingside.} 
9. Ne3 {9.h3is better, but we're still happy with the swap.} 
9. Bxf3
10. Qxf3
10. Qxf3
11. gxf3
11. Nh4 {White has to either drop the f3-pawn or allow their structure to be destroyed with12.Nf5Nxf5.} 
