5. Qf6 {A sideline that's really in vogue. We defend the pawn and prepare to develop our knight via e7 to g6. The plan is to castle queenside. If White plays slowly, we're able to generate very quick kingside attacks.5...f6is the main line.6.d4exd47.Nxd4and here it's quite difficult to castle queenside. Black tends to play7...c5and exchange queens. As Kramnik observes, Black should be okay, but White has some small pressure.7...Qd6!?is the recent choice in Solak-Shankland, Chennai 2022. Sam switches back to the plan of castling queenside against the Exchange Spanish.} 
6. d4 {White tends to expand in the center. Otherwise, White struggles to come up with a plan.} 
6. exd4 {White will be able to gain time on our queen here, but the bishop won't be particularly impressive on g5. We'll soon force it to move.} 
7. Nxd4
7. Bd7 {This is the principal advantage of5...Qf6over the old main line of5...f6. We find it very easy to castle queenside. If White wants to play this way, then they shouldfirst include Bg5 and ...Qd6.} 
8. Nc3
8. O-O-O {The position is already quite difficult with the annoying pin. White will probably play Be3 but then ...Nh6 both threatens ...Ng4 and supports a later ...f7-f5.} 
