6. exd4 {White will be able to gain time on our queen here, but the bishop won't be particularly impressive on g5. We'll soon force it to move.} 
7. e5
7. Qg6 {We've already discussed that pushing the pawn to e5 is a big concession. The pawn itself becomes weaker, but the primary drawback is losing control of the light squares. As White has already exchanged their light-squared bishop, this is very risky.} 
8. Nxd4 {Taking with the queen is better but we'll shunt it away with ...c6-c5. We'll then castle queenside, developing our bishop to either e6 or, if necessary, d7 to block the d-file.} 
8. Bh3 {Developing with a mating threat.} 
9. Qf3
9. Bg4 {And then gaining time on White's queen.} 
10. Qg3
10. O-O-O {And now against White's knight; ...Ne7 comes next.} 
