5. Qf6 {A sideline that's really in vogue. We defend the pawn and prepare to develop our knight via e7 to g6. The plan is to castle queenside. If White plays slowly, we're able to generate very quick kingside attacks.5...f6is the main line.6.d4exd47.Nxd4and here it's quite difficult to castle queenside. Black tends to play7...c5and exchange queens. As Kramnik observes, Black should be okay, but White has some small pressure.7...Qd6!?is the recent choice in Solak-Shankland, Chennai 2022. Sam switches back to the plan of castling queenside against the Exchange Spanish.} 
6. d4 {White tends to expand in the center. Otherwise, White struggles to come up with a plan.} 
6. exd4 {White will be able to gain time on our queen here, but the bishop won't be particularly impressive on g5. We'll soon force it to move.} 
7. Bg5 {Most natural. After all, White gains a tempo on our queen and temporarily prevents us from castling queenside. However, the critical test involves White returning the bishop to e3, so they're not actually gaining much time.} 
7. Qd6
8. Nxd4 {With the bishop already developed, this is a much better version.} 
8. Be7 {We still want to castle queenside. Question time for White. Exchanging has been shown to be very comfortable, so the recent trend is to drop back.} 
9. Bxe7
9. Nxe7 {Here, the key thing to remember is that our king still wants to go long. In the early kick-off for the final round of the Olympiad, I was a bit befuddled and suffered after castling kingside.} 
10. Nc3
10. Bd7 {This development plan should look familiar by now. White finds it tough to do anything when they have to defend their d4-knight, so they always drop it back somewhere.} 
11. Nde2 {A better route for White's knight.} 
11. O-O-O {White's queen is boxed in by the e2-knight. Therefore, we're not worried about keeping the queens on the board.} 
12. Qc1
12. Ng6
13. Qe3
13. b6 {Again, just make sure that White doesn't penetrate with Qa7. With ...Rhe8, we'll have harmonious development.} 
