[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24) Ruy Lopez: Early alternatives − Conclusion"]
[Black "Conclusion: Spanish − White's Early Alternatives"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {We wrapped up our coverage of the Ruy Lopez with a look into White’s early alternatives.5.Nc3is quite topical, when I recommend following Levon Aronian with5...d6!?. A practical benefit is that White’s most common move,6.d4?!, is already an error. If White plays correctly, we reach positions that are very similar to the6.Bxc6+section of the Steinitz Deferred. Try to understand the difference between White having castled and putting the knight on c3.  The setups with an early5.Qe2remain popular at the club level, but I believe the queen is misplaced here. We can either play our usual setups or defuse it simply with5...b56.Bb3Bc5.  The5.d4Spanish turned out to be the biggest section by far. White isn’t close to an advantage, but play is very forcing. Unfortunately, we aren’t able to play our usual setup. Still, if we’re well prepared, we can put a lot of pressure on White’s position.  We finished by examining the Exchange Variations,4.Bxc6. Taking on move five,5.Bxc6, is odd. I don’t believe theextra ...Nf6 can really be a liability. Our setup with bishops on e6 and d6 and castling queenside is straightforward and gives us very good chances.The pure Exchange is more serious. There I recommend the topical5...Qf6!?. It looks strange to move the queen so early, especially when White can gain timewith a subsequent Bg5. The point is that we want to castle queenside. There are a lot of very similar queenless middlegames, but in all of them, White lacks a plan. Despite its drawish reputation, I believe we have very good chances to outplay our opponents.} 1. --
