8. Ba6 {Dropping back with8...Nb6is another heavily debated line, but I prefer the pin. White won't find it so easy to both develop their pieces and hold onto the e-pawn.} 
9. g3 {White can start with this move.} 
9. g6 {White should now make haste with the other fianchetto and transpose with10.b3, as10.Bg2Bg7will already leave it a bit too late to hold onto the central pawns. White's alternatives will be examined later in the chapter.} 
