11. Bb2 {The pawn needs defending. It's too late for11.f4?. After11...f6!, White's position already collapses.} 
11. O-O {There's a big question, which side of the board should we castle? It's very likely to reach the same endgame, although going queenside allows White a couple of additional setups. For a while, it was considered that the king was better on c8 than g8, but I don't think it changes the evaluation. I decided to be consistent and generally choose to go short. We're less likely to get muddled by tricky move orders.} 
12. Nd2 {A move I somewhat naively played twice. Despite the fact I scored 2/2 against two strong GMs, it's not to be recommended.} 
12. d6 {These days Stockfish 15 already gives Black a clear advantage. I don't think that was the case back in 2009.} 
13. Qe4 {My over-the-board attempt in Jones-Smeets, London 2009. It worked as Jan erred with13...Nb4?!and I actually won quite quickly.} 
13. Bxe5 {Boom! This is an incredibly difficult tactic to find over the board, but White's already losing. Somewhat surprisingly, White fell for this in a relatively recent correspondence game.} 
14. cxd5 {The route of the correspondence game.} 
14. cxd5 {White cannot vacate the e-file, and so there's only one square to choose from.} 
15. Qe3 {But here it looks like we've miscalculated. We're a piece down, the one on a6 is hanging, and the other bishop is pinned.} 
15. Bxb2 {A fantastic queen sacrifice. It turns out we'll recoup all our invested material.} 
16. Qxe7
16. Rfe8 {The other rook was chosen in Horak-Baciak, ICCF email 2017, but I don't think it makes any difference.} 
17. Qxe8+
17. Rxe8+
18. Kd1 {I can imagine not knowing how to assess this one with the clock ticking, but the engines are already chalking up the victory.} 
18. Bxf1 {We have to take this one first. Now, if White simply recaptures, we'll be two pawns up in the endgame.} 
19. Rb1
19. Be2+ {Saving one bishop.} 
20. Kc2
20. Bd4 {And the other. Material is level: two pawns for the exchange. But White's position is resignable. White's pieces cannot coordinate in the slightest.} 
21. f4 {Otherwise, the pawn drops.} 
21. Re3 {...Rc3+ will be decisive.} 
