11. O-O {There's a big question, which side of the board should we castle? It's very likely to reach the same endgame, although going queenside allows White a couple of additional setups. For a while, it was considered that the king was better on c8 than g8, but I don't think it changes the evaluation. I decided to be consistent and generally choose to go short. We're less likely to get muddled by tricky move orders.} 
12. Bg2 {The most natural, and by far White's main try.} 
12. Rae8 {We're back at the main line. It's generally considered that this is the correct rook. That's because White might otherwise be able to capture on d5 with tempo on our a8-rook. Shankland gives the other rook to e8 an exclamation mark, but it's a matter of taste.} 
13. O-O {It's too late to hold onto the e5-pawn.13.f4?!f6would see White in a lot of trouble.} 
13. Bxe5 {Time to take. We can't allow White time to consolidate with14.Re1. Now we get lots of exchanges.} 
14. Qxe5 {Taking with the bishop first comes to the same thing.} 
14. Qxe5
15. Bxe5
15. Rxe5 {Time for the first pause. White can now play the intermezzo16.f4!?. We'll respond16...Re3, but we'll cover it via the 18.f4 move order.} 
16. cxd5
16. Bxf1
17. Kxf1
17. cxd5 {This endgame, or something extremely similar, has been debated many times through the years. We have a rook and two pawns for the bishop and knight, traditionally a slight material advantage, but the presence of the second rook favors White. If we can exchange one pair of rooks we'll be extremely happy.  Our general plan is to play ...c7-c6 to support the d5-pawn, followed by combining activating our rooks and bringing our king to its ideal location on d6. White will try to provoke weaknesses in our position and find a firm outpost for the knight.  Despite playing the Scotch for many years, my only experience of this endgame is from Black's side. I think it's extremely difficult for White to play. In recent years, the strongest player to consistently defend White has been Rustam Kasimdzhanov. Notably, his only victory came on as Black, with 0/3 for White since 2021.} 
18. f4 {White wants one pawn back immediately, but they now struggle to develop their queenside. This forcing route was Magnus Carlsen's attempt, way back in the mists of time (2010).} 
18. Re3 {We could also have reached this position had White started with16.f4. We're preventing White from developing the knightto c3 and hoping to reach the back rank via d3.} 
19. Bxd5 {Otherwise, there was no point in shunting our rook away. White has regained one pawn, but the pieces are now placed precariously.} 
19. Rd3 {The most combative move. We both attack the bishop and threaten to leave White in an infinite pin with ...Rd1+. This position is the reason it's considered preferable to play the a-rook to e8. Had we started with12...Rfe8, our rook would now be attacked. While19...Rfe8is also fine, the text puts a lot more pressure on White's position.} 
20. Bf3 {White absolutely has to know this move.} 
20. Re8 {We threaten to take the bishop now that White cannot play Ke2. By the way, it's a moot point whether we could actually have fallen into White's trap and taken on f3. After20...Rxf3+21.Ke2, our rook is trapped, but it's not clear whether White can actually escape the pin after21...Re8+22.Kxf3Re1. Still, there's no reason to play for a draw in such a cowardly fashion.} 
21. Kf2 {The only way to defend the bishop and keep control of the d1-square.} 
21. Kf8 {Black has tried many different moves here, but this one makes the most sense to me. We're just getting ready to activate our king. If White sits, we'll next advance with ...d7-d5.} 
22. Na3 {This succeeds in developing the knight but also looks rather miserable.} 
22. Rd2+ {Okay, we didn't get the back rank, but a rook on the seventh is pretty powerful too.} 
23. Kg1
23. d5 {The knight on a3 cannot truthfully be described as well-placed. White would like to activate the rook, but it cannot leave the back rank without allowing mate.} 
24. Nb5
24. c5 {We're getting ready to create a passed pawn.} 
25. Nc7
25. Re3 {Our pawn is safe.26.Bxd5?Re7collects a piece. White's best is26.Rf1. We'll then exchangethe a2-pawn for the one on d5. White has to capture with the bishop to protect the b3-pawn, but we can then double on the second rank. It seems White has to allow a pair of rooks to be exchanged, and then suffer to hold the endgame. I'm a bit perplexed why White would go anywhere near this whole variation!} 
