18. Nc3 {White's main move. White logically attacks the d5-pawn. However, the knight might not be on the best route.} 
18. c6 {We defend the pawn. We don't want to push unless we have a concrete follow-up. The c6 and d5-pawns are doing a fantastic job blunting White's bishop. White has a few different setups they can employ here, but ...Rb8 works well against all of them.  We have ideas of activating our rook via b4. Remember, we'd be very happy to exchange rooks if White plays the rook to d4. White can try bringing the knight around to c5 when we should normally defend the pawn with ...Re7. We don't want to create any weaknesses. It may look passive for a move or two, but our king is coming to the center to give the pawn support.} 
19. Rd1 {White's usual continuation. They develop the rook. They'd like to activate it via d4, but that's not very practical when the e1-square is unguarded.} 
19. Rb8 {A good approach generally, and also the one recommended by Vladimir Kramnik.} 
20. Bf3 {White both gives their king an escape square and defends the e2-square.} 
20. Rb4 {We get to the fourth rank before White. White is deprived of a plan. If the knight hops around to c5, we'll just drop back with ...Re7. That defends the pawn and prevents the fork on d3. We can advance with ...f7-f5, ...a7-a5, and bring our king into the game, either via g7-f6 or f8-e7/e8. Objectively, the position remains equal, but White has to sit and await developments.} 
