[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27) Scotch Old Main Line 10.f4"]
[Black "10.f4 g5 11.f5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. d4
3. exd4
4. Nxd4
4. Nf6
5. Nxc6
5. bxc6
6. e5
6. Qe7
7. Qe2
7. Nd5
8. c4 {The most common move order. Note that White has quite a few different move orders. Kasimdzhanov prefers8.g3, transposing after8...g69.c4Ba610.b3. This was also my own try in a recent game against Ivan Cheparinov.} 
8. Ba6 {Dropping back with8...Nb6is another heavily debated line, but I prefer the pin. White won't find it so easy to both develop their pieces and hold onto the e-pawn.} 
9. b3 {The most efficient way to give White's pawns more support. The c-pawn is now safely defended, and the bishop can support the e-pawn via b2. White also has ideas of Ba3 attacking our queen.} 
9. g6 {Our bishop belongs on the long diagonal. Not only will we threaten the e-pawn, but White's rook could also be in trouble.I remember there being a trend for9...g5after its use in the 1995 World Championship match between Kasparov and Anand. Its popularity abated,as it was discovered White has some dangerous ideas involving h2-h4.White now has a big choice.10.f4and10.Bb2are two main lines, while10.Ba3!?became quite topical in the past couple of years. We'll examine those next. Finally,10.Nd2will be covered via the earlier9.Nd2.} 
10. f4 {Historically, this is the absolute main line. White supports the e5-pawn and prepares to sidestep with Qf2.} 
10. g5 {This was first played by the Ukrainian genius, Vasyl Ivanchuk, back in 2002, but I believe it was a recommendation of Garry Kasparov. The former World Champion was certainly the strongest player to play the Scotch regularly, and so we have to take his suggestions extremely seriously.  It looks odd to move the pawn a second time, but we're attempting to blow open the center before White gets their king to safety. I remember a Magnus Carlsen interview. I can't recall the exact phrase, but the gist was that if a king could get to safety in two moves, then the position is probably safe, but if it takes three to castle, then an attack is likely to succeed.  Here it will take White at least three tempi to castle on either side of the board − already extremely risky! I won't go quite as far as saying this refutes White's setup, but it is extremely difficult to play. In correspondence, White is holding, but we have all the practical chances.10...d6is the main line. This also looks rosy for Black, but it's what White is presumably hoping for. There are a couple of very forcing lines where Black needs to be careful.} 
11. f5 {It looks logical to keep the center and try to prevent ...Bg7, but White's position is now rather too loose.} 
11. O-O-O {Job achieved. The e-pawn is no longer defended and White's queen is tied down.} 
12. Ba3 {Our queen can no longer enter via c5, but this costs White some time.} 
12. Qe8 {We can't play ...Qc5 or ...Re8 anymore, but we still have plenty of ways to target White's position. The dark squares are so vulnerable.} 
13. g3
13. Bxa3 {Allowing the bishops to be exchanged just increases White's woes.} 
14. Nxa3
14. Qe7 {We gain a tempo on the knight.} 
15. Nc2
15. Rhe8 {And we're getting ready to collect the e-pawn.} 
