12. Nd2 {The correct way to develop.} 
12. Qxg5 {Back to material equality.} 
13. Nf3 {This is why it was more accurate to start with the knight. White can compete on the c1-h6 diagonal for now.} 
13. Qg4 {13...Qg6also sets White some practical problems. To be honest, I'm not sure when we'd actually get this position. It already seems so unattractive for White, but if they hadn't prepared deeply, then they'd have played an inferior earlier sideline.  White has been successful in holding draws in correspondence chess, but with a few losses and no wins. We have plenty of interesting ideas, and White has to find a perfect defense everywhere.} 
14. Bd2 {The best try. White wants to control the c3-square. Now they're ready to play Qf2.The immediate14.Qf2ran into14...Nc3!followed by ...Ne4. By the way, we don't generally need to be worried about White grabbing on a7 in the Scotch. It looks scary, but dropping the bishop back to b7 keeps our king perfectly safe. White cannot afford the tempi to go pawn-grabbing.} 
14. Rg8 {We put more pressure on the g2-square preparing our knight jump. The dynamic14...f6!?is also fun.} 
15. Qf2 {White wants the knight to budge.15.O-O-OBa3+16.Kb1c5doesn't look like much fun. We have one bad piece,the a6-bishop, but that's ready to re-enter via b7.} 
15. Nf4 {Attacking the g-pawn.} 
16. g3 {White's dark squares are vulnerable enough already. They certainly shouldn't exchange their bishop.} 
16. Ne6 {Our knight has found a safe harbor. Next, we'll probably play 17...Bc5, although 17...Re8 eyeing White's king is interesting too.After17.Be2Bc5, White really has to allow a draw with18.Be3Bb4+19.Bd2Bc5. We can also play on byexchanging on d2.I highly doubt you'll get this position unless you're playing high-level correspondence. In a practical game, White will play10.f4hoping for an idea after10...d6. They'll likely be thrown by10...g5. Without preparation, the chance White survives the opening is minuscule.} 
