4. Nxd4
4. Nf6
5. Nxc6
5. bxc6
6. e5
6. Qe7
7. Qe2
7. Nd5
8. c4 {The most common move order. Note that White has quite a few different move orders. Kasimdzhanov prefers8.g3, transposing after8...g69.c4Ba610.b3. This was also my own try in a recent game against Ivan Cheparinov.} 
8. Ba6 {Dropping back with8...Nb6is another heavily debated line, but I prefer the pin. White won't find it so easy to both develop their pieces and hold onto the e-pawn.} 
9. b3 {The most efficient way to give White's pawns more support. The c-pawn is now safely defended, and the bishop can support the e-pawn via b2. White also has ideas of Ba3 attacking our queen.} 
9. g6 {Our bishop belongs on the long diagonal. Not only will we threaten the e-pawn, but White's rook could also be in trouble.I remember there being a trend for9...g5after its use in the 1995 World Championship match between Kasparov and Anand. Its popularity abated,as it was discovered White has some dangerous ideas involving h2-h4.White now has a big choice.10.f4and10.Bb2are two main lines, while10.Ba3!?became quite topical in the past couple of years. We'll examine those next. Finally,10.Nd2will be covered via the earlier9.Nd2.} 
10. Ba3 {Brought to prominence by Garry Kasparov after playing it against Ivanchuk in 1994. I played it myself against Erwin L'Ami in Wijk aan Zee in 2017. I thought with the surprise value gone, this chapter of the Scotch had finished. However, Fabiano Caruana recently tried it against Wesley So (Wijk aan Zee, January 2023). Wesley found the correct response and made the draw from a position of strength.} 
10. Nb4 {The most aggressive and most popular response. We block the attack on our queen, move our knight from an attacked square, and prepare to break in the center ourselves. We also have a hidden trick.} 
11. Bb2 {White drops back immediately. It looks odd, but the e-pawn needed the support. White now argues our knight is misplaced on b4.} 
11. Bg7
12. a3 {White decides that they would prefer the knight back on d5.} 
12. Nd5 {After the bishop and knight dance, we've reached a position that's familiar from our first segment. The only difference is that White has an extra a2-a3. This is double-edged.White claims that we can no longer play ...Nb4, as we will against10.Bb2Bg711.Nd2.But the b3-pawn is now much weaker, and so we often have sacrificial attacks along the b-file.} 
13. Nd2 {White wants to castle quickly. After all, this is the main reason for having a2-a3 on the board.} 
13. O-O {King safely castled. Next, we'll target the e-pawn. With the kings about to be on opposite flanks, this is an extremely sharp position.} 
14. O-O-O {White could also start with14.g3but after14...Rfe8, there is nothing better than transposing with15.O-O-O.} 
14. Rfe8 {We eye the e-pawn. We're not yet threatening to take as our knight hangs, but we do threaten ...Nf4 followed by capturing.Note: this line appears to have been worked out to a draw. If you want to deviate, then14...Rab8!?is a good alternative.15.h4Rfe8is a fresher, extremely double-edged position.} 
15. g3 {Tried in Landa-Leko, Sochi 2012. The former World Champion challenger dropped the knight back.} 
15. d6 {But we can open the center immediately. The threat is to capture on e5 with the bishop. After the exchange, ...dxe5 will attack the a-pawn, another downside to the earlier a2-a3.} 
16. Qf3
16. Nb6
17. exd6
17. Bxb2+
18. Kxb2
18. cxd6 {White isn't yet lost, it's just rather unpleasant with the weaker king.} 
19. Qxc6 {The pawn is poisoned.} 
19. Bb7 {The other rook drops.} 
