10. Ba3 {Brought to prominence by Garry Kasparov after playing it against Ivanchuk in 1994. I played it myself against Erwin L'Ami in Wijk aan Zee in 2017. I thought with the surprise value gone, this chapter of the Scotch had finished. However, Fabiano Caruana recently tried it against Wesley So (Wijk aan Zee, January 2023). Wesley found the correct response and made the draw from a position of strength.} 
10. d6 {A decent low memorization approach, especially if your opponent thrives in chaos.} 
11. exd6 {White really has to capture this now, as we were ready to play ...Bg7.11.Qe4?fails to the typical11...f5!} 
11. Qxe2+
12. Bxe2
12. Bg7 {The point. Black's position looks disastrous, but we're collecting the trapped rook.} 
13. cxd5
13. Bxe2 {Most sensible, but Stockfish 15 makes a case for13...Bb5!?, with the favoriteevaluation of 0.00. The rook isn't going anywhere after all.} 
14. Kxe2
14. Bxa1 {A strange-looking endgame. We're currently the exchange for a pawn up, but White will probably win a pawn back in the d-pawn versus c-pawn fight.} 
15. Rc1 {White's only way to maintain equality. They should capture on c6 with the rook. A pawn on c6 looks promising, but after we castle queenside, it wouldn't get any further. Meanwhile, our rooks would thrive on the open e- and d-files.} 
15. O-O-O {An accurate response. Capturing on d6 would be inaccurate, as the pawn would become a liability.} 
16. f4 {Another precise move.16.Rxc6Rd7is still equal, but I believe it's Black who can press. Indeed both Wei Yi and Samuel Sevian defeated Iranian GM Pouya Idani here.} 
16. c5 {Blocking White's rook. As the d-pawn is hanging, White has to capture with the bishop.} 
17. Bxc5
17. Kb7 {We've been following my game with Erwin: Jones-L'Ami, Wijk aan Zee 2017. I tried pressing for a while, but Erwin held firm and we made a draw. I would slightly prefer to be White, but the position is equal. With the material imbalance, both sides have chances to win.} 
