[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. d4
3. exd4
4. Nxd4
4. Nf6
5. Nxc6
5. bxc6
6. e5
6. Qe7
7. Qe2
7. Nd5
8. h4 {Probably White's most interesting try at the time of writing. I used it myself to beat Esipenko in the French Team Championships in 2022. White can't claim an advantage, but the positions are highly complex.  This is Sethuraman's recommendation in his Lifetime Repertoire on the Scotch. It's something of a useful waiting move. One idea is to take control of the g5-square, perhaps to develop the bishop there. Another crucial idea is to swing the rook via h3-e3. I've added a couple of informational lines to try and demonstrate what White is hoping for.} 
8. f6 {The other main line.} 
9. c4
9. Ba6 {Or9...Nb610.exf6, when White has the better structure once again.} 
10. Rh3 {This is basically the whole point of 8.h4 and the reason it became trendy. The rook is getting ready to swing to a3 or e3, with a wildly irrational position. Black has three main moves here.10...fxe5is possible but pretty risky. White develops with tempo with11.Bg5.10...O-O-O11.Ra3is another bizarre line. It continues11...Nb412.Ra4, when our knight and bishop are a bit clumsy. I believe it's equal but both sides have to take care.10...Nb6was my choice against Ivan Cheparinov and also played by Andrey Esipenko against me. White then has a choice of their own.11.exf6was Ivan's choice, reaching a very complex ending, while I played the interesting sacrifice11.Nd2!?. These lines are fascinating, but they allow White to justify the early rook pawn advance.} 
