8. h4 {Probably White's most interesting try at the time of writing. I used it myself to beat Esipenko in the French Team Championships in 2022. White can't claim an advantage, but the positions are highly complex.  This is Sethuraman's recommendation in his Lifetime Repertoire on the Scotch. It's something of a useful waiting move. One idea is to take control of the g5-square, perhaps to develop the bishop there. Another crucial idea is to swing the rook via h3-e3. I've added a couple of informational lines to try and demonstrate what White is hoping for.} 
8. Qe6 {We react with something of a waiting move too. We get out of the way of the bishop. If White does nothing, we'll play either ...d7-d6 or ...Bc5. Just be careful. We'll now meet c2-c4 by moving our knight. We can no longer pin, as cxd5 will attack our queen. We have a lot of options here.Ivan Cheparinov was one of the early proponents of this variation. When we played I chose the other main line,8...f6, and that was also Esipenko's choice against me. That is also fine, but a bit more forcing. I think our choice is a bit tougher for White to play logically against.} 
9. g3 {The choice of the rising star Nodirbek Abdusattorov in a couple of blitz games.} 
