[White "31) Scotch: The topical 8.h4!?"]
[Black "8.h4 Qe6 9.Nd2 #4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. d4
3. exd4
4. Nxd4
4. Nf6
5. Nxc6
5. bxc6
6. e5
6. Qe7
7. Qe2
7. Nd5
8. h4 {Probably White's most interesting try at the time of writing. I used it myself to beat Esipenko in the French Team Championships in 2022. White can't claim an advantage, but the positions are highly complex.  This is Sethuraman's recommendation in his Lifetime Repertoire on the Scotch. It's something of a useful waiting move. One idea is to take control of the g5-square, perhaps to develop the bishop there. Another crucial idea is to swing the rook via h3-e3. I've added a couple of informational lines to try and demonstrate what White is hoping for.} 
8. Qe6 {We react with something of a waiting move too. We get out of the way of the bishop. If White does nothing, we'll play either ...d7-d6 or ...Bc5. Just be careful. We'll now meet c2-c4 by moving our knight. We can no longer pin, as cxd5 will attack our queen. We have a lot of options here.Ivan Cheparinov was one of the early proponents of this variation. When we played I chose the other main line,8...f6, and that was also Esipenko's choice against me. That is also fine, but a bit more forcing. I think our choice is a bit tougher for White to play logically against.} 
9. Nd2 {Sethuraman's recommendation. White leaves the kingside for the time being.} 
9. a5 {We want to play ...Ba6.9...d6is fine if you don't want to memorize any more theory, but I think the position is a little easier for White.After an exchange on d6 and a swap of queens, White has the better structure. With the pawn back on g2, we don't have the ...f7-f5-f4 counterplay. It's not yet established what White's best continuation is here.} 
10. c4 {Forcing our knight to make a decision.} 
10. Nb6 {Let's just drop back. Defending with11.b3isn't effective, when we can respond with11...a4.10...Nb4is also interesting, but White seems to be doing okay in the mess after11.Nf3Qg612.h5!We're going touse the b4-square for our bishop instead. We also have ideas of simply pushing ...d7-d5, and even ...a5-a4 and ...Ra5 going after the weak e-pawn. This position is already difficult for White. Those c- and e-pawns are vulnerable.} 
11. h5 {Another rather random move, but I think this might actually be White's best try. One idea is easily understood: to attack with h5-h6. The second, a rather hidden idea, is to be able to defend the c-pawn with a later Rh4.} 
11. h6 {Let's prevent that pawn from getting any further. We'll then return to our ...Bb4 plan.} 
12. g3
12. Bb4
13. a3
13. Be7 {But a slight difference now. That's because White was able to defend the c-pawn with Rh4. Instead, we're happy to drop back. The move a2-a3 has weakened White's control of the b3-square, and by extension, the c4-pawn. The rest isn't necessary to memorize, but it's quite instructive how quickly Black got a fantastic position in a recent correspondence game.} 
14. b3
14. a4 {Note how Black gains time to activate their bishop.} 
15. b4
15. O-O
16. Bb2
16. c5 {Preparing to play ...Bb7.} 
17. Bg2
17. cxb4 {A strong exchange sacrifice. White will be left with extremely exposed light squares.} 
18. Bxa8
18. Nxa8
19. axb4
19. Bxb4
20. O-O
20. Bb7 {The attack down the long diagonal is ferocious. White decided they had to give back their extra material.} 
21. Ne4
21. f5
22. exf6
22. Qxe4
23. Qxe4
23. Bxe4 {Ledford-Velde, ICCF email 2021. The two minor pieces are stronger than the rook and pawn here, but White held the draw.} 
