13. Kd1 {The c2-square is taken safely under control but at a big price. White has surrendered their castling rights.} 
13. c5 {We give our knight an escape route and open up the long diagonal for our bishop. If White attacks our queen with h4-h5, we can also slide over to b6. This position is very sharp, but I think it's easier for us. We can play logical developing moves. With their king in the center, White has a much tougher job.} 
14. a3 {It seems to be more accurate to start with this. White wants the sixth rank blocked before they attack our queen.} 
14. Nc6
15. h5
15. Qe6 {With the b6-square out of bounds, we should stop here. We don't need to fear16.h6. We'll simply capture it. Our structure is compromised,but the g7-square is suddenly available for our bishop.} 
16. Bd2
16. Be7 {The position remains very sharp, but I think we can leave it here. Once we've developed our bishop, we don't need to worry about any Ng5 jumps, we can simply take it. We'll react to h5-h6 by playing ...g7-g6, while Bh3 can be met by ...f7-f5. We'll castle and then orchestrate breaking in the center and catching White's king.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "32) Scotch 6.e5: White's final sidelines 7+8"]
[Black "7.Bf4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. d4
3. exd4
4. Nxd4
4. Nf6
5. Nxc6
5. bxc6
6. e5
6. Qe7 {Here we'll wrap up White's early sidelines in the Mieses Variation (6.e5). With most of these White is well-advised to play a quick c2-c4 and transpose back into the main lines.  Such move orders can be attempted to trick Black out of their chosen defense, but our plan of the kingside fianchetto works well everywhere. White now needs to block in their bishop. They don't have a playable alternative to hold onto the e-pawn.} 
7. Bf4
