6. Qe7 {Here we'll wrap up White's early sidelines in the Mieses Variation (6.e5). With most of these White is well-advised to play a quick c2-c4 and transpose back into the main lines.  Such move orders can be attempted to trick Black out of their chosen defense, but our plan of the kingside fianchetto works well everywhere. White now needs to block in their bishop. They don't have a playable alternative to hold onto the e-pawn.} 
7. Qe2
7. Nd5
8. Nd2 {Perhaps the most interesting line with any independent significance. However, the delay of c2-c4 gives us more options than White. We now have the additional plan of rerouting our knight via f4 to e6.} 
8. g6 {Pushing the a-pawn is also interesting, but let's be consistent. White's most common (and best) continuation is9.c4, when we'll transpose back into the 9.Nd2 section with9...Ba6.9...Nf4!?is an interesting independent path too.} 
