8. Nd2 {Perhaps the most interesting line with any independent significance. However, the delay of c2-c4 gives us more options than White. We now have the additional plan of rerouting our knight via f4 to e6.} 
8. g6 {Pushing the a-pawn is also interesting, but let's be consistent. White's most common (and best) continuation is9.c4, when we'll transpose back into the 9.Nd2 section with9...Ba6.9...Nf4!?is an interesting independent path too.} 
9. Nf3
9. Bg7
10. c4 {White cannot do without this. But the move order idea is quite tricky. White has waited for us to play ...Bg7 before pushing the pawn. That means that10...Ba6isn't quite a transposition to the 9.Nd2 line.There we wanted ...Qb4+ instead of ...Bg7.} 
10. Nb6 {Unfortunately for the concept, I don't think White can equalize here.} 
11. Bg5 {It's logical to develop with tempo, but White forces our queen where it wants to go.} 
11. Qb4+ {A move we've seen crop up in a few variations. Blocking with a bishop or knight drops the b-pawn. This is why11.b3is a bit more tenacious.} 
12. Qd2 {12.Kd1?Na4is not what White wants.} 
12. a5 {We simply defend our queen. White doesn't want to exchange. Not only do we improve our structure, but the a2-pawn is suddenly under fire.} 
13. O-O-O
13. O-O {Van der Wiel-Savina, Antwerp 2011. White's opening had been a bit of a disaster. We're ready to open the center with ...d7-d5, while ...Ba6 attacking the c-pawn will also be a problem. These sidelines are generally not very impressive. White is trying to confuse us, but our typical plans work very well.} 
