[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. d4
3. exd4
4. Nxd4
4. Nf6 {In this chapter, we'll wrap up White's alternatives to going into the complexities of Mieses Variation (the proper Scotch). White's most serious move by far would be5.Nc3, but that is simply a direct transposition to the Scotch Four Knights covered elsewhere.} 
5. Nxc6 {The usual.} 
5. bxc6 {6.Nc3is an illogical move order. After6...Bb4, we'll be back in the Scotch Four Knights once again, while6...d5is a reasonable additional option.6.Bg5?!h6and6.f3?!d5fail the same way as they did on the previous move.} 
6. Qe2 {This is the most Scotch-like of the alternatives. White is trying to be tricky with their move order. A later e4-e5 will transpose back to the typical Mieses structure. This had a swell of popularity a decade or so ago, and I even tried it once. But it makes a strange impression to willingly block the f1-bishop out of the game.} 
6. d5 {The most aggressive response. One of the reasons this line dropped out of fashion is that we have so many promising paths.6...Rb8!?is an interesting waiting move endorsed by both Kramnik and Gustafsson. We tend to reach improved versions of Scotch main lines.Meanwhile,6...Bc5is Shankland's recommendation, intending to sacrifice the exchange after asubsequent e4-e5, Qg4, and Bh6. Both of these are very decent, but I decided to offer something a little different. We offer a couple of pawns to open up lines and punish White for willingly delaying castling.} 
7. e5 {Declining with7.Nc3isn't very impressive either. We'll simply develop with7...Be7. White has no business putting their queenon e2 in a Four Knights.} 
7. Nd7 {This is a massively improved main line for us. That e-pawn is very vulnerable.} 
8. Bf4 {White attempts to give the pawn more support.} 
8. Rb8 {Antal-Erdos, Hungary 2015. An opening disaster for the Hungarian GM. He opted for9.Nd2, simply giving up the b-pawn.} 
9. b3
9. Rb4 {The problem. Our rook threatens to decisively land on e4.} 
10. c4
10. dxc4
11. bxc4
11. Bc5 {White's position is way too loose.} 
