10. Be2 {The most natural, but the following is quite illustrative.10.Nc3Nb4was seen in a correspondence game. After11.Qxd8Nxc2+!?12.Kd2Rxd8+13.Kxc2Bf5+, they actually agreed to a draw, as White's king cannot escape. It's also possible to continue there with ongoing compensation for a pawn with11...Rxd8.} 
10. Nb4
11. Qd1 {Essential, but still not pleasant.} 
11. Qxd1+ {Our initiative continues.} 
12. Bxd1
12. Bf6 {We tie the c1-bishop down and prepare to check.} 
13. O-O {I can't see someone choosing a different move, but White is now in trouble.} 
13. Ba6 {White has to give up the exchange.} 
14. Re1
14. Rfe8 {Now it's far worse. The weak back rank and b2-pawn mean White cannot hold their position together.} 
