[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "33) Scotch: White's early alternatives"]
[Black "5.Nxc6 bxc6 6.Qe2 #8"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. d4
3. exd4
4. Nxd4
4. Nf6 {In this chapter, we'll wrap up White's alternatives to going into the complexities of Mieses Variation (the proper Scotch). White's most serious move by far would be5.Nc3, but that is simply a direct transposition to the Scotch Four Knights covered elsewhere.} 
5. Nxc6 {The usual.} 
5. bxc6 {6.Nc3is an illogical move order. After6...Bb4, we'll be back in the Scotch Four Knights once again, while6...d5is a reasonable additional option.6.Bg5?!h6and6.f3?!d5fail the same way as they did on the previous move.} 
6. Qe2 {This is the most Scotch-like of the alternatives. White is trying to be tricky with their move order. A later e4-e5 will transpose back to the typical Mieses structure. This had a swell of popularity a decade or so ago, and I even tried it once. But it makes a strange impression to willingly block the f1-bishop out of the game.} 
6. d5 {The most aggressive response. One of the reasons this line dropped out of fashion is that we have so many promising paths.6...Rb8!?is an interesting waiting move endorsed by both Kramnik and Gustafsson. We tend to reach improved versions of Scotch main lines.Meanwhile,6...Bc5is Shankland's recommendation, intending to sacrifice the exchange after asubsequent e4-e5, Qg4, and Bh6. Both of these are very decent, but I decided to offer something a little different. We offer a couple of pawns to open up lines and punish White for willingly delaying castling.} 
7. exd5+ {White should accept our gambit.} 
7. Be7
8. dxc6
8. O-O {First the bad news. We're two pawns down. But in return, we've already castled, and are about to put our rook on the open e-file. The only piece that White has moved is in the way, the queen will soon have to move again. In a worst-case scenario, White will figure out a way to get their king to safety but will have to allow an exchange on c3. The trebled c-pawns will no longer really count as extra pawns, they'll just drop one by one.} 
9. Qd3 {9.Qd2is also played but this is a more natural square. White is dreaming of the queen exchange.} 
9. Nd5 {An interesting plan exploiting the queen on d3. We’d react to9.Qd2with9...Bd6, which would also be fine here. But now we have ideas of ...Nb4 too, when the c2-pawn will be tough to defend.} 
10. Be2 {The most natural, but the following is quite illustrative.10.Nc3Nb4was seen in a correspondence game. After11.Qxd8Nxc2+!?12.Kd2Rxd8+13.Kxc2Bf5+, they actually agreed to a draw, as White's king cannot escape. It's also possible to continue there with ongoing compensation for a pawn with11...Rxd8.} 
10. Nb4
11. Qxd8 {With queens off, it can't get that bad, can it?} 
11. Nxc2+ {A strong intermezzo.} 
12. Kd1
12. Rxd8+
13. Kxc2
13. Bf5+ {We're a piece and pawn down and queens are exchanged, but White is completely lost.} 
14. Kc3
14. Rab8 {Building a box. Amazingly, the king cannot escape.} 
15. Rd1
15. Bf6+ {We now drag the king forward to its doom.} 
16. Kc4
16. Be6+
17. Kc5
17. Be7+ {Goodbye.} 
