5. bxc6 {6.Nc3is an illogical move order. After6...Bb4, we'll be back in the Scotch Four Knights once again, while6...d5is a reasonable additional option.6.Bg5?!h6and6.f3?!d5fail the same way as they did on the previous move.} 
6. Bd3
6. d5 {The thematic continuation.} 
7. exd5 {White tends to immediately clarify the center.} 
7. cxd5
8. O-O {8.Bg5is also tried, but we can then develop our bishop more activelyto d6. We'll be in time to castle before White gets in Re1.} 
8. Be7 {Now that White was threatening a check we should develop our bishop more modestly. White now needs to decide on their plan. They can immediately fight for the center with9.c4, play slowly with a combinationof Nd2, b2-b3, Bb2, and h2-h3, or transpose to some sort of non-critical Four Knights with9.Nc3.} 
9. c4 {The most challenging try.} 
9. O-O {Pushing with9...d4is also possible, but we don't need to fix the structure yet. We don't really need to worry about the exchange. White will have a fractionally better structure, but our activity will compensate.} 
10. Nc3
10. d4 {Now we may as well push with tempo.} 
11. Ne4
11. Nxe4 {Very safe.11...Ng4!?followedby ...f7-f5 is a more fun alternative.} 
12. Bxe4
12. Rb8 {We'll challenge White's bishop with ...Bb7. The position is just level.} 
