[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "34) Scotch: Conclusion"]
[Black "Scotch − Conclusion"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {The Scotch is the most direct of White’s main openings. They immediately open lines for their pieces. Therefore, I believe we need to answer it forcefully. I’ve recommended the main line of4...Nf6, immediately attacking the weak point in White’s position: the undefended e-pawn. These lines are very sharp and are probably the most theoretical part of the whole course.  We started by looking at White’s critical tries in the Mieses Variation,6.e5. The double fianchetto quickly reaches an unbalanced endgame. We have a rook and two pawns for the bishop and knight. Such positions have been debated for decades, but the consensus that Black finds it easier to play hasn’t been altered.  We then moved onto the line with9.b3g610.f4. Historically, this was one of White’s main tries, but I believe10...g5!makes the variation almost unplayable. White needs to show computer levels of accuracy to survive, and even then Black has racked up a huge score in correspondence.  As White has been struggling a bit in these two main lines, they’ve started to look at early deviations.10.Ba3!?is a sideline I’ve tried myself. It’s a bit strange, White wants to provoke the knightto b4 before dropping the bishop back to b2. It recently received a top-level outing when Fabiano Caruana essayed it against Wesley So in the 2023 Wijk aan Zee super tournament. Despite Fabiano being able to demonstrate deep preparation, Wesley found the correct response and drew from a position of strength.9.Nd2is another sideline that has seen quite a bit of action. For a while, this was my main attempt, but I ran into former World Champion Vladimir Kramnik in 2017. The line he chose put me off the White side completely, and I’ve shared it with you. White’s main problem is that they’re forced to play with their king stuck in the center.  Of White’s other tries, the topical8.h4!?should be studied carefully. This was Sethuraman’s recommendation in his Lifetime Repertoire and reaches very irrational positions. I believe the line I’ve chosen forces White to be extremely careful to survive into a level middlegame.  The positions after6.e5are fascinating. White has more space but neglects their development and tends to have an extremely vulnerable e-pawn. Should White have time to coordinate their forces they’ll be doing well, but against a well-prepared opponent, there’s always the risk of losing a miniature. Therefore a lot of White players prefer playing more safely by simply defending their e-pawn.  There’s a recent trend for6.Nd2, but White isn’t showing anything in the dull positions after6...d5, while our recommendation of6...Bc5forces White to show accuracy to equalize. I doubt we’ll be seeing too much more of it at the top level.  The main move is6.Bd3, but our play there is very straightforward. We advance in the center and develop our pieces classically. Our initiative compensates for our slightly damaged queenside.} 1. --
