[White "35) Italian: Introduction"]
[Black "Italian − Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4 {Time to move onto the Italian, or the Giuoco Piano. Incidentally, when will we stop using the confusing medieval spelling and change it to the modern Italian 'gioco'?  We're in very old territory here, with games going back hundreds of years. When I was growing up this was looked down upon. Sure, you have natural development, but if you want to be a proper player then you should play the Spanish.  It was often played as a sort of mirrored London System. White would play Bc4, d2-d3, c2-c3, Bb3, Nbd2-f1-g3, h2-h3 and then stop and think. In the past decade or so there's been a radical overhaul, and almost all the top players now have the Italian in their repertoire.} 
3. Nf6 {The first decision. I'm proposing developing the knight first for two reasons. First, I believe the sidelines we're allowing here,4.Ng5and4.d4, are more interesting than allowing3...Bc54.c3followed by a quick d2-d4. Secondly, this gives us an additional setup, as we're not yet committed to developing ourbishop to c5.} 
4. d3 {The main line. White defends their pawn. We'll check out the alternatives later. Now we have a choice. I'm offering4...Bc5followed by ...d7-d6 and ...a7-a5 as our primary defense. This has an extremely good pedigree, having been used by Magnus Carlsen to wrap up his defense of the World Champion title against Ian Nepomniachtchi.I've also offered an interesting approach with4...h6,followed by ...d7-d6 and either ...g7-g5 or ...g7-g6. This is obviously riskier but puts White on the immediate backfoot.  Despite the Italian's recent reincarnation as a principled try, a lot of players still use it as a rote opening like the London System. They have a series of moves they wish to play, regardless of the setup Black employs. They'll have a rude awakening here.} 
4. Bc5 {The main move. We copy White and develop our bishop actively.4...h6!?Our alternative approach. We take the g5-square under control. We want to fianchetto our bishop. If White goes for a setup where they're threatening a quick d3-d4, we'll go for an accelerated fianchetto with ...g7-g5. The idea is to threaten to push White's knight away with ...g5-g4, and thereby take away the defender of the d4-pawn. This looks rather rash, but it's a lot better than it looks, with many elite players giving it a whirl. If White plays a slower setup, then we'll go for the more traditional King's Indian like ...g7-g6.5.O-Ois White's main line, but, it being an Italian, there are of course plenty of options.5...d6,we want to fianchetto our bishop but it's important to first defend the e-pawn. As our development is a bit slower, we have to make sure we're not steamrolled in the center with d3-d4.6.c3g5!The extended fianchetto. Of course, it's aggressive, but the main point is to make it harder for White to achieve the d3-d4 break.Instead6...g67.d4!is a little unpleasant. Now we'll be able to kick White's knight away from the defenseof the d4-square. The positions are rich, double-edged, and murky.} 
5. c3 {Both sides have thousands of possible move orders and nearly identical subtleties. It's impossible to cover absolutely everything, but I'll make sure we have all of White's critical tries covered, and hopefully provide a good grounding as to why they're critical.  White already has plenty of tries, but this is the main line. As we've seen in the Spanish, White needs a pawn on c3 to expand in the center with d3-d4. Here White may also want to push the b-pawn, while the c4-bishop will also need an escape route.} 
5. d6 {I believe this is the simplest. We don't yet commit our king, as then the lines with Bg5 become very sharp.} 
6. O-O
6. a5 {This is my proposed structure. We fight for control of the queenside. White has to shelve the plan of b2-b4-b5. This means we're quite happy to exchange bishops on e6. Without the plan of queenside expansion, White gets a bit stuck against our doubled e-pawns. We're ready to drop our bishop back to a7 so that White won't gain a tempo with d3-d4.  For now, we're delaying castling kingside, so we don't need to worry too much about White pinning our kingside knight. White's ideal formation would be to push d3-d4 and successfully hold onto those central pawns with Bd3, Be3, h2-h3, and Nbd2. If they manage it, then White normally has a small edge, but it's extremely difficult to achieve.  ...Bg4 pins are annoying, and often we can react to d3-d4 by exchanging and ...d6-d5. White doesn't normally want to be left with the IQP, and so they often have to move their bishop from c4 first. Our plans involve dropping the bishop back to a7, castling kingside, and either challenging White's bishop with ...Be6, or rerouting our knight around to g6. The knight on c6 tends to be our worst piece. Once it hops around it tends to be easier to break in the center. Let's jump right in!} 
