10. Bb5 {It looks odd to move the bishop again, but with the light-squared bishops exchanged White struggles to do very much. The game starts to resemble a very slow Spanish.} 
10. Ne7 {Our knight carries out the same journey as White's; g6 is a reliable square. It can't easily be shifted, it controls the e5-pawn making it easier to play ...d6-d5, and it's ready to hop menacingly into f4.} 
11. d4
11. Ng6 {A lot of very strong players have reached this position: Carlsen, So, Mamedyarov..., and with very good results. We've gained half a tempo on a theoretical position, as we haven't had to play ...h7-h6.} 
12. Bd3 {The ideal square for the bishop in the Italian.} 
12. Nh5 {But it won't stay there long. The g6-knight is doing an important job defending the e-pawn. The other one was no longer fulfilling a role, and it'll be much better placed on f4.} 
13. Nf1
13. Nhf4 {If White loses their light-squared bishop, they're in trouble.} 
14. Bc2
14. Qd7 {We're threatening to capture on h3.} 
15. Ng5 {Tempting, but this backfires.} 
15. h6
16. Nxe6
16. fxe6 {An instructive line given by David Anton. White has problems with both f2 and g2.} 
