7. Ba7 {This was brought to prominence when Magnus Carlsen used it to wrap up the World Champion title in 2021. We have to drop the bishop back at some point, as White will prepare to push in the center with d3-d4. By playing it early, we don't need to know as much in the early Bg5 lines.7...h6is also possible, but we're hoping to do without that until absolutely necessary.} 
8. Bb3 {I don't believe Anish Giri actually covers our move order, but, if White wants to reach his recommendation, then this would be a clever move order. As we've just seen, White should wait for us to castle before touching their h-pawn.} 
8. O-O {We no longer need to fear the pin. The lost tempo with Bb3 is important.} 
9. h3 {With our king on g8, we're less likely to advance our g-pawn.} 
9. h6 {We're ready to challenge White with ...Be6. Starting with9...Be6is possible, but10.Bc2is a bit annoying. White will manage toplay d3-d4 before we're absolutely ready for ...d6-d5. Now we won't have to worry about Ng5 ideas.} 
10. d4 {By transposition, we've reached Giri's recommendation against our setup. Therefore, we have to take it very seriously.} 
10. Re8 {...Be6 is no longer possible, as White would react with d4-d5, so we have to change the approach. But it's not so easy to hold on to both pawns.} 
11. Bc2 {White doesn't really want to close the center with d4-d5. Our a7-bishop would become very powerful, and we'd be free to start attacking on the kingside; ...Ne7, ...g7-g5!, ...Ng6 with a big attack.} 
11. Bd7 {It's possible to try and equalize immediately with ...d6-d5, but let's keep the tension. First of all, we ask White how they propose to continue their development. It's not easy to move either of the queenside pieces without losing the center. As for us, one plan is the Steinitz Deferred idea of ...exd4 and ...Nb4, collecting the bishop. Another is pushing the g-pawn and attacking!The immediate11...g5looks fun, but Giri observes White can fight back with12.Na3g413.Bxh6!Still, it's an idea we should keep in mind.} 
12. a4 {Continuing to follow Giri. If12.a3then we can revert to12...g5!White can no longer developwith Na3, and so is a bit stuck.} 
12. exd4 {Let's follow Magnus!12...Rc8!?is an interesting waiting move.} 
13. cxd4
13. Nb4 {Shades of our Steinitz Deferred Spanish. We collect the white bishop.} 
14. Nc3 {The downside to exchanging on d4 was that it gave White a good square for their knight.} 
14. Nxc2 {But we've nabbed the bishop.} 
15. Qxc2
15. c6 {A useful move. We prepare both ...d6-d5 and ...b7-b5 breaks.} 
16. Be3 {A horrible blunder in a classical game, by a player rated almost 2700.} 
16. Nxe4 {Yup, that pawn can safely be grabbed.} 
17. Nxe4
17. Bf5 {White cannot escape the pin. We'll regain the knight with either ...Qe7 or ...d6-d5.} 
18. Bxh6 {Desperation.} 
18. gxh6 {Giving up one piece hasn't helped.} 
19. Ra3
19. d5 {Predke-Harutyunian, Abu Dhabi 2022. After moving the f3-knight, White will manage one check, but that's it. An absolute disaster for the strong Russian, who had to resign after just 27 moves.} 
