[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d3
4. Bc5 {I've played quite a few Italians, or Giuoco Pianos, with both colors, but the move orders still confuse me. Still, I hope this repertoire will make sense. Against most setups, our next two moves will be ...d7-d6 and ...a7-a5.} 
5. c3 {White usually starts with this. There are lots of transpositions, but first, we'll concentrate on the main line.} 
5. d6
6. O-O
6. a5 {A few years ago, I was studying these positions in quite a lot of depth, as the Italian became my main opening. Black has many different setups, but this one seems quite straightforward. We give our bishop a retreat square and fight for possession of the queenside.  One key point is that we're almost always happy to offer an exchange of bishops with ...Be6. The structure after ...fxe6 can be a bit depressing if White can seize all the space on the queenside, but that's no longer possible.} 
7. Re1 {Once again, White has plenty of possible moves, but the rook is always useful on e1. It defends the e-pawn and helps prepare d3-d4, and gets out of the way of the b1-knight rerouting to the kingside via f1.} 
7. Ba7 {This was brought to prominence when Magnus Carlsen used it to wrap up the World Champion title in 2021. We have to drop the bishop back at some point, as White will prepare to push in the center with d3-d4. By playing it early, we don't need to know as much in the early Bg5 lines.7...h6is also possible, but we're hoping to do without that until absolutely necessary.} 
8. a4 {This is possible of course, but doesn't put any pressure on our position. There was a trend a couple of years ago where Black had played ...a7-a6 to later meet a2-a4 with ...a6-a5 to prevent White from expanding on the queenside. Clearly a tempo up we can't have any problems.} 
8. O-O {Once again, we needn't fear the Bg5 pin when White has lost a tempo. We'll be very quick with ...h7-h6, ...g7-g5, and ...Nh7.} 
9. Nbd2 {The most common, but actually rather risky. It's much safer to start with9.h3. Then we may as well follow with9...h6. Our next movewill be either ...Be6 or ...Ne7 with ideas of both ...Ng6 and fighting in the center with ...c7-c6 and ...d6-d5.} 
9. Ng4 {An idea we should always be on the lookout for. White has taken their eye off the f2-pawn.} 
10. Re2
10. Kh8 {Escaping the pin. Next, we'll push our f-pawn.} 
11. h3
11. f5 {Here we go!} 
12. exf5
12. Nh6 {Simple. Next, we'll recapture on f5.12...Nxf2followed by ...d6-d5 and ...Bxf5 is also promising.} 
13. g4 {Holding onto the pawn is too greedy.} 
13. Nxf5
14. gxf5
14. Bxf5 {Our pieces swarm into the attack. White's king is too exposed.} 
