[Black "7.Re1 Ba7 8.Na3 #3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d3
4. Bc5 {I've played quite a few Italians, or Giuoco Pianos, with both colors, but the move orders still confuse me. Still, I hope this repertoire will make sense. Against most setups, our next two moves will be ...d7-d6 and ...a7-a5.} 
5. c3 {White usually starts with this. There are lots of transpositions, but first, we'll concentrate on the main line.} 
5. d6
6. O-O
6. a5 {A few years ago, I was studying these positions in quite a lot of depth, as the Italian became my main opening. Black has many different setups, but this one seems quite straightforward. We give our bishop a retreat square and fight for possession of the queenside.  One key point is that we're almost always happy to offer an exchange of bishops with ...Be6. The structure after ...fxe6 can be a bit depressing if White can seize all the space on the queenside, but that's no longer possible.} 
7. Re1 {Once again, White has plenty of possible moves, but the rook is always useful on e1. It defends the e-pawn and helps prepare d3-d4, and gets out of the way of the b1-knight rerouting to the kingside via f1.} 
7. Ba7 {This was brought to prominence when Magnus Carlsen used it to wrap up the World Champion title in 2021. We have to drop the bishop back at some point, as White will prepare to push in the center with d3-d4. By playing it early, we don't need to know as much in the early Bg5 lines.7...h6is also possible, but we're hoping to do without that until absolutely necessary.} 
8. Na3 {The main theoretical test of the early bishop retreat. White aims to gain time with Nb5.} 
8. h6 {It's possible to start by castling, but I'd prefer to steer clear of the pin. Na3 turns out to be quite a useful move there.} 
9. Nb5 {Hassling the bishop is the thematic continuation.} 
9. Bb6 {We don't want to allow White to exchange knight for a bishop. I'd had both sides of these positions and they're quite interesting. On the one hand, the knight on b5 helps control the center and prepares the d3-d4 advance. But once Black moves the knight from c6, White has to be careful, as the knight will be shunted back with ...c7-c6.} 
10. Be3 {Our bishop is too strong. White needs to exchange it to get anywhere.} 
10. Bxe3
11. Rxe3
11. O-O {I had this position on June 9th 2022 in the French Club Championships as Black against Markus Ragger. Amusingly, the same position had been reached on the board next to me, Grandelius-Fressinet, while Vallejo Pons-Harikrishna was taking place in Prague at the same time. Needless to say, all three games were drawn.} 
12. h3 {Ragger's choice against me, and what I tried in a later game against David Anton Guijarro.} 
12. Re8 {The main line. Black should equalize by force here, but we need to take a bit of care. A simple alternative would be12...Nb8!?simply preparing to expelWhite's knight with ...c7-c6.} 
13. Qc2 {Ragger's choice.} 
13. Ne7 {The point of White's previous was to over-defend the e-pawn, and thereby prepare to push d3-d4. With our rook on e6 that would be a bit annoying, so let's reroute our knight instead.} 
14. Qb3
14. Rf8 {We need to undevelop for a move, but White has now lost control of the e4-square.} 
15. d4 {Ragger-Jones, Chartres 2022. I played the solid15...Ng6, but we have better.} 
15. d5 {A good time to fight back in the center. As ...dxc4 hits White's queen, they have to capture on d5.} 
16. exd5
16. e4 {Gaining a tempo on the knight.} 
17. Ne5
17. Nexd5
18. Bxd5 {White doesn't really want to retreat.} 
18. Nxd5 {White is winning a pawn, but in return, we're getting a powerful initiative.} 
19. Rxe4
19. Bf5 {Developing with tempo.} 
20. Ree1
20. c6 {We force White back.} 
21. Na3
21. Nf4 {In return for the sacrificed pawn we have a strong attack. ...Qg5 is a big problem, not only threatening mate on g2, but also getting ready to capture on h3.} 
22. c4 {The safest. White wants to defend along the third rank.22.Qxb7Qg523.Qxc6is possible but after23...Nxh3+followed byreturning to f4, our attack continues. ... f7-f6 becomes a big threat, as the knight doesn't have a good retreat square.} 
22. f6 {A good move here too. The knight is forced to retreat.} 
23. Nf3 {Or23.Ng4Qxd4.} 
23. Qd7 {...Bxh3 is the threat. Our pieces are much better coordinated than White's, and so we have good long-term compensation.} 
