12. d4 {Grandelius' try. The immediate advance should be critical. Vallejo chose 12.a4 but Black has lots of choices there. Simply 12...Re8followed by ...Be6 equalizes.} 
12. Bg4 {The pin adds more pressure to the center. This is quite thematic after White puts their pawn on d4 in Italian and Spanish. The immediate12...exd413.cxd4d514.exd5Ne7should also be okay.} 
13. h3
13. Bh5 {Maintaining the tension. In Volokitin-Matlakov, chess.com 2022, Black captured on f3, but there's no immediate need.} 
14. Qe1 {Kasimdzhanov's recommendation. It's not so easy for White to make progress.14.Qe2would allow14...exd415.cxd4d5!16.exd5Nb4. We weren't able to captureon d5 immediately, as our c7-pawn would be hanging. But with both knights controlling the square we'd regain the pawn next move.} 
14. Bxf3 {Now that White has left the pin, we don't want to allow White to recapture on d4 with the knight.} 
15. Rxf3
15. exd4 {This is a thematic idea. We're going to leave White with an IQP.} 
16. cxd4
16. d5 {This is the concept.} 
17. exd5 {Including17.Bxd5Nxd5doesn't change very much.} 
17. Nb4 {Just don't rush to recapture.17...Nxd5?18.Bxd5Qxd519.Nxc7is something to avoid. Next, we'll recapture with the b-knight.} 
18. d6
18. cxd6 {I believe this is the critical line, but we've solved our problems.} 
