[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "37) Italian setups without 5.c3"]
[Black "5.Nc3 a6 6.Nd5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d3
4. Bc5 {I've played quite a few Italians, or Giuoco Pianos, with both colors, but the move orders still confuse me. Still, I hope this repertoire will make sense. Against most setups, our next two moves will be ...d7-d6 and ...a7-a5.} 
5. Nc3 {A serious alternative setup. It used to be considered that the c3-square was for the exclusive use of the c-pawn. With a knight in the way, it's very difficult to achieve the d4-break. Still, this is pretty fashionable these days. White either wants to grab our bishop with Na4, or take control of the d5-square.} 
5. a6 {Our bishop is now safe. Pushing the pawn two squares makes less sense here. White controls the light squares well, so we should compete for them.} 
6. Nd5
6. h6 {We prevent White from putting us in an annoying pin with Bg5. Exchanging knights is also fine, but we're trying to be a bit more ambitious.} 
7. c3
7. d6 {We're ready to challenge the knight with ...Be6. As a rule, I'd prefer to wait for White to castle before touching our king. I don't want the pawn storm happening to us with h2-h3 and g2-g4.} 
8. h3
8. Ba7 {Following Vishy. Dropping the bishop back is definitely useful. We now threaten to collect White's bishop.9.O-Owas played against me here, but then9...Na5was awkward.} 
9. a4
9. Be6 {White's impressive-looking knight is getting undermined.} 
10. a5
10. Bxd5
11. exd5
11. Ne7 {Kramnik-Anand, Wijk aan Zee 2019. White has to be inventive to hold onto the d-pawn. In the game, Vishy was winning very quickly.} 
