[Black "5.Nc3 a6 6.O-O #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d3
4. Bc5 {I've played quite a few Italians, or Giuoco Pianos, with both colors, but the move orders still confuse me. Still, I hope this repertoire will make sense. Against most setups, our next two moves will be ...d7-d6 and ...a7-a5.} 
5. Nc3 {A serious alternative setup. It used to be considered that the c3-square was for the exclusive use of the c-pawn. With a knight in the way, it's very difficult to achieve the d4-break. Still, this is pretty fashionable these days. White either wants to grab our bishop with Na4, or take control of the d5-square.} 
5. a6 {Our bishop is now safe. Pushing the pawn two squares makes less sense here. White controls the light squares well, so we should compete for them.} 
6. O-O
6. d6
7. a4 {A recent trend.7.h3is the main move but rather risky. Time for7...h6, preparing to push the g-pawn. Instead,7.Bg5h6is likely to transpose to the 6.Bg5 move order.} 
7. O-O {We could also start with the usual7...h6, but we don't need to fear the pin here.} 
8. Be3 {8.h3Be6would be very similar.} 
8. Bxe3
9. fxe3
9. Be6 {Copying White. We almost have symmetry, but our control of the b4-square gives us some additional chances.} 
10. Nd2
10. Nb4 {Abdusattorov-Nakamura, Kolkata 2022. Thanks to White's knight on c3, it isn't easy to shift ours from b4. We take control of the d5-square and can slowly prepare to break in the center.} 
