5. a4 {White's final interesting try. The point is that White has not yet committed either knight or pawn to c3. White's tried various alternatives but we can play our usual setup with 5...d6 against almost all of them.5.Ng5?!is played a surprising amount, but just5...O-Oand we're substantially better.Next, we'll push the knight back with ...h7-h6.} 
5. d6 {We'll just continue as usual. White is hoping for something small after5...a56.Be3followed by Nc3 and maybe O-O-O. When White puts the knight on c3, we would prefer ...a7-a6.} 
6. a5 {White's only consistent continuation. Against6.c3or6.O-O, we'll play6...a5, while6.Nc3a6transposes to the 5.Nc3 move order.} 
6. a6 {White has succeeded in grabbing more space, but they've played a4-a5 earlier than they'd have liked to. We no longer have to worry about b2-b4-b5.} 
7. c3
7. h6 {The usual moves.} 
8. O-O
8. O-O {Next, ...Be6 or ...Ba7 equalizes.} 
