3. Nf6
4. d3
4. Bc5 {I've played quite a few Italians, or Giuoco Pianos, with both colors, but the move orders still confuse me. Still, I hope this repertoire will make sense. Against most setups, our next two moves will be ...d7-d6 and ...a7-a5.} 
5. c3
5. d6
6. Nbd2 {A move order tried a few times by Magnus Carlsen. It's probably a bit more flexible than6.Bb3. As well as the plan of rerouting the knightvia f1-g3, White retains plans of pushing their b-pawn.} 
6. a5 {Taking control of the b4-square.6...O-Ois also completely finenow that the bishop cannot go to g5, but White can at least steer the game into slightly different waters with7.b4Bb68.Bb3,intending Nc4 and collecting our bishop.} 
7. Nf1 {White continues the knight's journey.} 
7. Be6 {Let's challenge White's bishop immediately. Once again we're very happy with the doubled e-pawns.} 
8. Bb5 {White's only challenging continuation.} 
8. O-O {Magnus Carlsen had this position twice against Aryan Tari.} 
9. Ng3
9. d5 {9...Ne7was both Tari and So's choice in a later blitz game, but our thematic break equalizes immediately.} 
10. O-O
10. dxe4
11. dxe4
11. Qxd1 {The exchanges are simplest.} 
12. Rxd1
12. Na7 {Forcing the bishop back, and then we can return. If you want to play for more, then both12...Rfd8and12...Bd6are equal too.} 
