10. Bg3
10. O-O {It looks odd to castle directly after pushing the g-pawn, but White doesn't have a good way in. It's important that White has already committed to Nbd2, so their play with d3-d4 is much slower. Therefore, we have an improved version of the main line I was trying to prevent with7.Re1O-O8.Bg5.  These are still very sharp positions, but Black's results have been pretty good. We're going to move the knightfrom f6 and then start pushing. We can do that by pushing the h-pawn, bringing the knight around to g6 and playing ...g5-g4, or getting the king out of the way and going for ...f7-f5.} 
11. a3 {Praggnanandhaa's choice in a couple of games.} 
11. a4 {White wanted to expand with b2-b4, so let's prevent them! The pawn cannot be taken immediately, as ...Bxf2+ would collect the queen, but this is ultimately a pawn sacrifice. However, it costs valuable time to take it.} 
12. Bb5 {Immediately going after the pawn.} 
12. Nh5
13. Bxa4
13. Ne7 {White has won a pawn, but of more pressing relevance is our kingside attack. Next, we'll either push the f-pawn or play ...Ng6 and ...g5-g4 forcing the knight backwards. Either way, our initiative is ferocious.} 
