5. d6 {We set out our stall. The bishop is no longer going to develop to c5. By the way,5...Bc5is still possible. Comparedto ...Bc5 on the previous move we've committed to ...h7-h6 earlier than we'd like, but it's a possible move-order trick if you notice your opponent plays in a specific way against4...Bc5.} 
6. c3 {We've reached the main line position. White could also have got here with5.c3d66.O-O.} 
6. g5 {Vladimir Kramnik explains it very well: 'The idea is not that Black wants to play ...g5-g4 and ...h6-h5 to mate, but rather it's like a prolonged fianchetto with the potential of ...g4. It's a bit more difficult for White to develop here, as g4 is always on the agenda, especially when the d2 and e1-squares are occupied, like when White plays Nbd2 and Re1. After g4 in such a position, White has problems with the knight.'  The ensuing positions are extremely complicated. We're making it difficult for White to play their d3-d4 advance. As Vladimir notes, White has to take great care not to get their f3-knight trapped, so logical developing moves are off the books.  On the subject of not playing for mate, I would clarify his words a little. We're not playing for immediate mate, but the pawn advance will come at some point. First, we'll develop our pieces. We should delay ...g5-g4 unless we have a concrete follow-up. Otherwise White might be able to open up lines with f2-f4.  Our typical development plan is ...Bg7 and knight round to g6. If White targets the f7-square with Qb3, we'll normally want to react with ...Qd7. This keeps the e7-square free for our knight. The big downside to our setup is the weakening of the f5-square. Great care should be taken to prevent a painful knight hop.} 
7. Re1 {Marginally the most common reaction. White defends the e-pawn in readiness to push d3-d4.} 
7. Bg7 {Getting on with our usual development. The aggressive treatment with7...g4!?8.Nfd2h5followed by ...h5-h4 is quite interesting too.} 
8. Nbd2 {Played a surprising amount, including by strong grandmasters.} 
8. g4 {But the knight no longer has a good retreat route.} 
9. Nh4
9. Nxe4 {Opening a discovered attack on White's knight. We collect a pawn.} 
