[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d3
4. h6 {Our alternative setup. In the last few years, the plan of pushing the g-pawn has become pretty fashionable at the top level, but it's still likely to catch your opponent by surprise. Note that we first need to take control of the g5-square before we play ...d7-d6, as Ng5 would otherwise be extremely awkward.  White has tried a huge array of moves here. We're going to continue with ...d7-d6 and then see. If White is threatening to play d3-d4, we'll play ...g7-g5. If not, then we'll be happy with a normal fianchetto.} 
5. O-O {We'll start by covering the main lines. Later we'll investigate White's earlier alternatives. Your opponent will likely start with the same setup as they would against5...Bc5.} 
5. d6 {We set out our stall. The bishop is no longer going to develop to c5. By the way,5...Bc5is still possible. Comparedto ...Bc5 on the previous move we've committed to ...h7-h6 earlier than we'd like, but it's a possible move-order trick if you notice your opponent plays in a specific way against4...Bc5.} 
6. c3 {We've reached the main line position. White could also have got here with5.c3d66.O-O.} 
6. g5 {Vladimir Kramnik explains it very well: 'The idea is not that Black wants to play ...g5-g4 and ...h6-h5 to mate, but rather it's like a prolonged fianchetto with the potential of ...g4. It's a bit more difficult for White to develop here, as g4 is always on the agenda, especially when the d2 and e1-squares are occupied, like when White plays Nbd2 and Re1. After g4 in such a position, White has problems with the knight.'  The ensuing positions are extremely complicated. We're making it difficult for White to play their d3-d4 advance. As Vladimir notes, White has to take great care not to get their f3-knight trapped, so logical developing moves are off the books.  On the subject of not playing for mate, I would clarify his words a little. We're not playing for immediate mate, but the pawn advance will come at some point. First, we'll develop our pieces. We should delay ...g5-g4 unless we have a concrete follow-up. Otherwise White might be able to open up lines with f2-f4.  Our typical development plan is ...Bg7 and knight round to g6. If White targets the f7-square with Qb3, we'll normally want to react with ...Qd7. This keeps the e7-square free for our knight. The big downside to our setup is the weakening of the f5-square. Great care should be taken to prevent a painful knight hop.} 
7. Nbd2 {The choice of many strong grandmasters, and so I think we should make it our main line. White develops naturally while keeping the e1-square available for the other knight. Their usual plan is to drop back with Bb3 followed by Nc4. Once again, I'll analyze the a4-setups separately.} 
7. Bg7 {Time to calmly develop. I don't like touching the g-pawn yet. White's knight isn't trapped, while the rook still being on f1 means that White can generate dangerous play down the f-file.} 
8. Bb3 {White makes room for the knight. Just a reminder,8.Re1?!g4!would be a favorable transposition. We'll cover8.a4next, when considering all the differentlytimed a2-a4 moves.} 
8. a5 {This funny-looking pawn push has become trendy in the past couple of years. We grab space and prepare against White's plan of pushing their a-pawn. Mostly it's a useful waiting move. We stay flexible with our king, which might go in either direction. We're staying flexible with our c8-bishop too. If White continues their plan, we'll develop our bishop to e6. It turns out it's quite difficult for White to come up with a plan.All that being said, I think the old main line of8...O-Ois also okay, but we'll often end up pushing the a-pawn anyhow.} 
9. a4 {White responds in kind.} 
9. Bd7 {We refuse to be drawn. We keep the e7-square free for either queen or knight and keep open the plan of advancing on the kingside.I think9...O-Ois also okay, but White can at least then generate a plan with10.h4. Before we've castled, that's obviously very risky. However, I'm not very happy with Sethuraman's recommendation of9...Qe7, as10.d4looks unpleasant to me.} 
10. Nc4
10. Be6 {We accept a wasted tempo, but our bishop is still well-placed here. In fact, we're going to exploit the pawn being on a4.} 
11. Re1
11. g4 {This time we'll play a little differently. Castling would be okay, but then we'd definitely be a tempo down on the previous line. True, that might not matter so much when both sides were struggling for a plan, but still this is more ambitious. It turns out this works much better with the pawn on a4, as White no longer has Ba4 ideas.} 
12. Nfd2
12. h5 {Grabbing space.} 
13. Ne3
13. Qd7 {White's position is rather congested, with the d2-knight really getting in the way. We'll play for ...d6-d5 or reroute the knight round to g6. With the pawn back on a2, Ba4 would be really annoying, a good illustration as to why we were happy to give up the a2-a4 tempo.} 
