5. d6 {Remaining consistent. We have the potential of pushing the g-pawn one or two squares. A solid alternative is5...a5. We then have a wide range of possible ways to develop. Should White play6.Nc3, then we can pin with6...Bb4. Against White's other moves, we could eitherplay ...Bc5 or ...d7-d6. The former would be very similar to the 4...Bc5 setups we've already examined. We've played ...h7-h6 a bit earlier than we'd like there, but White has also pushed a2-a4 early.} 
6. a5 {White continues pushing.} 
6. a6 {Simplest. We prevent the pawn from advancing further. Starting with6...g6is also possible, but from personal experience, I found it hard playing against White's pawnon a6. We have to watch out for a chronically weak a7-pawn. If we always intend to meet a4-a5 with ...a7-a6, then we shouldn't get move ordered.  We're now going to perform the small fianchetto with ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7. An idea to bear in mind is playing ...b7-b6 or ...b7-b5 to provoke the en-passant. Our structure then looks a little ugly, but we'll be able to quickly break with ...d6-d5 followed by forcing the bishop back with ...b6-b5. White now has to decide whether they want to play with a knight or pawn on c3.} 
7. c3
7. g6 {Pushing the pawn two squares is possible, but, as White is no longer getting a quick d3-d4, the more compact structure is more reliable.} 
8. Qb3 {Tricky. If White wants to play this way, they should do it before we've had time to play ...Bg7. Otherwise, we'll just castle out of danger.Note that8.d4?!Nxe4is simply an extra pawn.} 
8. Qe7 {We should prefer this square now that we no longer have ...Na5 ideas.} 
9. O-O
9. Bg7 {We'll play in the same way. First, we get our king to safety.} 
10. Re1
10. O-O {White now has to decide what they're doing. The queen on b3 makes it harder for us to play ...d6-d5, but White will have to watch out for that c4-bishop.} 
11. d4 {Rare, but probably White's most challenging approach.} 
11. Nd7 {We attack the d-pawn and prepare our ...b7-b5 source of counterplay.} 
12. Be3 {Once again we'd be very happy to see White close the center. After12.d5Nd8, we're transforming the position into a King's Indian. We'll be readyfor ...f7-f5.} 
12. b5 {We want some space of our own and to push the bishop back.} 
13. axb6 {13.Bd5Bb7isn't worrying. We'll next returnwith ...Nf6, attacking the bishop.} 
13. Nxb6 {We'd quite like to get rid of White's bishop, but our main threat is to capture on d4 and e4.} 
14. Bd3
14. exd4 {Creating an outpost.} 
15. cxd4 {The natural recapture.15.Nxd4Ne5continues to annoy White's bishops.} 
15. a5 {Next, we'll hop with ...Nb4 followed by fighting for control of the center with ...c7-c5.} 
