5. d6 {Remaining consistent. We have the potential of pushing the g-pawn one or two squares. A solid alternative is5...a5. We then have a wide range of possible ways to develop. Should White play6.Nc3, then we can pin with6...Bb4. Against White's other moves, we could eitherplay ...Bc5 or ...d7-d6. The former would be very similar to the 4...Bc5 setups we've already examined. We've played ...h7-h6 a bit earlier than we'd like there, but White has also pushed a2-a4 early.} 
6. a5 {White continues pushing.} 
6. a6 {Simplest. We prevent the pawn from advancing further. Starting with6...g6is also possible, but from personal experience, I found it hard playing against White's pawnon a6. We have to watch out for a chronically weak a7-pawn. If we always intend to meet a4-a5 with ...a7-a6, then we shouldn't get move ordered.  We're now going to perform the small fianchetto with ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7. An idea to bear in mind is playing ...b7-b6 or ...b7-b5 to provoke the en-passant. Our structure then looks a little ugly, but we'll be able to quickly break with ...d6-d5 followed by forcing the bishop back with ...b6-b5. White now has to decide whether they want to play with a knight or pawn on c3.} 
7. Nc3 {White decides on the knight.} 
7. g6 {We'll be consistent. White will now prepare d3-d4 while we develop our pieces. White is not getting anywhere with the immediate advance. After8.d4, we can play8...Bg4, when White loses control.7...g58.h4is rather risky.} 
8. O-O
8. Bg7
9. h3
9. O-O {It's possible to start with9...Be6here too, but as White isn't about to start attacking on the kingside, there's no real need.} 
10. Re1 {By overprotecting the e-pawn, White prepares d3-d4.} 
10. Bd7 {Playing against White breaking in the center.} 
11. Be3
11. Qe7 {We again put pressure on the e-file, making it harder for White to advance in the center. This time the e7-square is slightly more accurate. It's useful to later control the c5 and h4-squares.} 
12. d4 {White is running out of useful improving moves.} 
12. exd4
13. Bxd4
13. Nxd4 {We're always happy to get rid of this bishop.} 
14. Qxd4
14. Rae8 {Bringing our final piece into the game. We're comfortably equal.} 
