5. a4 {The immediate advance. This allows us maximum flexibility.} 
5. d6 {Remaining consistent. We have the potential of pushing the g-pawn one or two squares. A solid alternative is5...a5. We then have a wide range of possible ways to develop. Should White play6.Nc3, then we can pin with6...Bb4. Against White's other moves, we could eitherplay ...Bc5 or ...d7-d6. The former would be very similar to the 4...Bc5 setups we've already examined. We've played ...h7-h6 a bit earlier than we'd like there, but White has also pushed a2-a4 early.} 
6. Nc3 {White's other independent try. Both6.c3and6.O-Owill be analyzed later.} 
6. g6 {The positions are very similar to those we just examined with a-pawn moves included. We're just a bit more flexible here. We can react to7.d4with either7...Bg4or7...exd4followed by quickly developing our kingside. White will struggle to hold onto the e-pawn. As White has spent a tempoon a2-a4, we don't need to have the ...g5-g4 resource. On the other hand, after6...g57.h4is a bit awkward. White is very quick to take control ofthe f5-square with Nh2-f1-g3.} 
7. h3 {White needs to take control of the g4-square sooner or later. Other move orders are likely to transpose.} 
7. Bg7 {White should probably include a4-a5 around here. Otherwise, we simply have more choices.} 
8. O-O {Or8.Be3Be6. The pawns remainingon a4 and a7 change little.} 
8. O-O {Both sides have sorted out their kingside. A good plan is now to shift our knight and then play ...c7-c5. It will then be very difficult for White to successfully achieve the d3-d4 advance.} 
9. Be3 {Giri's recommendation, and White's most natural move. They simply continue developing.Should White start with9.a5, we can transpose with9...a6, while9...Nb4, with the ideaof ...c7-c5, is also a good plan. White now has two plans. The primary one is to advance with d3-d4, but as long as we're careful that won't come to anything. The second is to play for f2-f4. That wasn't really an option when White had played Re1.} 
9. Ne7 {The same plan: we want to play ... c7-c5 next.9...Na5is fine too, although Anish shows some nifty tactics there. He takes advantage of the dark-squared bishop already being developed.He wants to exchange a pair of knights on f6 and then play Qd2. When we defend the pawn with ...Kh7, he'll unleash Ng5+. Black cannot take, as the queen is trapped on f6. As long as we're careful there, I think we're fine, but as d3-d4 isn't scary here, we might as well keep our knight more actively placed.} 
10. d4 {This is possible, but we're well prepared for it.} 
10. exd4
11. Bxd4 {11.Nxd4is the more natural capture, but then we equalize immediately with11....d5,followed by ...Nfxd5.} 
11. Nc6 {Back again. We want control of the long diagonal.} 
12. Be3
12. Be6 {We've got a pretty active version of this type of position, and are fine. If White exchanges on e6, we can play down the semi-open f-file. Otherwise, the e4-pawn won't be so easy for White to defend.} 
