8. O-O {Or8.Be3Be6. The pawns remainingon a4 and a7 change little.} 
8. O-O {Both sides have sorted out their kingside. A good plan is now to shift our knight and then play ...c7-c5. It will then be very difficult for White to successfully achieve the d3-d4 advance.} 
9. Be3 {Giri's recommendation, and White's most natural move. They simply continue developing.Should White start with9.a5, we can transpose with9...a6, while9...Nb4, with the ideaof ...c7-c5, is also a good plan. White now has two plans. The primary one is to advance with d3-d4, but as long as we're careful that won't come to anything. The second is to play for f2-f4. That wasn't really an option when White had played Re1.} 
9. Ne7 {The same plan: we want to play ... c7-c5 next.9...Na5is fine too, although Anish shows some nifty tactics there. He takes advantage of the dark-squared bishop already being developed.He wants to exchange a pair of knights on f6 and then play Qd2. When we defend the pawn with ...Kh7, he'll unleash Ng5+. Black cannot take, as the queen is trapped on f6. As long as we're careful there, I think we're fine, but as d3-d4 isn't scary here, we might as well keep our knight more actively placed.} 
10. Qd2 {We're following Anish.} 
10. Kh7 {Clearly, we had to defend the pawn. The plan remains the same.} 
11. Rae1 {White is getting ready to play on the kingside. The inclusion of Qd2 and ...Kh7 doesn't change much after11.d4exd4.} 
11. c5 {Our plan achieved.} 
12. Nh2 {We see Giri's reasoning for leaving the rook on f1. He wants to open up the f-file. This position feels much more like a Rossolimo Anti-Sicilian than a typical Italian!} 
12. Nh5 {The most combative move, and therefore the one most in the King's Indian spirit. We're wrestling for control of the f4-square.A solid alternative is12...Be6. Giri continues13.f4exf414.Bxf4Nc615.Rf2. I think Black has a few continuations that are okay there: the immediate15...d5,15...b6!?simply preparing it, or, my preference,15...Nh516.Be3Qd7,intending ...Rae8 and ...f7-f5.} 
13. g4 {White can't make any progress without this. Pushing the f-pawn immediately would be an improved version of 12...Nc6, as we'll get rid of White's bishop.13.Ng4?!f5!is definitely a step in the wrong direction. Suddenlythe e3-bishop and knight have run out of squares.} 
13. Nf4 {The point. We sacrifice a pawn, but in return deprive White of their dark-squared bishop. With White's pawns on light squares, that's a big liability.} 
14. Bxf4
14. exf4 {Next, we'll play ...g6-g5.} 
15. Qxf4
15. g5 {We continue the fight for the dark squares. Next, our knight will hop into play via g6. The position is very complicated, and White is certainly not playing without risk.} 
16. Qd2
16. Ng6 {Our knight and g7-bishop are both very happy pieces. Next, we're ready to develop the other bishop.} 
17. Ne2 {I don't see what White does other than preparing f2-f4.} 
17. Be6 {Completing our development. Now we threaten to advance in the center ourselves.17...Be5is also interesting.} 
18. f4 {White's only logical continuation. After18.Ng3Nf4,the weakness of the h3-pawn would force White to retreat. We could also start with18...Qd7, as19.Nf5Nf4would again exploit the weak h-pawn.} 
18. gxf4
19. Nxf4
19. Qg5 {An annoying pin. As White's queen is undefended, we threaten ...Be5 winning the knight.} 
20. Rd1 {White could also try20.Qc1, but then we'll exchangetwice on f4 followed by regaining the sacrificed pawn on b2.} 
20. Bxc4
21. dxc4
21. Rae8 {We've completed our development and can be very happy with our compensation. We have control of the dark squares, White has a weak e-pawn, and their king is very loose.} 
