6. c3 {White keeps their options open.} 
6. g5 {As White was preparing to advance in the center we should push the pawn two squares.} 
7. a4 {Only now. This time we have slightly different challenges, as we've committed to ...g7-g5. However, it's certainly not the end of the world. Since White has castled, we don't need to worry about h2-h4 as much. The knight's route to f5 is blocked by the f1-rook.} 
7. Bg7 {Preventing the pawn from advancing any further with7...a5is also respectable.} 
8. Re1
8. g4 {This is often well-timed once White moves the rook from the f-file. White's breaks with f2-f3/f4 are no longer so scary. Sethuraman recommends8...a6!?, which is okay, but feels a bit random to me.} 
9. Nfd2
9. h5 {Our idea is to grab maximum space. Of course, we have attacking ideas, but we also want to fight for control of the g5 and f5-squares.} 
10. Nf1
10. h4 {We make way for the rook to guard the g5-square.} 
11. Ne3 {The choice of a 2600+ GM.11.Bg5would be annoying were it not for11...Rh5!} 
11. Bh6 {We're now able to activate the bishop too.} 
12. b4
12. g3 {Well pushing the pawns turns out to be something about attacking too.} 
13. fxg3
13. hxg3
14. h3 {Petrosian-Dilanyan, Jermuk 2019.} 
14. Bf4 {In the game, Black played the interesting sacrifice14...Bxh3!?but it was better to prepare it. Now it's a big threat. Another plan is to hop our knight roundto g6. White is under a lot of pressure.} 
