7. Bg7 {We already covered the position after8.Bb3O-O, while we should again react to8.d4with8...exd4.} 
8. Re1
8. O-O {Now that we've castled we threaten ...Na5, either exchanging off White's light-squared bishop or gaining a lot of space on the queenside. Both9.Bb3Re8and9.a4a5would transpose to positions already covered.} 
9. b4 {An interesting try from Wesley So. White grabs space and cuts out ...Na5.} 
9. a6 {Let's prevent that pawn from marching any further. Against the natural9...Re8, White had the slightly annoying10.Qb3. Then10...Be611.Bxe6Rxe612.d4favors White. It's important for us to first take possession ofthe b5-square.} 
10. a4 {The logical continuation.10.Nf1?!d5would see us take over.} 
10. Re8 {Now we can return to the ...Be6 plan.} 
11. Qb3
11. Be6
12. Bxe6
12. Rxe6
13. d4 {Let's see why this is no longer so strong.} 
13. exd4
14. cxd4
14. Qe7 {We attack the e4-pawn. Without ...a7-a6 White could have dislodged our c6-knight with b4-b5. Now we can just capture. White wouldn't be able to recapture with the a-pawn, as the rook would hang. Next, we'll treble on the e-file.} 
15. d5 {The fork doesn't work.} 
15. Nxd5 {The a1-rook hangs. Thanks for the pawn!} 
