[White "42) Italian: Conclusion"]
[Black "Italian − Conclusion"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {The Italian is an extremely versatile opening. Some players still use it as an attempt to play chess without bothering too much about memorization. At the top level, it’s now one of the more principled tries and has exploded into sharp tactical duals, particularly in the setups with Bg5.I’ve offered a choice. With4...Bc5followedby ...d7-d6 and ...a7-a5 we follow in the footsteps of Magnus Carlsen. We prevent White from seizing space on the queenside. In general, the setup is quite easy to play. We’re happy to exchange bishops on e6. Our worst-placed piece tends to be the c6-knight, and so rerouting that to g6 makes a lot of sense.  The old-fashioned way of playing with Bb3 and Nbd2-f1 is too slow and leaves White struggling for equality. Our play in the center simply comes too quickly. The main line sees White angle for d3-d4, but with accuracy, it appears to have been defused. White is now looking at earlier deviations.We finished our coverage with the trendy early7.Bg5. These positions are extremely sharp, especially for an Italian. We attack on the kingside while White attempts to challenge us in the center. Black is currently holding firm.4...h6reaches completely different types of positions. We intend to fianchetto our bishop and take White out of their comfort zone. Pay attention to our decision on pushing the g-pawn one or two squares.  In the main line, White immediately prepares topush d3-d4, and so ...g7-g5 is key. The point is to dislodge the knight from f3, a key defender of the d4-square. These positions are extremely complicated. We often delay castling for a long time. The priority is to make it as difficult as possible for White to harmoniously develop.  Setups with an early a2-a4 are very popular, with different versions having been recommended in various repertoire guides. White makes sure their c4-bishop is safe and has a plan of expanding on the queenside. Remember the rule of thumb; if White plays a move that prepares d3-d4 then we should play ...g7-g5, otherwise, I prefer the more compact ...g7-g6.  We usually react to a4-a5 with ...a7-a6. White can play with either c2-c3 or Nc3, but our setup remains the same. White is often careless and allows us to exchange their light-squared bishop with ...Na5. Most of the lines boil down to whether White is able to successfully hold on to their center after d3-d4. It’s a lot more difficult than it might seem.} 1. --
