[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6 {In this chapter, we'll examine White's remaining paths after3...Nf6. The two main tries are the Scotch Gambit and4.Ng5.} 
4. Ng5 {White's attempt at refuting 3...Nf6. Its theoretical status has waxed and waned. It's currently had a re-emergence, with both Wesley So and Yuriy Krykun recommending it in their lifetime repertoires.4.d4exd4is the Scotch Gambit. This could also be reached via3.d4exd44.Bc4Nf6. This was my recommendation in my Coffeehouse Repertoire.5.e5White could also play5.O-O. There are a couple of tricks, but it shouldn't be challenging.5...d5is Black's typical retort. There's been a recent fashion for the solid5...Ne4too.6.Bb5Nd7!?But this is unusual. There's been a recent uptick in this move's popularity, but it's still likely to catch your opponent off-guard.  By far the main move is6...Ne4but White has quite good chances to get either an attack going or a structural nibble. Our knight is instead going on a strange journey,all the way back to b8, if necessary. The point is to control the c6-square, and therefore make it easier to advance with ...c6-c5. If White is not careful, they can easily be overrun.} 
4. d5 {The only way to hold on to the f-pawn. We're obliged to sacrifice a pawn.} 
5. exd5
5. Na5 {Taking the pawn is extremely risky.5...Nxd5?!6.Nxf7may well win by force, while6.d4is also very pleasant for White. Playing with a combination of5...b5and 6...Nd4 is possible, but for now, we'll follow established routes.} 
6. Bb5+ {None of White's alternatives are really playable.} 
6. c6 {The main line, but I'll also offer6...Bd7!?, which I believe is an underrated and easy-to-play alternative.} 
7. dxc6
7. bxc6 {The battle lines are drawn in an extremely peculiar variation. White has won a pawn, forced us to sideline our knight and damage our queenside. If they get time to develop their pieces properly, then they're practically winning. But that's a big if.White's problem is that the two developed pieces are both misplaced. The knight is about to be shunted back. It struggles to find a good square. That's why8.Bd3, giving theknight the e4-square, has become the main line. But that blocks White's d-pawn. It won't be easy to untangle.} 
