9. c3 {Rare, but I think this is the only way to try and make 6.d3 work.} 
9. O-O {We complete our development.} 
10. O-O
10. Re8 {The most ambitious. We could also regain the pawn with Sethuraman's recommendation of10...exd3, but we want more! White will now be able to hold onto their extra pawn but at a big cost.} 
11. b4 {White's most forcing try. White struggles to develop their queenside. Against waiting moves, we can capture on d3 followed by collecting the d5-pawn.} 
11. Nxc4
12. dxc4
12. Bd6 {Quite a typical setup for the 6.d3 lines. White is a pawn up, but that's the end of the good news; ...Ng4 is a big threat. Our queen and knight will join the bishop and e4-pawn in the attack. The d3-square is also a big weakness. White's extra queenside pawn actually makes it hard for White to develop.} 
