7. Bd6 {The main move historically, but interestingly it's fallen out of fashion recently, with7...Be7overtaking it. It's a tricky choice.From d6 we defend the e-pawn, and potentially eye White's h2-pawn. The downside is that it's far more likely to be a true pawn sacrifice now, as we'll struggle to regain the pawn on d5. Instead, we're likely to play ...c7-c6 and make it a full-blooded sac.} 
8. Nc3 {White's main try.} 
8. c6 {Rare, but I like this concept. We accept the pawn loss, but we're going to gain time on White's bishop to allow our knight to return to the action.} 
9. dxc6 {Starting with9.Nge4!?Nxe410.Nxe4Be7will come to the same thing,as White will have to capture on c6.} 
9. Nxc6 {The knight returns to the action.} 
10. Nge4
10. Nxe4
11. Nxe4
11. Be7 {We drop back temporarily but both ...Nd4 and ...f7-f5 are unpleasant to deal with.} 
