8. cxb5 {We call White's bluff. We're giving up the exchange, but the process of taking it takes quite a bit of time. Black is a bit spoilt for choice here. I also like8...Be7.} 
9. Qxa8
9. Qc7 {Ding Liren's9...Be7!?is also very interesting, but let's follow Fabi. Now we threatento entomb the queen with ...Nc6.} 
10. Qf3 {White has to get out of there.} 
10. Nc6 {This knight is usually a problem in the 4.Ng5 lines. It's a refreshing change to see it immediately charge for the center; ...Nd4 is a big threat.} 
11. c3 {White has to prevent our knight hop.} 
11. Bg4 {We develop another piece a tempo and force White to find another only move.} 
12. Qg3 {Here we have a choice.} 
12. Bf5 {A calm alternative. The only game to see this move saw Black successful in correspondence.} 
13. O-O {The most natural move. The correspondence game saw the inclusion of13.a4b4, but that just gives us more options.} 
13. h6 {Another test.} 
14. Nf3
14. Ne4 {Oops. White's queen is getting trapped.} 
15. Qh4
15. Be7 {Just one square left.} 
16. Qh5
16. g6 {Game over.} 
