10. Ne5
10. Bc5 {We play the same way. The threat of ...Qd4 is extremely awkward.10...Bd6is also promising.} 
11. O-O {This isn't very inspiring but seems to be the only way to keep the game balanced.} 
11. Qd6 {The simplest. Both11...Qd4!?and11...O-Oalso provide good play. But now White has to be extremely careful.} 
12. Ng4 {A slightly better retreat than12.Nc4?but White is still in a lot of trouble.} 
12. Bxg4
13. Bxg4
13. h5 {Our knight wants the g4-square. The following includes some very pretty mating patterns.} 
14. Be2
14. Ng4 {Our idea.} 
15. Bxg4
15. hxg4 {We renew the mate threat on h2.} 
16. g3
16. Qe6 {This one looks even stronger than Andrey's16...Rxh2. We hold onto the g-pawn to maintain the cage around White's king. We plan to double on the h-file and enter. There's not a lot White can do about it. We'll follow a correspondence game where White incautiously allowed our mating net.} 
17. d3
17. O-O-O
18. Qe1
18. Nc4 {Neat, but18...Rh3also won.} 
19. Bf4 {Capturing the knight immediately will come to the same thing after 19...Rh3.} 
19. Rh3
20. dxc4
20. g5 {Preventing White from any counterplay with Qa5-c7 threats.} 
21. Qa5
21. gxf4
22. Qxc5
22. Rxh2 {White resigned in Rodriguez-Antonov, ICCF 2018. There's no defense to mate along the h-file.} 
23. Kxh2
23. Rh8+
24. Kg1 {Including24.Kg2f3+doesn't alter anything.} 
24. Qh6 {White cannot prevent mate on either h1 or h2.} 
25. Qf5+
25. Kb7 {Just don't go to the wrong square allowing a queen trade. White has one more check but will then have to throw in the towel.} 
