4. d5
5. exd5
5. Na5
6. Bb5+ {Overwhelmingly played. We just investigated White's dodgy alternatives.} 
6. c6 {The principal reaction. We make it a proper pawn sacrifice and damage our queenside into the bargain. But in return, White struggles to find a safe haven for their bishop.} 
7. dxc6
7. bxc6 {White has a wide choice. These days the odd looking8.Bd3is by far the most popular and was endorsed by both So and Krykun. We'll examine that next. The classical8.Be2is still seen from time to time, while the weird8.Qf3sees an occasional outing or two.} 
8. Be2 {The Classical main line. This is the most comfortable spot for the bishop but does leave the knight to fend for itself.} 
8. h6 {Now the knight is the problem. It lacks a good square.} 
9. Nh3 {As White is suffering so much after9.Nf3, the top players have switched to this weird retreat.} 
9. Bd6 {I think this is the easiest setup. We'll just develop our pieces. Taking on h3 is very tempting, but generally, it's better to just leave it offside. White has a few different tries, but usually, we're going to castle and play ...c6-c5. That opens up the long diagonal and the c6-square for our knight to return. Dropping the bishop back to c7 and ...Rb8 also makes a lot of sense.} 
10. d3 {White will need this at some point. They have to develop their queenside eventually.} 
10. O-O {White tends to choose between castling immediately and developing the knight.} 
11. Nc3
11. c5 {Straightforward play. White would probably slightly prefer the knight on d2 here. Our plans are pretty interchangeable, and so11...Bc7is also strong. See the model game Kruk-Zemlyanov, email 2020 to see how we might finish White off.} 
