6. Bb5+ {Overwhelmingly played. We just investigated White's dodgy alternatives.} 
6. c6 {The principal reaction. We make it a proper pawn sacrifice and damage our queenside into the bargain. But in return, White struggles to find a safe haven for their bishop.} 
7. dxc6
7. bxc6 {White has a wide choice. These days the odd looking8.Bd3is by far the most popular and was endorsed by both So and Krykun. The classical8.Be2is still seen from time to time, while the weird8.Qf3sees an occasional outing or two.} 
8. Bd3 {We've seen the problems White has encountered in the other lines, so this retreat square is chosen by the process of elimination. Blocking the d-pawn looks very strange, but White is fighting for control of the e4-square.} 
8. Nd5 {As White's knight now has access to the e4-square, it's less logical to hit it with the pawn. By moving the knight we open up an attack on the knight and prepare either to hop in with ...Nf4 or get our f-pawn involved.} 
9. Ne4 {Supporting this square was the point of White's last, but the knight is going to get hit again.} 
9. Nf4 {First, we attack the bishop. White has a depressing choice.} 
10. O-O {White gives up their bishop. This would probably be my choice after playing 9.Ne4, but I wouldn't play it happily.} 
10. Nxd3
11. cxd3
11. Be7 {That pawn isn't going anywhere, so we don't need to rush. It's not just the damaged structure. White also has their typical problems developing the queenside.} 
12. b4 {The only way to complicate our play.12.Nbc3?!f5!is already horrible. The knight has to drop backto g3, but then we'll castle followed by ...f5-f4-f3 and attack!} 
12. Qxd3 {Making room for the knight to jump to c4, and making it easier to defend our bishop when it's on b4.} 
13. Re1
13. Bxb4
14. Qa4
14. Qb5 {The point behind capturing the d3-pawn. We defend the bishop and prepare to castle.} 
