15. gxf4 {What else?} 
15. Qh4 {Bringing the queen into the attack. I don't think White can survive.} 
16. fxe5 {White may as well take the pawn.} 
16. Rxe5+ {Now the f2-pawn is falling.} 
17. Kd1
17. Bxf2 {White has to plug the e-file.} 
18. Be2
18. Nc4 {This idea again. We're greedy in our attack. We want the d-file too.} 
19. dxc4
19. Rd8
20. Bd3
20. c5 {Two pieces down, but look at that coordination. As well as the rook, ...Bf3+ is a big threat.} 
21. Nd5
21. Qg4+
22. Be2
22. Qg2 {Gaining a tempo on the rook to get to the long diagonal.} 
23. Rf1
23. Bxd5 {If White doesn't capture on d5, then ...Rxe2 cleans up.} 
24. cxd5
24. Rexd5
25. Bc4
25. Kh8 {Sidestepping the pin. Time to reap the harvest.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "47) Forcing Italian 4.Ng5: 8.Bd3 Nd5 White alternatives"]
[Black "8.Bd3 Nd5 9.h4 Qc7 Informational"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. Ng5
4. d5
5. exd5
5. Na5
6. Bb5+ {Overwhelmingly played. We just investigated White's dodgy alternatives.} 
6. c6 {The principal reaction. We make it a proper pawn sacrifice and damage our queenside into the bargain. But in return, White struggles to find a safe haven for their bishop.} 
7. dxc6
7. bxc6 {White has a wide choice. These days the odd looking8.Bd3is by far the most popular and was endorsed by both So and Krykun. The classical8.Be2is still seen from time to time, while the weird8.Qf3sees an occasional outing or two.} 
8. Bd3 {We've seen the problems White has encountered in the other lines, so this retreat square is chosen by the process of elimination. Blocking the d-pawn looks very strange, but White is fighting for control of the e4-square.} 
8. Nd5 {As White's knight now has access to the e4-square, it's less logical to hit it with the pawn. By moving the knight we open up an attack on the knight and prepare either to hop in with ...Nf4 or get our f-pawn involved.} 
9. h4 {Quite a fashionable alternative. White maintains the knight on g5, but it's obviously very risky. These positions can get extremely messy. We'll analyze the main move,9.Nf3, in the next segment.} 
9. Qc7 {I was close to recommending this one, but the following line annoyed me a bit.} 
10. Nc3 {Taking on h7 with the bishop is sort of playable, but extremely dangerous. White is playing with fire.} 
10. h6
11. Nxd5 {White repairs our structure, but it's very concrete.} 
11. cxd5
12. Qh5
12. Bc5 {We want counterplay against White's f-pawn.} 
13. b4 {Deflecting the bishop. Immediately taking on f7 allows us to castle, with a huge mess.} 
13. Bxb4
14. Nxf7
14. O-O {We can't take the knight, as Bg6 would win our queen.} 
15. Nxe5
15. Rf5 {Forced. We attack the queen and knight.16.Bxf5?Qxe5+is not to be recommended.} 
16. Qe8+
16. Rf8 {Both sides' moves are forced.} 
17. Qh5
17. Rf5 {And a draw. Unfortunately, I couldn't see a good way to deviate, and so I shelved9...Qc7. Still, if you don't mind allowing White to make a theoretical draw, then9...Qc7is a very healthy alternative.} 
