14. Qf3 {The only square. White has to hold on to the g-pawn. Neither14.Qe4?!Bf5nor14.Qf1?Bf5is playable. In the latter scenario, White is too passive. They can't easily move the queen, and therefore the king is also stuck.} 
14. h5 {My preference. I want the g4-square for our bishop. Both Sethuraman and Gustafsson offer14...Bb7, which also looks promising. One final option is14...Nh5!?. We'd be happy to get the queens off, as the bishop will fall shortly.} 
15. Nc3
15. Bg4 {White loses more time with their queen.16.Qe4would now run into16...O-O-Ofollowed by ...Rd4.} 
16. Qg3
16. Bb4 {We're making life as hard as possible for White. They can't yet castle, as ...Ne2+ after an exchange on c3 will collect the queen.} 
17. a3 {White can't allow our bishop to sit there for long.} 
17. Bxc3 {The queen is still tied to the defense of the g-pawn and so White has a choice as to which pawn to recapture with.} 
18. dxc3
18. O-O-O {Always nice to castle and threaten mate.} 
19. f3 {White desperately needs to block our bishop.} 
19. Qd6 {Renewing the big threat of a check on d1.} 
20. Bxf4
20. exf4 {White has succeeded in preventing the check, but the king is now wide open.} 
21. Qf2
21. Re8+ {We don't want to allow White time to castle.} 
22. Kf1
22. Nc4 {Time for the knight to join in the attack.} 
23. fxg4 {Too greedy.} 
23. Ne3+ {White is a whole rook up after but cannot move at all.} 
24. Kg1
24. hxg4 {The h1-rook just gets in the way of White's king's safety. The bishop on h7 might as well have been removed from the board a dozen moves ago. The major threats are ...Nd1 and ...g4-g3. The game is likely to finish in the following way:} 
25. Re1
25. g3
26. Qf3
26. Qc5 {Uh oh.} 
27. b4
27. Qb6
28. Re2
28. Rd8 {Not the only way to do it, but the prettiest. Despite our rook deficit, our pieces are still the ones controlling all the squares.} 
