8. Bd3 {We've seen the problems White has encountered in the other lines, so this retreat square is chosen by the process of elimination. Blocking the d-pawn looks very strange, but White is fighting for control of the e4-square.} 
8. Nd5 {As White's knight now has access to the e4-square, it's less logical to hit it with the pawn. By moving the knight we open up an attack on the knight and prepare either to hop in with ...Nf4 or get our f-pawn involved.} 
9. h4 {Quite a fashionable alternative. White maintains the knight on g5, but it's obviously very risky. These positions can get extremely messy. We'll analyze the main move,9.Nf3, in the next segment.} 
9. h6 {We have a range of options, but I think this one is the simplest.9...Qc7and9...Bc5are also fine.9...Be7is probably also okay, but I think this is what White is hoping for. We have a mess after10.Qf3. White manages to sacrifice their bishop for three pawns, while our king has to start walking.} 
10. Qh5 {The point. White threatens mate. We should take a bit of care here.} 
10. Qf6 {The correct defense. We need to know how to handle White's various knight jumps.} 
11. Nh7 {An enterprising try.} 
11. Rxh7 {We sacrifice the exchange. In return, the bishop is entombed.} 
12. Bxh7
12. g6 {That bishop isn't coming out. We don't need to worry about taking it. First, we should develop and make life as hard as possible for White.} 
13. Qe2 {White needs to perform a strange dance with their queen.13.Qd1Qg7or13...Bf5!?would see us quickly collecting the bishop.} 
13. Nf4 {The knight jumps into its favorite square and forces the queen to move again. We don't want to allow d2-d4 to exploit the pin.} 
14. Qf3 {The only square. White has to hold on to the g-pawn. Neither14.Qe4?!Bf5nor14.Qf1?Bf5is playable. In the latter scenario, White is too passive. They can't easily move the queen, and therefore the king is also stuck.} 
14. h5 {My preference. I want the g4-square for our bishop. Both Sethuraman and Gustafsson offer14...Bb7, which also looks promising. One final option is14...Nh5!?. We'd be happy to get the queens off, as the bishop will fall shortly.} 
15. Nc3
15. Bg4 {White loses more time with their queen.16.Qe4would now run into16...O-O-Ofollowed by ...Rd4.} 
16. Qg3
16. Bb4 {We're making life as hard as possible for White. They can't yet castle, as ...Ne2+ after an exchange on c3 will collect the queen.} 
17. a3 {White can't allow our bishop to sit there for long.} 
17. Bxc3 {The queen is still tied to the defense of the g-pawn and so White has a choice as to which pawn to recapture with.} 
18. bxc3 {This doesn't feel like the right capture to me, but the open d-file generated too many problems.} 
18. O-O-O {Completing our development. Now we threaten ...Qf5.19.d3Nb3!is a pretty deflection crashing through.} 
19. f3 {White has to expel our bishop.} 
19. Bf5
20. d3 {White is slowly erecting a barricade.} 
20. Bxd3 {We won't allow that.} 
21. cxd3
21. Nb3 {Bringing all our pieces into the attack. We're starting to regain material.} 
22. Bxf4
22. exf4
23. Qh3+
23. Kc7 {White is a rook up but would struggle to intentionally put their pieces on more passive squares.} 
24. O-O {White cannot allow ...Qxc3+.} 
24. Nxa1
25. Rxa1
25. Qxc3 {Another pawn back.} 
26. Rd1 {Otherwise, we'd play ...Qxd3.} 
26. Qe5 {We have just one pawn for the piece, but a pawn is the maximum White will get for the bishop. Our queen dominates the board, while White's is completely sidelined. Our main job here is to keep White's queen out of the action.} 
