10. O-O {We have a few choices, but this retains the most winning chances.10...f5is the most forcing, and recommended by both Jan and Sethuraman. I think it's fine, but White can exploit the potential pin downthe a4-e8 diagonal to free roll a bit. Black has to show a bit of accuracy to hold the draw. If you like playing against White's doubled d-pawns then10...Nf4is a good alternative.} 
11. Be2 {White has to continue their plan.} 
11. f5 {And we continue ours.11...Nf4was Carlsen's attempt but is probably too late.} 
12. d3
12. Qc7 {A slight nuance. We're getting ready to play ...e5-e4, either immediately or after an exchange on c3.} 
13. g3 {This is Krykun's recommendation with the knights already exchanged on c3.} 
13. e4 {We can crash through anyway.} 
14. Nd4
14. Be5 {A key difference with the knight pair still on the board. White's other knight is undefended.} 
15. dxe4 {White is obliged to open the board anyway.} 
15. Nxc3
16. bxc3
16. fxe4 {White's position is already creaking; ...c6-c5 is one big threat, putting the bishop on h3 and rook on d8 others.} 
17. O-O
17. Rd8 {White will once again have to play very accurately to survive. Many of the 4.Ng5 lines aren't very practical. White has to know a lot and be very good at defensive calculation, or they'll run into immediate trouble.} 
