2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. Ng5
4. d5
5. exd5
5. Na5
6. Bb5+ {Overwhelmingly played. We just investigated White's dodgy alternatives.} 
6. c6 {The principal reaction. We make it a proper pawn sacrifice and damage our queenside into the bargain. But in return, White struggles to find a safe haven for their bishop.} 
7. dxc6
7. bxc6 {White has a wide choice. These days the odd looking8.Bd3is by far the most popular and was endorsed by both So and Krykun. The classical8.Be2is still seen from time to time, while the weird8.Qf3sees an occasional outing or two.} 
8. Bd3 {We've seen the problems White has encountered in the other lines, so this retreat square is chosen by the process of elimination. Blocking the d-pawn looks very strange, but White is fighting for control of the e4-square.} 
8. Nd5 {As White's knight now has access to the e4-square, it's less logical to hit it with the pawn. By moving the knight we open up an attack on the knight and prepare either to hop in with ...Nf4 or get our f-pawn involved.} 
9. Nf3 {The main move. Now that White has the e4-square under control, the knight can sit on f3 relatively comfortably.} 
9. Bd6 {This time we have to spend a move defending the e-pawn.} 
10. Nc3 {An interesting idea that became topical after Jorden Van Foreest successfully used it to get a great position against Magnus Carlsen. This is Yuriy Krykun's recommendation in his Dynamic Italian course. The point is to control the e4-square. White prepares to drop the bishop back to e2, and then they'll finally be able to coordinate properly.} 
10. O-O {We have a few choices, but this retains the most winning chances.10...f5is the most forcing, and recommended by both Jan and Sethuraman. I think it's fine, but White can exploit the potential pin downthe a4-e8 diagonal to free roll a bit. Black has to show a bit of accuracy to hold the draw. If you like playing against White's doubled d-pawns then10...Nf4is a good alternative.} 
11. Be2 {White has to continue their plan.} 
11. f5 {And we continue ours.11...Nf4was Carlsen's attempt but is probably too late.} 
12. d3
12. Qc7 {A slight nuance. We're getting ready to play ...e5-e4, either immediately or after an exchange on c3.} 
13. O-O {The most natural.} 
13. e4 {We start our operations.} 
14. dxe4
14. Nxc3 {With this knight trade, we're returning to the more usual12...Nxc3, but with White having committed to castling.} 
15. bxc3
15. fxe4 {The h2-pawn is ours whenever we feel like grabbing it.} 
16. Ng5 {White's best. They need to generate threats of their own.} 
16. Bf5 {We don't need to rush to capture on h2. White has to defend against ...Rad8, while the knight is also rather short on squares.} 
17. Bg4 {White is going after the e-pawn.} 
17. Bxh2+ {Regaining a pawn, and making sure White's king will never feel entirely comfortable.} 
18. Kh1
18. Be5
19. Bxf5
19. Rxf5 {Schulz-Schmidt, ICCF 2021. Yuriy goes this far and correctly notes it's equal. After capturing on e4, White will once again have an extra pawn, but it's an extra c-pawn and doesn't have much value. Our plan is to treble on the f-file. White will have to be very careful that painful things don't happen down the h-file.} 
