5. Na5
6. Bb5+ {Overwhelmingly played. We just investigated White's dodgy alternatives.} 
6. c6 {The principal reaction. We make it a proper pawn sacrifice and damage our queenside into the bargain. But in return, White struggles to find a safe haven for their bishop.} 
7. dxc6
7. bxc6 {White has a wide choice. These days the odd looking8.Bd3is by far the most popular and was endorsed by both So and Krykun. The classical8.Be2is still seen from time to time, while the weird8.Qf3sees an occasional outing or two.} 
8. Bd3 {We've seen the problems White has encountered in the other lines, so this retreat square is chosen by the process of elimination. Blocking the d-pawn looks very strange, but White is fighting for control of the e4-square.} 
8. Nd5 {As White's knight now has access to the e4-square, it's less logical to hit it with the pawn. By moving the knight we open up an attack on the knight and prepare either to hop in with ...Nf4 or get our f-pawn involved.} 
9. Nf3 {The main move. Now that White has the e4-square under control, the knight can sit on f3 relatively comfortably.} 
9. Bd6 {This time we have to spend a move defending the e-pawn.} 
10. O-O {After examining all the twists and turns, we've now reached the main line.} 
10. O-O {This is the most combative choice. We're going to repeat the same plan as we employed against 10.Nc3: castle and ...f7-f5. This is the most popular route, and you'll soon see why. The major alternative is ...Nf4xd3 reaching very weird positions. White has an extra pawn, but a compromised structure and difficulty developing their queenside.} 
11. Re1 {White goes after the e-pawn.11.Nc3?!f5would simply transpose to the 10.Nc3 variation.} 
11. f5 {We ignore White. We're offering the e-pawn, but it'll take White a couple of tempi to capture it. We're going to use those tempi to start a vicious assault.} 
12. Nxe5
12. Qf6 {Two pawns, but White has to waste another move.} 
13. Nf3
13. g5 {Exploiting White's two misplaced pieces. Our threat is ...g5-g4 trapping the knight.} 
14. c4 {Wesley So's recommendation. This is cutting-edge theory − the move didn't exist when Jan wrote his course. White's idea is to give up the knight, but in return grab space in the center and on the queenside. White's compensation is mostly positional, the a5-knight will be blocked out of the game. But we're not going to play along.} 
14. Nf4
15. Bf1
15. g4 {Time for White to part with their knight.} 
16. c5 {An interesting try seen in Paravyan-Motylev, Moscow 2021.} 
16. gxf3 {The Russian trainer dropped back with16...Bc7. The move is equally good, but I think capturing is easier. Let's just give back the piece.} 
17. cxd6 {Or17.Qxf3Bc7followed by ...Nd5.} 
17. fxg2
18. Bxg2
18. Nd3 {Our knight makes it very hard for White to get their queenside into the game.} 
19. Re3
19. Ba6 {With our knight supported, we're now ready to return to attacking on the kingside with ...f5-f4.} 
