10. O-O {This is the most combative choice. We're going to repeat the same plan as we employed against 10.Nc3: castle and ...f7-f5. This is the most popular route, and you'll soon see why. The major alternative is ...Nf4xd3 reaching very weird positions. White has an extra pawn, but a compromised structure and difficulty developing their queenside.} 
11. Re1 {White goes after the e-pawn.11.Nc3?!f5would simply transpose to the 10.Nc3 variation.} 
11. f5 {We ignore White. We're offering the e-pawn, but it'll take White a couple of tempi to capture it. We're going to use those tempi to start a vicious assault.} 
12. Nxe5
12. Qf6 {Two pawns, but White has to waste another move.} 
13. Nf3
13. g5 {Exploiting White's two misplaced pieces. Our threat is ...g5-g4 trapping the knight.} 
14. c4 {Wesley So's recommendation. This is cutting-edge theory − the move didn't exist when Jan wrote his course. White's idea is to give up the knight, but in return grab space in the center and on the queenside. White's compensation is mostly positional, the a5-knight will be blocked out of the game. But we're not going to play along.} 
14. Nf4
15. Bf1
15. g4 {Time for White to part with their knight.} 
16. d4 {This is the idea. Struggling to develop the queenside is such a common theme in this variation. It makes a refreshing change for White to have smooth development. Of course, they've had to give up a piece for it.} 
16. gxf3
17. Qxf3
17. Ne6 {It's important to attack the d-pawn. Otherwise, White would have time for c4-c5 and b2-b4. White now chooses between moving their queen and pushing the c-pawn immediately.} 
18. Qc3
18. Nxd4 {The main line is to drop the knight back with18...Nb7. But this gives White what they want. Instead, I want to fight for the initiative. I should mention that Demchenko's18...Qh4!?also looks challenging to meet.} 
19. c5 {Wesley's recommendation.} 
19. Be5 {We force White to capture the knight.} 
20. Qxa5
20. f4 {This isn't mentioned by Wesley, who instead only investigates going after the rooks with20...Nc2. I found this idea in 2021 and was looking forward to unleashing it against someone who was following So. Unfortunately, I was beaten to it.During the Olympiad in Chennai, I wandered over to watch our female team one round to see this position. My poor teammate, Zoe, had been hit by this improvement. Over the board, I think it's almost impossible to defend. ...Nc2 remains an idea, but Black also threatens ...f4-f3, developing the bishop to either f5 or g4, and the ...Nf3+ theme opening up the g-file crops up time and time again.} 
21. Qa4 {Defending the c2-square, and attempting to bring the queen back to a more relevant square.} 
21. Be6 {By covering the king, we threaten ...f4-f3 and ...Ne2+.21...Kh8attacking down the g-file was also promising.} 
22. Nc3
22. Kh8 {The threat is ...Nf3+ followed by doubling on the g-file. White would then not be able to prevent mate on either g1 or g2.} 
23. Kh1
23. Rad8 {An important idea. The point is to dissuade White from developing their bishop with Bd2. That's still White's only move, but we can then damage White's structure with ...Nf3. Once again we have a 0.00 position where White is needing to find a sequence of only moves not to get mated.} 
