21. Bf5 {With the f3-square under control, developing to g4 wouldn't have so much sense. But we can develop this way. White is really struggling to move. With the c2-square defended, we can also collect the exchange when we wish.} 
22. Nc4
22. Nf3+ {By this point, I hope this one doesn't come as a surprise.} 
23. gxf3 {Even though our rook isn't getting to the g-file immediately, this is still hopeless. White has to play23.Kh1. We then have a choice. We can captureon e1 immediately or we can throw in23...Bc3!?first, damaging White's structure. We'll reach a dynamically balanced middlegame; an achievement for White!} 
23. Qg5+
24. Kh1
24. Rf7 {White has the move, but won't be able to block the g-file for long.} 
25. Nxe5
25. Rg7 {Our battery. If you remember one idea from these forcing Ng5 lines, please make it this one.} 
26. Bc4+
26. Kf8 {We don't want to allow Nf7+.} 
27. Ng4
27. Bxg4
28. fxg4
28. Qxg4 {The mate threat is still there.20...f4is incredibly rare, with just one outing. It's very likely to catch out your booked-up opponent, who was relying on Wesley to steer them through the chaos. Of course, the positions are very messy, but I think it's very easy for White to fall into a quagmire.  It will be interesting to see whether there will be any future developments here. I imagine, though, that wise White players are too scared to go anywhere near it. I expect to see a resurgence of14.g3, but then14...g4!?is a very interesting new direction. It seems White is under practical pressure everywhere.} 
