[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6 {Before moving onto the Scotch Gambit which arises after4.d4exd4, we'll investigate White's other offbeat paths. We'll check4.Nc3from the Four Knights move order.} 
4. Qe2 {The best you can say about this is that it defends the e-pawn.} 
4. Bc5 {Fighting for control of the d4-square makes the most sense. We can play with the same setup as we do in pure Italians. Like in the Wormald/Worrall Attack variations of the Spanish, the queen is simply misplaced on e2. White will find it much harder to successfully take control of the center.} 
5. Bxf7+ {White spots a tactic.} 
5. Kxf7
6. Qc4+ {White regains the piece.} 
6. d5 {But this is a bit of a killer. We immediately regain the pawn and have a huge center.7.exd5?Qxd5defends the bishop, while after7.Ng5+?Kg6!8.Qxc5Kxg5, we're simply a piece up. White has no way to exploit our wide-open king. It can potter back to safety.} 
7. Qxc5
7. Nxe4
8. Qe3
8. Re8 {White's experiment has backfired. Next, we'll castle by hand. We have the center and development advantage.} 
