3. Nf6
4. d4 {The most direct approach. White opens the center.} 
4. exd4 {We could also get this position from a Scotch move order:3.d4exd44.Bc4Nf6. White's most challenging try is5.e5, which we'll examine next. First, we'll check out White's other options.} 
5. O-O {White develops as swiftly as possible, but this does give up a second central pawn. I used this as a surprise weapon to defeat Wesley So in a rapid game, but, so long as we're careful, it's White who has to be more accurate to equalize.} 
5. Nxe4 {Grabbing the pawn. Were it not for this then White's opening would be quite promising.6.Nxd4d57.Bb5Bd7was examined in White's offbeat 4th moves.} 
