[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d4 {The most direct approach. White opens the center.} 
4. exd4 {We could also get this position from a Scotch move order:3.d4exd44.Bc4Nf6. White's most challenging try is5.e5.} 
5. e5 {The pure Scotch Gambit. White solves the problem of the hanging pawn by pushing it. This was my recommendation in my Coffeehouse 1.e4 Repertoire.} 
5. d5 {The most principled response. We force White to move their bishop again. These days5...Ne4is quite topical, but the positions there can be very dry.} 
6. Bb5 {White should add this pin or they'll struggle to recoup their pawn. White has two aims. One is to capture on c6 and then get a bind over the c5-square. If White achieves it, then Black is left with a weakened queenside and no counterplay. The second is to use the e5-pawn to start kingside operations. In an ideal world, the f2-pawn joins its compatriot on the fifth rank.} 
6. Ne4 {The main line.} 
7. Nxd4 {Black now needs to address the threat of capturing on c6 twice.} 
7. Bd7 {The tactical7...Bc5is another defense. Due to the weakness of the f2-pawn, White should respond with8.Be3.} 
8. Bxc6
8. bxc6
9. O-O
9. Bc5
10. f3 {The knight is forced backwards.} 
10. Ng5 {A position I've had a fair bit. White is going to gain more time on our stray knight with f3-f4, either immediately or after11.Be3.Black can attempt counterplay along the b-file, but White is often happy to either sacrifice the b-pawn or allow their queenside structure to be damaged by exchanging knights on c3.  The subsequently doubled pawns look ugly, but they do a good job of preventing Black's counterplay with ...d5-d4. Objectively, Black should be fine, but this is the position White is aiming for. I don't think we should give our opponents satisfaction.} 
