6. Bb5 {White should add this pin or they'll struggle to recoup their pawn. White has two aims. One is to capture on c6 and then get a bind over the c5-square. If White achieves it, then Black is left with a weakened queenside and no counterplay. The second is to use the e5-pawn to start kingside operations. In an ideal world, the f2-pawn joins its compatriot on the fifth rank.} 
6. Nd7 {An unusual retreat. This will catch your opponents off-guard. The main line is6...Ne4.The d7-square looks more passive, but the knight often gets hit on e4, and simply accelerates White's plan of pushing the f-pawn. White now needs to be careful to keep the e-pawn defended.  The main idea is to contest for control of the c6-square. Blocking the a4-e8 diagonal is also useful. White will be forced to capture on c6 before they can take our d4-pawn. Our strategy is then to take control of the center with ...c6-c5. I see elite players are starting to agree with me. Levon Aronian played this way in August 2022, while a few days before writing, Yu Yangyi opted for our main line against Martyn Kravtsiv.} 
7. O-O {White shouldn't rush to reclaim the pawn.7.Nxd4?Ncxe5and ...c7-c6 next. We're just up a pawn.} 
7. Be7 {Modest development, but there's not much point in putting our bishop on c5 here. We want to keep that square free for our newly minted c-pawn.} 
8. Re1 {This is also played a fair bit.} 
8. O-O {This is very similar to the main line, but the inclusion of Re1 and ...O-O favors us.} 
9. Bf4 {White could try to wait a bit more, but it's not clear what useful move they might try.} 
9. Nc5 {Exploiting the bishop. Maybe something like9.h3was better, but it's extremely vague. I think I'd choose9...Nb6, but9...Re8is another useful improving move.} 
10. Bxc6
10. Ne6 {First, we gain a tempo on the bishop. Next, we'll take on c6.} 
