5. d5 {The most principled response. We force White to move their bishop again. These days5...Ne4is quite topical, but the positions there can be very dry.} 
6. Bb5 {White should add this pin or they'll struggle to recoup their pawn. White has two aims. One is to capture on c6 and then get a bind over the c5-square. If White achieves it, then Black is left with a weakened queenside and no counterplay. The second is to use the e5-pawn to start kingside operations. In an ideal world, the f2-pawn joins its compatriot on the fifth rank.} 
6. Nd7 {An unusual retreat. This will catch your opponents off-guard. The main line is6...Ne4.The d7-square looks more passive, but the knight often gets hit on e4, and simply accelerates White's plan of pushing the f-pawn. White now needs to be careful to keep the e-pawn defended.  The main idea is to contest for control of the c6-square. Blocking the a4-e8 diagonal is also useful. White will be forced to capture on c6 before they can take our d4-pawn. Our strategy is then to take control of the center with ...c6-c5. I see elite players are starting to agree with me. Levon Aronian played this way in August 2022, while a few days before writing, Yu Yangyi opted for our main line against Martyn Kravtsiv.} 
7. O-O {White shouldn't rush to reclaim the pawn.7.Nxd4?Ncxe5and ...c7-c6 next. We're just up a pawn.} 
7. Be7 {Modest development, but there's not much point in putting our bishop on c5 here. We want to keep that square free for our newly minted c-pawn.} 
8. c3 {An interesting attempt. I mentioned it in passing in my Coffeehouse repertoire, and I see it's now been taken up by the strong Russian GM Maxim Matlakov. With the developments in the main line, I would probably recommend White to choose this path.} 
8. dxc3 {Declining the pawn with8...d3is also possible, but let's grab.} 
9. Nxc3 {9.Qxd5doesn't really work. We can takeon b2 and castle.} 
9. Nb6 {I think this is the simplest way to approach the position. We defend the d-pawn and prepare to expel the bishop.If you're looking for chaos, I advise you to investigate9...a610.Bxc6bxc6. White has to then play11.Nd4!when we respond with our typical11...Nb8,preparing ...c6-c5. We have a very messy equality.} 
10. a4 {Unplayed, but it's vital for White to try and shift our knight.} 
10. a5 {Cementing our knight on b6.10...a6is another interesting path. With dynamic play, White should have enough for the pawn, but a moment's hesitation and their position will collapse.} 
11. Be3 {This was my suggested path in the book. The line I gave continued11...Be612.Nd4Bd7with equality. It seems that both sides struggle to improve; a draw with13.Nf3Be6is quite likely.} 
11. O-O {Allowing White their plan, but getting our king to safety.} 
12. Bxb6 {The point of White's previous move.} 
12. cxb6 {White is regaining the sacrificed pawn, but in the meantime, we've got our king safely castled.} 
13. Qxd5 {13.Nxd5Be6also looks comfortable.} 
13. Bc5 {Our doubled b-pawns are a bit ugly, but this is a handy outpost. We're ready to exchange queens and play ...Bg4. If White drops back with the queen, then we'll play ...Nd4. White could win a pawn by taking twice on c6, but then our bishop pair promises us very good compensation. White's e-pawn is also a long-term liability.} 
