6. Nd7 {An unusual retreat. This will catch your opponents off-guard. The main line is6...Ne4.The d7-square looks more passive, but the knight often gets hit on e4, and simply accelerates White's plan of pushing the f-pawn. White now needs to be careful to keep the e-pawn defended.  The main idea is to contest for control of the c6-square. Blocking the a4-e8 diagonal is also useful. White will be forced to capture on c6 before they can take our d4-pawn. Our strategy is then to take control of the center with ...c6-c5. I see elite players are starting to agree with me. Levon Aronian played this way in August 2022, while a few days before writing, Yu Yangyi opted for our main line against Martyn Kravtsiv.} 
7. O-O {White shouldn't rush to reclaim the pawn.7.Nxd4?Ncxe5and ...c7-c6 next. We're just up a pawn.} 
7. Be7 {Modest development, but there's not much point in putting our bishop on c5 here. We want to keep that square free for our newly minted c-pawn.} 
8. Bxc6 {The main line. White cashes in and reclaims the pawn.8.e6won't have any independent significance. We just take it, when White will have to captureon c6 next move anyway.} 
8. bxc6
9. Nxd4 {White has to continue playing dynamically. Taking with the queen wouldn't make much sense. We can just castle, play ...Re8, drop our knight back to f8, and play for ...c6-c5.} 
9. Nb8 {Once again we see our key concept. It may look very odd to undevelop this knight, but control of the c6-square is vital. We're ready with our plan of fighting back in the center with ...c6-c5.Capturing9...Nxe5would have been an error. White can develop swiftly with10.Bf4, and will quickly regain their pawn.} 
10. Nc3 {White defends tactically against our plan. Against any remaining moves, we'd just play ...c6-c5.} 
10. O-O {Be careful. First we should get our king to safety.} 
11. Qf3 {White tactically prevents ...c6-c5.} 
11. a5 {I was open when writing the Coffeehouse Repertoire that I thought this was the most serious Black try. At that point, it was incredibly rare, but players have evidently started agreeing with me. It turns out that it's actually quite hard for White to improve their position. Apart from simply gaining space, we have a sneaky idea of developing with ...Ra6. With the rook off the long diagonal, we can start advancing with ...c6-c5.} 
12. Re1
12. a4 {We'll play as Yu Yangyi did with the rook on d1. We simply gain more space. I didn't cover this semi-waiting move in my book. It's actually quite a tricky position for White to find a move.  We could carry out our plan with ...Ra6, but there's no rush. White's Nf5 exchange would work better then, as our rook would deprive our knight of the a6-square. We'll always want the pawn on a4 to target White's b2-pawn, so we might as well start with it. We can also improve with a later ...Re8.} 
13. Nf5 {In practice, I imagine White would play this knight jump at some point, but once again it's premature.} 
13. Bxf5
14. Qxf5
14. Qd7 {We have quite a few plans. Putting the knight on b4 goes after the c-pawn, while we can also consider attacking the e-pawn by fianchettoing our bishop with ...Re8, ...Bf8, ...g7-g6, and ...Bg7.} 
