[White "52) Forcing Italian: Conclusion"]
[Black "Chapters 43-51 − Conclusion"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {By far the most theoretical part of this segment was the discussion of4.Ng5. With this move White eyes theweak f7-pawn, and attempts to refute the Two Knights Variation.4...d55.exd5Na56.Bb5+is practically forced. First I offered the less theoretical6...Bd7!?. This alternative bypasses a lot of theory and seems completely playable to me. We then moved on to the irrational and highly theoretical main lines.White is a pawn up and Black has an offside knight on a5, but I believe it's still White who has to be more careful. The problem is that the knight on g5 struggles to find a safe haven.The Classical8.Be2is still playable, but White has to either retreat their knight to theugly h3-square or give back the pawn immediately.8.Qf3is another approach that's played quite a bit, but I find it extremely risky. I suggest sacrificing the exchange. In return, we have a massive lead in development, while White has problems with both the king and queen.  The recent trend has been for8.Bd3. This makes it much harder for White to develop their queenside, but controllingthe e4-square at least gives the g5-knight more hope.After8...Nd5, we first looked at the fashionable9.h4!?before turning our attention to the main line. With10...O-O11.Re1f5!we go for White's throat. We sacrifice two pawns and throw our g-pawn at White's king.  The modern trend is for White to sacrifice the knight. I think20...f4!is quite an important practical try, which is unmentioned by Wesley So. Instead of cashing in material, we want to maintain the initiative. The ensuing position is extremely hard for White to play, and so I expect White players to revert to the older14.g3. Then it'll be interesting to see whether my suggested14...g4!?becomes the fashionable antidote.  After a brief sojourn on White's early deviations, we examined the Scotch Gambit. Playing with5.O-Ois straightforward, but I think we're just a little better thanks to our better minor piece.5.e5is clearly critical. There’s been a recent trend for5...Ne4, but I find those positions too dry.  My recommendation of6...Nd7!?is rare, but starting to gain traction. The knight appears much more passiveon the d7-square rather than e4, but White often uses the latter to kickstart their attack by pushing the f-pawn.  Our plan is to control the c6-square and prepare to push White backwards with ...c6-c5. We’re happy to even play the bizarre undeveloped ...Nb8 to achieve our goal. We look passive for a moment, but the knight will be extremely strong on c6. It’s very difficult for White to know what to do.Yu Yangyi and Aronian have already tried6...Nd7and I imagine more players will try this interesting approach.} 1. --
