[White "53) Four Knights: Introduction"]
[Black "Four Knights − Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6 {We now move on to the Four Knights complex. With a symmetrical position, White can play almost anything, but the main division is between the Spanish Four Knights with4.Bb5and the Scotch Four Knights with4.d4.} 
4. d4 {The more topical route.4.Bb5is the Spanish Four Knights.4...Bc5!?This has been my preference for a more double-edged game.4...Nd4is the best if you want to force a draw, but White has a few ways to kill any enjoyment, including the immediate exchange, and 6.e5.  Keeping the symmetry with4...Bb4is also fine of course. If White now plays slowly we'll be doing well by exchanging a pair of knightswith ...Nd4.   We know from our Italian and Spanish that the c6-knight tends to be our worst-placed piece. White's critical attempts involve playing Nxe5 followed by forking our bishop and knight with d2-d4.} 
4. exd4
5. Nxd4 {We could also get this position via a Scotch move order.} 
5. Bb4 {Black has tried other moves, but this is the only satisfactory one. Thanks to the pin we attack the e-pawn, and so force White's hand.  Sethuraman's recommendation of5...Nxe4!?is interesting, but from a practical point of view, I don't like that White can decide whether to embrace the chaos or immediately make the game exceedingly dull.} 
6. Nxc6 {White has to first exchange knights to be able to defend the pawn with the bishop.} 
6. bxc6
7. Bd3
7. O-O {It's hard to find good winning chances against White's solid approach, but this is my attempt.7...d5is the recent trend.8.exd5O-O9.O-Ocxd5or9...Bg4!?. That looks exotic, but actually, it's an attempt at sucking all remaining life from the game.10.Bg5(the recent trend is for Kramnik's10.h3)10...Be6!?If you want to go this way, then I'd advise this approach over the main line of10...c6. But with Qf3 followed by an exchange on f6, the game remains very dry.} 
8. O-O
8. Re8 {Something a bit different. Instead of exchanging the central pawns, we'll attack the one on e4. This is obviously a bit riskier, but I think it's worth it to maintain winning chances.} 
