7. Bf4 {Both sides lose a tempo with their bishop. We've now transposed to the old main line of5...Be7, but these days White tries6.Bd3there instead.} 
7. d6 {Parrying the threat to the c7-pawn.} 
8. Nxd4 {White has to recapture the pawn.8.Bb5is sometimes played but we can just castle out of the pin.} 
8. O-O {Taking on d5 is also fine, but this forces White to show accuracy to equalize. The e4-pawn is a pain to defend.} 
9. Nb5 {The most common try. It's logical to go after the c7-pawn, but the knight ends up being rather misplaced.} 
9. Nxd5
10. exd5
10. Ne5 {We're ready to force back the bishop. The b5-knight is now rather aimless.} 
11. Be2
11. Ng6 {This time we should ask the bishop to make up its mind.11...c5?!wouldn't be effective here, as White is much quicker to castle.} 
12. Bg3 {Or12.Be3Bg5exchanging the bishops.} 
12. Bf6 {Our bishop takes up a pseudo-fianchetto.} 
13. c3
13. Bd7 {An interesting idea. We exploit the misplaced knight.} 
14. O-O
14. h5 {The e2-bishop is overworked, so we can grab some space. Our pieces are better placed, and so we are able to drum up an initiative.} 
