7. Bd3 {Most of White's other options simply transpose elsewhere.7.Bg5h68.Bh4O-Ois a transposition. Likewise7.f3O-Oand7.Qd3O-Ohave both already been covered.If White tries7.Bd2, then we can either transpose to 9.Bd2 after7...O-O8.Bd3Re89.O-O, or punish White with7...Qe7going after the e-pawn.} 
7. O-O {7...d5is the main line these days, but we're going for a slightly different approach. Rather than exchanging central pawns immediately, we want to continue putting pressure on the e-pawn. We'll only offer the trade once White's bishop is sidetracked.} 
8. O-O {Neither8.Bg5h6nor8.Bd2Re8will alter play.} 
8. Re8 {The secondary line in terms of popularity. We attack the e-pawn. Keeping the central pawns on the board keeps more life in the game.  I believe our opponents won't feel as comfortable here as in the main lines. White now has to choose how to defend the e-pawn.} 
9. Re1
9. d6 {It might look a bit odd, but moving our pawn just one square is quite a bit more aggressive. Our idea is to reroute our knight round to e5.} 
10. h3
10. Nd7 {White ruled out the g4-route, but we can go this way too. We're not committed to the e5-square either, we might want to hop into c5 to put more pressure on the e4-pawn. We've also made way for our queen to join the action on f6.} 
11. Be3 {Clearly not forced, but quite an illustrative move. White could try to prevent the doubling of their pawns with11.Bd2, but we can then exploit the weakening of the b2-pawn with11...Rb8. It's then not clear how White is going to continue.} 
11. Bxc3 {We don't need to rush with the exchange, but we're now getting a nice double-edged structure.} 
12. bxc3
12. c5 {This is the type of position we're aiming for. It's not that we're better, but we've maintained equality while keeping good winning chances. We'll put pressure on both e4 and c3-pawns with ...Bb7 and ...Qf6.} 
