[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "55) Four Knights: Spanish"]
[Black "4.Bb5 Bc5 5.d3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. Bb5 {Let's move onto the Spanish Four Knights.} 
4. Bc5 {Black has plenty of choices here. If we want to force a draw, then4...Nd4is probably best, but there are a few forced draw lines and some that are very tedious.  Keeping the symmetry with4...Bb4is also a good option, but I believe this is the most ambitious. White is really forced to act. If we're given time to complete our development and exchange a pair of knights on d4, we're doing well. The critical lines arethose where White captures on e5, and then plays d2-d4 forking our bishop and knight.} 
5. d3 {This position is actually more commonly reached via a 4.d3 Berlin move order3.Bb5Nf64.d3Bc55.Nc3. But playing Nc3 so early isn't considered to be so challenging.} 
5. Nd4 {A key idea. If you recall the Spanish and Italian chapters, the c6-knight is often a bit of a pain. Therefore we want to exchange it. It also makes White's light-squared bishop look a bit stupid.   White can exchange on d4, but then we can choose how to recapture it; with the pawn is fine here, but it's probably more consistent to always take with the bishop. Then we can set up on the queenside with ...c7-c6, ...d7-d6, and ...a7-a5.   It's just like a very comfortable Italian. White's light-squared bishop will get kicked around, and the c3-knight is misplaced.} 
6. Bc4 {This position is more often reached via the Four Knights move order with4...Nd45.Bc4Bc5. But by starting with 4...Bc5 we've avoided White's drawing lines.} 
6. O-O {Offering a transposition back to 6.Nxe5.6...d6is a simple alternative.} 
7. Bg5 {An additional plan, but not a good move. White's other main try,7.Nxe5would transpose to the 6.Nxe5 move order, while7.O-Od6is very comfortable.We threaten ...Bg4.} 
7. h6 {We force the bishop back.} 
8. Bh4
8. c6 {Another big benefit of our knight jump. With ...c7-c6 we take possession of the d5-square, and so we no longer need to worry about any knight jumps.  We're also preparing ...b7-b5 and ...a7-a5-a4, when White's bishop would run out of squares.} 
9. Nxe5 {Too late.} 
9. d5 {White is going to have severe problems down the e-file.} 
10. exd5 {This makes matters worse. The refutation is quite thematic.} 
10. Re8 {The fact that the engine advocates castling here, and giving up the knight for free, demonstrates how much trouble White is in.} 
11. f4 {White defends the knight, but now the king is stuck.} 
11. b5 {Forcing the bishop back. Now we'll be able to exchange it whenever we want.} 
12. Bb3
12. g5 {White's f4-pawn was keeping their position together. We get rid of it.} 
13. Bg3
13. gxf4
14. Bxf4
14. Bg4 {Developing with tempo, and making sure White can't castle on either flank.} 
15. Qd2
15. Qd6 {...Rxe5 next will clean up. White's king is a sitting duck.} 
