2. Nc6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. Bb5 {Let's move onto the Spanish Four Knights.} 
4. Bc5 {Black has plenty of choices here. If we want to force a draw, then4...Nd4is probably best, but there are a few forced draw lines and some that are very tedious.  Keeping the symmetry with4...Bb4is also a good option, but I believe this is the most ambitious. White is really forced to act. If we're given time to complete our development and exchange a pair of knights on d4, we're doing well. The critical lines arethose where White captures on e5, and then plays d2-d4 forking our bishop and knight.} 
5. d3 {This position is actually more commonly reached via a 4.d3 Berlin move order3.Bb5Nf64.d3Bc55.Nc3. But playing Nc3 so early isn't considered to be so challenging.} 
5. Nd4 {A key idea. If you recall the Spanish and Italian chapters, the c6-knight is often a bit of a pain. Therefore we want to exchange it. It also makes White's light-squared bishop look a bit stupid.   White can exchange on d4, but then we can choose how to recapture it; with the pawn is fine here, but it's probably more consistent to always take with the bishop. Then we can set up on the queenside with ...c7-c6, ...d7-d6, and ...a7-a5.   It's just like a very comfortable Italian. White's light-squared bishop will get kicked around, and the c3-knight is misplaced.} 
6. Ba4 {A more passive-looking retreat square, but at least the bishop will no longer be hit by ...d7-d5.} 
6. c6 {A good antidote. We prepare to annoy the bishop by pushing our a and b pawns. Starting with6...O-Ois also fine, and likely to transpose to 6.d3.} 
7. O-O {Safer, but these positions are not at all threatening.} 
7. d6 {White has to address the threat of ...Bg4.} 
8. Nxd4
8. Bxd4 {Caruana-Mamedyarov, Bucharest 2021. We have a very comfortable Italian-style position. White's bishop is severely misplaced. We'll continue with ...a7-a5.} 
