4. Bb5 {Let's move onto the Spanish Four Knights.} 
4. Bc5 {Black has plenty of choices here. If we want to force a draw, then4...Nd4is probably best, but there are a few forced draw lines and some that are very tedious.  Keeping the symmetry with4...Bb4is also a good option, but I believe this is the most ambitious. White is really forced to act. If we're given time to complete our development and exchange a pair of knights on d4, we're doing well. The critical lines arethose where White captures on e5, and then plays d2-d4 forking our bishop and knight.} 
5. Nxe5 {We should always be alert to this tactic.} 
5. Nxe5
6. d4 {We now have a choice. If you're happy to go into the main line, then I'd advise6...Bd6, but if you want to play the shortcut with 7...d5!?, then we should prevent the transposition with6...a6!?.} 
6. Bd6 {The usual approach. We don't want to concede our bishop. Instead, we get ready to recapture.7.dxe5Bxe58.O-OO-Oand7.O-OO-Oare both covered in the main line with 6.Nxe5.} 
7. f4
7. Nc6 {Jumping into g4 anyway is possible, but now we're in time to construct a bind on the light squares.} 
8. e5
8. Bb4
9. d5
9. Qe7 {We just saw this idea. White cannot castle as ...Qc5+ and ... Bxc3 wins the bishop. That means the pin is rather annoying.} 
10. dxc6
10. dxc6 {White has restored material equality, but now we can develop easily.} 
11. Bd3
11. Bg4 {Next we'll castle queenside. We're the side attacking.} 
