4. Bb5 {Let's move onto the Spanish Four Knights.} 
4. Bc5 {Black has plenty of choices here. If we want to force a draw, then4...Nd4is probably best, but there are a few forced draw lines and some that are very tedious.  Keeping the symmetry with4...Bb4is also a good option, but I believe this is the most ambitious. White is really forced to act. If we're given time to complete our development and exchange a pair of knights on d4, we're doing well. The critical lines arethose where White captures on e5, and then plays d2-d4 forking our bishop and knight.} 
5. O-O
5. O-O
6. Nxe5 {The critical test. We've seen this theme already, but it's generally considered more accurate for White to include castling.} 
6. Nxe5
7. d4
7. d5 {A useful shortcut. This is extremely rare, with just two games in the online database, but it seems completely playable to me. White is no longer going to get their big center.} 
8. exd5
8. Bd6
9. dxe5
9. Bxe5 {We're temporarily a pawn down, but White won't be able to hold on to the d-pawn forever.} 
10. Qd3 {White defends their knight and prevents our bishop from developing to f5.} 
10. a6 {We don't really want to capture on c3 now, as the bishop pair will be strong on the open board. Instead, we're going to sideline White's minor pieces.} 
11. Bc4
11. b5 {We highlight the drawback to the queen on d3.} 
12. Bb3
12. b4 {All of White's developed pieces are in the firing line.} 
13. Ne2
13. a5 {By gaining space on the queenside we threaten to annoy White's queen with ...Ba6. The b2-pawn is also a pain. It's very difficult for White to coordinate their pieces and enjoy the extra pawn. I think we can be happy with this theory-saving line.} 
