3. Nf6 {We've investigated White's main two moves. We'll now wrap up White's alternative tries.} 
4. g3 {If White wants to play with a kingside fianchetto, they have a few different move orders.} 
4. Bc5 {If you're unsure which setup to opt for, then this one can generally be recommended. We develop our bishop actively and will continue as we do in the Italian with ...d7-d6 and ...a7-a5.  We're actually reaching very similar positions to the 4...h6 Italian with reversed colors. In those positions, the extra tempo isn't very relevant, while the Italian is a very solid, flexible opening.The main move4...d5, is of course completely fine too.} 
5. Bg2
5. d6
6. d3 {White prepares to hassle our bishop. Starting with6.O-OO-Ois likely to transpose. White will need toplay d2-d3 sooner or later.6.Na4?!wasn't playable yet. We just grab the e-pawn.} 
6. a5 {Giving our bishop a retreat route. Pushing the pawn one square is fine too, but let's be consistent.} 
7. O-O
7. O-O {This position makes me think of color bias. If the pieces changed color, then I think our opponent would be pretty happy. They've taken a little risk to reach an unbalanced position with lots of play left. Such an approach works very well as Black but is very odd as White.  We have an easy position to play. The fianchettoed bishop and knight on c3 don't help the traditional d3-d4 break, and so we're now the ones on the front foot. White can play defensively, erecting a bind with c2-c4 as we do with colors reversed.  The only aggressive plan is to play for f2-f4, which takes time. We can grab more space on the queenside with ...a5-a4, and prepare to advance in the center ourselves with ...h7-h6 and ...Be6. We'll then be ready for ...d6-d5.} 
8. Bg5 {We don't need to fear the pin.} 
8. h6 {White doesn't want to give up this bishop for free.} 
9. Bh4
9. Bg4 {Our pin is scarier. We threaten both ...g7-g5 and ...Nd4.} 
10. Qd2 {White has to escape the pin.} 
10. Bxf3 {We're ready to win the bishop.} 
11. Bxf6 {White has to include the exchange or the bishop would be lost.} 
11. Qxf6
12. Nd5
12. Qg5 {White is just in time to keep level material, but the ensuing endgame is pretty unpleasant.} 
13. Qxg5
13. hxg5
14. Bxf3
14. Nd4 {We're about to force the knight back with ...c7-c6. Then we'll grab more space with ...a5-a4. White has managed to exchange some material, but this position is unpleasant.} 
