4. a3 {This is basically a waiting move. I played it myself a few times, but only because I wanted the Delayed Halloween Gambit.} 
4. g6 {Against White's random flank pushes I think we can revert back to our fianchetto. We'll now reach very similar positions to those examined in 4.g3, but with colors reversed. If you recall, that was a reversed 4...h6 Italian, so this one is a 'reversed reversed Italian'. I guess that just makes it a 4...h6 Italian!Breaking in the center with4...d5always equalizes too. We'd just be playing a Four Knights Scotch as White.The extra a2-a3, a2-a4, or h2-h3 doesn't change very much. Just be a bit careful with4...Bc5, as White would then take the opportunity to capture one5and play d2-d4.} 
5. d4 {Another scenario where White chooses to play as Black. With the pawn back on a2, we'd have a 4.g3 Four Knights. The pawn move isn't relevant.} 
5. exd4
6. Nxd4
6. Bg7 {With the pawn back on a2, it's considered that White has chosen a good setup to equalize. But we have a sensible structure too.} 
7. Nxc6
7. bxc6 {White now tends to choose between d3 and c4 for their bishop.} 
8. e5 {Too ambitious.} 
8. Qe7 {White has the Scotch problem. That e-pawn is vulnerable, while a2-a3 hasn't helped in the slightest.} 
9. Qe2
9. Nd5
10. Nxd5
10. cxd5
11. Bf4
11. O-O {We're preparing to increase pressure on the pawn.} 
12. O-O-O
12. d6 {13.exd6fails to13...Qf6,hitting both f4 and b2.} 
13. Rxd5 {Guseinov-Caruana, chess.com 2022.} 
13. Qe6 {Fabi played13...Rb8, but this is crushing. White can't allow our queen to landon a2.} 
14. Qc4
14. Ba6 {The queen is running out of squares. White is in a lot of trouble.} 
