[White "58) Vienna: Introduction"]
[Black "Vienna − Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nc3
2. Nf6 {The Vienna Game is extremely broad, seemingly covering everything that starts with 2.Nc3. Traditionally, it was played as a delayed King's Gambit, with f2-f4 automatically appearing next. These days the general consensus is that that's too risky.} 
3. f4 {The old main line. These days it's only likely to be played by Maverick GMs or at faster time controls.➟3.Bc4,apart from 3.Nf3, which is merely a transposition to the Four Knights after 3...Nc6, this is the most topical choice. White has been playing Italian setups with Nc3 everywhere, so it's not surprising this one has become popular too.3...Bc5is a good antidote. Of course, we might be transposing to traditional Italian structures, but I think we gain quite a lot by keeping our knight on b8.   We often have to spend a lot of time redeploying the c6-knight, now we could develop it to d7 instead. We're much quicker with ...c7-c6, a very useful move controlling the center, especially with a White knight on c3. White now has to decide whether the Vienna was a bluff, or if they really want to enter the complexities reached by pushing the f-pawn.➟3.g3is White's third most popular setup. There are a few move orders to reach a kingside fianchetto against 1...e5, but this is the most popular.3...Bc5−3...d5is the main line, but I like being consistent with developing ourbishop to c5. We're going for an ambitious plan of occupying the center with ...c7-c6 and ...d7-d5.} 
3. d5 {Unlike the pure King's Gambit, here we'll decline our pawn. Capturing on f4 doesn't combine well with our knight on f6. White would gain time with e4-e5. Our central play, however, is strengthened by our knight. Should White capture on d5, we can immediately recapture. White will already have to watch out for their king's safety.} 
4. fxe5 {The typical capture.} 
4. Nxe4 {White struggles to both get rid of our wonderful knight on e4 and adequately defend the e5-pawn. We're happy to even spend a tempo-provoking d2-d4, as then the knight cannot be shifted.   Exchanging knights doesn't help White that much. Our pawn on e4 prevents White's other knight from developing to the natural f3-square and makes it even harder to successfully hold on to the e5-pawn.} 
