[White "59) Vienna: The Old Fashioned 3.f4"]
[Black "2.Nc3 Nf6 3.f4 d5 4.exd5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nc3 {The Vienna. White has three main approaches: the old-fashioned3.f4, a kingside fianchetto, and Italian style with3.Bc4. First, we'll see why3.f4is no longer automatically played.} 
2. Nf6 {It's useful to be able to immediately play in the center with ...d7-d5. I was inspired by a couple of courses to study the Vienna from White's perspective.What really irritated me was Black delaying ...Nc6 entirely. If White plays3.f4, then we'll break in the center. Otherwise, our usual Italian setupwith ...Bc5 and ...d7-d6 works well.} 
3. f4 {The traditional main line, but a rare guest at the top level. White is claiming an improved King's Gambit, but Black has worked out a good response.} 
3. d5 {White would have an improved King's Gambit should we capture on f4. Our knight would be misplaced. Instead, we fight back in the center. White now chooses which pawn to capture.} 
4. exd5
4. Nxd5 {The extra f2-f4 doesn't help White much in this reversed Scotch structure.} 
5. Nxd5 {Not very inspiring.} 
5. Qxd5 {White's f-pawn is still hanging. In the meantime, we have very smooth development. As our queen can't be hit, it's on a great central square.} 
6. Qe2 {White pins our pawn, but this is very provocative. They're a long way from getting their king to safety.} 
6. Nc6 {We defend the pawn, but more pertinently threaten to hop in with ...Nd4. White doesn't really have a good move.7.Nf3Bg4just adds more pressure to their position.} 
7. c3 {The main move. White controls the d4-square, but it's pretty disgusting.} 
7. Be7 {Blocking the pin, and threatening an unpleasant check.} 
8. fxe5 {8.Nf3Bg4isn't really helping.} 
8. Bh4+ {Blocking the check drops material, and so White is condemned to living with their king in the center.} 
9. Kd1
9. Be6 {We have fantastic compensation for the pawn. But we also have a chance to finish the game immediately.} 
10. Nf3 {10.d4Nxd4!would only prolong the battle for a few moves. After giving a check on d4, we'll castle queenside. White's naked king stands no chance.} 
10. Qb3+ {Pretty.} 
11. axb3
11. Bxb3 {This pattern crops up all the time in puzzles, but it's rare to see it occur in an actual game.} 
