4. Nxe4 {We should keep a look out for ...Qh4+ ideas, but generally, we'll just going to develop. White's main problem is that it's very difficult to both shift our knight from e4 and defend the e5-pawn adequately. After d2-d4, our knight is a monster.   We're actually happy to spend a tempo to provoke the d-pawn forward. White can try stopping off with d2-d3, but after the exchange, we'll play ...d5-d4 ourselves, preventing the e-pawn from being defended.} 
5. Qf3 {The new main line. Our knight is such a thorn in White's side that they've decided to try and get rid of it asap.} 
5. Nc6 {I think this is easiest. White has to deal with ...Nd4 jumps.5...f5!?is fascinating. There was a recent elite game, Rapport-Abdusattorov, Wijk aan Zee 2023. Black won, but I think White had chances for an advantage.} 
6. Bb5 {White has to prevent ...Nd4.} 
6. Nxc3 {White has to decide how to recapture. We'll play ...Qh4+ and ...Qe4+ regardless.} 
7. dxc3 {This one is uglier, but it's important to be able to develop the bishop.} 
7. Qh4+ {The same plan. We're going to exchange queens on e4.} 
8. g3 {Parrying the check, but this creates more holes on the light squares.} 
8. Qe4+
9. Qxe4
9. dxe4 {We have the same position that we just examined, but with White's d2-pawn moved to b2. That makes it easier to activate the queenside pieces but also means that White has had to abandon hopes to be better. They'll no longer be able to build a center. In fact, they're still struggling to find equality.} 
10. Ne2 {White should probably start developing.} 
10. Bd7 {We attack the pawn.} 
11. Bxc6 {White feels obliged to make the exchange anyway.} 
11. Bxc6
12. Rf1 {White prevents us from castling queenside.} 
12. Be7
13. Be3
13. Bd7 {Redeploying the bishop. This was seen in Tedesco-Bernaert, ICCF 2021. White successfully held, but in a practical game, I'd be optimistic about my chances.   We'll play on the light squares with ...Bg4 or ...Bh3. Pushing the h-pawn also looks tempting. The e5-pawn also remains a liability, and I'm not sure where White's counterplay lies.} 
