[White "59) Vienna: The Old Fashioned 3.f4"]
[Black "4.fxe5 Nxe4 5.Qf3 #6"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nc3 {The Vienna. White has three main approaches: the old-fashioned3.f4, a kingside fianchetto, and Italian style with3.Bc4. First, we'll see why3.f4is no longer automatically played.} 
2. Nf6 {It's useful to be able to immediately play in the center with ...d7-d5. I was inspired by a couple of courses to study the Vienna from White's perspective.What really irritated me was Black delaying ...Nc6 entirely. If White plays3.f4, then we'll break in the center. Otherwise, our usual Italian setupwith ...Bc5 and ...d7-d6 works well.} 
3. f4 {The traditional main line, but a rare guest at the top level. White is claiming an improved King's Gambit, but Black has worked out a good response.} 
3. d5 {White would have an improved King's Gambit should we capture on f4. Our knight would be misplaced. Instead, we fight back in the center. White now chooses which pawn to capture.} 
4. fxe5 {The main approach. White forces our reply.} 
4. Nxe4 {We should keep a look out for ...Qh4+ ideas, but generally, we'll just going to develop. White's main problem is that it's very difficult to both shift our knight from e4 and defend the e5-pawn adequately. After d2-d4, our knight is a monster.   We're actually happy to spend a tempo to provoke the d-pawn forward. White can try stopping off with d2-d3, but after the exchange, we'll play ...d5-d4 ourselves, preventing the e-pawn from being defended.} 
5. Qf3 {The new main line. Our knight is such a thorn in White's side that they've decided to try and get rid of it asap.} 
5. Nc6 {I think this is easiest. White has to deal with ...Nd4 jumps.5...f5!?is fascinating. There was a recent elite game, Rapport-Abdusattorov, Wijk aan Zee 2023. Black won, but I think White had chances for an advantage.} 
6. Bb5 {White has to prevent ...Nd4.} 
6. Nxc3 {White has to decide how to recapture. We'll play ...Qh4+ and ...Qe4+ regardless.} 
7. dxc3 {This one is uglier, but it's important to be able to develop the bishop.} 
7. Qh4+ {The same plan. We're going to exchange queens on e4.} 
8. g3 {Parrying the check, but this creates more holes on the light squares.} 
8. Qe4+
9. Qxe4
9. dxe4 {We have the same position that we just examined, but with White's d2-pawn moved to b2. That makes it easier to activate the queenside pieces but also means that White has had to abandon hopes to be better. They'll no longer be able to build a center. In fact, they're still struggling to find equality.} 
10. Bxc6+ {White's usual try, but now there's a lot of suffering.} 
10. bxc6
11. Be3 {White doesn't want to allow11.Ne2Bc5, when their bishop would lack squares.} 
11. h5 {Creating further weaknesses in White's camp. They don't want to allow ...h5-h4.} 
12. h3 {Keeping the g4-square protected.} 
12. g6 {But now we can switch to winning the e5-pawn; ...Bg7 and ...O-O will put White under a lot of pressure.} 
