[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nc3
2. Nf6
3. Bc4 {This is the topical handling of the Vienna. As White has recently started playing Nc3 everywhere in the Italian, it's not really surprising that they should have started trying it out before touching the g1-knight. There's quite a bit of crossover here between the Vienna and the2.Bc4Italian too.} 
3. Bc5 {Of course, there are many options, but when I was looking at playing this with White, this one really bothered me. White can't even successfully transpose into an Italian, as the knight is not yet committed to c6.   If you recall, that knight is often our worst-placed piece in the Italian setups, and we happily spend a couple of tempi to move it. If White does a nothing move then we'll construct a setup with ...d7-d6, ...c7-c6, ...O-O, and ...a7-a5.} 
4. d3 {White stays flexible. The rash4.f4didn't really work, but they still hope to play aggressively.} 
4. O-O {This really bugged me when I was preparing the White side of this line. In fact, all Black's alternatives to4...Nc6were annoying:4...c6and4...d6too.} 
5. f4 {If your opponent has played this move order, then it's likely that this is what they intend.} 
5. exf4 {To be honest, I think Black has a lot of good paths here. I reached the position after5...Nc6by transposition, which is rather scary for White.5...d5!?is still very critical. Even5...d6, although it allows White's plan of6.f5, is praised by the engines.But I think this one is very straightforward. We're going to play ...c7-c6 and ...d7-d5.} 
6. Bxf4
6. c6 {Preparing the central break.} 
7. d4
7. Bb4 {We could even play7...d5!?here, but let's continue to follow Fabiano Caruana.} 
8. e5
8. d5 {Our central break arrives in time. Taking on f6 looks too scary. We recapture the piece on c4 and then ...Re8+ will force White's king to be stranded in the center. Nge2 would run into ...Bg4 pins.} 
9. Bd3
9. Ne4 {We both threaten to take on c3 and create weaknesses in White's position with ...Qh4+.} 
10. Nge2
10. Qh4+ {White has to weaken their light squares.} 
11. g3
11. Qh3 {We don't allow White to relieve the pressure by castling.} 
12. Bxe4 {Sooner or later this move is necessary anyway, as White can scarcely move.} 
12. dxe4
13. Bd2 {Threatening Nxe4.} 
13. Bxc3
14. Bxc3
14. Bg4 {We dominate on the light squares.} 
