4. Bg2
4. c6 {We're preparing to occupy the center with ...d7-d5. It's also possible to start with4...Nc6, when5.Nf3would transpose to 4.g3 in the Four Knights.However, White's knight might be a little better on e2, as White will find it easier to break with f2-f4.} 
5. Nge2 {The natural move, but now we can expand unmolested in the center.} 
5. d5
6. exd5 {White should start liquidating.} 
6. cxd5 {If White doesn't challenge in the center, we just have a pleasant edge.} 
7. d4
7. exd4
8. Nxd4
8. O-O {White has hopes of playing against our IQP, but our activity comes too quickly.} 
9. O-O
9. Bg4 {An annoying move. White is forced into a concession.} 
10. Nde2
10. Qd7 {Kramnik chose the c8-square, but there's no reason not to be a bit more active.} 
11. Bg5
11. Ne4 {Exploiting White's loose knight on e2.} 
12. Nxe4
12. dxe4 {White has no time to take on e4 again, as the knight will drop after the queen exchange.} 
13. Qxd7
13. Nxd7
14. Rfe1
14. f5 {We're ready to expel White's bishop and hop our knight into the game.} 
