[White "62) Vienna: Conclusion"]
[Black "Vienna − Conclusion"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {The Vienna has a proud history. These days it has been relegated behind the Spanish, Italian, and Scotch complexes in the popularity stakes, but of course, it still has a right to exist. As we’re only two moves in, the direction of the game is pretty broad.  White's problem is that the knight move doesn’t help either to control the pivotal d4-square or get White’s king castled.3.f4is clearly the move White would like to get to work. White’s playing in a romantic spirit, playing in a similar style to the King’s Gambit.  Indeed, it’s almost certainly an improvement. Grabbing on f4 is no longer so strong, as White would subsequentlygain time with e4-e5. Instead, we fight back in the center with3...d5. White tends to resolve the central tension by capturing on e5. After we capture on e4, our knight becomes extremely powerful.  An exchange deprives White’s kingside knight of its ideal f3-square, but it’s not easy to play around it either. White also has issues defending their e5-pawn.  The recent trend has been for the odd-looking5.Qf3. White tries to force us to shift our knight, but I think5...Nc6is a good antidote. Hopping into d4 is a big threat. White is forced to damage their structure, and allow an exchange of queens. The ensuing middlegames might be holdable, but they certainly don’t seem like a lot of fun.3.f4is generally considered too risky these days, and so3.Bc4is a more frequent guest at the top level. I was preparing to play this myself for a while, but I could never find a good way of playing against3...Bc5. White cannot even transpose back into the Italian, as we can take advantage of our undeveloped queenside knight.4.f4is much too risky, and so the critical line is with5.f4. We capture and thentake control of the center with ...c7-c6 and ...d7-d5. Despite the result, Aronian-Caruana reached a very promising position for Black out of the opening. White is in dire need of improvement.Finally, we wrapped up the Vienna section with White’s other third moves. Of the rare tries,3.d4!?is the most interesting. A specialty of Mamedyarov, White attempts to reach a type of Center Game. But moving the queen so many times in the opening is very risky. We can play logically, and so I think it’s much easier for us to play.  Finally, we looked at3.g3. Playing the kingside fianchetto is reasonably common, but combining theplan of ...Bc5, ...c7-c6, and ...d7-d5 works well once again.} 1. --
