[White "63) King's Gambit: Introduction"]
[Black "King's Gambit − Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. f4 {The romantic King's Gambit. White dreams of swashbuckling attacks, sacrificing everything for a beautiful mate, and spectators piling gold coins high on the board.} 
2. exf4 {Unfortunately, in the computer era such dreams are seldom realized. White has given away a pawn on move two and weakened their king. As is so often the case in the adventurous openings, the fun lines have simply been refuted. In order to play this way White has to either take grave risks or play a narrow accurate sequence to be a little worse in a depressing position.} 
3. Nf3 {The main line. White develops and prevents the check on h4.3.Bc4is the Bishop's Gambit. White's secondary approach has been under a theoretical cloud for quite some time.3...Nc6− if White now plays4.Nf3, we're pretty likely to transpose to3.Nf3d64.Bc4.4.d4Nf6.In a recent blitz game I went for the check on h4, but I think this is a simpler path. We're going to fight for control of the center with ...d7-d5 and ...Ne4.5.Nc3Bb4,we increase the pressure. White's best now seems to leave them in a fairly prospectless position with the worse structure.4.Nc3?!is too provocative.4...Qh4+5.Kf1Bc5and as White cannot now block with d2-d4, they're in some trouble. Their best is to exchange queens, but White has no compensation for the missing pawn.} 
3. d6 {Fischer's Defense. We take control of the e5-square and prepare to defend our extra pawn.} 
4. d4 {The most popular try, but criticized by Ian Nepomniachtchi in his course. White is not going to retrieve their sacrificed pawn.4.Bc4is Ian's approach. White is trying to find counterplay against the f7-pawn.4...h6!An odd little move, but very strong. We prepare to play ...g7-g5.   Had we played it immediately, White would have annoyed us with h2-h4, and then Ng5. The setup we're aiming for is to play ...g7-g5, ...Bg7, and ...Nc6. Our extra pawn on f4 does a fantastic job of stifling White's pieces. If White attempts to open up the f-file with g2-g3, we want to ignore it. We'll meet gxf4 with ...g5-g4, when the white knight struggles to find a safe square. We'll follow that with ...Qh4+.5.h4,White puts a stop to our plan.5...Nf6,but White's last created some holes. We intend to defend our extra pawn with ...Nh5. We'll also have ideas of hopping into g3 to annoy White.} 
4. g5 {We want the same setup as against4.Bc4.} 
5. h4 {The absolute main line in terms of games played, but neither Ian nor John Shaw in his Quality Chess tome trusted it.} 
5. g4 {The inclusion of d2-d4 and ...d7-d6 over the3...g5main line is a big improvement. White's knight can no longer jump forward successfully. We're now going to attempt to hold on to our extra pawnwith ...Qf6 and ...Bh6. While we keep the f4-pawn, White struggles to develop their pieces.} 
