[White "64) King's Gambit: 3.Nf3 Main Line"]
[Black "2.f4 exf4 3.Nf3 d6 4.Bc4 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. f4 {The King's Gambit. Despite playing 1...e5 for many years, I'm yet to face it in a classical FIDE-rated game.} 
2. exf4 {With the King's Gambit, White sacrifices a pawn to reach a murky complicated position. Let's be a pawn up in the complications!} 
3. Nf3 {The main move, and clearly the most logical. White develops and prevents any annoying check on h4.} 
3. d6 {Fischer's recommendation. In his Chessable course on the King's Gambit, Ian Nepomniachtchi called this 'the least fun for White'. Sounds good!We take control of the e5-square and prepare to defend our f-pawn with ...g7-g5. White now has two main moves, to develop with4.Bc4, or to grab the center with4.d4.} 
4. Bc4 {Ian's recommendation, although he admits he can't find equality. The idea is to target the f7-pawn. Now we have to watch out for Ng5 breaks.} 
4. h6 {Preventing White's plan. We're renewing ...g7-g5. We didn't want to play it immediately, as4...g55.h4!g46.Ng5would have been very annoying.} 
5. d4 {The main move in practice, but one we're very happy to see. Starting with5.O-Owill come to the same thing. After5...g5!, White doesn't have anything better than6.d4.White sometimes tries5.Nc3here, but it won't have any independent significance. After5...g5, White will have to move their d-pawn sooner or later.} 
5. g5 {This is a thematic position for our variation against the King's Gambit. Visually, it looks quite impressive for White. They have the center and a lead in development in return for the sacrificed pawn. The problem is that it's now very difficult to generate any plan.   Not only is the f4-pawn not dropping any time soon, but it also blocks White's hopes for playing down the f-file and keeps the c1-bishop out of the game. Next, we'll play ...Bg7 and ...Nc6. White has to figure out how to open the board while keeping their king secure. Holding on to their center isn't so straightforward either.} 
6. g3 {White is desperate to open some lines.} 
6. Nc6 {We don't need to touch our f-pawn yet. We could start with6...Bg7too, but this is a bit more accurate. White's last tries to open the g- or f-files, so it makes sense to keep the g-file clear for now.If White now plays7.O-O, we can annoy them with7...Bh3followed by ...Bg7. It turns out White has the much weaker king. We'll investigate that position viathe6.O-Omove order.} 
7. gxf4 {White could delay this, but next, we'll play ...Bg7. We can increase the pressure on the d4-pawn with ...Bg4 too. Should White defend the pawn with c2-c3 then we switch our focus to the e-pawn.} 
7. g4 {White has regained the pawn but now has to retreat.} 
8. Ng1 {8.d5gxf3followedby ...Qh4+ is hardly an improvement.} 
8. Qh4+ {White's center looks impressive, but they have problems with their king and kingside development.} 
9. Kf1
9. f5 {Probably an unnecessary improvement over the previously played9...Nf6, but White is in all kinds of trouble now.  If White doesn't push in the center, they'll lose their only trump and be left with a structure riddled with holes.} 
10. d5
10. Nce7
11. e5 {This looks scary, but White is not able to keep control.} 
11. dxe5
12. fxe5
12. Ng6 {Next, we'll play ...Bc5 threatening mate on f2. We can follow up by pushing the f-pawn. Meanwhile, White's impressive center can't be supported adequately and will soon crumble.} 
