[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. f4 {The King's Gambit. Despite playing 1...e5 for many years, I'm yet to face it in a classical FIDE-rated game.} 
2. exf4 {With the King's Gambit, White sacrifices a pawn to reach a murky complicated position. Let's be a pawn up in the complications!} 
3. Nf3 {The main move, and clearly the most logical. White develops and prevents any annoying check on h4.} 
3. d6 {Fischer's recommendation. In his Chessable course on the King's Gambit, Ian Nepomniachtchi called this 'the least fun for White'. Sounds good!We take control of the e5-square and prepare to defend our f-pawn with ...g7-g5. White now has two main moves, to develop with4.Bc4, or to grab the center with4.d4.} 
4. d4 {The main line. White takes the center. But Nepomniachtchi describes it as risky.4.d3g5would just be a more passive version.} 
4. g5 {We defend our pawn. We have a few transpositions here.5.Bc4h6was covered via the 4.Bc4 move order.5.Nc3Bg7is extremely likely to transpose elsewhere too, for example,6.Bc4h6is back in 4.Bc4, while6.g3will be covered via 5.g3.} 
5. g3 {GM John Shaw's recommendation in his The King's Gambit bible.} 
5. Bg7 {Remaining consistent. We leave the tension. We'll push ...g5-g4 once White captures on f4. That way White doesn't have access to the h4-square.} 
6. Nc3 {Another quite critical position. Nepo played it himself recently via the 5.Nc3 move order. If the two King's Gambit experts both want to go this way, we should prepare carefully.} 
6. Nc6 {Increasing the pressure on the d4-pawn.7.gxf4?!g4is still a disaster.} 
7. d5 {Shaw's recommendation. White will regain the pawn, but giving away control of the entire long diagonal is a big concession.} 
7. Ne5 {A wonderful knight and bishop.} 
8. gxf4 {8.Bb5+is rebuffed by8...c6.} 
8. gxf4
9. Bxf4
9. Bg4 {White has succeeded in regaining their sacrificed pawn. I suppose their hope is that they'll get time to get their king to safety and then attack down the f-file. But thanks to our control of the center that's not realistic.} 
10. Be2 {Blocking the pin. Here we still have the option to castle.} 
10. Nxf3+ {The other capture with10...Bxf3followed by 11...Qf6 is also promising. White is forced to allow us my favorite uncontested dark-squared bishop. But White has enough time to castle queenside, and probably just about hold.} 
11. Bxf3
11. Qf6 {We'd still like absolute control of the dark squares.} 
12. O-O {After12.Bxg4?!Qxf4, White's position is really miserable. Our initial threatsare ...Bxc3+ collecting the e-pawn and ...Qe3+. But any position where White is left with their bishop against either of our minor pieces is going to be a lot of suffering.} 
12. Bh3 {We're going to gain a tempo by exchanging bishops on the g-file.} 
13. Bg2
13. Bxg2
14. Kxg2
14. Qg6+ {Our queen is able to leave the f-file with tempo.} 
15. Kh3 {The king has to climb the board.15.Kh1Bxc3allows us to capture on e4 with check.15.Bg3h5!is an annoying pin.} 
15. Bxc3 {A shame to give up our beautiful bishop, but we're damaging White's structure.} 
16. bxc3
16. O-O-O {Our king finds safety.} 
17. Qg4+ {Another bonus to putting the king on h3.} 
17. Kb8 {White managed to hold in a couple of correspondence games, but it doesn't look like much fun to me. White has the weaker king, and so will probably want to exchange queens. But then the e4 and c3-pawns will be big weaknesses in the ending.} 
