3. d6 {Fischer's recommendation. In his Chessable course on the King's Gambit, Ian Nepomniachtchi called this 'the least fun for White'. Sounds good!We take control of the e5-square and prepare to defend our f-pawn with ...g7-g5. White now has two main moves, to develop with4.Bc4, or to grab the center with4.d4.} 
4. d4 {The main line. White takes the center. But Nepomniachtchi describes it as risky.4.d3g5would just be a more passive version.} 
4. g5 {We defend our pawn. We have a few transpositions here.5.Bc4h6was covered via the 4.Bc4 move order.5.Nc3Bg7is extremely likely to transpose elsewhere too, for example,6.Bc4h6is back in 4.Bc4, while6.g3will be covered via 5.g3.} 
5. h4 {We've finally made it to the main line. But there's a reason neither John nor Ian wanted to play this way.} 
5. g4 {We have an extra d2-d4 and ...d7-d6 over the 3...g5 main line. That doesn't look so bad for White, but it's actually a big improvement for us. The main line of Ne5 is obviously now impossible.} 
6. Ng5 {The knight walks to its doom.} 
6. f6 {Another bonus. We're able to trap the knight with our f-pawn. This wouldn't normally be possible, as the g4-pawn would be hanging.} 
7. Bxf4
7. fxg5
8. Bxg5
8. Be7 {Next, we'll force the exchange with ...h7-h6. It'll take us a few moves, but once we've castled we can start to convert our extra knight.} 
