6. Ng1 {The knight is forced to retreat.} 
6. Qf6 {We're in time to hold on to our extra pawn. We'll add more support with ...Bh6 and complete our kingside development with ...Ne7. If we succeed, then not only do we have an extra pawn but White will also struggle to either develop their queenside or defend the d4-pawn.} 
7. Nc3 {7.Ne2Bh6will likely come to the same thing.} 
7. Ne7 {Make sure not to allow the knight to jump into d5.} 
8. Nge2 {White is going to build up maximum pressure on our pawn.8.Qd2Bh69.Nge2is just a transposition.} 
8. Bh6 {We're staking everything on our extra pawn.} 
9. Qd3 {White is trying to castle.} 
9. Bd7 {The engine slightly prefers9...Nbc6!?, intending10.Nb5O-O!White loses too much time winning the c7-pawn. But I think it's more human not to allow it.} 
10. e5 {This is the reason the engine prefers to first develop the knight.} 
10. dxe5 {But we needn't be worried. We take a second pawn.} 
11. Ne4
11. Qe6 {We could use any of the other squares which defend the e-pawn too.} 
12. dxe5
12. Qxe5 {Stockfish's big point is to now play13.Qc3. White would then manage to win the f4-pawn, but would still be a clear pawn down in a queenless middlegame. It shows how little the silicon thinks of White's position that that would be considered a triumph.} 
13. Bd2 {I imagine this would be a human approach.} 
13. Bf5 {We ignore White's threat.} 
14. Bc3
14. Qxe4
15. Qxe4
15. Bxe4 {Surprisingly, we can give up the exchange and exchange queens, and yet Stockfish claims we're completely winning.} 
16. Bxh8
16. Nd7 {White's issue is that they cannot coordinate at all. Castling queenside is impossible, as we can react with ... f4-f3+. The kingside pieces are all falling over themselves. We threaten ...f7-f6 trapping the bishop in the corner. When it drops back, we'll take the center with our knights. Remember material is still actually equal here. We're completely winning.} 
