1. e4
1. e5
2. f4 {The King's Gambit. Despite playing 1...e5 for many years, I'm yet to face it in a classical FIDE-rated game.} 
2. exf4 {With the King's Gambit, White sacrifices a pawn to reach a murky complicated position. Let's be a pawn up in the complications!} 
3. Nf3 {The main move, and clearly the most logical. White develops and prevents any annoying check on h4.} 
3. d6 {Fischer's recommendation. In his Chessable course on the King's Gambit, Ian Nepomniachtchi called this 'the least fun for White'. Sounds good!We take control of the e5-square and prepare to defend our f-pawn with ...g7-g5. White now has two main moves, to develop with4.Bc4, or to grab the center with4.d4.} 
4. d4 {The main line. White takes the center. But Nepomniachtchi describes it as risky.4.d3g5would just be a more passive version.} 
4. g5 {We defend our pawn. We have a few transpositions here.5.Bc4h6was covered via the 4.Bc4 move order.5.Nc3Bg7is extremely likely to transpose elsewhere too, for example,6.Bc4h6is back in 4.Bc4, while6.g3will be covered via 5.g3.} 
5. h4 {We've finally made it to the main line. But there's a reason neither John nor Ian wanted to play this way.} 
5. g4 {We have an extra d2-d4 and ...d7-d6 over the 3...g5 main line. That doesn't look so bad for White, but it's actually a big improvement for us. The main line of Ne5 is obviously now impossible.} 
6. Ng1 {The knight is forced to retreat.} 
6. Qf6 {We're in time to hold on to our extra pawn. We'll add more support with ...Bh6 and complete our kingside development with ...Ne7. If we succeed, then not only do we have an extra pawn but White will also struggle to either develop their queenside or defend the d4-pawn.} 
7. Nc3 {7.Ne2Bh6will likely come to the same thing.} 
7. Ne7 {Make sure not to allow the knight to jump into d5.} 
8. Nge2 {White is going to build up maximum pressure on our pawn.8.Qd2Bh69.Nge2is just a transposition.} 
8. Bh6 {We're staking everything on our extra pawn.} 
9. Qd2 {White points everything at our f4-pawn.} 
9. Nbc6 {The pressure on the d4-pawn ensures White can still not regain the pawn.} 
10. Nb5 {White goes for counterplay.} 
10. Kd8 {The most ambitious and greedy. I don't think White has any way to take advantage of our centralized king. However,10...O-Owould also force White to show a lot of accuracy. There I think White can reach a slightly worse queen and rook endgame with perfect play, but here I can't find any escape.11.Nxf4doesn't really win the pawn back. With11...a6we expel the knight.Next, we'll play ...Nxd4. White's two tries are the central advances.} 
11. d5
11. a6 {It's important to expel the knight. We don't want to allow White to attack the c7-pawn twice.} 
12. Nbc3
12. Ne5 {Our beautiful knight.} 
13. Nxf4
13. g3 {We're not allowing White to escape the pin. Next, we'll increase the pressure with ...N7g6 or ...Rg8-g4. White's position is creaking.} 
