[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. f4 {The King's Gambit. Despite playing 1...e5 for many years, I'm yet to face it in a classical FIDE-rated game.} 
2. exf4 {With the King's Gambit, White sacrifices a pawn to reach a murky complicated position. Let's be a pawn up in the complications!} 
3. Nc3 {Apparently, this is the Keres Gambit. For those who really feel the need to give their king some exercise.} 
3. Qh4+ {Checking on h4 against3.Bc4is interesting, but here it's almost mandatory. Clearly, we're not worse with any normal move, but we should happily take the opportunity to force White's king up the board.} 
4. Ke2
4. d5 {It's possible to play more slowly, for example with Jan's recommendation of4...Qh5, or John Shaw's4...Qe7,intending ...Nf6. When I analyzed this many years ago I thought4...d5was a draw, but modern engines are extremely optimistic.} 
5. exd5
5. Bg4+ {Developing with tempo.} 
6. Nf3
6. Bd6 {Our f4-pawn is staying put.} 
7. Qe1
7. Qh6 {Keeping the queen out of the way. We'll develop our knights to e7 and d7 and castle kingside with a monumental initiative. White's king will have to drop back to d1, but he won't be happy about it.} 
*
