1. e4
1. e5
2. f4 {The King's Gambit. Despite playing 1...e5 for many years, I'm yet to face it in a classical FIDE-rated game.} 
2. exf4 {With the King's Gambit, White sacrifices a pawn to reach a murky complicated position. Let's be a pawn up in the complications!} 
3. d4 {Extreme aggression. I actually played this once in a blitz game, but it's really not to be recommended.} 
3. Qh4+ {3.d4has the same drawback as3.Nc3. White's king is forced forward.} 
4. Ke2
4. d5 {Continuing to play dynamically. It makes sense to open the center with White's king on e2, but John Shaw's4...Qe7!?also works well. White's best move there is to play5.Kf2, offering a repetition after5...Qh4+.} 
5. exd5 {5.Nf3Qe7!followed by ...g7-g5 is very strong.} 
5. Bg4+ {We can play as we did against 3.Nc3.} 
