3. Nc6 {The same treatment as against3.Qf3.White has many pretty terrible third-move alternatives, but it doesn't make sense to memorize something against all of them. Generally, we can either annoy them with a ...Qh4+ or open up the board with ...d7-d5.} 
4. c3 {White defends the d4-square. Neither4.Nf3g5nor4.Nc3Bc5are really playable.} 
4. Qh4+ {Once White puts the pawn on c3, the check is very tempting. White is unable to generate any counterplay with Nc3-d5.} 
5. Kd1
5. d6 {When needed, we'll keep our f-pawn with ...g7-g5. Our queen has a broad range of possible retreat squares, but I'll side with Gustafsson and recommend h6.} 
