2. exf4 {With the King's Gambit, White sacrifices a pawn to reach a murky complicated position. Let's be a pawn up in the complications!} 
3. Bc4 {The Bishop's Gambit. The choice of players who think merely playing the King's Gambit isn't exciting enough. Perhaps White dreams of playing another Immortal Game.} 
3. Nc6 {This is generally considered the drawback. John Shaw went as far as claiming it as the refutation of 3.Bc4. It's more accurate to start with3...Nc6rather than3...d6, as our bishop might want to develop more actively. We're now very likely to transpose to the 4.Bc4 lines examined in the previous segment.3...Qh4+is perfectly playable and computer-approved, but that type of mess is what White craves.} 
4. d4 {This was played against me by Aleksei Pridorozhni in a Titled Tuesday blitz event. I threw in the check on h4 which is fine, but my proposal is simpler.} 
4. Nf6 {The check is no longer so clear, as we can't follow it up with ...Bc5. I think Black is still better, but this is an easier attempt at exploiting White's unorthodox opening. We want to play a combination of ...d7-d5 and ...Ne4.} 
5. Nc3 {White attempts to keep the pawn on e4.} 
5. Bb4 {This is very simple. We renew the threat of capturing on e4.} 
6. Nge2 {An interesting idea. White is offering a second pawn to get castled. They'll then have some play down the f-file. It's important that c3 is now defended twice.} 
6. f3 {Instead of being two pawns up but having to suffer against White's initiative, we give back the pawn.} 
7. gxf3
7. d5 {White's center is too loose, they have to exchange.} 
8. exd5
8. Nxd5
9. O-O
9. Nxc3
10. bxc3
10. Bd6 {This might be one of White's better lines in theory, but it's pretty disgusting. There's no play, just weaknesses. The queenside is slightly damaged, but the pawn on f3 is the real problem. It weakens White's king while also preventing White from ever getting any play down the f-file.} 
