[White "66) King's Gambit: Conclusion"]
[Black "King's Gambit − Conclusion"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {I think we’ve seen the heyday of the King’s Gambit. Before the advent of strong computers, it was less of a risk to enter objectively dubious positions. These days White’s playable options have shrunk dramatically.  At the elite level, it’s reserved for speed chess or extremely occasional one-off surprises. Ian Nepomniachtchi did a brave attempt in his Long Live the King’s Gambit, but he had to acknowledge that White was worse against our proposed path. Both Ian and John Shaw in his The King’s Gambit bible, struggled against Fischer’s Defense.  The main line appears to be very promising for Black, and so they both went for earlier deviations. Ian analyzed the line beginning4.Bc4h6!5.h4Nf6deeply, but was forced to acknowledge White was groveling in an unpleasant middlegame.  John instead proposed4.d4g55.g3Bg7!6.Nc3, a line Ian actually played himself recently. But if we know our stuff White is only fighting to survive.  White’s other main attempt is3.Bc4, the so-called Bishop’s Gambit. This has been under a theoretical cloud for years, and John Shaw went as far as describing it as refuted.In practice, I think we’re likely to reach a very similar position against both of the main moves. White will take possession of the center, while we cling on doggedly to our extra pawn with ...g7-g5. Our setup with the bishop on g7, knight on c6, and pawns on h6, g5, f4, and d6 is extremely hard to break.   We safely secure the f4-pawn, meaning not just that we have a material advantage, but that White finds it very difficult to generate any play of their own. The bishop on c1 struggles to enter the game, and White’s impressive-looking center ends up just being a weakness.   We wrapped up the chapter looking at White’s remaining third move attempts. The only question there is whether they lose by force. I don’t think we need to memorize too much. In general either ...Qh4+ or slicing open White’s king with ...d7-d5 work well.} 1. --
