1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. c3 {The Ponziani. An opening I attempted to resurrect a few years ago. The large practical problem is that Black has a wide range of playable options. White is hoping to take control of the center with d2-d4.} 
3. d5 {3...Nf6is also fine, but this feels like the critical test. We exploit the downside to White's last. The b1-knight is often a serious problem.} 
4. Qa4 {This weird-looking move became main line by default.4.Bb5?The move White wants to play, but it was discovered the g2-pawn is too weak.4...dxe45.Nxe5Qg5!The problem. When White loses the g2-pawn their king is incredibly vulnerable. The lines are complicated, but objectively we're very close to winning. A safe alternative is5...Qd5.4.d3is the modern trend. But that's got little to do with the virtues of this modest push. White has just been encountering problems everywhere else.4...Nf6,in this reversed Philidor, we're very flexible. An easy setup is to play with ...Bd6, ...h7-h6, ...a7-a5, and castle kingside.} 
4. Bd7 {I recommend the Cozio Variation. We sacrifice a pawn, but in return, White is forced into a passive position. They have to be careful not to allow a knockout blow. Even if they succeed, their position lacks any activity, and so I think it's rather miserable to play.} 
