3. d5 {3...Nf6is also fine, but seeing as the intended 4.Bb5? has now been refuted, this feels correct.} 
4. Bb5 {White hopes to cause some mischief with the pin. Unfortunately, the g2-pawn is too weak.} 
4. dxe4
5. Nxe5
5. Qg5 {We can also get a comfortable advantage with5...Qd5, but this move is the reason this variation is no longer seen. It turns out that it doesn't matter how much material White collects on the queenside. Their light squares on the kingside are just much too vulnerable.} 
6. d4
6. Qxg2
7. Rf1
7. Bd6 {We develop and force White's hand.} 
8. Nxc6
8. Bd7 {White is a piece up for now, but the pin prevents White from consolidating it.} 
9. Qa4 {Or9.Nxa7c6!We immediately regain the piece.} 
9. a6 {White's pieces are stuck. The threat isn't immediate, but White can't move any of the pieces on the a4-e8 diagonal. We'll simply move the a8-rook. White's pieces will then fall like a pack of cards.} 
10. Na3 {In fact, if White didn't defend the bishop, then ...Ne7 was also winning.} 
10. Rc8 {White loses at least one of the hanging pieces.} 
