5. Qg5 {We can also get a comfortable advantage with5...Qd5, but this move is the reason this variation is no longer seen. It turns out that it doesn't matter how much material White collects on the queenside. Their light squares on the kingside are just much too vulnerable.} 
6. Qa4
6. Qxg2 {We plough on. We're happy to give our a8-rook.} 
7. Bxc6+
7. bxc6
8. Qxc6+
8. Kd8 {On the surface it looks like White must be doing well. They crashed through first. The queen and knight are attacking, and our king is forced to start scurrying. But looks can be deceptive. White doesn't have enough firepower to mate, and the rest of their army can't move. It's still White's chronically weak light squares that'll decide.} 
9. Qd5+ {This one was tried for a while. White is able to get the queens off the board, but it won't save them.} 
9. Bd6
10. Nxf7+
10. Ke7 {It might look scary, but of course, knowing it doesn't work is extremely useful. Our moves are all forced anyway, and so quite easy to find over the board.} 
11. Qg5+ {White's point. The queens come off.} 
11. Qxg5
12. Nxg5
12. Nf6 {So after all that White is a pawn up. But the knight is trapped on g5, and the light squares are still diabolically weak.} 
13. O-O {White is hoping for a trick on the e-file.} 
13. Ba6
14. Re1
14. Bd3 {Absolute domination. Even without queens White's king is in all kinds of trouble. White's queenside pieces are still snoozing.} 
