[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. c3 {The Ponziani. Another opening I dabbled with from the White side. White is attempting to play a sort of Alapin or c3-Sicilian. The downside, as against the Sicilian, is White's loss of control of the d5-square.} 
3. d5 {3...Nf6is also fine, but seeing as the intended 4.Bb5? has now been refuted, this feels correct.} 
4. d3 {This might be White's best move, but then the whole Ponziani is in a bit of a sad state.   White is playing some sort of reversed Philidor. Baadur Jobava champions this approach, and it's also recommended, at least as a safe alternative, by Levy Rozman in his GothamChess 1.e4 Repertoire. That alone is likely to mean the variation will have a surge in popularity. We needn't be concerned.} 
4. Nf6 {There's nothing wrong with capturing on e4 and exchanging queens either, but let's keep the tension. Our intended setup is ...Bd6, ...a7-a5, ...O-O, and ... h7-h6 in some order. We can play this way against a lot of White's offbeat second and third moves.} 
5. Nbd2
5. Bd6 {This is a reliable setup against any White move order.} 
6. Be2
6. h6
7. O-O
7. O-O {We'll continue with ...Re8 and ...a7-a5. White has a playable Philidor with the extra tempo, but it's also rather passive. We're comfortably equal.} 
