[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. c3 {The Ponziani. Another opening I dabbled with from the White side. White is attempting to play a sort of Alapin or c3-Sicilian. The downside, as against the Sicilian, is White's loss of control of the d5-square.} 
3. d5 {3...Nf6is also fine, but seeing as the intended 4.Bb5? has now been refuted, this feels correct.} 
4. Qa4 {If White wants to play a true Ponziani, then this is what they sadly have to try.} 
4. Bd7 {The Cozio Variation. This one scared me a lot from the White side. Recently4...f6has become the main line, and is recommended in quite a few Chessable courses already.4...Bd7is pretty forcing. Our idea is to exchange a pairof knights with ...Nd4xf3. White will be able to collect a pawn, but their development is very slow. We're going to combine attacking on the kingside with keeping White as passively placed as possible. I see this was even Anatoly Karpov's choice in a game from July 2022.} 
5. exd5 {The whole point was to take the pawn.} 
5. Nd4
6. Qd1 {White has to retreat.} 
6. Nxf3+
7. Qxf3
7. Nf6 {Pushing the f-pawn is tempting, but White can then fight back in the center with d2-d4. For now, we're just going to develop and make it as hard as possible for White to coordinate. One threat is ...Bg4 followed by ...Qxd5.} 
8. c4 {White demands they keep their extra pawn. First of all, moving the pawn twice is rather slow, but more importantly, we have been given an outpost on d4.} 
8. c6 {White doesn't want to accelerate our play further by exchanging on c6. White has only managed to develop their queen so far, and that will get hit around.} 
9. Nc3
9. Bc5 {We don't need to worry unduly about the pawn. Let's develop and see what happens.} 
10. Bd3 {The most active spot for that bishop, but the one on c1 isn't particularly happy.} 
10. O-O
11. O-O
11. cxd5 {Asking White the question. Perhaps they should take with the pawn, but they're condemned to a chronically bad structure. Our long-term plan will be to arrange our pieces to play ...f7-f5.} 
12. Nxd5
12. Nxd5
13. Qxd5 {White maintains their structure as much as they can after having played the ugly c3-c4.} 
13. Bd4 {We've got the outpost.} 
14. Qxb7 {Grabbing a second pawn is too risky.} 
14. Rb8 {If White drops back anywhere but d5, we'll start attacking with ...f7-f5.} 
15. Qd5
15. Qc7 {That queen is very short on squares. We'll combine threatening to trap her with pushing ...f7-f5. As often happens in the Ponziani, White's queenside pieces are mere bystanders.} 
