[White "69) Ponziani: Conclusion"]
[Black "Ponziani − Conclusion"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {The Ponziani isn’t seen much these days. To be honest, it just isn’t a very practical opening. Black has a wide range of playable options. White can cut down the workload by playing with4.d3, but that’s hardly challenging. We’re very flexible there, but I likethe setups with ...Bd6. They’re very simple to play.5...Qg5!seems to outright refute 4.Bb5? There’s quite a bit to know, but it wouldn’t even be a good gamble, as5...Qd5is also comfortable.4.Qa4is much more challenging. These days4...f6!?is topical, but I like the Cozio Variation:4...Bd7. We sacrifice a pawn but get a lead in development and active play. White struggles both to prevent our attack and to develop their queenside. The pawn on c3 just gets in the way.} 1. --
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "70) Remaining Gambits: Introduction"]
[Black "Remaining Gambits − Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5 {Time to move on to examine White's remaining gambits. The focus will be on the Danish and Göring Gambits, but we'll also check more exotic lines like the Urusov Gambit, and variations I don't know the name of.} 
2. Nf3 {2.d4exd43.c3is the Danish Gambit. I recall memorizing a lot of weird and wonderful stuff like3...dxc34.Bc4cxb25.Bxb2d5, but it seems all that is unnecessary.3...Qe7!We simply attack the e-pawn. It turns out it's not at all easy to defend. We could also play3...d5, which will likely transpose to our line against the Göring Gambit.} 
2. Nc6
3. d4
3. exd4
4. c3 {The Göring Gambit. I think the pawn sacrifice is more serious with the knights already developed. White is one step closer to castling kingside.} 
4. d5 {We decline the pawn and instead exploit White's lack of the c3-square for their knight. Our idea is to rush to develop our bishops. That way White will struggle to castle without exchanging queens. We're going to go long with our king.} 
