[White "71) Remaining Gambits"]
[Black "2.d4 exd4 3.Bc4 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5 {In this chapter, we'll examine a bunch of White gambit lines.} 
2. d4
2. exd4 {White now has to decide if they want to recapture the pawn.3.Qxd4is the Center Game, analyzed elsewhere.3.Nf3Nc6is covered via2.Nf3Nc63.d4exd4.} 
3. Bc4 {Apparently, this is the Urusov Gambit. Miodrag Perunovic recommends it (via the 2.Bc4 move order) in his Butcher 1...e5 course.} 
3. Nf6 {We attack the e4-pawn. If White now continues with4.Nf3, we have a choice. We can grab the e4-pawn, when I'm not convinced White has enough compensation, but it's simpler to play4...Nc6with a direct transposition to the Scotch Gambit.} 
4. Qxd4 {A dubious Center Game crossover.} 
4. Nc6 {The bishop has no business being on c4 so early. In the Center Game, White tries castling queenside very quickly. Here White's going to run into trouble on the e-file.} 
5. Qe3 {The best available square.5.Qd3Ne5forks the queen and bishop.Against5.Qd1we can get away with5...Nxe4, while5...Bb4+is still rather annoying.} 
5. Bb4+ {Developing with tempo. Our plan is simple. We're going to castle and play ...Re8. White doesn't have time to get their king safe and hold on to the e-pawn.} 
6. c3
6. Ba5 {Now we also have ideas of a subsequent ...Bb6.} 
7. Nf3
7. O-O
8. O-O
8. Re8 {White has to sacrifice the e-pawn.} 
9. Nbd2
9. d5 {White is in trouble down the e-file.} 
