3. c3 {The Danish Gambit.} 
3. Qe7 {I remember coming across this antidote many years ago. At that point, it was still rare, but now it's quite well-known. White struggles to defend the e-pawn.  If you don't fancy winning a pawn, then3...d5will probably transpose to our defense against the Göring Gambit (the Danish with Nf3and ...Nc6 included).} 
4. Qxd4 {Playing c2-c3 and then taking on d4 with the queen is pretty ugly.} 
4. f5 {Going after the e-pawn anyway. Developing the knights is also enough for an advantage.} 
5. Bd3
5. Nf6 {Increasing the pressure.} 
6. Bg5 {The pin is the only way to defend the e-pawn, but it won't hold for long.} 
6. Nc6
7. Qe3 {7.Bxf6gxf6would be similar.} 
7. Ne5 {Hassling White's pieces.} 
8. Be2
8. fxe4
9. Bxf6 {The only way to retrieve the pawn.} 
9. gxf6
10. Qxe4
10. c6 {White has managed to restore material balance, but we're still much better. Our plan is ...d7-d5, ...Bd7, and ...O-O-O. We have more space, the bishop pair, and an easy attack on the kingside.} 
