2. Nc6
3. d4
3. exd4 {We've already examined the Scotch with4.Nxd4and the Scotch Gambit with4.Bc4. Those are by far White's main options.} 
4. c3 {The Göring Gambit. Delaying the sacrifice for a move is more challenging than the Danish Gambit we just analyzed.} 
4. d5 {Of course, it's possible to take the pawn too, but I think this is easiest. After all, we don't want to give White what they want. As in the Ponziani, we'll take advantage of the fact that the b1-knight is temporarily deprived of the c3-square.  Another good option is4...Nf6. That's a direct transposition to a Ponziani, but a different variation to the one I recommend.} 
5. Bd3
5. Bg4 {We won't make it so easy for White to win back their pawn.} 
6. Qb3 {White has a 100% score here, but not because of their current position.} 
6. Bxf3 {First, we damage White's structure.} 
7. gxf3
7. Nge7 {And now we defend our knight. Our plan is just to fianchetto with ...g7-g6. If White captures on b7, we'll include ...Rb8. White has problems with their king.} 
