[White "73) Center Game: Introduction"]
[Black "Center Game − Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. d4
2. exd4
3. Qxd4 {The Center Game. When I lived in Italy, the coach at my local club was my good friend Riccardo Del Dotto. He loved the Center Game and even wrote a book on it.   Consequently, if you played 1...e5 you would reach this position. It's very aggressive. Unusually for 1.e4 e5 openings, White wants to castle queenside.} 
3. Nc6 {The obvious flaw is the time lost with White's queen. We're going to generate very quick counterplay down the e-file.} 
4. Qe3
4. Nf6 {4...g6is also interesting, and I was close to recommending it. What annoyed me was the Vienna move order employed by Mamedyarov after2.Nc3Nf63.d4. I've yet to see White players use that to reach the Center Game, but I don't want us to find ourselves tricked.} 
5. Nc3
5. Bb4 {Our plan is to castle and play ...Re8. The e4-pawn is weak, and ...d7-d5 becomes a big threat. White often abandons the pawn, and hopes to get somewhere on the kingside.   As we're about to castle on opposite flanks, the following positions are very sharp. White has been struggling recently. It seems the lost couple of tempi with the queen really do matter.} 
*
