1. e4
1. e5
2. d4
2. exd4
3. Qxd4 {The Center Game.} 
3. Nc6 {The queen is forced to move again.} 
4. Qe3 {White normally opts for this square. At least it won't get hit immediately. But White will have further problems down the e-file.} 
4. Nf6 {Our play is very straightforward. We're going to pin the knight with ...Bb4, castle, and play ...Re8. White will have problems with the e-pawn.Despite over 4000 games in the online database, White hasn't really been able to find a good antidote.5.Bc4is covered in the Gambits Chapter.} 
5. e5 {An old line that has now been refuted. White can win a piece, but they'll run into trouble down the e-file.} 
5. Ng4 {If the queen drops back with6.Qe2, we'll play6...d6!If White takes the pawn,then we'll block the check with ...Be6. We're happy to give the piece after7.h3Ngxe5. We'll immediately get two pawns, while White will have ongoing problems with their queen.} 
6. Qe4
6. Ngxe5
7. f4 {White's point. They're winning a piece, but it's taking too long.} 
7. d5 {Here come all our free tempi.} 
8. Qe3
8. d4 {We force the queen to move again. As Jan observes,9.Qe4Qh4+!prevents White from winning the piece. Thanks to the pin along the fourth rank, White cannot take our knight. If White tries to force our queen away, we'll drop it back to g6 and exchange queens.} 
9. Qe2
9. Bb4+ {Developing either bishop is promising.} 
10. Kd1
10. O-O {Or Jan's10...d3. There are a lot of roads to Rome at this point.} 
11. fxe5
11. Re8 {White is currently a piece for a pawn ahead, but that's the end of the good news. We're about to win a second pawn and enter down the e-file. White's king is weak, and no other pieces have developed.} 
12. Nf3
12. Nxe5
13. Nxe5
13. Qf6 {We're winning the house along the e-file.} 
