[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "76) 2.Bc4 and offbeat tries: Introduction"]
[Black "Offbeat Tries − Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5 {Here we'll wrap up White's offbeat second and third moves. None of them are particularly challenging. A lot of the lines see White playing a Black opening with an extra tempo.   We can normally be very flexible. If in doubt playing either our Italian setup with ...Bc5, ...a7-a5, or a Four Knights approach works fine. We can sometimes fianchetto our dark-squared bishop too. The question there should be whether White's previous move helped with d2-d4. If it did, then the fianchetto is a bit risky, otherwise, fianchetto away!} 
2. Bc4 {This is the most likely move covered in this chapter by far, but it's also extremely likely to transpose directly into the Italian or Vienna chapters.} 
2. Nf6 {White now tends to choose between either3.d3or the direct transposition to the Vienna with3.Nc3. We'll react to both the same way.3.d3Bc5and now the vast majority of the time White chooses between4.Nf3or returning to the Vienna with4.Nc3. After4.Nf3Nc6(or the flexible4...d6), we transpose directly into the Italian chapter.} 
