[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "77) 2.Bc4"]
[Black "2.Bc4 Nf6 3.Nf3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Bc4 {I see this one is sometimes known as the Italian, although I think it's easier to consider that as the whole Bc4 complex. The vast majority of the time, White uses this move order simply to bypass the Petroff.} 
2. Nf6 {Here3.Nc3is a direct transposition to the Vienna and3.d4exd4was covered via 2.d4 in the Gambits Chapter.} 
3. Nf3 {A move order that would make absolutely zero sense.} 
3. Nxe4 {There's no good reason not to take the pawn. We want to play ...d7-d5 next.3...Nc6would simply transpose to the Italian.} 
4. Nc3 {4.Nxe5d5and ...Bd6 is already a very good Petroff.} 
4. Nxc3 {Logical, but4...Nc6!?transposing to 4.Bc4 in the Four Knights complex is also interesting.} 
5. dxc3
5. f6 {The right way to defuse White's initiative. We defend the pawn and prevent Ng5 jumps. The whole concept is incredibly risky for White. If they're not able to crash through immediately, then our extra central pawn will decide the game.} 
6. Nh4
6. g6 {We should prevent Qh5+. If White now waits, we'll play ...c7-c6 and ...d7-d5.} 
7. f4
7. Qe7 {We have to guard against f4-f5.} 
8. f5
8. Qg7 {Our queen looks passive here, but if White is not able to break through immediately on the kingside, then they're basically just lost.} 
9. fxg6
9. hxg6
10. Qg4
10. Kd8 {The final move that refutes White's adventurous approach. By defending the bishop we threaten ...d7-d5. White has to drop back with11.Qg3, when11...g5is still a weird position, but we have an extra pawn.} 
