1. e5
2. Bc4 {I see this one is sometimes known as the Italian, although I think it's easier to consider that as the whole Bc4 complex. The vast majority of the time, White uses this move order simply to bypass the Petroff.} 
2. Nf6 {Here3.Nc3is a direct transposition to the Vienna and3.d4exd4was covered via 2.d4 in the Gambits Chapter.} 
3. d3
3. Bc5 {We play the same setup as against the Vienna.4.Nf3Nc6would be a direct transposition to a normal Italian while playing the flexible4...d6is also good.White tends to play either that or4.Nc3, when we would be directed back to the Vienna. In fact, most things will probably just transpose to uncritical Italian/Vienna crossovers.} 
4. f4 {White tries something a bit different.} 
4. d5 {We can exploit the lack of a knight on c3. White is going to have a really hard time castling.} 
5. exd5
5. O-O {Let's just attack.5...Ng4, going after the rookwith ...Nf2, was played in Aronian-Anand, Monte Carlo 2006, but was a bit messier.} 
6. Nf3
6. e4 {We're too quick.} 
7. Ne5 {White desperately attempts to keep the lines closed.} 
7. exd3
8. Qxd3
8. Ng4 {There's no escape for the white king.} 
