 {That’s it! Thanks for bearing with me and congratulations! You now have a full fighting repertoire against1.e4.These days it’s pretty rare that White doesn’t play either the Ruy Lopez, an Italian, or something in the Scotch family: the Four Knights if your opponent wants rather tedious positions or the main lines or Scotch Gambit for something a bit more fun.   I hope I’ve managed to convince you that the Steinitz Deferred is a logical and aggressive opening. We reach positions where your opponent won’t feel comfortable. Against the Italian, I’ve offered a choice dependent on mood and style. The ...Bc5 positions are much more mainstream, while the ...h7-h6 setups prevent White from playing on autopilot and force them to wake up much earlier.   The Scotch is a fascinating opening. I used to play it as my main weapon but decided that the main lines were much easier for Black. We reach complex positions without having to force anything. The onus is on White to survive the opening. Likewise, we should be ready for the Italianwith4.Ng5, but it’s White who has to show much greater accuracy to successfully develop their pieces.The Scotch Four Knights is much less exciting. However, by delaying ...d7-d5 we reach much more unbalanced positions. The rest are generally rare for a good reason. The various gambits appeal to romantically inclined players, but they tend to force White to show deep knowledge to reach anything remotely playable. On the other hand, we have plenty of choices on how to reach a very healthy middlegame.   Don’t hesitate with any questions. If you don’t understand something, I most probably didn’t explain it correctly, so let me know.   Thanks again, Gawain} 1. --
*
